1. --
{ Warm Welcome to Ratsma’s Complete Black and White Repertoire  Study Tips:  •	Start with the Course-Specific Rules: They teach you a chess logic, which is applied throughout the entire course, and makes it easier to remember and understand the theory.  •	Master the 7 Quickstarter guides first: The quickstarter guides cover a shorter version of all the most important variations and are essentially a summary of the whole course.  •	Use the Browse Tree Function: This allows you to check what I recommend quickly after you played a game and you are not sure if you remember the theory correctly.  •	Use the space bar and learn buttons: For the most convenient way to use the move trainer.   Course Philosophy:  •	Consistency: Whenever possible, you will pursue similar plans, both by applying the course-specific rules and by using similar development setups within openings.  •	Objectivity: The chosen lines are objectively sound and checked with powerful cloud engines. When something objectively doesn’t work out, you won’t keep holding on to the same plan for consistency, but in that case, you change your plans.  •	Practicality: When multiple moves are about equally good, you go for the lines that are most surprising and challenging for your opponent.  •	Transparency: Your opponents' best replies are also covered and discussed.  •	Broad Audience: The course is for everyone below the International Master level. Beginners and Casual players are recommended to start with the Ratsma’s Black & White opening repertoire for Beginners course. This course is the follow-up version of that course based on the same move recommendation and students can advance to this one when they grow stronger.  About the Authors:  •	Collaboration with GM Roeland Pruijssers: I collaborated with GM Roeland Pruijssers for valuable insights on many openings. Roeland is also a Chessable author. The majority of the course I completed myself  •	FM Midas Ratsma:  o	Full-time chess author and coach from the Netherlands.  o	Founder of the website thechesscommunity.com, where you can find a passionate chess coach.  o	6th course for Chessable, and this is the biggest one.  o	Previous publications include the beginner version of this course, an Attacking Repertoire for Club Players, a course Crush the Caro-Kann, and a tactics course.  o	More projects are in the pipeline, focusing on tactics and strategy.  Course support:  •	Clarity in Explanation: I have made every effort to explain all moves and variations clearly.  •	Opportunity for Questions: If you have any questions, you can place a comment by clicking a move of the variation you have a question about.  •	Acknowledgement of Previous Lack of Support: My support for previous publications has been lacking in the last few months. I'm sorry about that. I've picked up the support there again now.  •	Realistic Support Expectations: I aim to offer medium support and reply to all questions once a month.   •	Course updates: If a critical variation is missing, and I agree with your comment, I will update the course with new coverage on that line, either with a clickable or a new trainable variation. }
*

