[White "Repertoire Specific Rules"]
[Black "Three Golden Opening Rules"]
[Result "*"]

{ This Course Specific Rules chapter teaches you a chess logic that is applied throughout the whole course.  I bet you are familiar with the three Golden Opening Rules. You will learn why they are important and how to prioritize them. }
1. e4 e5 { Golden Rule 1: Place your pawns in the center. } 2. Nf3 Nc6
{ Golden rule 2: Develop your pieces. } 3. d4 { Again, Golden Rule 1. } 3...
exd4 4. Nxd4 Nxd4 5. Qxd4 d6 6. Nc3 { Again Golden Rule 2 } 6... Nf6 7. Bf4
{ Still Golden Rule 2 } 7... Be7 8. O-O-O
{ Golden Rule 3: Castle to safeguard your king. Castling is the only move in chess where you move two of your pieces simultaneously. Castling both secures your king and activates a rook. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Repertoire Specific Rules"]
[Black "Priority of Golden Rule 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 -- 2. d4
{ Placing your pawns in the center has priority over the other Golden Rules. Why?   Moving pawns into the center helps you to fulfill your other golden opening rules. This allows your bishops and queen to move freely and facilitates castling in either direction.   Additionally, it creates obstacles for your opponent in achieving their Golden Rules. It becomes more challenging for Black to place pawns in the center as they risk being captured. Consequently, it makes developing pieces and castling more difficult for them. }
*

