[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Repertoire Specific Rules"]
[Black "The Knights"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ The knight's role in the opening!    After placing your pawns in the center, the knights have three legal moves from their starting position. The optimal squares for the knights are f3 and c3 for White and f6 and c6 for Black.  Moving the knights to the edge of the board doesn't give control over the center and limits their mobility. Instead, placing the knight in front of your king or queen obstructs the development of your other pieces.    In this course, you always move your knights to the natural squares, regardless of whether you're playing White or Black pieces. While there are openings where knights are better placed on different squares to maintain simplicity, they aren't recommended in this repertoire.    Once you've achieved Golden Rule 1 - positioning your pawns in the center, your next priority is to develop your knights as their location is pre-established. This strategy allows you to spot your opponent's plan and determine the optimal squares for your bishops' development. }
3. Nf3 -- 4. Nc3
{ On the natural squares your knights control all four squares in the center! }
