[Black "Knights: Natural Squares"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. c4
{ Here's an essential note about the knights' natural squares.  If your opponent has a central pawn defended by the queen, you should first move your c-pawn before developing your queenside knight to its natural square.  Playing  4.Nc3?  doesn't apply much pressure on the center as the pawn is already protected by Black's queen. So, you should first play  4.c4  and then develop the knight to its natural square.  This applies in the French Defense too, where you'd play @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/8/3p4/3P4/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.c4  .   Similarly, when playing Black in the Semi-Tarrasch, you'd opt for @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p4/2PP4/2N2N2/PP2PPPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 3 4@@EndFEN@@  4...c5  . }
