[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Repertoire Specific Rules"]
[Black "The Queen "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5
{ Let's delve into the Queen's role.  Generally, you avoid moving your queen too early as it's your most valuable piece, and opponents can gain tempos by attacking it.  So here you don't follow the first golden rule with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppp1ppp/8/4p3/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq e6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.d4  , because after  2...exd4  3.Qxd4  , Black gains a tempo by threatening your queen with  3...Nc6  .  However, remember that it doesn't necessarily mean that involving your queen early is always bad.  If you play @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppp1ppp/8/4p3/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq e6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  instead, and Black responds with  2...Nc6  , you can then play  3.d4  .  If Black captures with  3...exd4  , you can recapture with  4.Nxd4  not fearing  4...Nxd4  since after  5.Qxd4  .  Now, your queen stands strong in the center and can't be threatened by Black's knight.   So, the priority should be developing your knights and bishops first. However, don't be afraid to allow your opponent to activate your queen in situations where it doesn't boost their development. }
