[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Repertoire Specific Rules"]
[Black "Pawns Facing in the Center "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ General Guideline: Capture the opponent's pawn when pawns in the center attack each other     The center is the four squares in the middle of the board. When pawns face off in the center, you typically have three choices. You can capture the opponent's pawn, advance your own pawn, or defend your pawn.   I recommend capturing the opponent's pawn as your default move in this course. This is a straightforward approach and always a good choice for the recommended openings. This rule is used to simplify your decision-making process; it doesn't mean that the alternatives to advance or defend your pawn are always bad.   With two examples from the Scandinavian and French openings, I will show you that capturing the opponent's pawn is usually a strong move, whereas advancing or defending the pawn is only a strong move in some of the openings. So, capturing the opponent's pawn when pawns face each other in the center is a reliable strategy you can use to make decisions easier. }
1... d5
{ The Scandinavian Defense. Black challenges your pawn and in this case capturing is the only good option.   1...e6  2.d4  d5  In the French Defense all three options would be fine.  3.exd5  By capturing you keep the initiative and don't give Black time to place pawns in the center or develop.  3...exd5  4.c4  You can use the initiative to target the center on the next move.   3.e5  Advancing the pawn is also a sound alternative. This is because it keeps the light-squared bishop locked behind the e6-pawn.  3...c5  The downside is that you give Black the time to target your center.   3.Nc3  Defending the central pawn is also sound.  3...Bb4  Most likely Black will ask you on the next move again to make a decision what to do with the central pawn. Black pins the knight and threatens to capture the pawn. }
2. exd5
{ You capture the pawn.   2.e5?  Advancing the pawn would be a mistake.  2...c5  Black prevents you from supporting the pawn with d4 and can start attacking the far-advanced e5-pawn with ...Nc6 and ...Qc7.   2.Nc3?  Defending the pawn would also be wrong!  2...d4  Black chases away your knight from the natural square.  3.Nce2  e5  Black places the other pawn in the center and opened the diagonals for the bishop whereas your bishops are still stuck. }
2... Qxd5 { Black recaptures. } 3. Nc3
{ You develop the knight and gain a tempo on the queen. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Repertoire Specific Rules"]
[Black "Flank Pawns Facing Center Pawns"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/5n2/3p4/2PP4/8/PP3PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ When a pawn from outside the center targets a pawn in the center, a flank pawn is facing a central pawn.  General rule: Don't exchange flank pawns that target center pawns unless it allows you to accelerate your development or is necessary to continue your development.  In the first position, making the move @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/5n2/3p4/2PP4/8/PP3PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  5.cxd5?  would reduce the tension in the center, and Black can respond by capturing back with the knight,  5...Nxd5  .   However, there's an alternative: instead of trading pawns, you develop the knight with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/5n2/3p4/2PP4/8/PP3PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  5.Nc3  as usual. If Black decides to capture the c4-pawn with  5...dxc4  , it's the perfect opportunity to activate the bishop with  6.Bxc4  .   Now, let's look at the second scenario. Here, you are playing with Black, and trading the flank pawn for the center pawn allows you to speed up your development.  Consider capturing with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp3ppp/4pn2/2pp2B1/2PP4/2N2N2/PP2PPPP/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...cxd4  .  If White responds by recapturing with the knight  6.Nxd4  , then  6...e5  drives the knight back. On the other hand, if White chooses to recapture with the queen via  6.Qxd4  , you can play  6...Nc6  to gain a tempo on the queen.  In the third situation, you are a little stuck in terms of development. You are playing with the Black pieces in this example. If you prematurely play @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp3ppp/4p3/2p5/3PP3/2P2N2/P4PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Nc6  , White can opt for  8.d5  , chasing away your knight.  To prevent this, start by exchanging with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp3ppp/4p3/2p5/3PP3/2P2N2/P4PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...cxd4  8.cxd4  , then proceed with  8...Nc6  .  Now, if White attempts  9.d5  , it's not as effective because after a trade  9...exd5  10.exd5  , you can play  10...Qa5+  .  After  11.Bd2  , you have the move  11...Qxd5  , which allows you to win the pawn. Also,  10...Bb4+  11.Bd2  Qxd5  is possible to win the pawn. }
4. Nc3 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter for White - Open Games 1.e4 e5  "]
[Black "Scotch 4...Nxd4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 { Golden Rule Number One: place your pawns in the center. } 1... e5
{ Black is copying your strategy! } 2. Nf3
{ If you play  2.d4  , putting your other pawn in the center, Black would play  2...exd4  3.Qxd4  Nc6  and get ahead by attacking your queen. That's why the second golden rule is to develop and play  2.Nf3  , hitting the pawn. }
2... Nc6 { Black also makes a move and protects the pawn. } 3. d4
{ You're using Golden Rule Number One again, moving another pawn to the center. Your knight protects the pawn, so you don't need to move your queen out to take back the pawn.  After  3...exd4  4.Nxd4  Nxd4  5.Qxd4  , it is powerful for your queen to be out since Black has no knight to attack it with ...Nc6.  The most popular alternatives are @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Bc4  , the Italian Opening, or  3.Bb5  , the Ruy Lopez. These also follow the golden rules as you develop and get ready to castle.  The Scotch also leads to more open games, making getting all your pieces out easier. }
3... exd4 { Black should take your pawn, or else you could take theirs. } 4.
Nxd4
{ You take the pawn back. In the Scotch, this opens up space for your other bishop, letting you develop your bishops wherever you like and castle on either side. }
4... Nxd4
{ This move, taking your knight, is a usual mistake at the club level. It helps you by letting you get your queen active, but Black doesn't get anything in return. }
5. Qxd4 { Your queen is powerful in the center. } 5... d6
{ A popular move at the club level. Black opens a path for their light bishop and protects against your e5 attack, so they can safely develop their knight with ...Nf6.  You can punish  5...Nf6  brutally with the direct  6.e5!  Also after  5...Qf6  attacking the queen with  6.e5  is the best move. }
6. Nc3
{ As usual you develop the knights first and you prepare to castle on the queenside.  With the d-file semi-open, your rook will be immediately active after castling queenside. }
6... Nf6 7. Bf4
{ You develop the bishop, getting ready to castle on the queenside.   7.Bg5  would pin the knight, but it's not a big problem for Black as they can unpin with  7...Be7  .  Trading your bishop for their knight is bad, as after  8.Bxf6  Bxf6  , Black's bishop, becomes very active. }
7... Be7 { Black develops and prepares to castle. } 8. O-O-O
{ You follow the third golden rule and castle. Next, you want to play e5 and open up the d-file!  You have punished the @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/8/3NP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nxd4  mistake from Black in the most effective way by castling queenside quickly and having a powerful rook on the d-file which will open up soon. Study more about the line variation here }
