[White "Quickstarter for White - Open Games 1.e4 e5  "]
[Black "Scotch 4...Qh4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 { Golden Rule Number One: place your pawns in the center. } 1... e5
{ Black is copying your strategy! } 2. Nf3
{ If you play  2.d4  , putting your other pawn in the center, Black would play  2...exd4  3.Qxd4  Nc6  and get ahead by attacking your queen. That's why the second golden rule is to develop and play  2.Nf3  , hitting the pawn. }
2... Nc6 { Black also makes a move and protects the pawn. } 3. d4
{ You're using Golden Rule Number One again, moving another pawn to the center. Your knight protects the pawn, so you don't need to move your queen out to take back the pawn.  After  3...exd4  4.Nxd4  Nxd4  5.Qxd4  , it is powerful for your queen to be out since Black has no knight to attack it with ...Nc6.  The most popular alternatives are @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Bc4  , the Italian Opening, or  3.Bb5  , the Ruy Lopez. These also follow the golden rules as you develop and get ready to castle.  The Scotch also leads to more open games, making getting all your pieces out easier. }
3... exd4 { Black should take your pawn, or else you could take theirs. } 4.
Nxd4
{ You take the pawn back. In the Scotch, this opens up space for your other bishop, letting you develop your bishops wherever you like and castle on either side. }
4... Qh4
{ Black gets bold, bringing out the queen early! Whenever the queen goes out, you would like to remind White that the c7-pawn is undefended and go for the Nb5 idea, but this time, it's more complicated.  The direct  5.Nb5?  runs into  5...Bb4+  when after  6.Nb1c3?  Ba5  Black can solve Nxc7+ threat without giving up the castle rights.  Therefore, you apply a smart strategy first to develop with @@StartFEN@@r1b1kbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/8/3NP2q/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Nc3  Bb4  6.Be2  and Black can only justify the early queen development by grabbing the pawn with  6...Qxe4  , but now after  7.Ndb5  Black can no longer defend with  7...Ba5?  because Black's bishop needed to keep your knight pinned to safeguard the queen  8.Nxc7+  is now crushing, and  8...Bxc7  9.Nxe4  wins the queen. }
5. Nc3 { You move your knight to protect the pawn. } 5... Bb4
{ Black pins your knight, creating a threat with ...Qxe4! It's tough to guard the e4-pawn.  Also, swapping knights with  6.Nxc6?  doesn't work because Black will take your pawn with  6...Qxe4+  and only then capture the knight. So, you decide to let go of the pawn for a lead in development. }
6. Be2 { You develop the bishop, preparing to castle. } 6... Qxe4
{ Black takes your pawn, and threatens to win your knight. } 7. Nb5
{ You move your knight, threatening Nxc7+ to fork Black's king and rook. } 7...
Bxc3+
{ Black takes your knight. To keep the fork threat alive, you recapture with the pawn.  Don't worry about  7...Qxg2  , because you can respond with  8.Bf3  attacking the queen and still threatening Nxc7. }
8. bxc3
{ This is the key to counter the early @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/8/3NP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Qf6  and  4...Qh4  variations.  At this point, Black has to make a significant concession and play @@StartFEN@@r1b1k1nr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1N6/4q3/2P5/P1P1BPPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Kd8  when you will have a safe king after  9.O-O   Note that Black can't play @@StartFEN@@r1b1k1nr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1N6/4q3/2P5/P1P1BPPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Qxg2  as after  9.Bf3  you have a direct attack on the queen, and you are threatening the fork of the king and rook. }
