1. e4 { Golden Rule Number One: place your pawns in the center. } 1... e5
{ Black is copying your strategy! } 2. Nf3
{ If you play  2.d4  , putting your other pawn in the center, Black would play  2...exd4  3.Qxd4  Nc6  and get ahead by attacking your queen. That's why the second golden rule is to develop and play  2.Nf3  , hitting the pawn. }
2... Nc6 { Black also makes a move and protects the pawn. } 3. d4
{ You're using Golden Rule Number One again, moving another pawn to the center. Your knight protects the pawn, so you don't need to move your queen out to take back the pawn.  After  3...exd4  4.Nxd4  Nxd4  5.Qxd4  , it is powerful for your queen to be out since Black has no knight to attack it with ...Nc6.  The most popular alternatives are @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Bc4  , the Italian Opening, or  3.Bb5  , the Ruy Lopez. These also follow the golden rules as you develop and get ready to castle.  The Scotch also leads to more open games, making getting all your pieces out easier. }
3... exd4 { Black should take your pawn, or else you could take theirs. } 4.
Nxd4
{ You take the pawn back. In the Scotch, this opens up space for your other bishop, letting you develop your bishops wherever you like and castle on either side. }
4... Bc5
{ The classical mainline.  These days, the Schmidt variation with  4...Nf6  is becoming more popular, so these are the two most important moves to face. Black develops the bishop and attacks the knight! Good news: you can use the Pin Development Setup against both. }
5. Nb3
{ You counterattack the bishop!  Developing and defending with  5.Be3  is more common. However, when Black replies with  5...Qf6  , attacking the knight again, you need to play  6.c3  , which unfortunately takes away the natural square for the knight. To keep things simple, I like that in every opening, you can develop the knights to f3 and c3. }
5... Bb6 6. Nc3 Nf6 7. Bd3
{ You follow the development plan with the Pin Setup! This is only the fourth most popular move for White in this position.  After the direct  7.Bg5?  h6  8.Bh4  g5  9.Bg3  Exploiting the fact that you haven't castled yet, Black can create a pin with  9...Qe7  . You defend the pinned pawn with  10.Bd3  , but Black attacks the pawn again with  10...d5  . I would rather avoid that. }
7... d6 8. O-O { You first castle and are ready for the pin next! } 8... O-O 9.
Bg5
{ You reached the Pin Development Setup.  You are ready for Kh1 followed by f4 to keep the knight pinned and prevent plans to break free with ...h6-g5 }
9... h6 10. Bh4
{ You will keep the pin! When Black doesn't play ...g5 to unpin the knight, you have the plan Kh1 unpinning the f2-pawn followed by f4. Which prevents the ...g5 and keeps the knight stuck in the pin. Learn more about how to exploit this powerful pin here }
*

