5. Nb3
{ You counterattack the bishop!  Developing and defending with  5.Be3  is more common. However, when Black replies with  5...Qf6  , attacking the knight again, you need to play  6.c3  , which unfortunately takes away the natural square for the knight. To keep things simple, I like that in every opening, you can develop the knights to f3 and c3. }
5... Bb6 6. Nc3 { Your usual move! You always develop the knights first. } 6...
d6 7. Bd3
