1. e4 { Golden Rule Number One: place your pawns in the center. } 1... e5
{ Black is copying your strategy! } 2. Nf3
{ If you play  2.d4  , putting your other pawn in the center, Black would play  2...exd4  3.Qxd4  Nc6  and get ahead by attacking your queen. That's why the second golden rule is to develop and play  2.Nf3  , hitting the pawn. }
2... Nc6 { Black also makes a move and protects the pawn. } 3. d4
{ You're using Golden Rule Number One again, moving another pawn to the center. Your knight protects the pawn, so you don't need to move your queen out to take back the pawn.  After  3...exd4  4.Nxd4  Nxd4  5.Qxd4  , it is powerful for your queen to be out since Black has no knight to attack it with ...Nc6.  The most popular alternatives are @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Bc4  , the Italian Opening, or  3.Bb5  , the Ruy Lopez. These also follow the golden rules as you develop and get ready to castle.  The Scotch also leads to more open games, making getting all your pieces out easier. }
3... exd4 { Black should take your pawn, or else you could take theirs. } 4.
Nxd4
{ You take the pawn back. In the Scotch, this opens up space for your other bishop, letting you develop your bishops wherever you like and castle on either side. }
4... Nf6 { Black develops the knight and attacks the e4-pawn. } 5. Nc3
{ You develop and defend the e4-pawn. . } 5... Nxe4
{ A modern move, which is good to be aware of! Black doesn't just blunder the knight but wants to win your knight back with a pin. I expect this move will gain more popularity in the coming years. }
6. Nxe4 Qe7 { Black pins the knight. } 7. Bd3
{ You develop the bishop and get ready to castle. It's fine to sacrifice a pawn since Black's pieces are so misplaced.   7.f3  is another possibility but after  7...d5  Black attacks your pinned knight and will still win the piece back }
7... Nxd4 8. O-O
{ You immediately castle and get ready to annoy Black's queen on the e-file. In this main chapter, you will learn a plan that may seem surprising. There are variations where, after Re1, you will aim for Ng5-Nh7-Nxf8 and capture the currently inactive bishop. This is because bishops are much stronger in these open positions than knights.  Typically Black plays  8...d5  and after  9.Ng5  h6  10.Re1  Ne6  you are ready to catch the bishop with  11.Nh7 }
