Nxd4
{ You take the pawn back. In the Scotch, this opens up space for your other bishop, letting you develop your bishops wherever you like and castle on either side. }
4... Nf6 { Black develops the knight and attacks the e4-pawn. } 5. Nc3
{ You develop and defend the e4-pawn. . } 5... Bb4
{ Black pins the knight and threatens to capture the e4-pawn with ...Nxe4!  Therefore, you exchange knights @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pppp1ppp/2n2n2/8/1b1NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 3 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Nxc6  bxc6  first and then play  7.Bd3  . }
6. Nxc6 bxc6
{ After  6...dxc6  , you play  7.Qxd8+  trades the queens and breaks Black's right to castle. }
7. Bd3
{ You develop your piece and protect the e4-pawn.  When Black plays  7...Bxc3+?  , leading to  8.bxc3  , the resulting trade works in your favor. Despite ending up with doubled pawns, you gain an advantage. In an open position like this, your bishop becomes more powerful than the knight. The bishop's long-range capabilities make it a stronger piece than the knight in open positions. }
7... d5 { Black strikes back in the center and threatens to win a pawn. } 8.
exd5 { You always trade the pawns when the face off in the center. } 8... O-O
{ Black continues development and doesn't recapture the pawn. } 9. O-O
{ You also castle and safeguard your king.   9.dxc6?  would be risky since Black can attack with  9...Re8+ }
9... Bg4
{ Black develops and attacks the queen.  9...cxd5  10.Bg5  transposes back to the mainline, which you will study soon.  When Black plays in this fashion, it's clear that they are prepared. I found a way to ask Black some uncomfortable questions without taking the risk of getting into a worse position. }
10. Be2
{ You strategically block the attack with your bishop.  Playing  10.f3  is also possible but weakens your pawn structure and opens a diagonal towards your king, a vulnerability you want to avoid. }
10... Bxe2 11. Nxe2
{ You capture with the knight because after Black recaptures with  11...cxd5  and you pin with  12.Bg5  you can nicely use the knight in the attack with Nd4 next when you can aim for a fork on c6 or possibly switch to attack with Nf5. }
11... cxd5
{ Black could also play  12...Re8  trying to keep the tension in the center. You can't capture with  13.dxc6  because after  13...Qxd1  14.Rxd1  Rxe2  , you lose the knight.  Therefore, you can immediately create the pin with @@StartFEN@@r2qr1k1/p1p2ppp/2p2n2/3P4/1b6/8/PPP1NPPP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 1 12@@EndFEN@@  13.Bg5  when Black has to recapture with  13...cxd5  , and you transpose }
12. Bg5
{ You are pinning the knight as usual. Also you get ready for Nd4 threatening a fork with Nc6 and Qf3 which puts more pressure on the pinned knight. }
