1. e4 { Golden Rule Number One: place your pawns in the center. } 1... e5
{ Black is copying your strategy! } 2. Nf3
{ If you play  2.d4  , putting your other pawn in the center, Black would play  2...exd4  3.Qxd4  Nc6  and get ahead by attacking your queen. That's why the second golden rule is to develop and play  2.Nf3  , hitting the pawn. }
2... Nc6 { Black also makes a move and protects the pawn. } 3. d4
{ You're using Golden Rule Number One again, moving another pawn to the center. Your knight protects the pawn, so you don't need to move your queen out to take back the pawn.  After  3...exd4  4.Nxd4  Nxd4  5.Qxd4  , it is powerful for your queen to be out since Black has no knight to attack it with ...Nc6.  The most popular alternatives are @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Bc4  , the Italian Opening, or  3.Bb5  , the Ruy Lopez. These also follow the golden rules as you develop and get ready to castle.  The Scotch also leads to more open games, making getting all your pieces out easier. }
3... exd4 { Black should take your pawn, or else you could take theirs. } 4.
Nxd4
{ You take the pawn back. In the Scotch, this opens up space for your other bishop, letting you develop your bishops wherever you like and castle on either side. }
4... Nf6 { Black develops the knight and attacks the e4-pawn. } 5. Nc3
{ You develop and defend the e4-pawn. . } 5... Bb4
{ Black pins the knight and threatens to capture the e4 pawn with Nxe4! You want to defend the pawn with 6.Bd3, but this move would result in losing your knight due to 6...Nxd4. Therefore, the correct approach is to exchange knights first, and then play Bd3. This sequence allows you to safeguard your pawn without sacrificing your knight. }
6. Nxc6 bxc6
{ After  6...dxc6  , you play  7.Qxd8+  trades the queens and breaks Black's right to castle. }
7. Bd3
{ You develop your piece and protect the e4 pawn.  When Black plays  7...Bxc3+?  , leading to  8.bxc3  , the resulting trade works in your favor. Despite ending up with doubled pawns, you gain an advantage. In an open position like this, your bishop becomes more powerful than the knight. The bishop's long-range capabilities make it a stronger piece than the knight in open positions. }
7... d5
{ Black strikes back in the center. Black threatens 8...Bxc3 bxc3 9.dxe4, so you need to trade the pawns. }
8. exd5 { You trade the pawns. } 8... cxd5 9. O-O
{ You follow the third golden rule and castle. } 9... O-O
{ Black also finishes development and castles } 10. Bg5
{ You reach the Pin Development Setup. Black should be careful now and support the center. }
10... c6 { Black supports the d5-pawn. } 11. Qf3
{ When you are pinning you want to add attackers. } 11... Be7
{ This is the most popular move! Black drops the bishop back to unpin the knight. Now it's time to continue your attack. }
12. Qg3
{ Discovering this move opens up powerful attacking possibilities. One idea is to initiate a mating attack with Qh4, Additionally, the queen controls the b8-square, preventing Black from activating their rook there. Study more about this move here
  While you might appear to be setting up for a Bh6 Qxg7 tactic, it's usually not the ideal plan, as Black can defend effectively with ...Nh5 after Bh6.  A common move here is  12...Kh8  when you immediately reach a winning position with  13.Qh4  going for a mating attack.  After the main move @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/p3bppp/2p2n2/3p2B1/8/2NB2Q1/PPP2PPP/R4RK1 b - - 3 12@@EndFEN@@  12...Nh5  , you will surprise your opponent with  13.Bxe7  Qxe7  14.Qe3!  when after  14...Qxe3  15.fxe3  , you want to exchange your pawn with e4 to be the one who has the better pawn structure.  In the beginner version of your repertoire, I recommended @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/p3bppp/2p2n2/3p2B1/8/2NB1Q2/PPP2PPP/R4RK1 w - - 2 12@@EndFEN@@  12.h3  , which is still a solid move. However, after Black's common responses like  12...h6  13.Bh4  Be6  14.Ne2  Nd7  15.Bxe7  Qxe7  16.Nd4  Ne5  or plans involving  13...Rb8  14.b3  Rb4  15.Bg3  Bd6  , the game tends to balance out. These positions are approximately equal, and because many minor pieces are exchanged, applying significant pressure on your opponent can be challenging. }
