[White "Quickstarter for White - Open Games 1.e4 e5  "]
[Black "Stafford Gambit"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 { Golden Rule Number One: place your pawns in the center. } 1... e5
{ Black is copying your strategy! } 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ The Petrov Defense! This is a solid opening choice for Black, aiming to contest the center right from the beginning. Good news! I recommend a solution where you will often transpose back to the Scotch Opening. The advantage of this strategy is that you can stay within a familiar territory, avoiding the main lines of the Petrov Defense. }
3. Nc3
{ You develop the knight and defend your central pawn. This simple move will likely bring you back to the Scotch opening.   3.Nxe5  is the most played move when Black first kicks back your knight with  3...d6  4.Nf3  and then also wins your central pawn with  4...Nxe4   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppp1ppp/5n2/4p3/4P3/2N2N2/PPPP1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3.d4  is also an alternative which I am recommending in my Attacking Repertoire for Club Players. }
3... Bc5 { This move leaves Black central pawn hanging for free. } 4. Nxe5
{ You capture the pawn. } 4... Nc6
{ The Stafford Gambit! A hugely popular online opening advocated by Eric Rosen. You should not underestimate this objectively dubious, as it contains devilish tricks.  The position gets complicated after  5.Nxc6  dxc6  when Black aims for ...Ng4 and start targeting our king with all the pieces. You can defend with  6.h3  , but after  6...h5  , the natural development moves  7.Be2  and  7.Bc4  would still be wrong, and you would have to play more unnatural moves to secure your opening advantage.  I recommend an approach that's less complicated. You retreat the knight, not activating Black's queen and bishop and keeping the pawn up. Also, in the position after @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pppp1ppp/2n2n2/2b1N3/4P3/2N5/PPPP1PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Nxc6  dxc6  , you cannot play d4; you play e4 and d4 in every White opening in the repertoire. There is one exception where you play dxc3 here but never play d3. }
5. Nf3
{ This is a key move for getting a significant advantage against the Stafford Gambit without running into complications. Study more about how to further crush your opponent when they try this dubious opening here. }
