1. e4 { Golden Rule Number One: place your pawns in the center. } 1... e5
{ Black is copying your strategy! } 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ The Petrov Defense! This is a solid opening choice for Black, aiming to contest the center right from the beginning. Good news! I recommend a solution where you will often transpose back to the Scotch Opening. The advantage of this strategy is that you can stay within a familiar territory, avoiding the main lines of the Petrov Defense. }
3. Nc3
{ You develop the knight and defend your central pawn. This simple move will likely bring you back to the Scotch opening.   3.Nxe5  is the most played move when Black first kicks back your knight with  3...d6  4.Nf3  and then also wins your central pawn with  4...Nxe4   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppp1ppp/5n2/4p3/4P3/2N2N2/PPPP1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3.d4  is also an alternative which I am recommending in my Attacking Repertoire for Club Players. }
3... Bb4 4. Nxe5 O-O
{ Black quickly brings the king to safety. You should always be careful to prevent pins on the e-file. Therefore, developing and placing your bishop on the e-file is a good idea. }
5. Be2 { You close the e-file to prevent Black from harassing your king. } 5...
Re8 { Skewer on the knight and pawn. } 6. Ng4
{ A move that rarely has been played before. In the only game, Grandmaster Paravyan won against Grandmaster Injic. Learn how to take down your opponent with this surprising and unknown move.  The idea is that you would like to trade your knight because with  6.Nf3  , it's blocking a powerful square for your bishop, and after  6.Nd3  , when Black wins the pawn back with  6...Bxc3  7.dxc3  Nxe4  , your knight is also misplaced since it's blocking your queen on the d-file.  @@StartFEN@@rnbqr1k1/pppp1ppp/5n2/4N3/1b2P3/2N5/PPPPBPPP/R1BQK2R w KQ - 3 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Nd3  or  6.Nf3  are much more common and sound alternatives. }
