[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter for White - Sicilian "]
[Black "Sicilian: Pin variation"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5
{ This move marks the Sicilian Defense. Black does not put a pawn directly in the center but controls it instead with a flank pawn. }
2. Nf3
{ You play in the same fashion as in the Open Games after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...e5  2.Nf3  You develop the knight and control the center.  Wait to put your other pawn in the center with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...c5  2.d4  because after  2...cxd4  3.Qxd4  Black can develop with tempo and attack your queen with  3...Nc6  . }
2... e6
{ Black opens up the diagonal for the dark-squared bishop and controls the d5-square. }
3. d4 { The Open Sicilian. } 3... cxd4 4. Nxd4
{ You capture with the knight as usual! } 4... Nf6
{ Black develops and attacks your pawn. } 5. Nc3 Bb4
{ The Pin-Variation is the only exception to the Robust Development Setup and Knight Domination Setup. This move has fallen out of fashion because White has a clear way of punishing this dubious variation. So, pay attention; this line is different and requires some memorization. }
6. e5 { The knight has two squares to go now. Going back is not good. } 6...
Ne4
{ This leads to a well-known sequence, where White gets a large advantage.  Also you learn a common theme in the Sicilian that when the knight goes to e4 your queen wants to go to g4.   6...Nd5  is a better and more move for Black, and the idea is the same to go  7.Qg4  and counterattack the g7-pawn. }
7. Qg4 { Double attacking the knight and the g7-pawn. } 7... Nxc3
{ Black captures your knight and it may look like you are in trouble since you can't recapture. }
8. Qxg7
{ None of Black's checks with the knight helps as you can always play c3 attacking the rook on h8 and the bishop on b4 simultaneously. }
8... Rf8 9. a3
{ The move to remember is to chase the bishop away from the  b4  square, where it protects the rook on f8. This idea also occurs in other variations in the course. Black is busted now and you can study the continuations here.  After  9...Ba5  10.Bh6  Qe7  11.Nb3!  Black's bishop, knight, and rook are all under attack, and you have a crushing advantage. }
