[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter for White - Sicilian "]
[Black "Sicilian: Kan variation #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5
{ This move marks the Sicilian Defense. Black does not put a pawn directly in the center but controls it instead with a flank pawn. }
2. Nf3
{ You play in the same fashion as in the Open Games after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...e5  2.Nf3  You develop the knight and control the center.  Wait to put your other pawn in the center with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...c5  2.d4  because after  2...cxd4  3.Qxd4  Black can develop with tempo and attack your queen with  3...Nc6  . }
2... e6
{ Black opens up the diagonal for the dark-squared bishop and controls the d5-square. }
3. d4 { The Open Sicilian. } 3... cxd4 4. Nxd4
{ You capture with the knight as usual! } 4... a6
{ This is the Kan Sicilian, named after the Soviet international master Ilya Kan. Black is looking to play his pawn to b5 early on and without Nc6. }
5. Nc3
{ White develops his knights first and is ready to continue with the robust development setup Be2, O-O, Be3. }
5... b5
{ Black is gaining space on the queenside and prepares for ...Bb7 and ...b4. }
6. Be2 Bb7 7. O-O
{ You are not impressed with Black's threats and keep the Robust Development Setup. }
7... b4 { Black goes after the e4-pawn. } 8. Na4 Bxe4 9. Bf3
{ It's time to control the diagonal and target the rook in the corner. } 9...
Bxf3 10. Qxf3 d5
{ Black closes the center and stays a pawn up! It looks like Black is safe, but this is not the case. }
11. Re1 Nf6 12. Bg5 { And Black's position is shaky. } 12... Be7
{ Black develops the bishop and is ready to castle. When Black consolidates with a pawn-up, you have a bad position, so it's time to strike now. This move is played almost every time, although Black should go for  12...Nbd7  is what Black should go for. Study this line here. }
13. Bxf6
{ A strange-looking move! The idea is to have more dynamite to sacrifice on e6 and include the knight on a4 in the game. }
13... Bxf6 14. Nc5
{ A stunning move! You want to sacrifice a knight on e6. After  14.Nxe6  directly Black can still shelter behind the bishop  14...fxe6  15.Rxe6+  Kf7  You will have enough compensation for the sacrificed piece but no advantage.  So after @@StartFEN@@rn1qk2r/5ppp/p3pb2/3p4/Np1N4/5Q2/PPP2PPP/R3R1K1 w kq - 0 14@@EndFEN@@  14.Nc5  , you don't mind losing the knight with  14...Bxd4  since after  15.Nxe6  fxe6  16.Rxe6  , the king can't shelter behind the bishop, and  16...Kd7  17.Qxd5+  Kc7  18.Qxa8  is forced when White is significantly better. }
