{ Here you go for the most principled variation: the Open Sicilian. White aims for quick and active development of his pieces. You follow the first golden move rule and place your pawn in the center.  The difference is that after  3...cxd4  , you can recapture with the knight and play  4.Nxd4  .  You saw before why you didn't play @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.d4  because after  2...cxd4  3.Qxd4  Nc6  Black gained a tempo in development by attacking your queen. }
3... cxd4 { Black's best move is to capture the pawn. } 4. Nxd4
{ Here, you recapture with the knight.  You have opened the diagonals for both bishops. You can continue with Nc3, Be2, Be3, and castle kingside. }
4... Nf6 5. Nc3 { Defending the pawn and developing the other knight. } 5...
Nc6
{ This is the Classical Sicilian. Black gets his knight out quickly and attacks the d4 knight. Also, Black remains flexible with the rest of his pawns. }
6. Be2 { White can safely continue developing as before. } 6... e5
{ Black plays ...e5, so you switch to the Knight Domination Setup. } 7. Nf3
{ You go back to the natural square for the knight! } 7... h6
