[White "Quickstarter for White - Sicilian "]
[Black "Sicilian: Sveshnikov"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5
{ This move marks the Sicilian Defense. Black does not put a pawn directly in the center but controls it instead with a flank pawn. }
2. Nf3
{ You play in the same fashion as in the Open Games after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...e5  2.Nf3  You develop the knight and control the center.  Wait to put your other pawn in the center with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...c5  2.d4  because after  2...cxd4  3.Qxd4  Black can develop with tempo and attack your queen with  3...Nc6  . }
2... Nc6
{ Black develops the knight and remains flexible with his pawns for now. The most popular move at the beginner and Club player level, and the second most popular move at the top level. }
3. d4
{ The Open Sicilian. Many White players are scared to play Open Silician because they think it's a heavy theoretical battleground. Black has many setups, and you must learn how to play against all of them. This course will teach you that it's possible to do well in the open Sicilian without learning a massive amount of theory. You will use a robust development setup that works versus almost all Sicilians. }
3... cxd4 4. Nxd4 { You capture with the knight as usual } 4... Nf6 5. Nc3 e5
{ This is the Sveshnikov Sicilian, named after the Soviet grandmaster Evgeny Sveshnikov. The ideas are similar to the Kalashnikov variation. }
6. Ndb5
{ White jumps in with his knight, just like against the Kalashnikov Sicilian. }
6... d6 { Black prevents the b5-knight from jumping in. } 7. Bg5
{ White develops his bishop and pins the f6-knight. Your knights can become very threatening on b5 and d5. Black has to be careful now and can't just continue development. Next move, you will capture the knight. }
7... a6
{ A precise move! Black kicks back your knight before they continue development. }
8. Na3 { You retreat the knight! } 8... b5
{ Threatening a fork with ...b4 so you should move the knight. } 9. Nd5
{ Reaching Knight Domination and attacking the pinned knight on f6. } 9... Be7
{ Black develops and threatens to win a piece with @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/4bppp/p1np1n2/1p1Np1B1/4P3/N7/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 2 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Nxd5  when they open up the attack against our bishop and after  11.Bxe7  , their knight, can escape back to safety with  11...Ndxe7  . }
10. Bxf6
{ You eliminate the knight and keep our knight on a powerful outpost.  After  10...Bxf6  , we don't want to trade with  11.Nxf6  Qxf6!  Our knight is powerful on the outpost, and you want to keep it there. }
10... Bxf6 11. c3
{ You get ready to bring your knight back into the game with Nc2 and can play a4 next to undermine Black's pawns on the queenside and get your bishop to c4.  Don't play @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/5ppp/p1np1b2/1p1Np3/4P3/N7/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11.Be2  , it's the Knight Domination Setup, and your bishop belongs on c4. You want to get ready to support your dominating knight with your friends. }
11... O-O 12. Nc2 Bg5 13. a4 { The same plan! } 13... bxa4 14. Rxa4 a5
{ Black secures the pawn. } 15. Bc4
{ You develop the bishop and support the knight on the outpost. This line clearly shows the plan of the knight domination setup where your light-squared bishop belongs on c4! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter for White - French & Caro-Kann"]
[Black "French #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6
{ The French! The third most popular opening. A lot of White players don't like facing the French. This is because you can end up in a closed French pawn structure after  2.d4  d5  3.e5  or this structure from another move order.  Black will try to break down your center with  3...c5  followed by ... Nc6 ...Qb6 and feel comfortable in that pawn structure. What French players often dislike to face is the exchange variation. They often think that this variation is boring and drawish.  There is certainly ground for these claims. If you look in the database, a lot of games go something like: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq d6 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.exd5  exd5  4.Nf3  Nf6  5.Bd3  Bd6  6.O-O  O-O  7.Bg5  Bg4  8.c3  c6  9.Qc2  Qc7  , and in this symmetrical position, the percentage of games that ended in draw is enormous.  I recommend you play the French exchange ambitiously and with  3.exd5  exd5  4.c4  when the symmetrical pawn structure will disappear after a trade on c4. This way, you avoid the complex strategical French pawn structures and get an open battle with lightning-fast development and similar plans as in the Panov Attack versus the Caro-Kann. }
2. d4 d5 { Black strikes back in the center. } 3. exd5
{ You go for the exchange variation. You will play this against both the French and Caro-Kann. In both cases, you position where you can play for lightning-fast development and place your pieces on the natural squares.  There are three other main options against the French:  3.Nc3  the Classical variation.  3.Nd2  is the Tarrasch variation, and  3.e5  is the Advanced variation. You must usually be ready to play the typical closed French pawn structure with your pawn on e5. }
3... exd5 4. c4
{ You challenge Black's center before you develop the knights. You always want to develop the knight into natural squares with Nc3 and Nf3.  In this pawn structure, the knight would be poorly placed with a direct  4.Nc3  , since this knight can't put much pressure on the center with the pawn still on c2. You also propose a trade to an isolated pawn structure instead of a symmetrical pawn structure. The symmetrical pawn structure has a drawish reputation. }
4... Nf6
{ The main move! Black develops the knight to defend the central pawn. In this position, you follow the rule of developing the knights first. It's important to note that Black can play in different way, and start, for example, with  4...Nc6  or  4...Bb4+  instead. Usually, the position will transpose into each other since you start developing your knights first. You will return to a position you studied a few moves later. }
5. Nc3 { Development as usual, You develop the knight! } 5... Bb4
{ Black develops the bishop, pins the knight, and prepares to castle. } 6. Nf3
{ You develop the other knight. } 6... O-O
{ Black safeguards the king first and castles. At this point, it may feel like you are in a difficult situation since your king is still in the middle. What you would love in this opening is to get your light-squared bishop to the c4-square, where it is powerful. It would have been best if Black would take your pawn earlier, and you would have gone there in one go. But also, if you have to move it twice, getting there is still worth it. It's time to develop the bishop. }
7. Be2 { You develop the bishop and get ready to castle. } 7... dxc4
{ Black captures your pawn at the perfect moment. You need to move your bishop again to recapture the pawn. It's worth it because you get to the best square. }
8. Bxc4 { Bringing your bishop to a powerful position. } 8... Re8+
{ The most played move at the club level, but this is not dangerous. You can block the check and develop your last minor piece. }
9. Be3 Ng4 { Black starts attacking your bishop! A common mistake. } 10. Bxf7+
{ It's time to strike! You sacrifice the bishop to go for a double attack.   10.O-O  is an alternative. When Black can't win the pawn with  10...Nxe3  11.fxe3  Rxe3?  because now  12.Bxf7+  starts a devastating attack. }
10... Kxf7 11. Qb3+ { Forking the king and bishop. } 11... Be6 12. Qxb4
{ You win the bishop back and are a pawn up. Also, your king is much safer as you are ready to castle on the next move. }
*

