{ You challenge Black's center before you develop the knights. You always want to develop the knight into natural squares with Nc3 and Nf3.  In this pawn structure, the knight would be poorly placed with a direct  4.Nc3  , since this knight can't put much pressure on the center with the pawn still on c2. You also propose a trade to an isolated pawn structure instead of a symmetrical pawn structure. The symmetrical pawn structure has a drawish reputation. }
4... Nf6
{ The main move! Black develops the knight to defend the central pawn. In this position, you follow the rule of developing the knights first. It's important to note that Black can play in different way, and start, for example, with  4...Nc6  or  4...Bb4+  instead. Usually, the position will transpose into each other since you start developing your knights first. You will return to a position you studied a few moves later. }
5. Nc3 { Development as usual, You develop the knight! } 5... Bb4
{ Black develops the bishop, pins the knight, and prepares to castle. } 6. Nf3
{ You develop the other knight. } 6... O-O
{ Black safeguards the king first and castles. At this point, it may feel like you are in a difficult situation since your king is still in the middle. What you would love in this opening is to get your light-squared bishop to the c4-square, where it is powerful. It would have been best if Black would take your pawn earlier, and you would have gone there in one go. But also, if you have to move it twice, getting there is still worth it. It's time to develop the bishop. }
7. Be2 { You develop the bishop and get ready to castle. } 7... dxc4
{ Black captures your pawn at the perfect moment. You need to move your bishop again to recapture the pawn. It's worth it because you get to the best square. }
8. Bxc4 { Bringing your bishop to a powerful position. } 8... Bg4
{ Black develops and pins your knight. } 9. O-O { You castle! } 9... Nc6
{ Black develops the knight and attacks the central pawn.  After  9...Bxf3  10.Qxf3  Qxd4  Black captures your central pawn and attacks the bishop, but you strike back with  11.Qxb7  capturing the pawn and attacking the rook in the corner. }
10. Be3
{ You develop the bishop and defend your central pawn. Black can't win a pawn with  10...Bxf3  11.Qxf3  Nxd4  since you take the pawn with  12.Qxb7  and keep the bishop pair and a better pawn structure.  If Black instead plays @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/ppp2ppp/2n2n2/8/1bBP2b1/2N1BN2/PP3PPP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 4 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Re8  , you can punish them by targeting the f7-pawn with  11.Qb3   To have an idea of your goals this variation is illustrative, @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/ppp2ppp/2n2n2/8/1bBP2b1/2N1BN2/PP3PPP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 4 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Qd6  11.h3  Bh5  12.Be2  to break the pin  12...Rad8  13.Qb3  Rfe8  14.Ne5!  is a good example. A common theme is to give Black a weak piece on h5 after trading the bishop and now after  14...Nxe5  15.dxe5  Rxe5  16.Bxh5  Rxh5  17.Rad1  wins a piece since the queen is overloaded  17...Qe7  18.Rxd8+  Qxd8  19.Qxb4 }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter for White - French & Caro-Kann"]
[Black "French #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6
{ The French! The third most popular opening. A lot of White players don't like facing the French. This is because you can end up in a closed French pawn structure after  2.d4  d5  3.e5  or this structure from another move order.  Black will try to break down your center with  3...c5  followed by ... Nc6 ...Qb6 and feel comfortable in that pawn structure. What French players often dislike to face is the exchange variation. They often think that this variation is boring and drawish.  There is certainly ground for these claims. If you look in the database, a lot of games go something like: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq d6 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.exd5  exd5  4.Nf3  Nf6  5.Bd3  Bd6  6.O-O  O-O  7.Bg5  Bg4  8.c3  c6  9.Qc2  Qc7  , and in this symmetrical position, the percentage of games that ended in draw is enormous.  I recommend you play the French exchange ambitiously and with  3.exd5  exd5  4.c4  when the symmetrical pawn structure will disappear after a trade on c4. This way, you avoid the complex strategical French pawn structures and get an open battle with lightning-fast development and similar plans as in the Panov Attack versus the Caro-Kann. }
2. d4 d5 { Black strikes back in the center. } 3. exd5
{ You go for the exchange variation. You will play this against both the French and Caro-Kann. In both cases, you position where you can play for lightning-fast development and place your pieces on the natural squares.  There are three other main options against the French:  3.Nc3  the Classical variation.  3.Nd2  is the Tarrasch variation, and  3.e5  is the Advanced variation. You must usually be ready to play the typical closed French pawn structure with your pawn on e5. }
3... exd5 4. c4
{ You challenge Black's center before you develop the knights. You always want to develop the knight into natural squares with Nc3 and Nf3.  In this pawn structure, the knight would be poorly placed with a direct  4.Nc3  , since this knight can't put much pressure on the center with the pawn still on c2. You also propose a trade to an isolated pawn structure instead of a symmetrical pawn structure. The symmetrical pawn structure has a drawish reputation. }
4... Nf6
{ The main move! Black develops the knight to defend the central pawn. In this position, you follow the rule of developing the knights first. It's important to note that Black can play in different way, and start, for example, with  4...Nc6  or  4...Bb4+  instead. Usually, the position will transpose into each other since you start developing your knights first. You will return to a position you studied a few moves later. }
5. Nc3 { Development as usual, You develop the knight! } 5... Be7
{ Black develops the bishop and gets ready to castle. } 6. Nf3
{ You develop the other knight. } 6... O-O 7. Be2
{ You also develop and get ready to castle. You are fine giving up a tempo and moving the bishop twice to recapture the pawn on c4 since c4 is such a good square for your bishop. }
7... dxc4 { Black captures the pawn now that you move the bishop. } 8. Bxc4
{ You capture back and get the bishop to the powerful square. } 8... Bg4 9. Be3
{ You develop the bishop and defend the pawn.  Going for  9.O-O  first is a sound alternative. But it allows Black an extra option with  9...Bxf3  10.Qxf3  Qxd4  .  Developing the bishop first likely transposes to variations with O-O without allowing Black this extra option. }
9... Nbd7 10. h3
{ You start to get rid of the pin and want to place your knight in the center. }
10... Bh5 11. g4
{ You make sure your knight no longer be pinned. In other variations where Black played ...Bb4, you were aiming for an idea with Be2, Qb3, Ne5, but when you can no longer attack Black's dark-squared bishop, this makes less sense. }
11... Bg6 12. Ne5
{ You firmly place your knight in the center, and your idea will be to start trapping the light-squared bishop with h4, h5. Black is under severe pressure.  Black equally often plays @@StartFEN@@rn1q1rk1/ppp1bppp/5n2/8/2BP2b1/2N1BN2/PP3PPP/R2QK2R b KQ - 2 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Nc6  but also there after  10.O-O  your plan is similar to aim for h3-g4-Ne5 and to go after Black's weak light-squared bishop. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter for White - French & Caro-Kann"]
[Black "Caro-Kann #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 { The Caro-Kann opening. } 2. d4
{ You prioritize the first golden rule so also place your other pawn in the center. }
2... d5
{ The Caro-Kann is quite similar to the French. Black wants to strike back in the center on the second move with ...d5! As you know, you approach the opening in the same fashion as the French. }
3. exd5
{ The exchange variation! You keep the initiative and want to take down Black's pawns in the center. }
3... cxd5 4. c4
{ Like against the French opening, you immediately continue to put pressure on the center. You want to play your c-pawn in this structure before developing the knight with Nc3. If you would develop the knight first, it cannot put much pressure on Black's central pawn. In the first couple of moves, you opened the diagonals for your bishops and queen. You know the plan already from other openings! The first step is to start developing the knights. }
4... Nf6 5. Nc3
{ As usual, you develop the knight! When Black still has a pawn on d5, you develop this knight first to attack in the center. }
5... e6
{ You can also get the same position after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/3p4/2PP4/8/PP3PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq c3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...e6  5.Nc3  Nf6 }
6. c5
{ A very interesting idea that hasn't been played much. It's uncommon that you already play another pawn move at this point, but you want to shut down Black's dark-squared bishop and, as quickly as possible, play Bb5+ and trade your light-squared bishop.   6.Nf3  is much more popular, but if you play like in the French with  6...Be7  7.Bd3  dxc4  8.Bxc4  , you also spent two tempos to get here, but now that Black's pawn on e6 is blocking your bishop, the bishop is not as strong. This would still be a playable option, but I would suggest an alternative approach. I call this structure the Bishop Shutdown Structure, as you make it difficult for Black to activate the bishops. }
6... b6 { Black immediately to get rid of you c5-pawn. } 7. b4
{ You support the pawn! It's important to hold on to the d4 and c5-pawns and keep this better structure that restricts Black. }
7... a5
{ A logical and thematic move undermining the pawn structure. You cannot defend this pawn with your a-pawn because  8.a3?  axb4  9.axb4  drops the rook  9...Rxa1   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/p4ppp/1p2pn2/2Pp4/1P1P4/2N5/P4PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq b3 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Be7  is also possible and transposes to the variation after  8.Nf3  O-O  9.Rb1  , you are back in the mainline, which you will learn later in this chapter. }
8. Na4
{ You get a strong counterattack on the b6-pawn. This is why it doesn't work for Black to break down your strong pawn structure immediately. Study more about these lines from here.  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/5ppp/1p2pn2/p1Pp4/NP1P4/8/P4PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8...bxc5  9.bxc5  keeps your fantastic pawn structure.  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/5ppp/1p2pn2/p1Pp4/NP1P4/8/P4PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8...axb4  9.Nxb6  gives you an outpost for the knight, and Black keeps a weak b4-pawn  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/5ppp/1p2pn2/p1Pp4/NP1P4/8/P4PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Nfd7  runs into the pin with  9.Bb5 }
*

