[White "Quickstarter for White - French & Caro-Kann"]
[Black "Caro-Kann #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 { The Caro-Kann opening. } 2. d4
{ You prioritize the first golden rule so also place your other pawn in the center. }
2... d5
{ The Caro-Kann is quite similar to the French. Black wants to strike back in the center on the second move with ...d5! As you know, you approach the opening in the same fashion as the French. }
3. exd5
{ The exchange variation! You keep the initiative and want to take down Black's pawns in the center. }
3... cxd5 4. c4
{ Like against the French opening, you immediately continue to put pressure on the center. You want to play your c-pawn in this structure before developing the knight with Nc3. If you would develop the knight first, it cannot put much pressure on Black's central pawn. In the first couple of moves, you opened the diagonals for your bishops and queen. You know the plan already from other openings! The first step is to start developing the knights. }
4... Nf6 5. Nc3
{ As usual, you develop the knight! When Black still has a pawn on d5, you develop this knight first to attack in the center. }
5... e6
{ You can also get the same position after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/3p4/2PP4/8/PP3PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq c3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...e6  5.Nc3  Nf6 }
6. c5
{ A very interesting idea that hasn't been played much. It's uncommon that you already play another pawn move at this point, but you want to shut down Black's dark-squared bishop and, as quickly as possible, play Bb5+ and trade your light-squared bishop.   6.Nf3  is much more popular, but if you play like in the French with  6...Be7  7.Bd3  dxc4  8.Bxc4  , you also spent two tempos to get here, but now that Black's pawn on e6 is blocking your bishop, the bishop is not as strong. This would still be a playable option, but I would suggest an alternative approach. I call this structure the Bishop Shutdown Structure, as you make it difficult for Black to activate the bishops. }
6... Be7
{ The best move for Black! Black should make sure to castle as quickly as possible and then start undermining your pawns. At first, it may seem hard to understand why Black would have to castle so quickly, but it's because of a deep tactical idea that is shown in the variation here. }
7. Nf3 O-O
{ By castling, Black prepares for their standard pawnbreak with ...b6 and ...a5! You need to anticipate it. }
8. Rb1
{ This is only the move number either in popularity and likely your opponent has never seen this before. It has been played by Grandmaster Jobava who is known for his original play.  The idea is straightforward: you want to keep your pawn construction that shuts down the dark-squared bishop and anticipate that Black will try to take it down.  Now, after  8...b6  , you can defend with  9.b4  , and after  10...a5  , you can defend with  11.a3  because after  11...axb4  12.axb4  , your rook is no longer hanging. }
