[White "Quickstarter for White - French & Caro-Kann"]
[Black "Caro-Kann #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 { The Caro-Kann opening. } 2. d4
{ You prioritize the first golden rule so also place your other pawn in the center. }
2... d5
{ The Caro-Kann is quite similar to the French. Black wants to strike back in the center on the second move with ...d5! As you know, you approach the opening in the same fashion as the French. }
3. exd5
{ The exchange variation! You keep the initiative and want to take down Black's pawns in the center. }
3... cxd5 4. c4
{ Like against the French opening, you immediately continue to put pressure on the center. You want to play your c-pawn in this structure before developing the knight with Nc3. If you would develop the knight first, it cannot put much pressure on Black's central pawn. In the first couple of moves, you opened the diagonals for your bishops and queen. You know the plan already from other openings! The first step is to start developing the knights. }
4... Nf6 5. Nc3
{ As usual, you develop the knight! When Black still has a pawn on d5, you develop this knight first to attack in the center. }
5... Nc6 6. Nf3 Bg4 { Black develops the bishop and pins your knight. } 7. cxd5
{ You also capture the pawn and open up the diagonal for your bishop. In the Beginner version of the course, I recommended  7.Bg5  , which is also a good move. I changed my mind after seeing the game between top GMs Jorden Van Foreest and Vincent Keymer, where Black got completely crushed. }
7... Nxd5 8. Qb3
{ You attack again and increase the pressure on the knight and b7-pawn. } 8...
Bxf3 9. gxf3 e6
{ Black supports the knight  9...Nb6  10.d5  Nd4  transposes to the variation you learned with  11.Bb5+ }
10. Qxb7 { You capture the pawn and target the knight. } 10... Nxd4
{ Black fights back to capture your pawn in the center. The knight is threatening some forks now so it's time to attack with your bishop. }
11. Bb5+ { You attack on the light-squares. } 11... Nxb5
{ Black has to eliminate the knight. } 12. Qc6+
{ A cunning check that forces Black to misplace the queen.  After  12.Qxb5+  Qd7  13.Qxd7+  Kxd7  14.Nxd5  exd5  Black is doing fine in the endgame. }
12... Ke7
{ Black's only move as  12...Qd7?  Would allow  13.Qxa8+  when you win the rook with a check. }
13. Qc5+
{ It's time to surprise your opponent now.  13.Qxb5  is the most popular move, but I feel that Black is generally better prepared against this, and it's also less challenging for Black. The main variation with  13...Qd7  14.Nxd5+  Qxd5  15.Qxd5  exd5  leads to an equal endgame that would make it difficult to crush your opponent in the opening phase. }
13... Nd6 { Black's best move is to block with the knight. } 14. Nxd5+
{ You capture the knight to open the d-file. } 14... exd5 15. Qxd5
{ A fantastic move! You are a piece down but look at Black's king, which stands there unsafe on an open but blocking in its bishop. You want to continue with O-O and Bf4, and get your rooks involved to target the king with all your pieces. Make sure to study all the lines in the Caro-Kann chapter to crush the Caro-Kann.   15.O-O  has been played much more, so Black likely won't expect this. Black got crushed in the top GM battle between Van Foreest and Keymer. }
