1. e4 d5
{ The Scandinavian opening. Black directly strikes back in the center. As explained in the pawn structure sheet here, capturing the pawn is the only good option. You lure Black's queen forward to gain a tempo in development. }
2. exd5 Nf6
{ Black doesn't capture the pawn back yet but attacks it with the knight instead. }
3. c4 { You defend the pawn! } 3... e6
{ Black challenges your central pawn and wants to lead development after  4.dxe6  Bxe6  when placing a pawn in the center can be problematic with  5.d4  since after  5...Bb4+  6.Nc3  Black can increase the pressure on your pinned knight with  6...Ne4 }
4. d4
{ You refuse the pawn sacrifice and place your pawn in the center.  And after  4...exd5  , you go back to the French opening. }
