1. e4 d5
{ The Scandinavian opening. Black directly strikes back in the center. As explained in the pawn structure sheet here, capturing the pawn is the only good option. You lure Black's queen forward to gain a tempo in development. }
2. exd5 Qxd5 { Black's queen recaptures } 3. Nc3
{ You develop the knight and gain a tempo on the queen. This strategy is in line with the logic that after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  you don't play  2.d4  because Black trades with  2...cxd4  3.Qxd4  and then gains the tempo on your queen with  3...Nc6 }
3... Qa5 4. d4 { The standard move placing your pawn in the center. } 4... Nf6
5. Nf3 { You develop the knight as usual. } 5... Bg4
{ Black pins your knight! } 6. h3
{ Your standard response in the Scandinavian, immediately attacking the bishop. }
6... Bh5
{ The bishop keeps the pin.  The trade with  6...Bxf3  7.Qxf3  is good for you, and after  7...c6  8.Bd2  , you are ready to castle queenside. }
7. g4 Bg6 8. Ne5
{ Next, you are ready to develop the bishop! In the Scandinavian structure usually Black's position is solid except for one issue, the light-squared bishop. You will aim to harass that bishop and want to trap it with h4, h5, or f4, f5. }
