[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter for White - Scandinavian and Sidelines"]
[Black "Scandinavian #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5
{ The Scandinavian opening. Black directly strikes back in the center. As explained in the pawn structure sheet here, capturing the pawn is the only good option. You lure Black's queen forward to gain a tempo in development. }
2. exd5 Qxd5 { Black's queen recaptures } 3. Nc3
{ You develop the knight and gain a tempo on the queen. This strategy is in line with the logic that after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  you don't play  2.d4  because Black trades with  2...cxd4  3.Qxd4  and then gains the tempo on your queen with  3...Nc6 }
3... Qa5 4. d4 { The standard move placing your pawn in the center. } 4... Nf6
5. Nf3 { You develop the knight as usual. } 5... Bf5 6. Ne5
{ In this structure, the e5-square practically functions as an outpost for the knight. Black will never chase away your knight with ...f6. Also, you make it difficult for Black to continue development, as you will see now. Developing one of your bishops may feel more natural, but they don't have such good squares yet.  Whenever Black doesn't pin your knight yet, you place the knight in the center, so @@StartFEN@@rnb1kb1r/ppp1pppp/5n2/q7/3P4/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...c6  , you play  6.Ne5  and the variations can transpose into each other. }
6... c6 7. Bc4 { You develop and attack the f7-pawn. } 7... e6
{ Black has to block the attack. } 8. g4
{ You start harassing Black's bishop. } 8... Bg6
{ Black's bishop should instead drop back. } 9. h4
{ You threaten to trap the bishop with h5 next move. } 9... Nbd7
{ Black must challenge your knight in the center. } 10. Nxd7
{ You capture the knight. } 10... Nxd7 11. h5
{ You continue with the plan to trap the bishop. } 11... Be4 12. O-O
{ Whenever your rook is attacked your castle. } 12... Bd5 13. Nxd5
{ Now that you no longer have ideas with a sacrifice on f7, you capture with your knight.   13.Bxd5?  cxd5  would leave your knight on c3 misplaced. }
13... cxd5 14. Bd3
{ You drop back with the bishop. You now have the bishop pair and you want to keep the pawn structure closed on the kingside so that Black can't attack and start putting pressure on the queenside with a4, c3 }
