[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter for White - Scandinavian and Sidelines"]
[Black "Alekhine Defense"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ Get ready to tackle the sidelines! What's going to be super helpful here is everything you've learned from the course. It's good to get your pawns in the middle. Remember, you usually develop the knights first, and hunting your opponents' knights can be smart. Sometimes, you'll play against opponents who don't know their openings well and do something offbeat. If that happens, stay calm. Use the concepts you've learned to take advantage of their unusual start. }
1... Nf6 2. e5 { You hunt the knight! A concept you have seen before. } 2...
Nd5 3. c4
{ You strengthen your center and chase the knight again.  Placing your other pawn in the center with  3.d4  is equally good and will likely result in the same position after  3...d6  4.c4 }
3... Nb6 { The knight jumps back! } 4. d4
{ You place your other pawn in the center.  Kicking the knight again with  4.c5?  is not useful. The knight returns to a central position with  4...Nd5  , and your c-pawn can become weak when it's too far advanced. }
4... d6 { Black attacks your central pawn. } 5. exd6
{ You trade the pawns!  Supporting the center with  5.f4  is an alternative, but in this case, after  5...dxe5  6.fxe5  Nc6  , the standard plan was to develop the knights first with  7.Nf3  works less well as you immediately get pinned with  7...Bg4!  That's why, in this variation,  7.Be3  first is a better move. }
5... cxd6
{ Black can also go for  5...exd6  , but this doesn't change your plan much. The game could continue with  6.Nf3  Be7  7.Nc3  , and you want to develop the bishops on e2 and e3 and play h3 to prevent Black from playing ...Bg4 }
6. Nf3 g6 7. Nc3
{ You develop the other knight. In this position, your bishops are well placed on e2 and e3. Black's light-squared bishop wants to pin your knight on g4, so it's a good idea to play h3 to prevent that or to chase away the bishop. If your opponent played an offbeat sideline, which is not covert in the course, you can use the concepts you've learned to take advantage. }
7... Bg7 8. h3 { You want to avoid getting pinned later. } 8... O-O 9. Bg5
{ You develop the bishop and pin the e5-pawn. In all sidelines, Black's strategy typically is to give you the center and apply pressure with a strong fianchetto bishop. One good way to deal with this is to quickly get all the pieces away from the long diagonal with the dark-square bishop, and that's also something you can opt for here with Qd2, d5, b3, and Rc1. }
*

