[White "Quickstarter for White - Scandinavian and Sidelines"]
[Black "Owen Defense"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ Get ready to tackle the sidelines! What's going to be super helpful here is everything you've learned from the course. It's good to get your pawns in the middle. Remember, you usually develop the knights first, and hunting your opponents' knights can be smart. Sometimes, you'll play against opponents who don't know their openings well and do something offbeat. If that happens, stay calm. Use the concepts you've learned to take advantage of their unusual start. }
1... b6 { Black aims to attack from the flank. } 2. d4 { The common strategy! }
2... Bb7 3. Nc3 { You develop the knight and defend the central pawn. } 3... e6
{ Black gets ready to pin your knight. This is nothing to be worried about. }
4. Nf3 { You develop the other knight. } 4... Bb4
{ Black pins your knight! This means that Black threatens to capture your central pawn on e4 on the next move. }
5. Bd3 { You develop and defend the pawn. } 5... Nf6 6. e5
{ You start hunting the knight!   6.Qe2  is an alternative, and also  6.Nd2  is a cunning move to break the pin and defend the e4-pawn. }
6... Ne4
{ The knight goes towards the center and puts pressure on your pinned knight. You are happy to sacrifice the pawn. }
7. O-O { You follow the golden rule to castle and unpin the knight. } 7... Nxc3
8. bxc3 Bxc3 { Black wins the pawn, but the bishop can be in trouble on c3. }
9. Rb1
{ You sidestep with the rook. Black is in a difficult situation now.  Study the lines further from here.  9...O-O?  already runs into the famous Greek Gift tactic  10.Bxh7 }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter for White - Scandinavian and Sidelines"]
[Black "Pirc Defense"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ Get ready to tackle the sidelines! What's going to be super helpful here is everything you've learned from the course. It's good to get your pawns in the middle. Remember, you usually develop the knights first, and hunting your opponents' knights can be smart. Sometimes, you'll play against opponents who don't know their openings well and do something offbeat. If that happens, stay calm. Use the concepts you've learned to take advantage of their unusual start. }
1... d6 2. d4
{ You follow the first golden rule and place the other pawn in the center. }
2... Nf6 3. Nc3
{ You develop your knight and defend the pawn.  It would be wrong to hunt the knight now with  3.e5?  since after  3...dxe5  4.dxe5  , Black can trade queens and break your right to castle with  4...Qxd1+  5.Kxd1  , and also fork your two pawns with  6...Ng4 }
3... g6
{ The Pirc opening. Black hasn't tried to put pressure on your center yet. } 4.
Nf3 { You follow the standard plan and develop the knights first, as usual. }
4... Bg7 5. Bg5
{ Only the fifth most popular move in the position, but one that fits the style to start the direct battle.  You would like to start hunting Black's knight with e5, but to prepare for that, you first want to connect your rook and queen.  5.e5?  is bad because after  5...dxe5  6.dxe5  Qxd1+  you have to make a sad choice to either retreat your knight back or capture with your king and give up your right to castle.  After @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Bg5  O-O  6.e5  it's a very different story because now after  6...dxe5  7.dxe5  Qxd1+  , you are very happy to play  8.Rxd1  and control the d-file with your rook. }
5... O-O
{ When Black castles, you can go for your plan!   5...h6  is not dangerous, and it will weaken the h6-pawn after  6.Bf4  O-O  7.Qd2  Black should play  7...Kh7  will not further weaken the pawns after  8.O-O-O  You have a lead in development and would like to play h3 and g4, taking away important squares for Black's pieces to start an attack. }
6. e5 { You go for the plan and chase the knight away. } 6... dxe5
{ Trading the pawn is the most popular and also the best move for Black. } 7.
dxe5 { You continue putting pressure on the knight. } 7... Qxd1+
{ Trading the queens is too dangerous for Black as it allows you rook to control the open d-file. Also, Black now loses control of the c7-pawn, which the queen previously defended. }
8. Rxd1
{ That's why you develop your dark-squared bishop! Capturing back with the knight or king would, of course, be horrible. Your rook now nicely controls the open d-file. }
8... Ng4
{ Black goes after the e5-pawn.  Black also has another options here but after  8...Nfd7  , you can reply in the same fashion with  9.Nd5 }
9. Nd5 { You go after both the c7 and e7-pawns and threaten to trap the rook. }
