[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter for Black vs. Italian and Ruy Lopez "]
[Black "Four Knights Italian: 4.Nc3 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 { Overwhelmingly the most popular move at the club player level. } 1...
e5
{ Prepare to begin with the Black pieces. Even though you haven't learned any moves from the Black side yet, you already understand the concepts from studying the moves from the White side. The principles of the opening stay the same. Your priority is controlling the center with pawns, and you do that from your first move. }
2. Nf3 { White develops and attacks your central pawn! } 2... Nc6
{ It's time to develop and defend the pawn. } 3. Bc4
{ This is the Italian Game, a very popular choice at the beginner level. White plans to castle quickly and points the bishop towards your f7-pawn. }
3... Nf6
{ Applying what you've learned, you start by developing your knights before moving on to your bishops. }
4. Nc3
{ White develops the other knight. A common move at the Beginner level. } 4...
Nxe4
{ You are going for a tactic! You don't give up the knight for free. After White captures you, you can place your pawn in the center with a fork to regain the piece. Usually, when White goes for this, they are not too well-prepared, so you learn some fascinating variations and develop tactics to take your opponent down early on. }
5. Nxe4 d5 { Forking the bishop and knight } 6. Bd3
{ The best move for White keeping the bishop alive. } 6... dxe4
{ You capture the knight. } 7. Bxe4 Bd6
{ You develop the bishop, defend your central pawn, and prepare to castle. With a pawn in the center, you have a comfortable position. }
8. O-O O-O 9. Re1
{ The only good move for White since the direct  9.c3  allows you to attack with immediately  9...f5  and get a good position. }
9... Bg4
{ You continue to pin the knight! Pinning the knight is only something you usually want to do when you can add an attacker. And you can do that with ...f5-e4! You can consider starting with ... Kh8 to prevent any bishops check when you go for the attack. }
10. h3 { White somehow has to deal with pin, so attacks your bishop. } 10...
Bh5 { You keep the pin! } 11. g4 f5
{ It's a fascinating and crushing move that has rarely been played! And even in a top GM game between So and Mamedyarov, Mamedyarov missed the chance to play this brilliant move. You will sacrifice your knight, but it will be more than worth it as your pin becomes deadly, and White's king will become even more vulnerable.  Make sure to study this in more detail: The next moves are forced  12.Bxc6  fxg4  13.hxg4  Bxg4  when you have such a powerful pin that you will win the piece back and keep an advantage because of White's weak king. }
