[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter for Black vs. Italian and Ruy Lopez "]
[Black "Italian Knight Attack: 4.Ng5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 { Overwhelmingly the most popular move at the club player level. } 1...
e5
{ Prepare to begin with the Black pieces. Even though you haven't learned any moves from the Black side yet, you already understand the concepts from studying the moves from the White side. The principles of the opening stay the same. Your priority is controlling the center with pawns, and you do that from your first move. }
2. Nf3 { White develops and attacks your central pawn! } 2... Nc6
{ It's time to develop and defend the pawn. } 3. Bc4
{ This is the Italian Game, a very popular choice at the beginner level. White plans to castle quickly and points the bishop towards your f7-pawn. }
3... Nf6
{ Applying what you've learned, you start by developing your knights before moving on to your bishops. }
4. Ng5
{ White directly targets your f7-pawn, aiming for a potential fork on your queen and rook. Your next move should block the bishop's diagonal to prevent White's plans. }
4... d5 { You block the bishop's diagonal to secure the f7-pawn. } 5. exd5
{ White has taken the pawn. Recapturing at this point could be risky, as it would reactivate White's strong bishop on the light squares. }
5... Na5
{ You aim at the light-squared bishop. You shouldn't play  5...Nxd5  as this could lead to  6.Nxf7  Kxf7  7.Qf3+  , where White forks your king and knight.  In my 'Attacking Repertoire for Club Players for Black' course, I suggest @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/ppp2ppp/2n2n2/3Pp1N1/2B5/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...b5  , a move to counterattack the bishop. If  6.Bxb5  is played, then  6...Qxd5  forks the bishop and pawn. Both  5...b5  and  5...Na5  offers good opportunities for Black. While  5...b5  can likely be an option that surprises your opponent more  5...Na5  is a more professional approach as it doesn't give White a slight objective edge }
6. Bb5+
{ White relocates the bishop and delivers a check! Other moves aren't great, as guarding the bishop doesn't protect White's central pawn.  For instance,  6.Qe2  lets you take the strong bishop  6...Nxc4  7.Qxc4  , and then take back the central pawn with  7...Qxd5 }
6... c6
{ You start harassing the bishop!   6...Bd7  is a possible alternative. A trade of bishops would be good for you, but after  7.Qe2  , White can back up the bishop and has a strong chance for an opening advantage. }
7. dxc6 bxc6 { You capture back with the pawn and attack the bishop again. } 8.
Qf3
{ White develops and pins the c6-pawn.  When White plays  8.Qf3  or  8.Bd3  and supports the e4-square, you don't go for  8...h6  because now with  9.Ne4  the knight has a good square. }
8... Be7
{ At this point, remember that White poses no immediate threats. White's light-squared bishop is a powerful piece, and if White captures your pawn next; you will have the opportunity to exchange it for your knight at the cost of a pawn. This is a good trade for you. So, there's no need to protect the c6-pawn.  Playing  8...h6!?  to push away the knight is useful only when you force the knight to a less advantageous square. Now, the knight can move to the center with  9.Ne4  , and this doesn't mean you can take the bishop freely with  9...cxb5  because White can use a discovered attack with  10.Nxf6+  gxf6  11.Qxa8  and capture your rook in the corner. }
9. Bd3 O-O
{ You castle. Next, you plan to activate your rook with ...Rb8-Rb4 when you are controlling an important rank and can start harassing White's misplaced knight. }
10. Nc3 Rb8
{ You are going for a cunning plan! You want to swing over the rook with ...Rb4.  This both aims to trap White's g5-knight as well as to setup a potential attack against White's king.  10...h6  is a common alternative but I prefer to wait with hunting this knight until you have the rook involved. }
