1. e4 { Overwhelmingly the most popular move at the club player level. } 1...
e5
{ Prepare to begin with the Black pieces. Even though you haven't learned any moves from the Black side yet, you already understand the concepts from studying the moves from the White side. The principles of the opening stay the same. Your priority is controlling the center with pawns, and you do that from your first move. }
2. Nf3 { White develops and attacks your central pawn! } 2... Nc6
{ It's time to develop and defend the pawn. } 3. Bc4
{ This is the Italian Game, a very popular choice at the beginner level. White plans to castle quickly and points the bishop towards your f7-pawn. }
3... Nf6
{ Applying what you've learned, you start by developing your knights before moving on to your bishops. }
4. d3 { This is a slower move that White often plays to support the pawn. }
4... Bc5
{ You develop the bishop as usual!   4...Be7  is a sound alternative. } 5. O-O
O-O
{ In this position, White can play a lot of moves that do not involve the c3 move for White. This makes it harder to go for the Pin setup in certain cases. }
6. Bg5 { The most played move other than c3. } 6... h6 7. Bh4 Be7
{ Introducing: The anti-pin setup! An idea that many top Grandmasters implemented to solve the problem of the pin. The idea is to solve the pin on your knight by moving the bishop back. This ensures you don't have to weaken your position with ...g5.  Therefore, moving the dark-squared bishop twice is warranted! @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pppp1pp1/2n2n1p/2b1p3/2B1P2B/3P1N2/PPP2PPP/RN1Q1RK1 b - - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7...d6  is an alternative but after  8.c3  White keeps the pin on your knight and playing ...g5 could be risky to break the pin. On the other hand, it would also be annoying if your knight stays pinned. }
8. Nc3 { White put the knight towards the center. } 8... d6 9. a4
{ To prevent you from grabbing the bishop pair with ...Na5! This move has rarely been played, but it is the best move.  This move is similar to  9.a3  .  There, you can reply in the same way. }
9... Nh5
{ You opt for your ... Nh5 plan to start an offensive on the kingside. After the trade of bishops, it's both possible to opt for the offensive and go for ...Kh8 and ...f5 or you could also play in a calmer fashion and bring your knight back! }
