[White "Quickstarter for Black vs. Italian and Ruy Lopez "]
[Black "Italian Giuoco Pianissimo: 4.d3 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 { Overwhelmingly the most popular move at the club player level. } 1...
e5
{ Prepare to begin with the Black pieces. Even though you haven't learned any moves from the Black side yet, you already understand the concepts from studying the moves from the White side. The principles of the opening stay the same. Your priority is controlling the center with pawns, and you do that from your first move. }
2. Nf3 { White develops and attacks your central pawn! } 2... Nc6
{ It's time to develop and defend the pawn. } 3. Bc4
{ This is the Italian Game, a very popular choice at the beginner level. White plans to castle quickly and points the bishop towards your f7-pawn. }
3... Nf6
{ Applying what you've learned, you start by developing your knights before moving on to your bishops. }
4. d3 { This is a slower move that White often plays to support the pawn. }
4... Bc5
{ You develop the bishop as usual!   4...Be7  is a sound alternative. } 5. c3
{ The slow Italian or Giuoco Pianissimo. } 5... O-O
{ You castle!  Don't rush with  5...d5?  here since after  6.exd5  Nxd5  7.Qb3  , you have an issue since your knight, f7-pawn, and b7-pawn are under attack. }
6. O-O d5
{ When you get the chance you like to place your pawn in the center instead of going for a more passive  6...d6 }
7. exd5 { White needs to trade on d5. } 7... Nxd5 8. Re1
{ White attacks the e5-pawn twice. } 8... Bg4
{ Pinning the knight on f3. White can still win the pawn on e5, but you will make sure that White has to open his whole kingside for this to happen! }
9. h3 Bh5 10. Nbd2 Nb6
{ You target the bishop on c4 and, with that, the pawn on d3! } 11. Bb3
{ A new move White has been trying out on the top level. White gives the pawn on e5 but gets the e5-pawn in return without having to play g4. }
11... a5
{ You like to chase the bishop away! This will unpin your f7-pawn and make it possible to go for the ...f5 plan again.   11...Qxd3  is also possible and much more popular, but after  12.Nxe5  Qf5  13.Nef3  , the position is complex, and you are under some severe pressure. After  13...Rad8  White could have the option to fork you with  14.g4  , which eventually after  14...Bxg4  15.hxg4  Qxg4+  16.Kh1  Qh3+  17.Nh2  Bd6  18.f4  Bxf4  19.Re2  will go to an endgame where White has a piece for three pawns. It's much more practical to sidestep these long forcing variations and go for a plan where you also play for ...f5, which you used to do in the other variations. }
12. Ne4
{ White attacks your dark-squared bishop.  Study here what to do when White stops your pawn with  12.a4  and learn why including a4 and ...a5 can be a significant advantage for you. }
12... a4
{ The light-squared bishop is the strongest minor piece from White in this position. You are more than happy to sacrifice a pawn to trade the bishops. }
13. Bc2 { The bishop drops back! } 13... Ra5
{ You use your rook to defend! As the line continues, you will see here that you can use the rook to attack pressure the d3-pawn to avoid losing your a4-pawn.   13...Bd6  is also possible but could be a bit difficult to play since after  14.Ng3  Bg6  15.Be3  White is about to capture your knight on b6 to win the a4-pawn. You have to play accurately to prove the compensation. }
