[White "Quickstarter for Black vs. Italian and Ruy Lopez "]
[Black "Four Knights Ruy Lopez #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ The Ruy Lopez! A major opening in chess. White develops the bishop, targets your knight, and gets ready to castle. }
3... Nf6
{ You stick to the principles and develop your knight first. This is known as the Berlin Defense. I suggest playing the Berlin in a modern and aggressive way.  Moving your pawn to the center with  3...d5?  wouldn't work for the usual reason: after  4.exd5  Qxd5  , White gains a tempo on the queen with  5.Nc3  . Another problem with  3...d5?  is that your knight is pinned, so  4.Nxe5  would lose a pawn.   3...a6  is the Spanish opening and an alternative move. }
4. Nc3 { The four knights Ruy Lopez! } 4... Bc5
{ You develop the bishop as usual. } 5. Nxe5
{ White immediately goes for the trick you also use against the Four Knights Italian. }
5... Nxe5 { You capture back. } 6. d4 { White forks the bishop and knight. }
6... Bd6 { You prefer to keep the bishop. } 7. f4
{ The ambitious move for White, they don't take back their piece immediately as they know it is possible to win it later with a fork. }
7... Nc6 { You drop back with the knight to the natural square. } 8. e5 Bb4
{ You start pinning the knight. } 9. exf6 Qxf6 10. a3
{ White wants to break the pin on the knight. } 10... Ba5
{ You keep the knight pinned and still have an attack on the d4-pawn. } 11. Be3
O-O { You castle and get your king to safety. } 12. O-O
{ Now that White has castled it is time to capture the knight. } 12... Bxc3
{ You capture the bishop now!  Note that by playing @@StartFEN@@r1b1k2r/pppp1ppp/2n2q2/1B6/1b1P1P2/P1N5/1PP3PP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Ba5  , first, you forced White to play  11.Be3  the bishop is here in a worse place than c1 as it's vulnerable. }
13. bxc3 d5
{ You get your pawn in the center, and White's dark-squared bishop is poorly placed now.  It's important now that  14.f5  doesn't work for White since after  14...Bxf5  15.Bd3  , you can get out of the pin with a counterattack and play  15...Qe6   White's move f5 would have been very powerful for White if their dark-squared bishop was still on c1. After @@StartFEN@@r1b1k2r/pppp1ppp/2n2q2/1B6/1b1P1P2/P1N5/1PP3PP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Bxc3?  11.bxc3  O-O  12.O-O  d5  13.f5  White would be close to winning as their dark-squared bishop is about to dominate the board on f4 or g5  13...Bxf5?  loses the piece now after  14.g4  or  14.Bd3  , since you don't have a counterattack against the dark-squared bishop }
