1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ The Ruy Lopez! A major opening in chess. White develops the bishop, targets your knight, and gets ready to castle. }
3... Nf6
{ You stick to the principles and develop your knight first. This is known as the Berlin Defense. I suggest playing the Berlin in a modern and aggressive way.  Moving your pawn to the center with  3...d5?  wouldn't work for the usual reason: after  4.exd5  Qxd5  , White gains a tempo on the queen with  5.Nc3  . Another problem with  3...d5?  is that your knight is pinned, so  4.Nxe5  would lose a pawn.   3...a6  is the Spanish opening and an alternative move. }
4. d3 { White defends the central pawn, and this is a popular sideline. } 4...
Bc5
{ Your standard development move. This prevents White's plan to capture your knight and win your central pawn. }
5. c3 { White pushes the pawn forward to control the center. } 5... O-O
{ You castle! } 6. O-O
{ When White plays  6.Bxc6  you can take towards the center with  6...bxc6  and after  7.Nxe5  d5  , you start putting pressure on White's center. }
6... d5 { You use the first golden rule and place your pawn in the center. } 7.
exd5 Qxd5
{ With White's c3-square now blocked by their pawn, it's okay to take with your queen.  If White plays  8.Bxc6  , you're fine with having double pawns after  8...bxc6  because you've taken White's strong bishop.  If you played @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp2ppp/2n2n2/1BbPp3/8/2PP1N2/PP3PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b - - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Nxd5?  , White could gain a pawn with  8.Bxc6  bxc6  9.Nxe5  . }
8. Bc4 Qd8
{ You go back as you don't want to block any of your bishops. In this position ...h6 and are both useful move to take away square for White's minor pieces. You also want to play ...Re8 to support your central pawn more and develop with ...Bf5 }
