[White "Quickstarter for Black vs. Italian and Ruy Lopez "]
[Black "Berlin Mainline 4.O-O and 5.Re1 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ The Ruy Lopez! A major opening in chess. White develops the bishop, targets your knight, and gets ready to castle. }
3... Nf6
{ You stick to the principles and develop your knight first. This is known as the Berlin Defense. I suggest playing the Berlin in a modern and aggressive way.  Moving your pawn to the center with  3...d5?  wouldn't work for the usual reason: after  4.exd5  Qxd5  , White gains a tempo on the queen with  5.Nc3  . Another problem with  3...d5?  is that your knight is pinned, so  4.Nxe5  would lose a pawn.   3...a6  is the Spanish opening and an alternative move. }
4. O-O { White castles } 4... Nxe4
{ You take the pawn because it's undefended. This is the same strategy you use against the Italian when White leaves their pawn unprotected. }
5. Re1
{ White immediately attacks your knight!  This is a solid alternative for White, which will generally lead to a less crazy position than after  5.d4  exd4  6.Re1  f5  , which you will learn in the next chapter }
5... Nd6
{ You drop back and immediately harass the bishop.   5...d5?  would be awful placing your knight in a pin and after  6.d3  Nd6  7.Nxe5  both White's rook and bishops are eyeing your king, and White is winning. }
6. a4
{ A move that is not played so frequently but one that is trendy at the top level and that you should take seriously. White wants to keep the bishop in an active position. }
6... Be7 { You continue your development and get ready to castle. } 7. Nc3
{ White's idea is not to capture the pawn back but to develop quickly and get compensation for the pawn with active piece play. }
7... O-O
{ The fighting option! You continue your development and stay a pawn up.  A solid alternative would be to go for  7...a6  when after  8.Bf1  e4  , you can give back the pawn, and after  9.Nxe4  Nxe4  10.Rxe4  d5  11.Re1  , you can either go for  11...Bg4  or  11...d4  to avoid a position after  11...O-O?  12.d4  where your knight on c6 would be slightly misplaced. }
8. d4 { White aims to open up the game! } 8... exd4 { You capture as usual. }
9. Nd5
{ White is two pawns down but starts creating some threats. They threaten to eliminate your knight with Bxc6 and win your bishop. }
9... Re8 { You defend your bishop. } 10. Bf4 b6
{ You continue with the plan to develop the bishop! Make sure to study these lines in more detail in the here. After developing the bishop White can go for variation where they march the h-down the board to attack. You will learn here how to counter this and how to likely end up on the attacking side. }
