1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ The Ruy Lopez! A major opening in chess. White develops the bishop, targets your knight, and gets ready to castle. }
3... Nf6
{ You stick to the principles and develop your knight first. This is known as the Berlin Defense. I suggest playing the Berlin in a modern and aggressive way.  Moving your pawn to the center with  3...d5?  wouldn't work for the usual reason: after  4.exd5  Qxd5  , White gains a tempo on the queen with  5.Nc3  . Another problem with  3...d5?  is that your knight is pinned, so  4.Nxe5  would lose a pawn.   3...a6  is the Spanish opening and an alternative move. }
4. O-O { White castles } 4... Nxe4
{ You take the pawn because it's undefended. This is the same strategy you use against the Italian when White leaves their pawn unprotected. }
5. Re1
{ White immediately attacks your knight! This is a solid alternative for White, which will generally lead to a less crazy position than after  5.d4  exd4  6.Re1  f5! }
5... Nd6
{ You drop back and immediately harass the bishop.   5...d5? would be awful placing your knight in a pin and after 6.d3 Nd6 7.Nxe5 both White's rook and bishops are eyeing your king, and White is winning. }
6. Nxe5 Be7
{ You block the e-file to defend against the discovered attack.   6...Nxe5  is a sound alternative, and after  7.Rxe5+  , you can also block the e-file with  7...Be7 }
7. Bd3
{ White places the bishop on a square that looks very bad. This blocks the d-pawn from moving forward. White has the idea to use the bishop and attack, though, and can, in some cases, sacrifice the bishop on h7. }
7... Nxe5 8. Rxe5 { You first trade the knights. } 8... O-O
{ Its safe to castle! } 9. Nc3 c6
{ You want to prevent Nd5 and like to keep your bishop. Next, you want to play ...Ne8 like in the other variation. This makes it possible to use your knight as a defender and to activate your light-squared bishop.   9...Bf6  is also possible but can become more complex since after  10.Re3  Bd4  11.Bxh7+  is possible, and you rather want to avoid these complications. }
10. b3 Ne8
{ This is your usual plan in this line and an effective move to both prepare ...d5 and use your knight in the defense. Also, by not playing ...Bf6 too quickly, you still keep this square free for your knight, and your position is rock solid. White takes some serious strategic risk with the bishop on d3. }
