[Black "Scotch Gambit #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4
{ The Scotch opening! White uses the same strategy as you. } 3... exd4
{ You capture the central pawn. } 4. Bc4
{ The Scotch Gambit! A dangerous opening weapon from White, which I recommend for the White pieces in my Attacking Repertoire for Club Players 1.e4! White is quick with development and is already ready to castle. }
4... Nf6 { You follow the opening principles and develop the knight first. } 5.
O-O { White follows the third golden rule and castles. } 5... Nxe4
{ You capture the central pawn! There is no need to fear the pin on the e-file since you can defend and place your pawn in the center with ...d5 }
6. Re1 { White pins your knight! } 6... d5
{ You keep following the opening concepts and place your pawn in the center to defend the knight and attack the bishop. }
7. Bxd5
{ White captures your pawn! White has some tactics now to regain the sacrificed material. }
7... Qxd5 { You capture back with the queen. } 8. Nc3
{ An excellent move from White exploiting the fact that your knight and central pawn are both pinned. Therefore, you should avoid capturing the knight. }
8... Qd7
{ Currently, you possess the bishop pair and are ahead by a pawn! Nonetheless, your king remains central. Your main goal should be to castle quickly and stabilize the situation. Giving back your central pawn for this would be a worthwhile exchange.  I suggest a move that might seem unconventional as it obstructs your light-squared bishop with your queen. The idea is that defending the e7-square proves beneficial as White is attacking the e-file. Furthermore, defending your c6-knight with the queen is useful in anticipating White's potential Nxd4, followed by the Nxc6 maneuver.  After  9.Nxe4  Be7  , the position is immediately safe, and you are ready to castle.  If White instead opts for  9.Rxe4  Be7  10.Nxd4  , it's strong to first chase the rook to a poor square with  10...f5  and only castle on the next move after  11.Rf4  O-O }
