[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter for Black vs Scotch and 1.e4 e5 Sidelines"]
[Black "Scholars Mate "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Qh5
{ The Wayward Queen Attack. It's a common choice among beginners who aim to win with the scholar's mate. What White hopes that after  2...Nc6  3.Bc4  , you'd miss the mate threat and make the move  3...Nf6  , leading to  4.Qxf7#  .   It's the right moment to surprise those using this tactic, ensuring you are on the offensive. }
2... Nf6
{ Right away, you target the queen and sacrifice a pawn in exchange for rapid piece development. }
3. Qxe5+ Be7
{ You are ready to gain another tempo with ...Nc6 and place your pawn in the center with ...d5. Learn how to get a strong initiative in the and study the lines here. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter for Black vs Scotch and 1.e4 e5 Sidelines"]
[Black "Vienna Gambit"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. f4
{ The Vienna Gambit! Unlike the King's Gambit, accepting the sacrifice isn't smart because, after  3...exf4  , White will begin chasing your knight with  4.e5  , leaving you with no good squares to relocate to. The only safe spot is to return to the starting position with  4...Ng8  , but reversing your development isn't desirable. }
3... d5 { You place your pawn in the center to counter the gambit. } 4. fxe5
{ White takes your pawn and starts to chase your knight. However, this time, you can move forward and recapture a pawn. }
4... Nxe4 5. Qf3
{ White targets your knight and applies pressure in the center. } 5... Nc6
{ As usual, start by developing the knights! I also recommend this line in my course 'Attacking Repertoire for Club Players for Black'  Also after  5.Nf3  , you would stick to your opening rules and reply with  5...Nc6 }
6. Nxe4
{ This would be a common mistake for White.  Learn more about the main move  6.Bb5  here. }
6... Nd4
{ A brilliant intermediate move! You target the queen and threaten the fork on the king and rook.  This is still an important line to study in more detail because after  7.Qd3?  dxe4  8.Qxe4  Bf5  9.Qxb7  Nxc2+  you fork the king and rook, but after  10.Kd1  Rb8!  should be played before capturing the rook so that after  11.Qxa7  Nxa1  White doesn't have any counterattack with Bb5+ }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter for Black vs Scotch and 1.e4 e5 Sidelines"]
[Black "Bishop Opening "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Bc4
{ The bishop opening! This opening will likely transpose back to the Italian opening. }
2... Nf6 { You develop and attack White's central pawn. } 3. d3 Nc6
{ You develop the other knight! } 4. Nc3 Bc5
{ An alternative is  4...Na5  immediately after White's light-squared bishop. }
5. f4 O-O { You castle and continue your development! } 6. Nf3 d6
{ You push the pawn forward and get ready to develop your light-squared bishop. }
7. f5
{ White tries to shut down your bishop. You have to be a bit careful now because White plans to go for Bg5, pinning your knight followed by the attack with Nd5! }
7... Nd4
{ You move your knight forward, get ready to play ...c6, and take control of the d5-square. }
8. Bg5 { By far the most played move, but already a big mistake! } 8... c6
{ Black stops the knight from coming to d5, and now White's light-squared bishop is in trouble. }
