1. e4 e5 2. f4 { The King's Gambit } 2... exf4
{ You capture the pawn and accept the challenge } 3. Nf3
{ White develops the knight } 3... g5
{ You support your f4-pawn.  Placing the pawn in the center is an alternative but could cause difficulties since after  3...d5  4.exd5  if you recapture with  4...Qxd5?  White gains a tempo with  5.Nc3   Developing the knight with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppp1ppp/8/8/4Pp2/5N2/PPPP2PP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  is possible, too, but White can hunt your knight with  4.e5  when you have to go to the edge of the board with  4...Nh5 }
4. h4 { White attacks your pawn! } 4... g4
{ You immediately attack the knight!  For those of you who had the Beginner version of this course there, I recommended  4...d5  , which is also a sound alternative. I changed the recommendation because I thought this new approach is easier to play, and practice shows that White can easily go very wrong in this line in the next couple of moves. }
5. Ne5 Nc6
{ An uncommon move that is likely to surprise your opponent. You develop your knight as usual and challenge White's knight in the center! White only has one good option.   6.Nxg4?  is common and after  6...d5  you will get an overwhelming initiative with Black. Study these lines here.  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1p1p/2n5/4N3/4PppP/8/PPPP2P1/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 6@@EndFEN@@  6.d4  is the only good move for White, and learn more about that here. }
