[Black "King's Gambit #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. f4 { The King's Gambit } 2... exf4
{ You capture the pawn and accept the challenge } 3. Nf3
{ White develops the knight } 3... g5
{ You support your f4-pawn.  Placing the pawn in the center is an alternative but could cause difficulties since after  3...d5  4.exd5  if you recapture with  4...Qxd5?  White gains a tempo with  5.Nc3   Developing the knight with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppp1ppp/8/8/4Pp2/5N2/PPPP2PP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  is possible, too, but White can hunt your knight with  4.e5  when you have to go to the edge of the board with  4...Nh5 }
4. Bc4
{ White's most popular move at the club level. White aims to sacrifice a knight after  4...g4  5.O-O  gxf3  6.Qxf3  , and even though this sacrifice is dubious, White gets a powerful attack, and I wouldn't recommend going there. You already have a good position with Black and are a pawn-up. You can develop all pieces without trouble, and White doesn't have any attack. }
4... Nc6
{ You develop the knight as usual. Next, you can develop with ...Bg7, and after playing both ...h6 and ...d6, you are ready to play ...Nf6! You stay a pawn up, and White has nothing to show for it.  You avoid the objectively strong  4...g4!?  White is hoping for when after  5.O-O  gxf3  6.Qxf3  when White is a piece down but gets strong attacking chances. }
