[White "Quickstarter for Black vs. 1...d4, English and Reti "]
[Black "Queens Gambit Declined Early Exchange: 3.cxd5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ The second most popular move at the Beginner level. You should stop White from dominating the center. }
1... d5 { You apply the first golden rule and place your pawn in the center. }
2. c4
{ The Queen's Gambit. White challenges your center. While you can accept the Queen's Gambit, I don't recommend it because after  2...dxc4  3.e4  , White establishes a strong pawn center and threatens to retake your pawn. }
2... e6
{ You reinforce your pawn to support the center.  A common error is to play  2...Nf6?  , supporting the center with your knight, but after  3.cxd5  Nxd5  , White can gain complete control of the center with  4.e4 }
3. cxd5
{ After learning the lines, you know that you usually like to take back with the knight when White takes your d5-pawn. If White trades right away, this isn't possible. }
3... exd5 { Without the c4-pawn, the pressure on your center decreases. } 4.
Nc3
{ White develops the knight. Now, you have be careful not run into unfamiliar theory. }
4... Bb4
{ You pin White's knight! This is a special moment when you make an exception to the rule of developing knights first. This is strong to do this since White's move already allowed an appealing option for your bishop to pin the knight.  After  4...Nf6  , White can pin you with  5.Bg5  and your standard plans with  5...c5?  won't work anymore because after  6.Bxf6  , you don't have a good way to recapture:  6...exf6  ruins your pawn structure, and  6...Qxf6  allows  7.Nxd5  , losing your central pawn.  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/8/3p4/3P4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...c5  to prepare for ...Nc6 is possible and aligns with the course ideas. But, as a Semi-Tarrasch player, you generally avoid these pawn structures, and  4...c5  leads towards the Tarrasch, which is another big theoretical variation you would rather avoid. }
