[White "Quickstarter for Black vs. 1...d4, English and Reti "]
[Black "Queens Gambit Declined Modern Variation: 4.Bg5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ The second most popular move at the Beginner level. You should stop White from dominating the center. }
1... d5 { You apply the first golden rule and place your pawn in the center. }
2. c4
{ The Queen's Gambit. White challenges your center. While you can accept the Queen's Gambit, I don't recommend it because after  2...dxc4  3.e4  , White establishes a strong pawn center and threatens to retake your pawn. }
2... e6
{ You reinforce your pawn to support the center.  A common error is to play  2...Nf6?  , supporting the center with your knight, but after  3.cxd5  Nxd5  , White can gain complete control of the center with  4.e4 }
3. Nc3 { White develops the knight! } 3... Nf6
{ You also develop the knight and support the center. } 4. Bg5
{ White develops the bishop and pin your knight! } 4... c5 5. cxd5 cxd4
{ You take the central pawn, tempting White's queen to advance.   5...exd5?  is less ideal since White can respond with  6.Bxf6  . If you retake with your queen,  6...Qxf6  , White wins the central pawn with  7.Nxd5 }
6. Qxd4 Be7
{ You develop your bishop, breaking the pin on your knight.   6...Nc6?  seems reasonable, but it doesn't work out well. While White can't take your knight because you pin the central pawn, White can play  7.Bxf6  and launch a counterattack on your queen. After  7...gxf6  is played, then  8.Qe3  creates a pin on the e-pawn, and you can't recapture the central pawn. }
7. e4 { White tries to hold on to the central pawn. } 7... Nc6
{ You attack the queen and use the pin on the central pawn. } 8. Qd2 exd5 9.
Bxf6 Bxf6 10. exd5 Bxc3
{ An important novelty because after  10...Ne5  Black should also be doing fine but will get a position where you only defend for the draw with a pawn down.  This move is key for your setup to work well against the modern variation with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p4/2PP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Bg5!  Study the details in the main chapter!  After @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pp3ppp/2n5/3P4/8/2b5/PP1Q1PPP/R3KBNR w KQkq - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11.Qxc3  Qxd5  12.Qxg7  Qa5+  13.Qc3  Qxc3  14.bxc3  Be6  , you can castle queenside and play ...Rhe8 and start attacking with both rooks in the center.  Instead, after @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pp3ppp/2n5/3P4/8/2b5/PP1Q1PPP/R3KBNR w KQkq - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11.bxc3  Ne5  White will keep a weak pawn on d5 and won't be able to develop the knight with Nf3. }
