[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter for Black vs. 1...d4, English and Reti "]
[Black "Semi-Tarrasch: 7.Rb1 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ The second most popular move at the Beginner level. You should stop White from dominating the center. }
1... d5 { You apply the first golden rule and place your pawn in the center. }
2. c4
{ The Queen's Gambit. White challenges your center. While you can accept the Queen's Gambit, I don't recommend it because after  2...dxc4  3.e4  , White establishes a strong pawn center and threatens to retake your pawn. }
2... e6
{ You reinforce your pawn to support the center.  A common error is to play  2...Nf6?  , supporting the center with your knight, but after  3.cxd5  Nxd5  , White can gain complete control of the center with  4.e4 }
3. Nc3 { White develops the knight! } 3... Nf6
{ You also develop the knight and support the center. } 4. cxd5
{ White directly exchanges the pawns, a cunning move. } 4... Nxd5
{ Like in earlier scenarios, you recapture using the knight. Your goal is to transition to known positions and cleverly sidestep extensive theory.  Taking with the pawn is more common, but the problem now is that after  4...exd5  5.Bg5  , you can't opt for your usual setup with  5...c5  , as White can strike with  6.Bxf6  , and  6...Qxf6  would lead to the loss of your central pawn after  7.Nxd5 }
5. e4 { White places the pawn in the center. } 5... Nxc3
{ You go for the standard trade! } 6. bxc3 c5
{ You pressure White's center as usual. } 7. Rb1
{ White tries to capitalize on your different move order.  The idea is that after  7...cxd4  8.cxd4  , you can't play ...Bb4+ anymore. In most games, If White continues with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp3ppp/4p3/2p5/3PP3/2P5/P4PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Nf3  , you get back to the Semi-Tarrasch. You've successfully avoided the Queen's Gambit Exchange variation without studying extra theory. }
7... cxd4
{ You trade the center pawns as usual.   7...Nc6?  first would run into  8.d5 }
8. cxd4 Nc6 { You put pressure on the center with your knight. } 9. Bb5
{ White pins your knight!  When you are an absolute pin, you can't move, so  9...Bb4+?  would be a horrible blunder since White would capture the bishop for free with  10.Rxb4 }
9... a6
{ A common motif in your repertoire, you want to get rid of the pin immediately. }
10. Bxc6+
{ White is obligated to trade the bishop otherwise, you would win the d4-pawn. }
10... bxc6 11. Nf3 c5
{ You make a daring move and immediately want to get rid of your isolated pawn. You challenge the center. As usual, you want to avoid capturing it immediately when you have a flank pawn that attacks the center.  Developing immediately with  11...Be7?  gives White the chance to attack your weak pawn with  12.Ne5  and now  12...c5  is no longer possible since White goes for  13.Qa4+  and can stop you from castling. }
12. O-O Be7
{ It's time to start developing! As usual you don't trade the flank pawn for the central pawn since after  13.dxc5  Qxd1  14.Rxd1  Bxc5  , your bishop is well-placed on c5. }
