[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ The second most popular move at the Beginner level. You should stop White from dominating the center. }
1... d5 { You apply the first golden rule and place your pawn in the center. }
2. c4
{ The Queen's Gambit. White challenges your center. While you can accept the Queen's Gambit, I don't recommend it because after  2...dxc4  3.e4  , White establishes a strong pawn center and threatens to retake your pawn. }
2... e6
{ You reinforce your pawn to support the center.  A common error is to play  2...Nf6?  , supporting the center with your knight, but after  3.cxd5  Nxd5  , White can gain complete control of the center with  4.e4 }
3. Nc3 { White develops the knight! } 3... Nf6
{ You also develop the knight and support the center. } 4. Nf3
{ White brings out the other knight! This is one of the main moves.  It could be tempting to play  4...Nc6?  in line with the opening principles you learned earlier. However, in the d4-variations, your knight can only apply a little pressure on the center if your pawn is behind it. Therefore, you first play  4...c5  and aim to increase the pressure on the center with ...Nc6 next. }
4... c5
{ You always push this pawn and get ready to develop your knight next. } 5.
cxd5 { White goes for the trade } 5... Nxd5 6. e4
{ White places the pawn in the center. } 6... Nxc3 { You trade the knights. }
7. bxc3 cxd4
{ It's important to trade pawns in the center before developing the knight.  If you play  7...Nc6  too early, White can push  8.d5  , and your knight has no good square. }
8. cxd4 Nc6
{ Trading pawns makes it safe to develop the knight.  You could also play  8...Bb4+  , but it's your common strategy to develop the knight first, which sets some nasty traps for White. }
9. Bc4
{ Quick side note here that @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp3ppp/2n1p3/8/3PP3/5N2/P4PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 1 9@@EndFEN@@  9.d5?  is not possible since after  9...exd5  10.exd5  Qa5+  , you win the pawn since White has to play  11.Bd2  and allow  11...Qxd5   @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp3ppp/2n1p3/8/3PP3/5N2/P4PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 1 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Bb5?  is even worse for White and blunders the bishop to  9...Qa5+ }
9... Bb4+ { You develop with a check! } 10. Bd2 Bxd2+
{ You exchange the bishops! In the Beginner version of this course, I recommended  10...Qa5  , which is an interesting alternative. I changed my mind since this option is easier to play since you can use your standard setup. }
11. Qxd2 O-O
{ You are ready to castle.  You follow the standard plan as before to go for the provocative development setup with ...Qd6-...Rd8 and ...h6. If White wants to prove something, they should start pushing pawns forward at some point also gives you counter chances. Study more about these variations in the main chapter. }
