1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3
{ The Catalan! An opening where White aims to create a powerful light-squared bishop.  This position can also be reached from the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.g3  Nf6  4.Nf3  move order }
4... dxc4 { You capture the pawn. } 5. Bg2 c5
{ As typical for the d4-openings. You want to play your c-pawn first before placing your knight on c6 so that you can apply pressure on the center. }
6. O-O { White castles and is quick with development. } 6... Nc6
{ You develop the knight as usual. } 7. Ne5
{ White places the knight in the center.  The idea from White is that after  7...Nxe5?  8.dxe5  Qxd1  9.Rxd1  dxe5  10.Nd5  White can trade off your central knight with  10.Nc3  when after  10...Nxc3  11.bxc3  White has a monster bishop on g2, which is pinning the b7-pawn, and it's challenging for you to develop your light-squared bishop. }
7... Bd7 { You develop the bishop and support your knight. } 8. Na3
{ White develops the knight and is ready to regain the c4-pawn. } 8... cxd4
{ You capture in the center. } 9. Naxc4 { White wins back your c4-pawn. } 9...
Be7 { You develop the bishop and get ready to castle. } 10. Qb3
{ The typical move in this position that White tries to bring you in trouble. }
10... Qc7
{ You use the aggressive approach, defending the pawn and attacking the knight in the center. }
11. Bf4 Nd5
{ The same move as in the other line directly targeting the bishop.   11...Nh5  is much more common, and it gives White an extra option of playing  12.Bxc6  Bxc6  13.Nxc6  Qxc6  14.Be5   This is not necessarily problematic @@StartFEN@@r3k2r/ppqbbppp/2n1pn2/4N3/2Np1B2/1Q4P1/PP2PPBP/R4RK1 b kq - 4 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Nd5  also gives White an extra option of playing  12.Bxd5  exd5  When both options are about equally good, I like to pick one that your opponent is likely less familiar with.  Study more about these exciting variations in the main chapter @@StartFEN@@r3k2r/ppqbbppp/2n1p3/3nN3/2Np1B2/1Q4P1/PP2PPBP/R4RK1 w kq - 5 12@@EndFEN@@  12.Nxc6  Nxf4  13.Nxe7  Nxg2  is safe for Black! You will win back the knight on e7 and since the knight is trapped you are not in a rush and can first opt for ...Qc5 ideas to prevent any counterattack on the dark-squared from White when you collect the knight.  @@StartFEN@@r3k2r/ppqbbppp/2n1p3/3nN3/2Np1B2/1Q4P1/PP2PPBP/R4RK1 w kq - 5 12@@EndFEN@@  12.Bxd5  exd5  13.Nxf7  dxc4  14.Qxc4  Qc8  15.Nxh8  Be6  is a variation where White may think the game is going to end in a move repetition after  16.Qd3  Bf5  17.Qc4  , but you will continue with  17...Qe6!  and win the knight in the corner }
