1. d4 d5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Bf4
{ In the Jobava London system, White's plan often includes aggressive maneuvers such as Nb5-Nc7+, which pose a threat to your king and rook by potentially delivering a fork. }
3... e6
{ You move your pawn forward, anticipating White's knight jump to b5.  You don't go for the usual move  3...c5  .  Even though it's possible, if after  4.e3  you play  4...Nc6  , White can respond with  5.Nb5  You'd have no good way to prevent the fork with Nc7+. }
4. Nb5 { White immediately goes for the attack and threatens Nxc7+ } 4... Bb4+
{ You deliver a check to bring your bishop to a defensive position on a5!  You could also consider  4...Na6  , but you prefer to develop the knight to the natural squares in your strategy. }
5. c3 { White blocks the check. } 5... Ba5
{ You defend against the fork, and White's attack led nowhere. } 6. a4
{ White gets ready to start trapping your bishop with b4-a5! } 6... a6
{ You counterattack the knight. } 7. b4 { White goes after the bishop. } 7...
Nc6
{ You get the knight to the natural square!  The problem with  7...Bb6  is that  8.a5  traps the bishop, and after  8...axb5  9.axb6  , you will end up with a bad pawn structure. After the direct  7...axb5  , White plays immediately  8.axb5  and will win your bishop back, which is still pinned.  The pawn on b5 is annoying, not allowing your knight to develop to its natural square. Also, after @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/1pp2ppp/p3pn2/bN1p4/PP1P1B2/2P5/4PPPP/R2QKBNR b KQkq b3 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Bxb4  8.cxb4  axb5  9.axb5  White would keep a pawn on b5. }
8. bxa5 { White captures the bishop! } 8... axb5 9. axb5 Nxa5
{ You win back all the material! You can continue development with ...O-O, ...Bd7 ...c5 and eventually the b5-pawn will become a target. }
