1. d4 d5 2. Bf4
{ The London opening! White typically develops the pieces in on similar setup. They aim to get the dark-squared bishop out of the pawn chain and solidly develop all the other pieces. You will logically reply, developing your pieces and neutralizing White's London bishop. }
2... Nf6 { As usual, you develop the knights first. } 3. e3 c5
{ You follow the general strategy in d4-variations, before you develop the other knight, you want to advance your c-pawn. }
4. c3 Nc6
{ You develop the other knight!  Trading the pawns with  4...cxd4  5.exd4  would benefit White more as the e-file opens up for them. }
5. Nd2 e6
{ Your usual setup. You are ready to neutralize White's London bishop on the next move with ...Bd6 }
6. Ngf3 { This position can come from multiple move orders. } 6... Bd6
{ You develop the bishop to neutralize the London bishop. A trade would be beneficial for you. }
7. Bg3
{ A cunning move from White. White only wants to trade the bishop on their terms, and the h-file will open up for the rook after a trade. I don't recommend trading the bishops.  At this point, you have already neutralized the influence of White's dark-squared bishop. If White instead places the knight in the center with  7.Ne5  , you can put more pressure on the knight with  7...Qc7 }
7... O-O { You follow the golden rules and castle. } 8. Bd3
{ White develops the light-squared bishop. } 8... a5
{ A waiting move that gains space on the queenside. You want to wait till White castles before you play ...b6  The most common move is  8...b6  , but now the problem is that after  9.e4  , you can't use the rule that when pawns are facing in the center, you capture because after  9...dxe4  10.Nxe4  White targets your bishop and forces  10...Nxe4  11.Bxe4  when White has a powerful pin on your knight.  The second most common move is @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp3ppp/2nbpn2/2pp4/3P4/2PBPNB1/PP1N1PPP/R2QK2R b KQ - 5 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Qe7  preparing ...e5, but White can stop the plans with  9.Ne5  and after  9...Nd7  challenging the knight, I don't like that White has a variation where they can force a draw but also can keep the game going. }
