1. c4 { The English opening. } 1... e6
{ Your opening strategy against @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  can be effectively utilized against  1.c4  and  1.Nf3  .  With Black, you adopt the same setup, and if White eventually plays d4, you can transpose back to the familiar variation. If White refrains from playing d4, the arising variations are generally not threatening, as White won't have any central pawns.  Moving your e-pawn to support ...d5 on the next move is crucial. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/2P5/8/PP1PPPPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq c3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...d5?  does not achieve the same setup and after  2.cxd5  Qxd5  3.Nc3  , White gains a tempo on your queen. }
2. Nf3
{ You place your pawn in the center and go for the familiar Semi-Tarrasch setup }
2... d5
{ You place your pawn in the center and reach the same setup as against 1.d4 }
3. g3
{ If White tries a setup with 3.b3, you can play 3. ..d4 and after 4.Bb2 c5 makes the bishop look miserable on b2. }
3... Nf6
{ You keep applying the concepts as if you played against a d4 opening. So you develop the knight first. }
4. Bg2
{ White opts for a setup that looks like a Catalan. Therefore, you can treat it similarly.  This position could also be reached from the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppp1ppp/4p3/8/2P5/8/PP1PPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.g3  d5  3.Bg2  Nf3  4.Nf6  move order. }
4... dxc4 { You capture the pawn, like you do against the Catalan. } 5. Qa4+
Bd7
{ As usual, you want to play ...Nc6 eventually.  The direct  5...Nc6  runs into some trouble after  6.Ne5  when White targets your pinned knight three times. }
6. Qxc4 c5
{ As usual, before playing. ..Nc6, you push the pawn forward to put pressure on the center. }
7. Ne5
{ The main move! White opens the diagonal for the light-squared bishop and targets the b7-pawn. }
7... Qc8
{ You support the b7-pawn.  Playing  7...Nc6?  at this point could lead to doubled pawns on the c-file after  8.Nxc6  Bxc6  9.Bxc6  bxc6  .   Therefore, it's better to delay this move until your queen also provides control over the c6-square. @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/pp1b1ppp/4pn2/2p1N3/2Q5/6P1/PP1PPPBP/RNB1K2R b KQkq - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Qc7?  leaves the queen unprotected which means your c5-pawn is pinned so after  8.d4  you won't be able to capture with  8...cxd4?  since it drops the queen  9.Qxc7 }
