1. Nf3 { The Reti opening. } 1... d5
{ You have the opportunity to set your pawn in the middle of the board quickly. Following this, you can proceed with the usual strategy of developing your knights. However, prioritize playing ...c5 before bringing out your queenside knight. You only have to play ...e6 to solidify your pawn center in case White opts to play c4. }
2. g3 { White aims to fianchetto the bishop. } 2... Nf6
{ You develop your knight. } 3. Bg2 { White fianchettos the bishop. } 3... c5
{ You again play like in a d4-opening.   3...Nc6?  would not apply much pressure on the center when White plays  4.d4 }
4. O-O Nc6
{ You develop the knight and aim to take control of the center with ...e5 } 5.
d4 { White places the pawn in the center. } 5... e6
{ 6.c4  is the best and most popular move when you transpose back to the Catalan after  6...dxc4  .   You save time using the Semi-Tarrasch setup against the English and Reti openings. Since most of the time you transpose to variation, you already learned against @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4   Also, for the sidelines, the default option to go for the Semi-Tarrasch setup works well. }
