[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1a) Scotch Sidelines"]
[Black "Scotch: 4...Nxd4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 { Golden rule number one: place your pawns in the center. } 1... e5
{ Black is copying your strategy! } 2. Nf3
{ If you play  2.d4  , putting your other pawn in the center, Black would play  2...exd4  3.Qxd4  Nc6  and get ahead by attacking your queen.   That's why the second golden rule is to develop and play  2.Nf3  , hitting the pawn. }
2... Nc6 { Black also makes a move and protects the pawn. } 3. d4
{ You're using golden rule one again, moving another pawn to the center. Your knight protects the pawn, so you don't need to move your queen out to take back the pawn.  After  3...exd4  4.Nxd4  Nxd4  5.Qxd4  , it is powerful for your queen to be out since Black has no knight to attack it with ...Nc6.  The most popular alternatives are @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Bc4  , the Italian Opening, or  3.Bb5  , the Ruy Lopez. These also follow the golden rules as you develop and get ready to castle.  But the Scotch Opening is challenging Black right after  3...exd4  4.Nxd4  .  They shouldn't trade knights here. And it's good for you because, at the Club Player level, many players still make the mistake of trading knights with  4...Nxd4  .  The Scotch also leads to more open games, making getting all your pieces out easier. }
3... exd4 { Black should take your pawn, or else you could take theirs. } 4.
Nxd4
{ You take the pawn back. In the Scotch, this opens up space for your other bishop, letting you develop your bishops wherever you like and castle on either side. }
4... Nxd4
{ This move, taking your knight, is a mistake that is still quite frequently played. It helps you by letting you get your queen active, but Black doesn't get anything in return. }
5. Qxd4 { Your queen is powerful in the center. } 5... Nf6 6. e5
{ You're hunting the knight! Why aren't you developing more pieces? Remember, the golden rules apply to both you and your opponent. If you prevent your opponent from developing, it's okay not to develop yourself for a move. The best place for the knight now is its starting spot. After Black moves the knight back, you can keep developing your pieces. }
6... Qe7
{ Black tries to fight back by pinning your e5-pawn. But their queen is misplaced. If Black had played  6...c5  , you could play  7.Qe3  , avoiding Black's pin on the e5-pawn with ...Qe7.  Then, after  7...Nd5  8.Qf3  Nb4  , Black might try to fork with ...Nxc2+, but you can ignore that and keep developing with  9.Bc4  , setting up a checkmate threat with Qxf7#. }
7. Be3
{ You develop another piece and unpin the pawn, threatening to capture the knight again.  If Black played  7...Nh5  , you could trap the knight with  8.g4  .  7...Ng8  is the best move for Black. It's sad for them as the knight returns to where it started. }
7... c5
{ Black counterattacks the queen! Should you react to the threat they create? }
8. exf6
{ By grabbing the knight, you also attack their queen, and you will win a piece. }
8... cxd4 9. fxe7 dxe3 10. exf8=Q+
{ After all the captures, you stay a piece up with a winning position.  Note that if you had played @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/ppppqppp/5n2/4P3/3Q4/8/PPP2PPP/RNB1KB1R w KQkq - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Be2  to unpin the pawn, after  7...c5  8.exf6  Black still could avoid losing a piece with  8...Qxe2+  9.Kxe2  cxd4 }
*

