{ Black develops their bishop and sets up a checkmate threat!  Playing  5...Bb4?  would be less effective since you can block it with  6.N1c3  . }
6. Qe2
{ You defend against the mate threat.  Another option,  6.Qf3  is possible, but it leads to an endgame after  6...Qxf3  7.gxf3  Kd8  , which is less favorable when the queens are off the board. }
6... Bb6 7. N1c3 { You develop your other knight. } 7... a6
{ If Black tries to kick your knight back, don't back down. } 8. Nd5
{ You move your knight, keeping a strong position. } 8... Ba5+
{ Black's only good response is to check. } 9. Nbc3
{ Your knight returns to a dominant spot. } 9... Bxc3+ 10. bxc3
{ You recapture, keeping your strong knight in the center. You can continue with Bb2 and O-O-O, dominating the long diagonal with your bishop and using your rook on the semi-open d-file. }
*

