[White "1a) Scotch Sidelines"]
[Black "Scotch: 4...Qf6 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 { Golden rule number one: place your pawns in the center. } 1... e5
{ Black is copying your strategy! } 2. Nf3
{ If you play  2.d4  , putting your other pawn in the center, Black would play  2...exd4  3.Qxd4  Nc6  and get ahead by attacking your queen.   That's why the second golden rule is to develop and play  2.Nf3  , hitting the pawn. }
2... Nc6 { Black also makes a move and protects the pawn. } 3. d4
{ You're using golden rule one again, moving another pawn to the center. Your knight protects the pawn, so you don't need to move your queen out to take back the pawn.  After  3...exd4  4.Nxd4  Nxd4  5.Qxd4  , it is powerful for your queen to be out since Black has no knight to attack it with ...Nc6.  The most popular alternatives are @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Bc4  , the Italian Opening, or  3.Bb5  , the Ruy Lopez. These also follow the golden rules as you develop and get ready to castle.  But the Scotch Opening is challenging Black right after  3...exd4  4.Nxd4  .  They shouldn't trade knights here. And it's good for you because, at the Club Player level, many players still make the mistake of trading knights with  4...Nxd4  .  The Scotch also leads to more open games, making getting all your pieces out easier. }
3... exd4 { Black should take your pawn, or else you could take theirs. } 4.
Nxd4
{ You take the pawn back. In the Scotch, this opens up space for your other bishop, letting you develop your bishops wherever you like and castle on either side. }
4... Qf6
{ Black goes after your knight. You want to immediately make Black regret moving the queen, so you target the c7-pawn with  5.Nb5  .   If you play  5.Be3  , Black can develop with  5...Bc5  , and you'll need to defend with  6.c3  , losing a good spot for your other knight. I suggest you keep c3 free for your other knight.  Notice here that on both sidelines where Black brings out the queen early, you use this same strategy to counterattack the c7-pawn.  In the @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/8/3NP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Qf6  variation, this is done with the immediate  5.Nb5  , but in the @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/8/3NP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Qh4  line it was a little more complicated and only after  5.Nc3  Bb4  6.Be2  Qxe4  , you attack with  7.Nb5 }
5. Nb5
{ You quickly go after Black's c7-pawn, showing Black the downside of moving the queen early. }
5... Bc5
{ Black develops their bishop and sets up a checkmate threat!  Playing  5...Bb4?  would be less effective since you can block it with  6.N1c3  . }
6. Qe2
{ You defend against the mate threat.  Another option,  6.Qf3  is possible, but it leads to an endgame after  6...Qxf3  7.gxf3  Kd8  , which is less favorable when the queens are off the board. }
6... Bb6 7. N1c3 { You develop your other knight. } 7... Nge7 8. Be3
{ You look to trade dark-squared bishops, reinforcing your fork threat on c7. }
8... Ba5 { Black moves their bishop to maintain c7 protection. } 9. O-O-O
{ You castle, freeing your knight. } 9... a6
{ If Black castles with  9...O-O?  , then  10.Nd5!  is powerful. } 10. Nd5
{ You attack directly, not retreating your knight. } 10... Nxd5 11. exd5 Ne7
12. Na3 { You threaten Nc4, targeting the bishop. } 12... b5 13. h4
{ You prevent Black from castling. } 13... Bb4
{ Black adds another defender to the knight. } 14. Bg5 Qd6 15. Rd4
{ Your rook move is effective.  After  15...f6  16.Bf4  Qc5  17.d6  , you attack the pinned knight strongly. }
15... Bxa3 16. Bxe7 Qxe7 17. Re4 { You pin and win the queen. } *

