{ You're using golden rule one again, moving another pawn to the center. Your knight protects the pawn, so you don't need to move your queen out to take back the pawn.  After  3...exd4  4.Nxd4  Nxd4  5.Qxd4  , it is powerful for your queen to be out since Black has no knight to attack it with ...Nc6.  The most popular alternatives are @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Bc4  , the Italian Opening, or  3.Bb5  , the Ruy Lopez. These also follow the golden rules as you develop and get ready to castle.  But the Scotch Opening is challenging Black right after  3...exd4  4.Nxd4  .  They shouldn't trade knights here. And it's good for you because, at the Club Player level, many players still make the mistake of trading knights with  4...Nxd4  .  The Scotch also leads to more open games, making getting all your pieces out easier. }
3... exd4 { Black should take your pawn, or else you could take theirs. } 4.
Nxd4
{ You take the pawn back. In the Scotch, this opens up space for your other bishop, letting you develop your bishops wherever you like and castle on either side. }
4... Qh4 { Black gets bold, bringing out the queen early! } 5. Nc3
{ You move your knight to protect the pawn. } 5... Bb4
{ Black pins your knight, creating a threat with ...Qxe4! It's tough to guard the e4-pawn.  Swapping knights with  6.Nxc6?  doesn't work because Black will take your pawn with  6...Qxe4+  and only then capture the knight. So, you decide to let go of the pawn for a lead in development. }
6. Be2
{ You develop the bishop, preparing to castle. There is a cunning tactical idea behind this move.  Like in the @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/8/3NP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Qf6  variation, you also want to use the  5.Nb5  idea to counterattack the c7-pawn. Unfortunately in this line after @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/8/3NP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Qh4  5.Nc3  Bb4  the direct  6.Ndb5  doesn't work well yet because Black can defend it with  6...Ba5   By first developing with @@StartFEN@@r1b1k1nr/pppp1ppp/2n5/8/1b1NP2q/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 3 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Be2  and giving up the pawn  6...Qxe4  , you make sure that after  7.Ndb5  Black can no longer defend with  7...Ba5?  Black's bishop needed to keep your knight pinned to safeguard the queen.  8.Nxc7+  is now crushing because after  8...Bxc7  9.Nxe4  wins the queen }
6... Qxe4 { Black takes your pawn, making a threat with ... Qxd4. } 7. Nb5
{ You move your knight, threatening Nxc7+ to fork Black's king and rook. } 7...
Bxc3+
{ Black takes your knight. To keep the fork threat alive, you recapture with the pawn.  Don't worry about  7...Qxg2  , because you can respond with  8.Bf3  attacking the queen and still threatening Nxc7. }
8. bxc3 Kd8
{ Black moves their king to counter your threats. This means they can't castle anymore. }
9. O-O
{ You castle, finishing your development. You have plans to move Bf3 to improve your bishop's position and use your rooks on Rb1 and Re1 for the open files. }
9... a6
{ Black tries to push your knight away.  If Black plays  9...Nf6  , you have many good moves like  10.Bg5  to pin the knight or  10.Re1  to get the rook on the open file. }
10. Nd4 Nxd4 11. cxd4
{ You're a pawn down but have the bishop pair, a safer king, and are ahead in development.  You want to get your rook to the open e-file with Re1. If Black plays  11...Nf6  , consider  12.Bg5  to pin the knight. }
