{ The Classical Mainline. Against all the main responses in the Scotch you aim for the pin setup. The two main variations are the Classical mainline and the Schmidt Variation.   4...Nf6  The Schmidt Variation, which is about as popular as the Classical Mainline  5.Nc3  Bb4  6.Nxc6  In this variation, you trade the knights first.  6...bxc6  7.Bd3  And you will also aim for the pin setup with O-O and Bg5. }
5. Nb3
{ You counterattack the bishop!  Developing and defending with  5.Be3  is more common. However, when Black replies with  5...Qf6  , attacking the knight again, we need to play  6.c3  taking away the natural square for the knight. To keep things simple, I like that in every opening, we can develop our knights to f3 and c3. }
5... Bb6 6. Nc3 d6 7. Bd3 { 7...Nf6  transposes here. } 7... Nge7
{ Black choses the e7-square to avoid the pin. } 8. Qe2
{ Black cleverly avoids allowing you to block his knight, as after @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/ppp2ppp/1bnp4/8/4P3/1NNB4/PPP2PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Nf6  8.O-O  O-O  9.Bg5  .  The pin when Black has the Knight on e7 is not effective; the Knight is safer and Black can block it with...f6.  So, you change your strategy. Now you aim to play Be3, exchanging Black's strong dark bishop, and castling on the queenside.   This does not work well after @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/ppp2ppp/1bnp4/8/4P3/1NNB4/PPP2PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Nf6  , since after  8.Qe2  there is a strong Black response,  8...Ng4  attacking the vulnerable f2 pawn. }
8... O-O 9. Be3
{ You neutralize Black's powerful dark-squared bishop. Now that you have your bishop here, there is no need to exchange it directly as it could help Black activate the rook. }
9... Ng6 10. f4
{ You gain more control in the center and take away the e5-squares for Black's knights. Next, you get ready to castle queenside and play g3 to solidify your pawns on the kingside. }
10... Nb4 11. f5
{ You kick the knight away to prepare to castle queenside.   11.O-O-O?  is not good because Black can play  11...Bg4!  when after  12.Qxg4  Bxe3+  13.Kb1  Bxf4  Black wins a pawn. }
11... Ne5 12. O-O-O
{ In this position, you like to play Kb1 to get a safer position. After that, you can aim for more aggressive ideas with Bb5, Bf4 aiming to target the pinned knight. }
