{ You're using golden rule one again, moving another pawn to the center. Your knight protects the pawn, so you don't need to move your queen out to take back the pawn.  After  3...exd4  4.Nxd4  Nxd4  5.Qxd4  , it is powerful for your queen to be out since Black has no knight to attack it with ...Nc6.  The most popular alternatives are @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Bc4  , the Italian Opening, or  3.Bb5  , the Ruy Lopez. These also follow the golden rules as you develop and get ready to castle.  But the Scotch Opening is challenging Black right after  3...exd4  4.Nxd4  .  They shouldn't trade knights here. And it's good for you because, at the Club Player level, many players still make the mistake of trading knights with  4...Nxd4  .  The Scotch also leads to more open games, making getting all your pieces out easier. }
3... exd4 { Black should take your pawn, or else you could take theirs. } 4.
Nxd4
{ You take the pawn back. In the Scotch, this opens up space for your other bishop, letting you develop your bishops wherever you like and castle on either side. }
4... Bc5
{ The Classical Mainline. Against all the main responses in the Scotch you aim for the pin setup. The two main variations are the Classical mainline and the Schmidt Variation.   4...Nf6  The Schmidt Variation, which is about as popular as the Classical Mainline  5.Nc3  Bb4  6.Nxc6  In this variation, you trade the knights first.  6...bxc6  7.Bd3  And you will also aim for the pin setup with O-O and Bg5. }
5. Nb3
{ You counterattack the bishop!  Developing and defending with  5.Be3  is more common. However, when Black replies with  5...Qf6  , attacking the knight again, we need to play  6.c3  taking away the natural square for the knight. To keep things simple, I like that in every opening, we can develop our knights to f3 and c3. }
5... Bb6 6. Nc3 Nf6 7. Bd3
{ You follow the development plan with the Pin Setup! This is only the fourth most popular move for White in this position.  After the direct  7.Bg5  h6  8.Bh4  g5  9.Bg3  Black can use the fact that you haven't castle yet and create a pin with  9...Qe7  10.Bd3  and attack the pinned pawn with  10...d5  I wouldn't rather avoid that. }
7... d6 8. O-O O-O 9. Bg5
{ You are ready for Kh1 followed by f4 to keep the knight pinned and prevent plans to break free with ...h6-g5 }
9... h6 10. Bh4
{ You will keep the pin! When Black doesn't play ...g5 to unpin the knight, you have the plan Kh1 unpinning the f2-pawn followed by f4, which prevents ...g5 and keeps the knight stuck in the pin. }
10... Re8 11. Kh1 Be6
{ This transposes with @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp2ppp/1bnp1n2/6B1/4P3/1NNB4/PPP2PPP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 3 9@@EndFEN@@  10...Be6  11.Kh1  Re8 }
12. f4
{ At this point, the knight is in an eternal pin! You don't need to rush to attack the pinned knight. }
12... g5
{ Black can try to unpin with a tactical trick! When Black doesn't play ...g5 their knight will stay stuck in the pin. You plan to play Nd2-Nf3 and prepare e5 to attack the pinned knight! }
13. fxg5 Ng4 { Now Black is suddenly pinning your g5-pawn. } 14. Nd5
{ After  14.Qd2  Black has the resource  14...Be3  double attack. } 14... hxg5
15. Nf6+
{ A fantastic idea! You give up the knight to return to the situation where you are pinning the knight. }
15... Nxf6 16. Bxg5
{ You return to the classical pin setup with a devastating effect! In the next move, you will win back the knight with Bxf6 and have a crushing kingside attack. }
