14. Kh1 { You go for the standard plan and aim for f4! } 14... Nxe4
{ Black has to play actively and use a tactical combination to win a pawn as their kingside is severely weakened. }
15. Nxe4 d5 { Black attacks the pinned knight. } 16. f4
{ You continue with your attacking plan! } 16... Rxe4 17. Qh5
{ You're setting up to open the f-file with fxg5. In this position, Black can survive your attack with careful play, but being White is more advantageous. Black's best response is  17...gxf4  , followed by  18.Bxf4  .  The crucial move for Black then is  18...Qf6  , which is their strongest defense. However, this move allows a discovered attack with  19.Bxc7  , where you win a pawn. The game should continue with  19...Qg6  20.Qxg6  fxg6  21.Bxb6  axb6  .   Alternatively, if Black plays @@StartFEN@@r2q2k1/ppp2p2/1bn4p/3p2pQ/4rP2/1N4B1/PPP3PP/R4R1K b - - 1 17@@EndFEN@@  17...Qf6  , you can proceed with  18.fxg5  .  In this scenario, Black cannot recapture the pawn and should aim to exchange queens with  18...Qg6  .  This allows you to gain a material advantage with  19.Qxh6  , capturing another pawn. }
