{ You attack the bishop immediately! There is also nothing wrong with 12.Rb1 }
12... Bxa1 { Black should capture the rook now! } 13. Qxa1 O-O
{ Black's position allows castling, as your knight now blocks the bishop's diagonal.  However, this move allows you to regain material through a discovered attack. If Black plays  13...Qd4  , you can smartly sidestep with  14.Qb1  .  This maneuver leaves Black unable to castle in either direction.  Should Black attempt  14...O-O  , you have a sharp tactical response with  15.Bxh7+  .  This move cannot be safely recaptured by  15...Kxh7  , due to the discovered attack you unleash with  16.c3+  .  Therefore, Black's best reply is @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/ppp2ppB/2n1b3/2N5/3q4/B7/P1P2PPP/1Q3RK1 b - - 0 15@@EndFEN@@  15...Kh8  , but this still leaves them vulnerable to another discovered attack. You can then play  16.Nxe6  fxe6  17.Bxf8  , seizing a significant material advantage. }
14. Nxe6 fxe6 15. Bxf8 Qxf8 16. Re1
{ The dust has settled! You attack the e6-pawn. When Black defends, Qb1 is a good move to attack the b7-pawn. }
