8... Re8
{ Black brings the rook to the open file and attacks the e4-pawn again.   8...d5  transposes to the mainline. }
9. Bg5 { You develop and pin the knight. } 9... h6
{ Black tries to push your bishop away, marking a crucial moment in the game. Your bishop is more valuable than the knight right now. Because of the pin the knight can't move, which is a significant advantage for you.  So, taking the knight with  10.Bxf6?  would be a mistake; it would relieve the pressure and allow Black's queen to become active with  10...Qxf6  .  The better move is to maintain the pin by playing  10.Bh4  . }
10. Bh4 g5
{ Black forces unpinning the knight, which weakens their king safety.  After  10...Be7  , you have multiple strong plans! You can keep developing with  11.Re1  d6  and go for  12.f4  Also, you can go for the direct  11.e5  when after  11...Nd5  12.Bg3  is strong, keeping Black's queen stuck and planning Qf3-Qe4-Qh7+  @@StartFEN@@r1bqr1k1/p1pp1pp1/2p2n1p/8/1b2P2B/2NB4/PPP2PPP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 1 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Rb8  11.f4  transposes to the line you saw before. }
