{ You develop and defend the e4-pawn. An alternative that I don't recommend is to go for the Scotch mainline with  5.Nxc6  bxc6  6.e5  when Black will go for  6...Qe7  pinning your pawn. I believe that the Scotch mainline and  5.Nc3  offer equally good chances to put pressure on your opponent. A big advantage of the  5.Nc3  move is that you can also get these positions versus the Petrov defense, which cuts down the theory you need to study for another important opening.  So @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppp1ppp/8/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Nf6  The Petrov Defense is answered with  3.Nc3  when the most common move  3...Nc6  4.d4  exd4  5.Nxd4  you are back in this same position }
5... Bb4
{ Black pins the knight and threatens to capture the e4-pawn with ...Nxe4!    Therefore, you first exchange knights and then play Bd3 to guard the pawn. }
6. Nxc6 bxc6
{ After  6...dxc6  , you play  7.Qxd8+  trades the queens and breaks Black's right to castle. }
7. Bd3
{ You develop your piece and protect the e4-pawn.  When Black plays  7...Bxc3+?  , leading to  8.bxc3  , the resulting trade works in your favor. Despite ending up with doubled pawns, you gain an advantage. In an open position like this, your bishop becomes more powerful than the knight. The bishop's long-range capabilities make it a stronger piece than the knight in open positions. }
7... d5 8. exd5 { The pawns are facing in the center so you trade } 8... O-O
{ Black continues development and doesn't recapture the pawn. } 9. O-O
{ You also castle and safeguard your king.  9.dxc6?  would be risky since Black can attack with  9...Re8+ }
9... Bg4
{ Black develops and attacks the queen.  9...cxd5  10.Bg5  transposes back to the mainline, which you will study soon. }
10. Be2
{ You strategically block the attack with your bishop.  Playing  10.f3  is also possible but weakens your pawn structure and opens a diagonal towards your king, a vulnerability you want to avoid. }
10... Bxe2 11. Nxe2
{ You take with the knight because, after Black recaptures with  11...cxd5  and you pin with  12.Bg5  ,  you can nicely use the knight in the attack. You can then play Nd4 next, aiming for a fork on c6, or possibly switch to attack with Nf5. }
11... cxd5
{ Black could also play  12...Re8  trying to keep the tension in the center. You can't capture with  13.dxc6  because after  13...Qxd1  14.Rxd1  Rxe2  you lose the knight. Therefore, you can immediately create the pin with @@StartFEN@@r2qr1k1/p1p2ppp/2p2n2/3P4/1b6/8/PPP1NPPP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 1 12@@EndFEN@@  13.Bg5  when Black has to recapture with  13...cxd5  and you transpose here. }
12. Bg5 { You are pinning the knight as usual. } 12... c6 13. Nd4 Rc8
{ Defending with the rook is risky for Black. } 14. Qf3
{ You increase the pressure on the knight. } 14... Be7
{ Defending with the bishop now would be horrible! } 15. Nf5
{ You bring your knight in the attack! } 15... h6 16. Bxh6
{ Thank you for the pawn!  16.Rae1  would have been just as crushing when after  16...hxg5  17.Nxe7+  wins the exchange with the fork. }
16... gxh6 { Black shouldn't capture back, as this is now losing! } 17. Qg3+
{ This check is deadly! } 17... Ng4 18. Qxg4+ Bg5 19. f4
{ And you win the pinned bishop!   19.h4  would also be winning but why not activate your rook by opening the f-file? }
