{ Whenever you can cause the doubled pawns and Black also spent a tempo on ...h6 you capture. }
12... Qxf6 13. Qxf6 gxf6 14. Ne2
{ You move your knight away. In this endgame, you would like to prove that Black's damaged pawn structure is problematic. }
14... Bd6 15. Nd4
{ You jump forward to pressure the c6-pawn and eye for the strong f5-square immediately. }
15... c5 { Black should immediately attack your knight. } 16. Nf5
{ You always like to control the weak f5-square in this endgame. } 16... Bxf5
{ Capturing the knight is the most common response in this situation. Contrary to what many might think, an endgame with opposite-colored bishops is not always an easy draw. This is evident from Grandmaster Parayan's games, where he triumphed over Grandmasters Hansen, Jumabayev, Parligras, Tang, Lazavik, and Raja from this position. If a player can consistently win against six grandmasters, it indicates that this endgame scenario is not a straightforward draw.  Another viable option for Black is @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/p4p2/3b1p1p/2pp1N2/8/3B4/PPP2PPP/R4RK1 b - - 1 16@@EndFEN@@  16...Be5  , though it's not frequently played. In response, a straightforward approach for you would be  17.Nxh6+  Kg7  18.Nf5+  Bxf5  19.Bxf5  Bxb2  , followed by  20.Rd1  .  This puts significant pressure on Black's d5 pawn. }
17. Bxf5 Be5
{ Black can also play other moves, but your plans will always be similar to going for Rad1 and putting pressure on the d5-pawn. Also, b3 is always a typical move to safeguard your own pawns. }
18. Rad1 { You get your rook to the center. } 18... Bxb2 19. Rxd5 Bd4 20. Rd7
{ Your move positions the rook to watch over the a7-pawn, effectively keeping Black's rook on  a8  inactive. This strategic placement gives you various options to increase pressure on your opponent. You can consider moving your bishop to Bd3 and Bc4, which would intensify the attack on the f7-pawn.  Another beneficial move is g3, allowing you to free your f2-pawn by moving your king to Kg2.  In the games that reached this position,  20.c3  was the most common move. Unfortunately, after  20...Bxc3  21.Rxc5  , the game typically reaches a position with limited opportunities for further play, often resulting in a draw. Trading the c-pawn has the advantage for Black that the a7-pawn can also be defended by the bishop. }
