{ Discovering this move opens up powerful attacking possibilities. One idea is to initiate a mating attack with Qh4, Additionally, the queen controls the b8-square, preventing Black from activating their rook there.  While you might appear to be setting up for a Bh6 Qxg7 tactic, it's usually not the ideal plan, as Black can defend effectively with ...Nh5 after Bh6.  In the beginner version of your repertoire, I recommended @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/p3bppp/2p2n2/3p2B1/8/2NB1Q2/PPP2PPP/R4RK1 w - - 2 12@@EndFEN@@  12.h3  , which is still a solid move. However, after Black's common responses like  12...h6  13.Bh4  Be6  14.Ne2  Nd7  15.Bxe7  Qxe7  16.Nd4  Ne5  or plans involving  13...Rb8  14.b3  Rb4  15.Bg3  Bd6  , the game tends to balance out. These positions are approximately equal, and because many minor pieces are exchanged, applying significant pressure on your opponent can be challenging. }
12... Be6 13. Rae1
{ Moving your rook to the center is a strategic choice. In such positions, keeping the rook on f1 is often beneficial, as advancing the f-pawn can be a strong attacking maneuver.  However, opting for  13.Qh4  immediately isn't advisable here. If you play  13.Qh4  , Black can respond with  13...h6  . Then, if you continue with  14.Bxh6  , Black has the strong move  14...Ne4  , creating a discovered attack on your queen. Following up with  15.Qh5  gxh6  16.Qxh6  would result in losing your bishop for two pawns and, importantly, without a potent attack.  Another tempting move might be @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/p3bppp/2p1bn2/3p2B1/8/2NB2Q1/PPP2PPP/R4RK1 w - - 4 13@@EndFEN@@  13.Bh6  , aiming to threaten mate. But this move is easily neutralized by  13...Nh5  from Black effectively counters your threat. In this scenario, it's crucial to consider moves that maintain pressure while keeping your major pieces active and ready for future tactical opportunities. }
13... Nh5
{ Black attacks your queen.   13...Kh8?  is still played frequently here when you can again go for your devastating attack with  14.Qh4 }
14. Bxe7
{ You capture the bishop and give Black a dilemma in deciding whether they should capture back or take your queen. }
14... Nxg3
{ The wrong choice for Black, as now you will gain two pieces for the rook. }
15. Bxd8 Nxf1 16. Bg5
{ And the knight is trapped.  Black could still play  16...h6  , but it doesn't help since after  17.Bc1  or  17.Bf4  g5  18.Bc1  , the knight is still trapped. }
