{ If you play  2.d4  , putting your other pawn in the center, Black would play  2...exd4  3.Qxd4  Nc6  and get ahead by attacking your queen. That's why the second golden rule is to develop and play  2.Nf3  , hitting the pawn. }
2... Nc6 { Black also makes a move and protects the pawn. } 3. d4
{ You're using golden rule one again, moving another pawn to the center. Your knight protects the pawn, so you don't need to move your queen out to take back the pawn.  After  3...exd4  4.Nxd4  Nxd4  5.Qxd4  , it is powerful for your queen to be out since Black has no knight to attack it with  ...Nc6  .  The most popular alternatives are @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Bc4  , the Italian Opening, or  3.Bb5  , the Ruy Lopez. These also follow the golden rules as you develop and get ready to castle.  But the Scotch Opening is challenging Black right after  3...exd4  4.Nxd4  .  They shouldn't trade knights here. And it's good for you because, at the Club Player level, many players still make the mistake of trading knights with  4...Nxd4  .  The Scotch also leads to more open games, making getting all your pieces out easier. }
3... exd4 { Black should take your pawn, or else you could take theirs. } 4.
Nxd4
{ You take the pawn back. In the Scotch, this opens up space for your other bishop, letting you develop your bishops wherever you like and castle on either side. }
4... Nf6
{ Black develops the knight and attacks the e4-pawn.  This is the Schmidt variation, which is becoming more popular than the classical mainline }
5. Nc3
{ You develop and defend the e4-pawn. An alternative that I don't recommend is to go for the Scotch mainline with  5.Nxc6  bxc6  6.e5  when Black will go for  6...Qe7  pinning your pawn. I believe that the Scotch mainline and  5.Nc3  offer equally good chances to put pressure on your opponent. A big advantage of the  5.Nc3  move is that you can also get these positions versus the Petrov defense, which cuts down the theory you need to study for another important opening.  So @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppp1ppp/8/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Nf6  The Petrov Defense is answered with  3.Nc3  when the most common move  3...Nc6  4.d4  exd4  5.Nxd4  you are back in this same position }
5... Bb4
{ Black pins the knight and threatens to capture the e4-pawn with ...Nxe4!    Therefore, you first exchange knights and then play Bd3 to guard the pawn. }
6. Nxc6 bxc6
{ After  6...dxc6  , you play  7.Qxd8+  trades the queens and breaks Black's right to castle. }
7. Bd3
{ You develop your piece and protect the e4-pawn.  When Black plays  7...Bxc3+?  , leading to  8.bxc3  , the resulting trade works in your favor. Despite ending up with doubled pawns, you gain an advantage. In an open position like this, your bishop becomes more powerful than the knight. The bishop's long-range capabilities make it a stronger piece than the knight in open positions. }
7... d5 8. exd5 { The pawns are facing in the center so you trade } 8... cxd5
9. O-O { You follow the third golden rule and castle. } 9... O-O
{ Black also finishes development and castles } 10. Bg5
{ You reach the Pin Development Setup. Black has to be careful and support the center on the next move }
10... c6 { Black supports the d5-pawn. } 11. Qf3
{ When you are pinning you want to add attackers. } 11... Be7 12. Qg3
{ Discovering this move opens up powerful attacking possibilities. One idea is to initiate a mating attack with Qh4, Additionally, the queen controls the b8-square, preventing Black from activating their rook there.  While you might appear to be setting up for a Bh6 Qxg7 tactic, it's usually not the ideal plan, as Black can defend effectively with ...Nh5 after Bh6.  In the beginner version of your repertoire, I recommended @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/p3bppp/2p2n2/3p2B1/8/2NB1Q2/PPP2PPP/R4RK1 w - - 2 12@@EndFEN@@  12.h3  , which is still a solid move. However, after Black's common responses like  12...h6  13.Bh4  Be6  14.Ne2  Nd7  15.Bxe7  Qxe7  16.Nd4  Ne5  or plans involving  13...Rb8  14.b3  Rb4  15.Bg3  Bd6  , the game tends to balance out. These positions are approximately equal, and because many minor pieces are exchanged, applying significant pressure on your opponent can be challenging. }
12... Nh5
{ Black starts harassing your queen and gives a discovered attack on the bishop.   12...Bd6  is another option for Black, which is not played much, and after  13.Qh4  Black is obligated to play  13...h6  , after which you can go for the typical trade with  14.Bxf6  Qxf6  15.Qxf6  gxf6  16.Ne2  , this is an endgame position you are used to. }
13. Bxe7 { It's time to capture the bishop and attack back. } 13... Qxe7 14.
Qe3
{ This move, which involves trading queens and resulting in an isolated e-pawn, might seem unusual and has been played only once. At first glance, it appears counterintuitive – why would one willingly enter into a position with a pawn weakness and reduced material? You will see that this trade can open the f-file for the rook, but also, having the pawn on the e-file allows you to trade it later with e4 and give Black a worse pawn structure. }
14... Qxe3 15. fxe3
{ The idea is that you plan to trade off this weak pawn with e4. After that you would have a better pawn structure. Also, this move opened up the f-file for the rook. }
15... f5 { Getting more control on the e4-square doesn't help Black. } 16. g4
{ You use some tactics and fork the knight and pawn.  Also, even  16.e4  would have been possible because after  16...fxe4  17.Nxe4  Black cannot capture the knight with  17...dxe4  since  18.Bc4  is a deadly check. }
16... Nf6 { The knight goes back. } 17. gxf5
{ You capture the pawn and are a pawn up! You want to go for Rae1 and e4, getting rid of your backward e-pawn. When Black attacks with ...Rb8, you can always play b3 to safeguard your pawn. }
*

