{ You can make Black's pawn structure weaker with  12.Bxf6  Qxf6  13.Qxf6  gxf6  .   Doing this would give Black the advantage of having the bishop pair. But you don't need to hurry to make this move. Your position is already strong because you are pinning Black's knight. The knight can't move, and Black's queen has to keep protecting it. It's best to capture the knight only when you can mess up Black's pawns and force Black to play ...h6. This strategy keeps you in control, letting you choose the right moment to strike. }
12. h3
{ GM Roeland Pruijssers had some games with  12.Ne2  and made a draw with this line against top GM Andreikin. }
12... h6 13. Bxf6
{ YYou capture the knight whenever Black provokes you to do so, which also destroys their pawn structure. }
13... Qxf6 14. Qxf6 gxf6 15. Ne2
{ You anticipate a possible pin on the knight! If Black could move again with  15...Rb8  16.b3  Be5  would pin the knight. }
15... Rb8 16. b3
{ In the position you've reached, all your pieces are securely defended, a hallmark of a robust setup. It's a common misconception among club players that games are lost primarily due to a single tactical error. However, such blunders are often caused by minor mistakes, like placing pieces on unprotected squares, slow development, or a weak pawn structure. In a well-coordinated position like this, where every piece is protected, the likelihood of falling into tactical traps is significantly reduced.   This solid foundation allows you to play with more confidence and less risk of making big blunders. You can further improve your position by playing Rad1 and Rfe1, enabling you to target the d5-pawn with c4. Additionally, consider repositioning your knight with Nd3-Nf5. This maneuver targets Black's bishop and puts pressure on the h6-pawn, potentially creating weaknesses in Black's pawn structure that you can exploit. }
