{ Your opponent pins your knight! So let's create a counterpin.  13...h6  brings you to the same endgame  14.Bxf6  Qxf6  15.Qxf6  gxf6  16.Ne2  . }
14. Bf4
{ Pinning the bishop to the rook!   14.Bd2  would be a sound alternative. When Black adds an attacker to the pinned piece with  14...Qa5  , you still have your knight sufficiently protected  15.Rae1  moves out of the pin and attacks the bishop, after which  15...Bxc3  16.Bxc3  Qxc3  falls for the discovered attack  17.Bxh7+  . }
14... Bxc3
{ When Black plays  14...Bxf4  15.Qxf4  Be6  , you can go for  16.Na4  , aiming for Nc5. Also, you can reroute the knight with  16.Ne2  as you did before. }
15. Bxb8 Bxa1 16. Rxa1 Bg4
{ A precise move from Black, regaining the bishop pair. } 17. hxg4 Qxb8 18. Re1
{ You get your rook to the open file! Black is in a difficult situation. }
18... Re8
{ This would be an obvious move for Black that is wrong. I had this position in a classical game against Van Der Linde and my opponent played this within 1 minute, after which I converted the rest of the game quite smoothly. }
19. Rxe8+ Qxe8 20. Qf4
{ Your queen is strong on this diagonal and you will start attacking Black's weak pawns on the queenside. }
20... Qe1+ 21. Bf1
{ You block with the bishop! Black doesn't have a good way to use the pin, and you still threaten backrank mate.  After  21.Kh2?  Nd7  22.Qc7  doesn't win anything because Black can still exchange the queens with  22...Qe5+  or Black could even play  22...Qxf2  when after  23.Qxd7  Qh4+  24.Kg1  Qe1+  , the game would end in a perpetual with  25.Bf1  Qe3+  26.Kh2  Qh6+  27.Kg3  Qe3+ }
21... h5 { Black's only move to get some counterplay! } 22. Qb8+ Kh7 23. Qxa7
hxg4 24. Qe3
{ Next, you want to start running your passed a-pawn down the board as quickly as possible.   24...Qxe3?  25.fxe3  would be a winning endgame for White.  @@StartFEN@@8/5ppk/2p2n2/3p4/6p1/1P2Q3/P1P2PP1/4qBK1 b - - 1 24@@EndFEN@@  24...Qb1  is Black's only good move when you can start with  25.a4 }
