3... Nc6 4. d4
{ The Four Knights Scotch. You use the first golden rule and place the pawn in the center.  After  4...exd4  5.Nxd4  , you are back in your Scotch theory and managed to deal with the Petrov opening without studying much more theory. }
4... Bb4
{ One other option for Black is to pin the knight.  After  4...d6  , you can again play  5.dxe5  dxe5  and break Black's right to castle with  6.Qxd8+ }
5. Nxe5
{ You capture the pawn with the knight. Capturing with the knight opens the diagonal for the queen, which can come in handy. }
5... O-O 6. Nxc6
{ You trade the knights! Your e4-pawn is in danger because of the pin on your knight so you want to move it forward. }
6... dxc6 7. e5 { It's time to attack! } 7... Ne4
{ Black puts pressure on your pinned knight! Other attempts from Black are not as threatening as  7...Nd5  can be met with  8.Bd2  , although there is also not much wrong with  8.Qd3  . }
8. Qd3
{ You support your knight with the queen!  8.Bd2?  would be a big mistake since this allows  8...Qxd4  . }
8... Bf5 { Black desperately needs to find some counterplay. } 9. a3
{ A thematic move. You force Black to get rid of the pin. } 9... Bxc3+
{ Black goes for the trade.  After  9...Qd7  , you have multiple good options  10.axb4  is strong even though it allows  10...Nxf2  11.Qc4  Nxh1  but after  12.Be3  Black's knight is misplaced in the corner.  Apart from that, after @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/ppp2ppp/2p5/4Pb2/1b1Pn3/P1NQ4/1PP2PPP/R1B1KB1R b KQ - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Qd7  you could also sidestep the attack with  10.Qf3 }
10. bxc3 Bg6
{ Black wants to make sure the bishop is defended to threaten ...Nxf2 } 11. Qe3
{ You sidestep and get away from the attack. In this position, you want play Bb2 and castle queenside as quickly as possible. After that, you can also try to trap the knight with f3.  If you could move again, don't go for @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/ppp2ppp/2p3b1/4P3/3Pn3/P1P1Q3/2P2PPP/R1B1KB1R w KQ - 2 11@@EndFEN@@  12.f3  directly, as Black has  12...Qh4  with a counterattack.  Also, this @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/ppp2ppp/2p3b1/4P3/3Pn3/P1P1Q3/2P2PPP/R1B1KB1R w KQ - 2 11@@EndFEN@@  12.f3  wouldn't even have trapped the knight as after  12...Nd6  , you can't capture  13.exd6  since  13...Re8  pins your queen. When you are castled queenside, f3 is a move that can trap the knight. }
