[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ The Petrov opening! This is a solid opening choice for Black, aiming to contest the center right from the beginning. Good news! I recommend a solution where you will often transpose back to the Scotch Opening. The advantage of this strategy is that you can stay within a familiar territory, avoiding the main lines of the Petrov Defense. }
3. Nc3
{ You develop the knight and defend your central pawn. This simple move will likely bring you back to the Scotch opening.   3.Nxe5  is the most played move when Black first kicks back your knight with  3...d6  4.Nf3  and then also wins your central pawn with  4...Nxe4   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppp1ppp/5n2/4p3/4P3/2N2N2/PPPP1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3.d4  is also an alternative which I am recommending in my Attacking Repertoire for Club Players. }
3... Nc6 4. d4
{ The Four Knights Scotch. You use the first golden rule and place the pawn in the center.  After  4...exd4  5.Nxd4  , you are back in your Scotch theory and managed to deal with the Petrov opening without studying much more theory. }
4... Bb4
{ One other option for Black is to pin the knight.  After  4...d6  , you can again play  5.dxe5  dxe5  and break Black's right to castle with  6.Qxd8+ }
5. Nxe5
{ You capture the pawn with the knight. Capturing with the knight opens the diagonal for the queen, which can come in handy. }
5... Qe7 6. Qd3
{ You go for the same plan and support the e4-pawn.   6.Nxc6?  now would allow Black to capture a pawn with check  6...Qxe4+  before recapturing the knight. }
6... Bxc3+
{ The best move for Black is to capture your knight! This move isn't played that often. }
7. Qxc3 Nxe4 { Black wins the central pawn. } 8. Qe3 { You block the e-file. }
8... Nd6 9. Bd2 { You develop and go for a queenside castle. } 9... Nf5
{ Black goes for a double attack on your queen and central pawn, but you anticipated this. }
10. Nxc6 { You counterattack Black's queen and set a little trap. } 10... Nxe3
{ Capturing the queen would be a big mistake for Black. } 11. Nxe7 Nxc2+ 12.
Kd1 Nxa1 { You will win this knight back in the corner. } 13. Nxc8
{ You trade the knight for the bishop. } 13... Rxc8 14. Bd3
{ You will win the knight back with Bf4, Kd2, Rxa1 or with Ke2, Rxa1, and after, you will have a dominating advantage in the endgame with the bishop pair. }
