[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2a) Petrov and Philidor Defenses "]
[Black "Stafford Gambit: 3...Bc5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ The Petrov opening! This is a solid opening choice for Black, aiming to contest the center right from the beginning. Good news! I recommend a solution where you will often transpose back to the Scotch Opening. The advantage of this strategy is that you can stay within a familiar territory, avoiding the main lines of the Petrov Defense. }
3. Nc3
{ You develop the knight and defend your central pawn. This simple move will likely bring you back to the Scotch opening.   3.Nxe5  is the most played move when Black first kicks back your knight with  3...d6  4.Nf3  and then also wins your central pawn with  4...Nxe4   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppp1ppp/5n2/4p3/4P3/2N2N2/PPPP1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3.d4  is also an alternative which I am recommending in my Attacking Repertoire for Club Players. }
3... Bc5 { This move leaves Black central pawn hanging for free. } 4. Nxe5
{ You capture the pawn. } 4... Nc6
{ The Stafford Gambit! A hugely popular online opening advocated by Eric Rosen. You should not underestimate this objectively dubious gambit, as it contains devilish tricks.  The position gets complicated after  5.Nxc6  dxc6  when Black aims for ...Ng4 and start targeting our king with all the pieces. You can defend with  6.h3  , but after  6...h5  , the natural development moves  7.Be2  and  7.Bc4  would still be wrong, and you would have to play more unnatural moves to secure your opening advantage.  I recommend an approach that's less complicated. You retreat the knight, not activating Black's queen and bishop and keeping the pawn up. Also, in the position after @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pppp1ppp/2n2n2/2b1N3/4P3/2N5/PPPP1PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Nxc6  dxc6  , you cannot play d4; you play e4 and d4 in every White opening in the repertoire. There is one exception where you play dxc3 here but never play d3. }
5. Nf3 { You are ready to play d4 next move. } 5... O-O
{ Black speeds up development. 5...Nd4 is the best move according to the computer, but it doesn't pose any danger. You can keep developing with 6.Be2 and stay a healthy pawn up. }
6. d4 { You take the center and gain a tempo back. } 6... Bb4
{ Black pins your knight and targets the e4-pawn. } 7. Bd3
{ You develop and secure the e4-pawn. You are ready to castle on the next move. }
7... Re8 8. O-O { 8.e5 to save the pawn is a sound alternative. } 8... Bxc3
{ Black eliminates your defending knight. } 9. bxc3 Nxe4
{ Black captures your central pawn. This is risky for Black! You can force the rook forward and start an attack. }
10. Bxe4 Rxe4 11. Ng5
{ You bring your knight into the attack with crushing power! Hitting the rook but also eyeing at the weak f7 and h7-pawns. }
11... Re8
{ After  11...Rh4  , the rook is misplaced, and the most straightforward way is to go for  12.g3  since  12...Rh6  leads to  13.Nxf7+  discovered attack  13...Kxf7  14.Bxh6 }
12. Qh5
{ It's game over; you destroyed the Stafford Gambit, as Black can't defend against both Qxf7+ and Qxh7+ }
*

