{ The Stafford Gambit! A hugely popular online opening advocated by Eric Rosen. You should not underestimate this objectively dubious, as it contains devilish tricks.  The position gets complicated after  5.Nxc6  dxc6  when Black aims for ...Ng4 and start targeting our king with all the pieces. You can defend with  6.h3  , but after  6...h5  , the natural development moves  7.Be2  and  7.Bc4  would still be wrong, and you would have to play more unnatural moves to secure your opening advantage.  I recommend an approach that's less complicated. You retreat the knight, not activating Black's queen and bishop and keeping the pawn up. Also, in the position after @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pppp1ppp/2n2n2/2b1N3/4P3/2N5/PPPP1PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Nxc6  dxc6  , you cannot play d4; you play e4 and d4 in every White opening in the repertoire. There is one exception where you play dxc3 here but never play d3. }
5. Nf3 { You are ready to play d4 next move. } 5... O-O
{ Black speeds up development. 5...Nd4 is the best move according to the computer, but it doesn't pose any danger. You can keep developing with 6.Be2 and stay a healthy pawn up. }
6. d4 { You take the center and gain a tempo back. } 6... Bb4
{ Black pins your knight and targets the e4-pawn. } 7. Bd3
{ You develop and secure the e4-pawn. You are ready to castle on the next move. }
7... Re8 8. O-O { 8.e5 to save the pawn is a sound alternative. } 8... Bxc3
{ Black eliminates your defending knight. } 9. bxc3 Nxe4
{ Black captures your central pawn. This is risky for Black! You can force the rook forward and start an attack. }
10. Bxe4 Rxe4 11. Ng5
{ You bring your knight into the attack with crushing power! Hitting the rook but also eyeing at the weak f7 and h7-pawns. }
11... Re7 { Black is trying a better defense as they still cover the f7-pawn. }
12. d5
{ You attack the knight, which lacks good squares.   12.Qd3  is an alternative that's also crushing. }
12... Na5
{ When the knight goes to the edge of the board it no longer defends the rook and allows a winning tactical combination. }
13. Qd3 { Going for checkmate. } 13... g6 14. Nxh7
{ And after this strike it will really be game over! } 14... Kxh7 15. Bg5
{ The pin is deadly and next move Rae1 is coming. Besides that you threaten checkmate, which is also not unimportant, Qh3 gets the queen on the h-file with check and with your queen and bishop Black's king is helpless in the defense. }
15... d6 { Black controls the h3-square to prevent checkmate. } 16. Rae1
{ You attack the pinned rook and will win the rook or the queen.  Don't go for  16.Bxe7?  , your bishop is much stronger than the rook now that you are having this dominant pin. }
16... Rxe1 17. Bxd8 { White has a winning material advantage. } *

