1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ The Petrov opening! This is a solid opening choice for Black, aiming to contest the center right from the beginning. Good news! I recommend a solution where you will often transpose back to the Scotch Opening. The advantage of this strategy is that you can stay within a familiar territory, avoiding the main lines of the Petrov Defense. }
3. Nc3
{ You develop the knight and defend your central pawn. This simple move will likely bring you back to the Scotch opening.   3.Nxe5  is the most played move when Black first kicks back your knight with  3...d6  4.Nf3  and then also wins your central pawn with  4...Nxe4   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppp1ppp/5n2/4p3/4P3/2N2N2/PPPP1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3.d4  is also an alternative which I am recommending in my Attacking Repertoire for Club Players. }
3... Bb4 4. Nxe5 Bxc3
{ Black eliminates the knight! The most popular move at the Beginner level. }
5. dxc3 { You capture back and open the diagonal for the bishop. } 5... Qe7
{ Black skewers the knight and pawn. } 6. Nf3
{ You retreat the knight. Defending the knight with  6.Bf4  is also an option but doesn't save the central pawn since Black chases the knight away with  6...d6  and after  7.Nf3  Black wins the central pawn with  7...Qxe4+   @@StartFEN@@rnb1k2r/ppppqppp/5n2/8/4P3/2P2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Qd4?  would be a poor way to defend the knight since Black can chase away your queen with  6...c5  , you can't keep defending the knight, and Black will win the knight on the next move. }
6... Qxe4+ { Black captures the pawn with a check. } 7. Be2
{ You develop the bishop and get ready to castle. } 7... O-O 8. O-O
{ You follow the third golden rule and castle. You have a lead in development and would like to bring your rook to the open file to direct it towards the Black queen. }
