1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ The Petrov opening! This is a solid opening choice for Black, aiming to contest the center right from the beginning. Good news! I recommend a solution where you will often transpose back to the Scotch Opening. The advantage of this strategy is that you can stay within a familiar territory, avoiding the main lines of the Petrov Defense. }
3. Nc3
{ You develop the knight and defend your central pawn. This simple move will likely bring you back to the Scotch opening.   3.Nxe5  is the most played move when Black first kicks back your knight with  3...d6  4.Nf3  and then also wins your central pawn with  4...Nxe4   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppp1ppp/5n2/4p3/4P3/2N2N2/PPPP1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3.d4  is also an alternative which I am recommending in my Attacking Repertoire for Club Players. }
