1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ The Petrov opening! This is a solid opening choice for Black, aiming to contest the center right from the beginning. Good news! I recommend a solution where you will often transpose back to the Scotch Opening. The advantage of this strategy is that you can stay within a familiar territory, avoiding the main lines of the Petrov Defense. }
3. Nc3
{ You develop the knight and defend your central pawn. This simple move will likely bring you back to the Scotch opening.   3.Nxe5  is the most played move when Black first kicks back your knight with  3...d6  4.Nf3  and then also wins your central pawn with  4...Nxe4   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppp1ppp/5n2/4p3/4P3/2N2N2/PPPP1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3.d4  is also an alternative which I am recommending in my Attacking Repertoire for Club Players. }
3... Bb4 4. Nxe5 O-O
{ Black quickly brings the king to safety. You should always be careful to prevent pins on the e-file. Therefore, developing and placing your bishop on the e-file is a good idea. }
5. Be2 { You close the e-file to prevent Black from harassing your king. } 5...
Re8 { Skewer on the knight and pawn. } 6. Ng4
{ A move that rarely has been played before. In the only game, Grandmaster Paravyan won against Grandmaster Injic.  The idea is that you would like to trade your knight, because with  6.Nf3  , it's blocking a powerful square for your bishop, and after  6.Nd3  , when Black wins the pawn back with  6...Bxc3  7.dxc3  Nxe4  your knight is also misplaced since it's blocking your queen on the d-file.  @@StartFEN@@rnbqr1k1/pppp1ppp/5n2/4N3/1b2P3/2N5/PPPPBPPP/R1BQK2R w KQ - 3 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Nd3  or  6.Nf3  are much more common and sound alternatives. }
6... Nxe4 { Black can also directly grab back the pawn in the center. } 7. Nxe4
{ You are going for a trade of knights. } 7... Rxe4 8. c3
{ You immediately kick the bishop back. } 8... Bf8 9. d4
{ Now you create a beautiful square for your knight on e5, where it almost traps the rook. }
9... d5 { Black places the pawn in the center. } 10. Ne5
{ You get ready to trap Black's rook. } 10... Nc6
{ Signals an exchange sacrifice from Black. } 11. f3 { You trap the rook. }
11... Nxe5 12. fxe4 Qh4+ { Black is going for the counterattack. } 13. g3 Qxe4
14. O-O { Your king is safe here. } 14... Bh3 15. Rf2 Ng4 16. Rf3
{ You keep defending against the mate. Your bishop is stronger than the knight, so there is no need to give up on the light squares with  16.Bxg4  Bxg4 }
16... Re8 { The rook joins the attack. } 17. Bf1
{ You offer a trade of bishops and defend your back rank. } 17... Bxf1 18. Rxf1
{ Don't play  18.Qxf1?  as this allows  18...Qc2  and you are in big trouble as ...Qxh2# is coming. }
18... Bd6 19. Qf3
{ When your king is less safe, you should trade queens. Black should either retreat or trade. After  19...Qxf3  20.Rxf3  Re1+  21.Rf1  Rxf1+  22.Kxf1  Black can win a pawn back with  22...Nxh2+  23.Kg2  As so many pieces are traded, Black has no attack anymore, and White is doing well in the endgame. }
