[Black "Philidor 3...Nf6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d6 { The Philidor variation. } 3. d4 Nf6
{ Black counterattacks your center! } 4. dxe5 { You capture the pawn. } 4...
Nxe4
{ Black takes back your central pawn.   4...dxe5  would be an error as it allows you to play  5.Qxd8+  Kxd8  . This move disrupts Black's ability to castle. You can then go ahead with  6.Nxe5  and threaten a fork on the king and rook with Nxf7+. }
5. Bc4
{ You move your bishop and prepare a powerful double attack with Qd5, threatening both the mate and the knight.  At this moment, developing your knight first with  5.Nc3  isn't the best choice because Black can exchange with  5...Nxc3  6.bxc3  , and you will end up with doubled pawns. }
5... c6 { Black anticipates the threat. } 6. O-O
{ You follow the third golden rule and castle. } 6... d5
{ Black gets the pawn in the center and chases away your bishop. } 7. Be2
{ You retreat the bishop!   7.Bd3  is also an option, but the minor downside is that Black can aim at your strong bishop with  7...Nc5  , and then you would still have to pull back with  8.Be2  . }
7... Be7 { Black develops the bishop. } 8. c4
{ As usual, when the opponent has a central pawn defended by the queen, you first play c4 before going Nc3 }
8... O-O 9. Nc3
{ As usual, you develop the knight and challenge the center.  Exchanging with  9...Nxc3  10.bxc3  is good for you since it opens the b-file for your rook. You will only keep the doubled c-pawns temporarily since your c4-pawn will be exchanged for Black's central pawn. }
