[Black "Philidor 3...Nd7 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d6 { The Philidor variation. } 3. d4 Nd7 4. dxe5
{ The usual rule is that when pawns face each other in the center, you trade!  4.Nc3  would also be a sound alternative. }
4... dxe5 5. Nc3 { You develop the knights first, as usual. } 5... Ngf6 6. Bc4
{ Your bishop sits nicely on c4, aiming at the f7-pawn. Your next goal is to castle. After that, you can play Qe2 and Rd1 to get your rook to control the open d-file. }
6... Bb4
{ Black pins your knight! It's a good moment to safeguard your king and castle. }
7. O-O
{ You follow the third golden rule and castle.  If you attack with  7.Ng5?  Black can solve the threat by castling  7...O-O }
7... O-O
{ Black makes a good choice by castling as well.  If Black were to try  7...Bxc3  8.bxc3  Nxe4  , you could respond strongly with  9.Qd5  , threatening mate and attacking the knight. This would be a big mistake for Black. }
8. Qe2
{ You move your queen to clear the d-file for your rook and support your central pawn.  While  8.Bg5  might look like a good move because it develops a piece and pins Black's knight, it doesn't achieve much because Black's knight is very well protected. }
*

