1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d6 { The Philidor variation. } 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3
{ You develop the knight as usual! } 5... Be7 6. Bf4
{ You go for the same development setup as in the Scotch variation with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/8/3NP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nxd4  5.Qxd4 }
6... O-O 7. Qd2 c6 8. O-O-O { You can continue the the standard plan. } 8... b5
{ Black wants to play ...b4 to chase away your knight and challenge the center pawn. }
9. f3 { The standard move to support your center. } 9... b4 10. Na4
{ It's important to jump forward. Your knight can block attacking ideas with  10...Qa5  since now, after  11.b3  , Black can't win the a2-pawn. }
10... Bd7 11. g4
{ Going for the attack directly works tactically well for you. } 11... c5
{ Discovered attack, and both your knights are under attack. } 12. Nf5 Bxa4 13.
Nxe7+
{ In return for the knight, you will get an exchange and some pawns, but also a dominating advantage because of the open d-file. }
13... Qxe7 14. Bxd6 { You skewer the queen and rook. } 14... Qb7 15. Bxf8
{ You capture the rook! } 15... Kxf8 16. e5
{ You increase the pressure by hunting the knight. } 16... Ne8 17. Qf4
{ White has a dominating advantage because Black has no good way to continue the game and develop the knight.   17...Nd7  is not an option because you attack with  18.e6  17...Nc6  would leave the bishop trapped after  18.b3  because when Black plays  18...Bb5  19.Bxb5  Qxb5  , the queen stops defending the seventh rank, and you have  20.e6  again with a devastating, powerful attack.  @@StartFEN@@rn2nk2/pq3ppp/8/2p1P3/bp3QP1/5P2/PPP4P/2KR1B1R b - - 2 17@@EndFEN@@  17...Na6  may develop the knight, but after this, it can only go backward, and you can increase the pressure with  18.Bc4  preparing e6. }
*

