[Black "Philidor 3...exd4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d6 { The Philidor variation. } 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3
{ You develop the knight as usual! } 5... Be7 6. Bf4
{ You go for the same development setup as in the Scotch variation with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/8/3NP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nxd4  5.Qxd4 }
6... O-O 7. Qd2 c6 8. O-O-O { You can continue the the standard plan. } 8... b5
{ Black wants to play ...b4 to chase away your knight and challenge the center pawn. }
9. f3 { The standard move to support your center. } 9... b4 10. Na4
{ It's important to jump forward. Your knight can block attacking ideas with  10...Qa5  since now, after  11.b3  , Black can't win the a2-pawn. }
10... Bd7 11. g4
{ Going for the attack directly works tactically well for you. } 11... c5
{ Discovered attack, and both your knights are under attack. } 12. Nf5 Bxa4 13.
Nxe7+
{ In return for the knight, you will get an exchange and some pawns, but also a dominating advantage because of the open d-file. }
13... Qxe7 14. Bxd6 { You skewer the queen and rook. } 14... Qe8
{ The queen drops back! After  14...Qb7  , you can go for  15.Bxf8  Kxf8  and  16.e5  kicking the knight back. }
15. g5
{ You chase the knight away and keep your attack going.  Also  15.Bxc5  is a powerful alternative, winning a pawn before you capture the already trapped rook. There is no rush to capture the rook since it is trapped either way. }
15... Nfd7 16. b3
{ A classy prophylactic move. You kick the bishop back to c6 to ensure Black's knight on b8 will stay stuck. }
16... Bc6 17. h4
{ This is a beautiful and cruel variation. As Black's rook is trapped either way, you don't need to rush to capture it. All Black's pieces are tied down, so the plan is to continue with Qf4, h5, and g6, and when also your light-squared bishop joins the attack it will be game over soon. Black has no good way to counter-attack.  After  17...Ne5  18.Be2  also, Bxc5, and f4 will become threats. }
*

