1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d6 { The Philidor variation. } 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3
{ You develop the knight as usual! } 5... Be7 6. Bf4
{ You go for the same development setup as in the Scotch variation with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/8/3NP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nxd4  5.Qxd4 }
6... O-O 7. Qd2 Nc6 8. O-O-O { You continue your plan and castle queenside. }
8... Nxd4
{ Black should exchange knights to have the e6-square available for the bishop. }
9. Qxd4 Be6 10. f3
{ You control the center and can start an attack with g4 and h4! Usually, when you have more control in the center, starting an attack is easier. }
10... a6 11. g4 b5 12. h4
{ Freeing the h2-square as a retreat for your bishop to prepare to play g5. }
12... c5 13. Qe3 b4 14. Na4
{ This is important as you want to use the knight in the defense to block Black's queen on the a-file.   14.Nd5  Nxd5  15.exd5  Bd7  exchanges the knights, which you would rather not do, as Black's knight was a target. You were about to play g5 and hunt the knight to a bad square. }
14... Qa5 15. b3
{ You have formed a nice blockade. You can continue the attack with g5 or first h5 and then g5 next.  When Black plays  15...Bd7  , don't be scared to play  16.h5  and allow  16...Bxa4  17.bxa4  Qxa4  because after  18.Bc4  , your light-squared bishop is untouchable, blocking all Black's pawns, and now Black's attack has led to nothing. You have a positionally winning position. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2a) Petrov and Philidor Defenses "]
[Black "Philidor 3...exd4 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d6 { The Philidor variation. } 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3
{ You develop the knight as usual! } 5... Be7 6. Bf4
{ You go for the same development setup as in the Scotch variation with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/8/3NP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nxd4  5.Qxd4 }
6... O-O 7. Qd2 Nc6 8. O-O-O { You continue your plan and castle queenside. }
8... Nxd4
{ Black should exchange knights to have the e6-square available for the bishop. }
9. Qxd4 Be6 10. f3
{ You control the center and can start an attack with g4 and h4! Usually, when you have more control in the center, starting an attack is easier. }
10... Nd7 { Black lacks space and wants to play ...Bg5 to trade the bishops. }
11. h4
{ You prevent ... Bg5 and start the attack. You are ready to keep the attack going with g4-g5 and take away the f6-square for Black.   11...Bxh4?  is something you would only like to encourage Black to play as the h-file for your rook opens up, strengthening your attack. }
