[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3a) Sicilian Nimzowitch and Pin Variations"]
[Black "Sicilian: Nimzowitch Variation #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5
{ This move marks the Sicilian Defense. Black does not put a pawn directly in the center but controls it instead with a flank pawn. }
2. Nf3
{ You play in the same fashion as in the Open Games after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...e5  2.Nf3  You develop the knight and control the center.  Wait to put your other pawn in the center with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...c5  2.d4  because after  2...cxd4  3.Qxd4  Black can develop with tempo and attack your queen with  3...Nc6  . }
2... Nf6
{ The Nimzowitch-Rubinstein variation.  This move is only popular among Club Players. The downside for Black is that you can immediately harass the knight. Let's grab the chance and chase the knight to a worse square. Since Black attacks the e4-pawn, you don't play  3.d4  as Black wins the pawn with  3...Nxe4  .  After other moves, you will play d4 and go for the Open Sicilian. }
3. e5
{ You immediately harass the knight and force it to move again. At the beginner level, the development move  3.Nc3  is much more popular, which supports the pawn. Thinking about the golden opening rules, this looks logical.  3.Nc3  develops the knight, whereas  3.e5  doesn't develop anything.  3.Nc3  , however, doesn't prevent Black from developing, so Black could play  3...Nc6  and also develop a piece.   Development rule: Development should be counted as a race. After  3.e5  Nd5  , both sides have one piece developed, and after  3.Nc3  Nc6  ,  both sides have two pieces developed. Therefore, both are equally good in terms of development. 3. e5 chases Black's knight to a worse square and is stronger. }
3... Nd5 4. Nc3
{ You develop the knight and force the knight on d5 to move again. } 4... Nxc3
5. dxc3
{ You open the diagonal for the bishop and the d-file for our queen. White is now ready to develop both of the bishops and gain a lead in development soon. Generally, it's best to capture towards the center since center pawns are better. This position is an exception.  You love to arrange your pawn structure to maximize our piece activity, and where  5.dxc3  activates your bishop and queen  5.bxc3  doesn't help your development. }
5... Nc6
{ Black develops the knight!   5...d5  would be a mistake since after  6.exd6  exd6  7.Bf4  , you plan to go for Qd2 and O-O-O when the d6-pawn is a target. }
6. Bf4
{ Developing and preparing to castle queenside. It's a recurring theme that if you have a semi-open or open d-file, you would like to cast queenside to position your rook well immediately.  The bishop on f4 prevents Black from pushing the d-pawn forward. After  6...d5  7.exd6  exd6  8.Qd2  , you are planning O-O-O to attack the d6-pawn one more time. The plan is Qd2 and O-O-O! }
6... e6
{ After  6...Qb6  attacking the b2-pawn, you can play  7.b3  to secure the pawn and continue with the same plan. }
7. Qd2
{ You are ready to castle queenside! After that, you can develop with Bd3 and play for a kingside attack with h4, Rh3, Rg3. }
7... Qc7 8. O-O-O h6 9. h4
{ Allowing Black to play ...g5 could hurt your position sometimes, so it's a good idea to prevent it! }
9... b6 10. Bd3 Bb7 11. Be4
{ A way to continue is to slowly strangle Black like a boa constrictor with moves like h5 and c4 to ensure that Black can not make pawn breaks to get out of our grasp! }
*

