[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3a) Sicilian Nimzowitch and Pin Variations"]
[Black "Sicilian: Nimzowitch Variation #7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5
{ This move marks the Sicilian Defense. Black does not put a pawn directly in the center but controls it instead with a flank pawn. }
2. Nf3
{ You play in the same fashion as in the Open Games after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...e5  2.Nf3  You develop the knight and control the center.  Wait to put your other pawn in the center with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...c5  2.d4  because after  2...cxd4  3.Qxd4  Black can develop with tempo and attack your queen with  3...Nc6  . }
2... Nf6
{ The Nimzowitch-Rubinstein variation.  This move is only popular among Club Players. The downside for Black is that you can immediately harass the knight. Let's grab the chance and chase the knight to a worse square. Since Black attacks the e4-pawn, you don't play  3.d4  as Black wins the pawn with  3...Nxe4  .  After other moves, you will play d4 and go for the Open Sicilian. }
3. e5
{ You immediately harass the knight and force it to move again. At the beginner level, the development move  3.Nc3  is much more popular, which supports pawn. Thinking about the golden opening rules, this looks logical.  3.Nc3  develops the knight, whereas  3.e5  doesn't develop anything.  3.Nc3  , however, doesn't prevent Black from developing, so Black could play  3...Nc6  and also develop a piece.  Development rule: Development should be counted as a race. After  3.e5  Nd5  , both sides have one piece developed, and after  3.Nc3  Nc6  , both sides have two pieces developed. Therefore, both are equally good in terms of development.  3.e5  chases Black's knight to a worse square and is stronger. }
3... Nd5 4. Nc3
{ You develop the knight and force the knight on d5 to move again. } 4... e6
{ Black doesn't want to capture your knight after 4...Nxc3 5.dxc3 speeds up your development. }
5. Nxd5 { You capture the knight giving Black doubled pawns. } 5... exd5 6. d4
{ You follow the first Golden Rule and place your other pawn in the center.   6...cxd4  7.Qxd4  speeds up your development and makes the d5-pawn weak. }
6... Nc6
{ The main move here is to grab a pawn with  7.dxc5  Bxc5  8.Qxd5  when Black plays  8...Qb6  threatening ... Bxf2, and the position becomes sharp and complicated.  In the previous move, you saw that @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp1p1ppp/8/2ppP3/3P4/5N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...exd4  was a poor move for Black since the d5-pawn gets weak. Black is not threatening to win a pawn with  7...cxd4  8.Nxd4  Nxe5  , however, this is not a dangerous threat as this automatically means Black weakens the d5-pawn more. So, since there is no real threat to you from Black, you can use the first Golden Rule and develop. }
7. Be2 { You calmly develop your bishop. } 7... d6
{ Instead of grabbing the pawn, Black challenges your center.   7...Be7  would allow you to win the pawn with  8.dxc5  Bxc5  9.Qxd5  when  9...Qb6  is no longer dangerous after  10.O-O }
8. O-O dxe5 { The most played move. } 9. Nxe5 { Forward! } 9... Bd6 10. Nxc6
bxc6 11. dxc5 Bxc5 12. b4
{ You kick the bishop back and set up a trap.   12.Bd3  is also a sound alternative. }
12... Bb6 13. b5
{ You attack the pawn, and there is no way for Black to hold on to it.   13...Bd7?  would allow  14.bxc6  ,  Bxc6  , and  15.Ba3!  and is Black unable to castle  Also, @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/p4ppp/1bp5/1P1p4/8/8/P1P1BPPP/R1BQ1RK1 b kq - 0 13@@EndFEN@@  13...c5?  runs into  14.Bf3  with a powerful pin on the d5-pawn. }
13... O-O { Black makes a wise decision to castle. } 14. bxc6
{ You capture the pawn, and it will still be a bit challenging for Black to win back the pawn as you also have pressure against the d5-pawn. }
