[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3a) Sicilian Nimzowitch and Pin Variations"]
[Black "Sicilian: Pin Variation #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5
{ This move marks the Sicilian Defense. Black does not put a pawn directly in the center but controls it instead with a flank pawn. }
2. Nf3
{ You play in the same fashion as in the Open Games after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...e5  2.Nf3  You develop the knight and control the center.  Wait to put your other pawn in the center with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...c5  2.d4  because after  2...cxd4  3.Qxd4  Black can develop with tempo and attack your queen with  3...Nc6  . }
2... e6
{ Black opens up the diagonal for the dark-squared bishop and controls the d5-square. }
3. d4 { The Open Sicilian. } 3... cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Bb4
{ The Pin-Variation is the only exception to the Robust Development and Knight Domination setups. This move has fallen out of fashion because White has a clear way of punishing this dubious variation. So, pay attention; this line is different and requires some memorization. 5...Nc6 6. Be2 transposes to the Four Knights Variation 5...d6 transposes to the Scheveningen variation. }
6. e5 { The knight has two squares to go to now. Going back is not good. } 6...
Ne4
{ This leads to a well-known sequence, where White gets a large advantage. } 7.
Qg4 { Double attacking the knight on g4 and the pawn on g7. } 7... Nxc3
{ 7...Qa5  Looks scary, but it loses for Black  8.Qxg7  Black can start attacking with  8...Bxc3+  9.bxc3  Qxc3+  10.Ke2  , your king is safe here, and giving up the dark-squared bishop means Black can no longer save the rook  10...Rf8  11.Bh6  , and you threaten Qxf8# with a winning position.  After @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp1p1ppp/4p3/4P3/1b1N2Q1/2n5/PPP2PPP/R1B1KB1R w KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  7...Qa5  also capturing the knight with  8.Qxe4  gives you a better position. But going for the rook instead with  8.Qxg7  is much stronger. }
8. Qxg7
{ None of Black's checks with the knight help as you can always play c3 attacking the rook on h8 and the bishop on b4 simultaneously. }
8... Rf8 9. a3
{ The move to remember is to chase the bishop away from the b4 square, where it protects the rook on f8. }
9... Ba5
{ 9...Qa5  is another move that Black has tried sometimes. All ideas you have learned give White a significant advantage  10.Bh6  10.Nb3  , so it's not necessary to train this variation.  The most convincing is  10.axb4  immediately eliminates the bishop when after  10...Qxa1  11.Nb3  Qb1  12.bxc3  wins the knight, and if Black were to play  12...Qxc2  it allows  13.Bh6! }
10. Bh6
{ You are threatening Qxf8#   10.Bg5?  runs into a discovered attack now  10...Ne4+ }
10... Qe7 11. Nb3
{ A beautiful move! The bishop and knight are hanging.  Black has to move the bishop, and you win the knight  11...Bc7  12.bxc3  is in the remaining position. You don't have to rush with the trades on f8 since the rook can't run away either way, so after  12...Nc6  , you can support your center with  13.f4 }
*

