[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3a) Sicilian Nimzowitch and Pin Variations"]
[Black "Sicilian: Pin Variation #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5
{ This move marks the Sicilian Defense. Black does not put a pawn directly in the center but controls it instead with a flank pawn. }
2. Nf3
{ You play in the same fashion as in the Open Games after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...e5  2.Nf3  You develop the knight and control the center.  Wait to put your other pawn in the center with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...c5  2.d4  because after  2...cxd4  3.Qxd4  Black can develop with tempo and attack your queen with  3...Nc6  . }
2... e6
{ Black opens up the diagonal for the dark-squared bishop and controls the d5-square. }
3. d4 { The Open Sicilian. } 3... cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Bb4
{ The Pin-Variation is the only exception to the Robust Development and Knight Domination setups. This move has fallen out of fashion because White has a clear way of punishing this dubious variation. So, pay attention; this line is different and requires some memorization. 5...Nc6 6. Be2 transposes to the Four Knights Variation 5...d6 transposes to the Scheveningen variation. }
6. e5 { The knight has two squares to go to now. Going back is not good. } 6...
Nd5 { The better move, yet things are much easier here. } 7. Qg4
{ You play in the same way as after  6...Ne4  7...Nxc3  8.Qxg7  transposes to the variation you learned. }
7... g6
{ Black can also choose another way to weaken the position with  7...Kf8  when you also play  8.Bd2  . Or Black can play  7...O-O  , which runs into  8.Bh6! }
8. Bd2 { You unpin the knight! } 8... Nxc3
{ This is by far Black's most-played move.  After  8...Bxc3?  9.bxc3  Black will suffer by giving up the dark-squared bishop in a position where their dark-squares are weak.  When Black plays @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp1p1p1p/4p1p1/3nP3/1b1N2Q1/2N5/PPPB1PPP/R3KB1R b KQkq - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Qa5  , you can defend and support your knight with  9.Qg3  or the even more powerful  9.Ndb5  . }
9. bxc3 Be7 10. h4
{ Black's position is about to fall apart! You get ready for h5 which also involves your rook and demolishes the kingside position. }
10... Nc6
{ Black attacks in the center.   10...h5?  11.Qg3  would make the g6-pawn so weak for Black that plans with Bd3-Bxg6 become crushing }
11. Qg3
{ You defend the e5-pawn; there is no rush to continue the attack directly. You are only interested in trading the knights on your terms and would like to go for Nb5-Nd6+, forcing Black to give up on the dark-squared bishop. However, if Black is willing to capture your knight in the center with ...Nxd4 and you can improve your pawn structure after cxd4, you would also be happy with that. }
