[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3b) Sicilian Four Knights, Taimanov and Kan Variations"]
[Black "Robust Development Setup"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5
{ This move marks the Sicilian Defense. Black does not put a pawn directly in the center but controls it instead with a flank pawn. }
2. Nf3
{ You play in the same fashion as in the Open Games after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...e5  2.Nf3  You develop the knight and control the center. Wait to place your other pawn in the center with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.d4  because after  2...cxd4  3.Qxd4  Black can develop with tempo and attack our queen with  3...Nc6  . }
2... -- 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4
{ Against all Sicilians, you have two battle plans! The Robust Development Setup and the Knight Domination Setup. By default, you go for the Robust Development Setup, and you switch to the Knight Domination Setup when Black plays ...e5.     The Robust Development Setup is to continue with Nc3, Be2, O-O and Be3. You would like to play the moves in this order. I will explain the ideas behind these moves. In this example, Black doesn't make any moves.    You will use the Robust Development Setup versus:  The Kan Sicilian   The Taimanov  The Four Knights Sicilian  The Hyperaccelerated Dragon  The Dragon  The Classical variation  The Najdorf variation when Black doesn't play ...e5. }
4... -- 5. Nc3
{ This is the best square for the knight. The knight is defending the e4-pawn. Typically c3 and f3 are the best squares for the knight.   5.Nd2  would be blocking the queen and bishop. }
5... -- 6. Be2
{ Developing the bishop and preparing to castle. This square may seem passive for the bishop, but it isn't easy to pick a better alternative.   6.Bd3  would be blocking the queen.   6.Bc4  doesn't create an attack, and in many Sicilians, Black can harass the bishop with either ...a6-b5 ...e6-d5 or ... Qc7.   6.Bb5  usually leads to trading your bishop against Black's knight or light-squared bishop. Or it gives Black a chance to target your bishop with ...a6. It doesn't bring you much.  With  6.Be2  , Black cannot target the bishop, you keep the d-file open, and you control the g4-square. Next move, you are ready to safeguard the king with a castle and activate your rook. }
6... -- 7. O-O
{ You follow the third Golden Rule and bring your king to safety. Also, you activate your rook. }
7... -- 8. Be3
{ You finished the Robust Development Setup! You followed the three Golden Move Rules: 1@@EndBracket@@ placing the pawns in the center 2@@EndBracket@@ developing the pieces 3@@EndBracket@@ safeguarding the king. The bishops cooperate well with each other. Your light-squared bishop prevents Black from targeting your dark-squared bishop with ...Nf6-Ng4-Nxe3.  Your dark-squared bishop didn't have good alternatives, either:   8.Bd2?  would block the d-file and leaves your knight undefended.   8.Bf4?  often gives Black a chance to target your bishop and go for a fork with ...e5.   8.Bg5?  in most Sicilians, it would attack Black's knight, which developed to f6. Usually, you are not interested in trading your bishop for a knight.   8.Be3  doesn't give Black a chance to target your bishop. It keeps the d-file open and defends the knight.  Note that if you finished the Robust Development Setup, you are still working on development. You already have developed all your minor pieces @@StartBracket@@bishops and knights@@EndBracket@@, but to master the game of chess, you also want to involve your heavy pieces @@StartBracket@@queen and rooks@@EndBracket@@. Typically you can continue with f4, and Bf3 and increase your control over the center. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3b) Sicilian Four Knights, Taimanov and Kan Variations"]
[Black "Sicilian: Four Knights Variations #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5
{ This move marks the Sicilian Defense. Black does not put a pawn directly in the center but controls it instead with a flank pawn. }
2. Nf3
{ You play in the same fashion as in the Open Games after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...e5  2.Nf3  You develop the knight and control the center.  Wait to put your other pawn in the center with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...c5  2.d4  because after  2...cxd4  3.Qxd4  Black can develop with tempo and attack your queen with  3...Nc6  . }
2... e6
{ Black opens up the diagonal for the dark-squared bishop and controls the d5-square. }
3. d4 { The Open Sicilian. } 3... cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nc3 Nf6
{ This is the Four Knights Sicilian.  After  5...Bb4  , you can punish Black with a clearance tactic  6.Nxc6  bxc6  7.Qd4  with a double attack on the bishop and g7-pawn. It is also fine to continue the Robust Development Setup with  6.Be2  when after  6...Nf6  7.O-O  you transpose back to the Four Knights Sicilian }
6. Be2 { You develop as planned. } 6... Bb4
{ 6...Be7  7.O-O  O-O  8.f4  d6  transposes to the Scheveningen. } 7. O-O
{ Just as in the Kan, you can shrug your shoulders on the e4-pawn.  When Black doesn't go for the pawn and plays  7...O-O  , you can play  8.Nxc6  bxc6  9.e5  chasing away the knight. This motif only worked for you after castling, because if you played @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pp1p1ppp/2n1pn2/8/1b1NP3/2N5/PPP1BPPP/R1BQK2R w KQkq - 5 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Nxc6  bxc6  8.e5  Black has  8...Nxe4  attacking the pinned knight on c3. }
7... Bxc3
{ Black is more or less forced to eliminate the knight and go after the pawn.  After  7...O-O?  you can go for the powerful  8.Nxc6  bxc6  9.e5  hunting the knight when after  9...Nd5  10.Ne4  Black's light-squared bishop will stay passive }
8. bxc3 Nxe4
{ Black enters the Poisoned Pawn variation! When Black plays ... Nxe4, you also want to play Qg4, so you move the bishop out of the way first. }
9. Bd3
{ This idea has been used by Caruana and Dubov. When Black's knight captures the e4-pawn, you like to counter with Qg4 as in the pin variation.   9.Nxc6  is also an alternative but not consistent with the other variations in your repertoire. }
9... Nf6 10. Ba3
{ The most logical move! Developing the last minor piece and preventing Black from castling.  10.Nb5  is a strong alternative aiming to dominate Black by placing pieces on the d6-square. A difficult thing to remember here is that after  10...O-O  11.Ba3  Re8  12.Nd6  Rf8  , your knight on d6 stopping Black's development is so strong that winning an exchange with  13.Nxc8  Rxc8  14.Bxf8  Qxf8  would be a significant mistake. }
10... d6 { The most popular move among club players. } 11. Nb5
{ You will win the d6-pawn } 11... O-O 12. Bxd6 Re8 13. Nc7
{ Forking the rooks!  Black can't capture your bishop with  13...Qxd6  because of the discovered attack  14.Bxh7+  , and you win the queen. }
*

