[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3b) Sicilian Four Knights, Taimanov and Kan Variations"]
[Black "Sicilian: Taimanov Variation #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5
{ This move marks the Sicilian Defense. Black does not put a pawn directly in the center but controls it instead with a flank pawn. }
2. Nf3
{ You play in the same fashion as in the Open Games after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...e5  2.Nf3  You develop the knight and control the center.  Wait to put your other pawn in the center with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...c5  2.d4  because after  2...cxd4  3.Qxd4  Black can develop with tempo and attack your queen with  3...Nc6  . }
2... e6
{ Black opens up the diagonal for the dark-squared bishop and controls the d5-square. }
3. d4 { The Open Sicilian. } 3... cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nc3 Qc7
{ This is the Taimanov Sicilian, named after the Soviet grandmaster Mark Taimanov. }
6. Be2
{ You will go for the robust development setup. By starting with  6.Be2  , you can castle quickly. Even though the bishop doesn't do much on e2, you can play the magical move of castling, which safeguards your king and activates your rook.  There was no better square for the bishop as  6.Bc4  looks at a wall of pawns as the e6-pawn is double protected. Also,  6.Bb5  wouldn't make much sense as Black is happy to make the trade after  6...a6  7.Bxc6  dxc6  . }
6... a6
{ When Black plays in the style of the Four Knights Variation it is not dangerous  6...Nf6  7.O-O  Bb4  8.Be3  Bxc3?  and you have the cunning fork with  9.Nb5  and will win the bishop back with a fantastic position. }
7. O-O
{ You are ready to make our magical move and castle. I cannot emphasize the importance of castling enough. Castling is the only move in chess where you are allowed to move two pieces at the same. It contributes to two golden rules with one move as you safeguard our king and develop. The moment that one side is castled is often the moment when this player has consolidated their position. After castling, all White's pieces are protected. As a coach, it's my experience that at the beginner and club player level, the player who castles first most often wins the game. }
7... Bb4 8. Nxc6 bxc6 9. Qd4
{ And Black has to defend the bishop on b4 and the g7-pawn. } *

