Bxf3 10. Qxf3 d5
{ Black closes the center and stays a pawn up! It looks like Black is safe, but this is not the case. }
11. Re1 Nf6 12. Bg5 { And Black's position looks quite safe but is  shaky. }
12... Nbd7
{ Therefore Black should prevent your knight from coming to c5 and play 12... Nbd7 }
13. c4
{ You need to involve your knight in the game again, so force Black to capture en-passant. }
13... bxc3 14. Nxc3 { The e6-pawn pinned so you threaten Nxd5 } 14... Bc5
{ Black attacks the knight so prevents Nxd5 for now. The only move for Black.  14...Be7  runs into  15.Nc6! }
15. Nc6 Qb6
{ Black targets the f2-pawn and knight! After  15...Qc7  , you will play in the same way  16.Nxd5  Nxd5  17.Qxd5  . }
16. Nxd5
{ You capture the pawn! Your knight on c6 is safe  16...Qxc6  17.Nxf6+ } 16...
Bxf2+ 17. Kh1
{ Your king is safe in the corner. After  17.Qxf2  Qxf2+  18.Kxf2  Nxd5  Black has a better endgame. }
17... Nxd5 18. Qxd5 { And you threaten Rxe6+ } 18... Bxe1 19. Rxe1
{ You threaten Rxe6+ when mate will follow soon! } 19... O-O
{ Black should give back their knight to survive the attack. You have two pieces for a rook and two pawns. }
20. Qxd7
{ After  20...Qxb2  21.Be7  Rfe8  , it doesn't work to play  22.Nd8  trapping the rook since  22...Qb5  defends.  Instead, you can play @@StartFEN@@r3r1k1/3QBppp/p1N1p3/8/8/8/Pq4PP/4R2K w - - 2 22@@EndFEN@@  22.h3  to free the back rank for the king! Now, after  22...Qxa2?  23.Nd8!  would trap the rook. }
