Be3
{ It's a common theme that sacrificing the e4-pawn is powerful!  The Robust Development Setup also stands strong against the most critical test.  @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/1bqp1ppp/p3p3/1p6/3NP3/2N5/PPP1BPPP/R1BQ1RK1 w kq - 2 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Re1  is a sound alternative. }
8... b4 { Black chases away the knight! } 9. Na4
{ You are not going back, so this is the only square to go to! } 9... Bxe4
{ Black wins a pawn, but you have a big lead in development. } 10. Bf3
{ You will take over the diagonal! This variation is quite similar to what you learned before. There are a couple of sound alternatives at this point.  10.c3  or  10.Rc1  to open the c-file. }
10... Bxf3
{ After  10...Nf6  11.Bxe4  Nxe4  12.Qf3  d5  , you play the thematic  13.c3  when after  13...bxc3  14.bxc3  , you are ready to break down the center again with c4. }
11. Qxf3 Nc6
{ 11...d5  is way too risky for Black.  12.c4  is thematic to open the center after  12...bxc3  13.Rac1  You have a massive lead in development, and Black's position collapses. }
12. c3 { You open up the c-file to pressure the knight. } 12... bxc3 13. Rac1
{ You have pressure on the c6-knight.  13...cxb2  14.Nxb2  opens up the c-file. }
