2. Nf3
{ You play in the same fashion as in the Open Games after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...e5  2.Nf3  You develop the knight and control the center.  Wait to put your other pawn in the center with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...c5  2.d4  because after  2...cxd4  3.Qxd4  Black can develop with tempo and attack your queen with  3...Nc6  . }
2... e6
{ Black opens up the diagonal for the dark-squared bishop and controls the d5-square. }
3. d4 { The Open Sicilian. } 3... cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ This is the Kan Sicilian, named after the Soviet international master Ilya Kan. Black is looking to play his pawn to b5 early on and without Nc6. }
5. Nc3
{ White develops his knights first and is ready to continue with the robust development setup Be2, O-O, Be3. }
5... Qc7 { Black controls the center with the queen! } 6. Be2
{ If you have the choice! Go for Be2 and O-O first, before you play  6.Be3  .  It's safer to be castled as quickly as possible. }
6... b5 7. O-O Bb7
{ This looks like a critical try to refute the Robust Development Setup! } 8.
Be3
{ It's a common theme that sacrificing the e4-pawn is powerful!  The Robust Development Setup also stands strong against the most critical test.  @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/1bqp1ppp/p3p3/1p6/3NP3/2N5/PPP1BPPP/R1BQ1RK1 w kq - 2 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Re1  is a sound alternative. }
8... Nf6
{ Black adds another attack to the e4-pawn instead of chasing the knight. A cunning move. }
9. f4 { You go for the standard setup and sacrifice the pawn. } 9... d6
{ Arguably the most critical move to refute the Robust Development Setup. Black plays it slowly and keeps the pressure on the e4-pawn. Black wants to consolidate the position before they capture the pawn. }
10. f5
{ After  10.Bf3  Nbd7  , nothing too dramatic is happening, but the position becomes more convenient for Black. You will have to play  11.a3  to prevent b4-ideas. Black continues with development  11...Be7  12.Qe1  O-O  13.Qg3  and will attack the e4-pawn.  13...Nc5  with a slightly better position for Black. You would like to avoid that. }
10... e5 11. Ne6
{ An instructive piece sacrifice which has never been played before. The idea will be to restrict Black's knight on the queenside. }
11... fxe6 12. fxe6 Be7
{ The only good move for Black to survive, supporting the knight with the bishop.  Black can't just keep developing with  12...Nc6  because  13.Rxf6  gxf6  14.Bh5+  Kd8  15.Nd5  starts a crushing attack. }
13. Nd5 { You will make sure you get a pawn on d5! } 13... Bxd5 14. exd5
{ Your idea is that Black's knight on the queenside will not be able to develop! }
14... Qb7 15. c4 bxc4 16. Bxc4
{ Your center is unbreakable, and Black's knight on the queenside stays inactive. g4, g5 will give you a powerful attack on the kingside.  Also, in case Black would have opted for @@StartFEN@@rn2k2r/2q1b1pp/p2pPn2/1p1Pp3/8/4B3/PPP1B1PP/R2Q1RK1 b kq - 0 14@@EndFEN@@  14...O-O  15.g4  would be a powerful attack. }
