[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3b) Sicilian Four Knights, Taimanov and Kan Variations"]
[Black "Sicilian: Kan Variation #10"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5
{ This move marks the Sicilian Defense. Black does not put a pawn directly in the center but controls it instead with a flank pawn. }
2. Nf3
{ You play in the same fashion as in the Open Games after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...e5  2.Nf3  You develop the knight and control the center.  Wait to put your other pawn in the center with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...c5  2.d4  because after  2...cxd4  3.Qxd4  Black can develop with tempo and attack your queen with  3...Nc6  . }
2... e6
{ Black opens up the diagonal for the dark-squared bishop and controls the d5-square. }
3. d4 { The Open Sicilian. } 3... cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ This is the Kan Sicilian, named after the Soviet international master Ilya Kan. Black is looking to play his pawn to b5 early on and without Nc6. }
5. Nc3
{ White develops his knights first and is ready to continue with the robust development setup Be2, O-O, Be3. }
5... Qc7 { Black controls the center with the queen! } 6. Be2
{ If you have the choice! Go for Be2 and O-O first, before you play  6.Be3  .  It's safer to be castled as quickly as possible. }
6... Nf6 7. O-O
{ You castle and are ready to develop the bishop.  Black can play  7...Bb4  to put pressure on our knight. When Black captures the knight to win a pawn, it will activate your pieces on the queenside. It's fine to continue with your development plan with  8.Be3  when after  8...Bxc3  9.bxc3  Qxc3  , you have sacrificed a pawn for active pieces on the queenside  10.Qd3  Qxd3  11.cxd3  allows you to activate our rook with Rab1 and Rfc1!  The position after @@StartFEN@@rnb1kb1r/1pqp1ppp/p3pn2/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP1BPPP/R1BQ1RK1 b kq - 5 7@@EndFEN@@  7...d6  will be covered in the Scheveningen. }
7... Nc6 { Black develops the knight. } 8. Be3 Bb4
{ Black goes after the knight. } 9. Nxc6
{ You first trade the knight before you go for your plan with f4!  The reason is clear in the line  9...bxc6  10.f4  Bxc3  11.bxc3  Nxe4  12.Bd3  d5  since now you can play the powerful  13.Bxe4  dxe4  14.Bc5  and your bishop is strong, preventing Black from castling.  The direct @@StartFEN@@r1b1k2r/1pqp1ppp/p1n1pn2/8/1b1NP3/2N1B3/PPP1BPPP/R2Q1RK1 w kq - 8 9@@EndFEN@@  9.f4  Bxc3  10.bxc3  Nxe4  11.Bd3  d5  wouldn't make that possible since after  12.Bxe4  dxe4  13.Nxc6  Black will change its mind now and play  13...Qxc6  preventing Bc5 }
9... bxc6
{ Overwhelmingly the most played move.   9...Qxc6  is not good because you can start hunting the knight with  10.e5!  Also  10.Bd4  would be a powerful move.  @@StartFEN@@r1b1k2r/1pqp1ppp/p1N1pn2/8/1b2P3/2N1B3/PPP1BPPP/R2Q1RK1 b kq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...dxc6  is not so popular, but going with the same plan with  10.f4  is strong when Black shouldn't play  10...Bxc3  11.bxc3  Nxe4  because now after  12.Bf3  Nf6  13.Bc5!  Black won't be able to castle. }
10. f4
{ You can shrug your shoulders again on the e4-pawn. If Black doesn't take the pawn, you can push it to e5.  In these Sicilian positions where you played f4, if Black goes for  10...d5  , which is always a mistake, you should go for  11.e5  and not trade the pawns. This is an exception to the rule that you always want to trade pawns when they face each other in the center. Understand that the rule that trading the pawns when they face off in the center is usually strong is a guideline, like a rook is worth more than a knight. Of course, exceptions exist where a knight is stronger than a rook or where trading the pawns in the center is not the best. As your experience and understanding of the games grow, you will be able to spot the positions that are exceptions to the rule. I encourage you to use the guidelines you learned but not always to follow them blindly. }
10... O-O 11. e5
{ You start hunting the knight, as usual!  11.Na4  is also a sound alternative. }
11... Nd5 12. Nxd5 { You trade and give Black doubled pawns. } 12... cxd5 13.
c3 Bc5 14. Qd2
{ You aim for b4 and want to keep Black's light-squared bishop passive. } *

