[Black "Sicilian: Hyperaccelerated Dragon #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5
{ This move marks the Sicilian Defense. Black does not put a pawn directly in the center but controls it instead with a flank pawn. }
2. Nf3
{ You play in the same fashion as in the Open Games after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...e5  2.Nf3  You develop the knight and control the center.  Wait to put your other pawn in the center with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...c5  2.d4  because after  2...cxd4  3.Qxd4  Black can develop with tempo and attack your queen with  3...Nc6  . }
2... g6 3. d4
{ The Open Silician. You follow the first golden move rule and place the pawn in the center. Many White players are scared to play Open Silician because they think it's a heavy theoretical battleground. Black has many setups, and you must learn how to play against them. This course teaches you that it's possible to do well in the Open Sicilian without learning much theory. You will use a development setup that works versus almost all Sicilians. }
3... cxd4 4. Nxd4
{ Next, your development plan is Nc3, Be3, Be2, and O-O, a robust option against Black's different setups and allows you to develop the minor pieces and safeguard the king.   Exceptions to this Robust Development Plan are the O'Kelly variation and the Sveshnikov and Kalashnikov variations. }
4... Bg7 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Be3
{ Developing and defending the knight. Like you saw in the Scotch opening the trades with  6...Nxd4  7.Bxd4  Bxd4  8.Qxd4  would benefit you as you activate the queen and harass the rook in the corner. }
6... Nf6 7. Be2
{ So you followed the plan. You may wonder why you don't play  7.Bc4  as the bishop looks more active here. This is also the most played move, but White has to remember numerous important details there. After  7...O-O  Black has a trick if you continue development as after  8.O-O  Nxe4  9.Nxe4  d5  forks the bishop and knight.  Therefore, the way to play is @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp1pppbp/2n2np1/8/2BNP3/2N1B3/PPP2PPP/R2QK2R w KQ - 7 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Bb3  when also after  8...d6  , you can't continue easy development with  9.O-O  as Black can attack with  9...Ng4  harasses the bishop on e3 when you miss having your bishop on e2. I want to make life easy for you and recommend 7.Be2. }
7... O-O 8. O-O
{ White has developed all the minor pieces, and Black should still develop the light-squared bishop. }
8... d6
{ This position can also be reached after Black plays @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...d6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  g6  . That is actually the most common move order to reach this position. For the overview, the line is put after 2...g6. }
9. f4 { Your standard plan to improve the position. } 9... Bd7 10. Bf3 Rc8
{ Black moves the rook to the c-file!   10...a6  is also played a lot, but you will see the variation in the transposition  11.a4  Rc8  12.Nb3 }
11. Nb3 { You avoid that Black can trade knight and open the c-file! } 11... a6
{ Black plans to play ... b5 to gain space on the queenside and kick your knight away with ...b4. }
12. a4
{ You give a cold shower to Black's plans on the queenside. You aim to cement their position with a5, gaining an outpost for the bishop or knight on b6. Answer ...a6 with a4, and you stop Black's queenside play. }
12... Qc7 { When Black plays a calm move, you can continue your plan! } 13. a5
{ This is what you are aiming for! You prevent Black's play on the queenside, and their pieces are stuck. Next, you can kick the queen from with c-file with Bb6 and go for Nd5.  Black can't eliminate your knight, which protects the a5-pawn with  13...Be6  since it runs into  14.Nd5!  When Black plays  13...e5  , you can switch to the Knight Domination Setup.  14.f5  aiming for Bxf6 and Nd5 }
