{ Developing and defending the knight. Like you saw in the Scotch opening the trades with  6...Nxd4  7.Bxd4  Bxd4  8.Qxd4  would benefit you as you activate the queen and harass the rook in the corner. }
6... Nf6 7. Be2
{ So you followed the plan. You may wonder why you don't play  7.Bc4  as the bishop looks more active here. This is also the most played move, but White has to remember numerous important details there. After  7...O-O  Black has a trick if you continue development as after  8.O-O  Nxe4  9.Nxe4  d5  forks the bishop and knight.  Therefore, the way to play is @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp1pppbp/2n2np1/8/2BNP3/2N1B3/PPP2PPP/R2QK2R w KQ - 7 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Bb3  when also after  8...d6  , you can't continue easy development with  9.O-O  as Black can attack with  9...Ng4  harasses the bishop on e3 when you miss having your bishop on e2. I want to make life easy for you and recommend 7.Be2. }
7... O-O 8. O-O
{ White has developed all the minor pieces, and Black should still develop the light-squared bishop. }
8... d5 9. exd5 Nxd5 10. Nxd5 Qxd5
{ 10...Nxd4  is also an option for Black when after  11.Bxd4  Qxd5  12.Bxg7  Qxd1  13.Rfxd1  Kxg7  14.c4  you reach an endgame where you have the rook on the open file! You can play b3 next to create a stable pawn chain and do the same on the kingside with f4 and g3, and you can play Bf3 and pressure the b7-pawn. }
11. Bf3 Qa5
{ Black plays a provocative move from Black, but it doesn't sacrifice a pawn yet because after  12.Nxc6  bxc6  13.Bxc6  Rb8  , Black won back the b2-pawn. }
12. Nxc6 { You capture the pawn to weaken the structure. } 12... bxc6 13. Qc1
{ You support your b2-pawn, and Black's pawns are now split. } 13... Rb8 14. c3
{ You shut the bishop down. } 14... c5 15. Rd1
{ You bring the rook to the open file. } 15... Bf5
{ Black has to be careful where to develop the bishop! } 16. Rd5
{ You are pinning the pawn! } 16... Rfc8 17. b4
{ You fork the queen and the pawn while the pawn is still pinned. } 17... Qa4
18. Rxc5 { You will get a pawn up. } 18... Rxc5 19. Bxc5 a5
{ Black should go for active counterplay. } 20. Bxe7
{ You capture another pawn. } 20... Qd7
{ A difficult move for Black to retreat the queen when you are two pawns down.   20...axb4  21.Bxb4  Rxb4  22.cxb4  Bxa1  23.Qxa1  should be a winning endgame for White with the passed a-pawn. }
21. Bc5 axb4 22. Bxb4 Rxb4
{ Capturing is the only move that doesn't lose for Black. } 23. cxb4 Qd4
{ Again, the only move for Black to survive. } 24. g4
{ At first sight  24.Rb1  also looks strong but after  24...Bxb1  25.Qxb1  Qd2  Black can go for Bd4 next and should have enough counterplay to hold the endgame. }
24... Bxg4 25. Qd1
{ You force the exchange to an endgame that should be difficult for Black to hold. }
25... Qxa1
{ 25...Qxb4  is also a move for Black when you can escape with the rook and play  26.Rc1  You are an exchange up and only playing for two results. }
26. Qxa1 Bxa1 27. Bxg4
{ The computer says Black should hold this, but it's not easy. You want to involve your king first and, at a later stage, start running with your passed pawns. }
