{ You stay consistent with your plan and kick away the queen. Other moves like  15.Qe2  or  15.Qd2  are also sound! Generally, you are happy when Black captures your c2-pawn and opens the c-file. }
15... Qxc2
{ By far the most played move at the club level, and you are happy with the trade.  Black's best move is  15...Qc5  when you can attack with  16.Be3!  When Black goes back with  16...Qc3  , you can choose if you want to repeat with  17.Bd2!  But you can also go for a queen trade with  17.Qd2  .   In case Black doesn't repeat but plays  16...Qa3  instead, you attack with  17.g4  when after  17...Be6  , you can snatch the pawn with  18.Bxc6 }
16. Qxc2 Bxc2 17. Rbc1
{ Your rook occupies the c-file, and Black's pawn on c6 is doomed. } 17... Bd3
18. Rfe1
{ You attack the e7-pawn as well! The c6-pawn is not defendable.  After  18...e6  I like to play  19.Red1  and start targeting the bishop. Since Black is unable to defend the c6-pawn sufficiently. You don't have to rush to capture the pawn. You would also have a good position after  19.Rxc6  . }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3c) Sicilian Hyperaccelerated Dragon and Dragon"]
[Black "Sicilian: Dragon #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5
{ This move marks the Sicilian Defense. Black does not put a pawn directly in the center but controls it instead with a flank pawn. }
2. Nf3
{ You play in the same fashion as in the Open Games after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...e5  2.Nf3  You develop the knight and control the center.  Wait to put your other pawn in the center with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...c5  2.d4  because after  2...cxd4  3.Qxd4  Black can develop with tempo and attack your queen with  3...Nc6  . }
2... d6
{ Black opens up the diagonal for the light-squared bishop and controls the e5-square. }
3. d4
{ Here you go for the most principled variation: the Open Sicilian. White aims for quick and active development of his pieces. You follow the first golden move rule and place your pawn in the center.  The difference is that after  3...cxd4  , you can recapture with the knight and play  4.Nxd4  .  You saw before why you didn't play @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.d4  because after  2...cxd4  3.Qxd4  Nc6  Black gained a tempo in development by attacking your queen. }
3... cxd4
{ Black's best move is to capture the pawn.  After  3...Nc6  , you can start harassing the knight with  4.d5  . When Black plays  3...Nf6  , you develop and defend the pawn with  4.Nc3  . }
4. Nxd4
{ Here, you recapture with the knight. You have opened the diagonals for both bishops. You can continue with Nc3, Be2, Be3, and castle kingside.  One move Black could play to disturb your plan is  4...e5  here, you can immediately go for  5.Bb5+  when after  5...Bd7  6.Bxd7+  Nxd7  7.Nf5  is strong, and you are attacking the d6-pawn.  Instead, you can also play  5.Nf3  and you will transpose to one of the other variations you will learn in the course, most likely the Najdorf variation }
4... Nf6 5. Nc3 { Defending the pawn and developing the other knight. } 5... g6
{ This is the Dragon Sicilian. Black quickly makes a fianchetto for a safe king. }
6. Be2 { You can develop with the robust development plan. } 6... Bg7 7. O-O
O-O 8. Be3
{ You finished developing the minor piece and have a healthy position. You transpose back to the Hyperaccelerated Dragon after  8...Nc6  9.f4 }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3d) Sicilian Scheveningen and Classical Variations"]
[Black "Sicilian: Scheveningen Variation #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5
{ This move marks the Sicilian Defense. Black does not put a pawn directly in the center but controls it instead with a flank pawn. }
2. Nf3
{ You play in the same fashion as in the Open Games after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...e5  2.Nf3  You develop the knight and control the center.  Wait to put your other pawn in the center with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...c5  2.d4  because after  2...cxd4  3.Qxd4  Black can develop with tempo and attack your queen with  3...Nc6  . }
2... d6
{ Black opens up the diagonal for the light-squared bishop and controls the e5-square. }
3. d4
{ Here you go for the most principled variation: the Open Sicilian. White aims for quick and active development of his pieces. You follow the first golden move rule and place your pawn in the center.  The difference is that after  3...cxd4  , you can recapture with the knight and play  4.Nxd4  .  You saw before why you didn't play @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.d4  because after  2...cxd4  3.Qxd4  Nc6  Black gained a tempo in development by attacking your queen. }
3... cxd4
{ Black's best move is to capture the pawn.  After  3...Nc6  , you can start harassing the knight with  4.d5  .  When Black plays  3...Nf6  , you develop and defend the pawn with  4.Nc3  . }
4. Nxd4
{ Here, you recapture with the knight. You have opened the diagonals for both bishops. You can continue with Nc3, Be2, Be3, and castle kingside.  One move Black could play to disturb your plan is  4...e5  here, you can immediately go for  5.Bb5+  when after  5...Bd7  6.Bxd7+  Nxd7  7.Nf5  is strong, and you are attacking the d6-pawn.  Instead, you can also play  5.Nf3  and you will transpose to one of the other variations you will learn in the course most likely the Najdorf variation }
4... Nf6 5. Nc3 { Defending the pawn and developing the other knight. } 5... e6
{ The Scheveningen Variation, named after a city in the Netherlands. } 6. Be2
Be7 { Black castles get's his king castled before anything else. } 7. O-O O-O
8. Be3 Nc6
{ This position can also be reached through the Classical Sicilian.  8...a6  transposes to the Najdorf. }
9. f4
{ The position will almost always transpose to the Najdorf Variation after  9...a6  10.Bf3  Qc7  Also  9...Bd7  10.Nb3  a6  11.Bf3  Qc7  transposes. }
9... e5 { The only move that doesn't transpose back to the Najdorf. } 10. Nf3
{ The typical reaction in the Najdorf and Classical variations. } 10... Ng4
{ Black can also go for  10...exf4  11.Bxf4  Be6  , when can you place your king safely in the corner with  12.Kh1 }
11. Bc1 { 11.Bd2  is also strong! } 11... Qb6+
{ After  11...exf4  12.Bxf4  Qb6+  , you keep the same ideas. Black shouldn't play  12...Qb6+ }
12. Kh1 Nf2+ 13. Rxf2 Qxf2 14. Nd5
{ The power of knight domination is indisputable. You are ready to trap the queen with Be3.  After  14...Qc5  15.b4  Black's queen has so few squares that Black has to play  15...Nxb4  allowing  16.Nxe7+  , which gives you the bishop. }
*

