[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3d) Sicilian Scheveningen and Classical Variations"]
[Black "Knight Domination Setup"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5
{ This move marks the Sicilian Defense. Black does not put a pawn directly in the center but controls it instead with a flank pawn. }
2. Nf3
{ You play in the same fashion as in the Open Games after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...e5  2.Nf3  You develop the knight and control the center. Wait to place your other pawn in the center with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.d4  because after  2...cxd4  3.Qxd4  Black can develop with tempo and attack our queen with  3...Nc6  . }
2... d6
{ Black opens up the diagonal for the light-squared bishop and controls the e5-square. }
3. d4
{ You go for the most principled variation: the Open Sicilian. White aims for quick and active development of his pieces.  You follow the first golden move rule and place your pawn in the center. The difference compared to one move before is that after  3...cxd4  , you can recapture with the knight and play  4.Nxd4  .  You saw before why you didn't play @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.d4  because after  2...cxd4  3.Qxd4  Nc6  Black gained a tempo in development by attacking our queen. }
3... cxd4
{ Black's best move is to capture the pawn. After  3...Nc6  , you can start harassing the knight with  4.d5  .   When Black plays @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/3p4/2p5/3PP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  , you develop and defend the pawn with  4.Nc3  . }
4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 { Defending the pawn and developing the other knight. } 5...
a6 6. Be2 e5
{ You go for the Robust Development Setup by default and switch to the Knight Domination Setup whenever Black plays ...e5 }
7. Nf3
{ The knight retreats to the natural square. In the Knight Domination Setup, Bg5 and Bc4 are the best squares for your bishops. By playing,...e5 Black has weakened the d5-square on which you want to dominate with your knight. Your dark-squared bishop wants to eliminate Black's knight that controls the d5-square. Your light-squared bishop also wants to support the d5-square. You want to reach Knight Domination by having your knight on the outpost d5 in a dominating position. }
7... Be7 8. Bg5
{ With the Knight Domination Setup, you want to dominate with your knight on the d5-outpost. Therefore you want to eliminate the knight that controls d5. }
8... Be6 9. Bxf6
{ You eliminate the knight and don't give Black the chance to support it with ...Nbd7. }
9... Bxf6 10. O-O
{ You are not in a rush to go to the outpost so first safeguard the king by castling.   10.Nd5  to dominate with the knight is also strong. }
10... O-O 11. Nd5
{ You reach the Knight Domination Setup. You can go for the Knight Domination Setup whenever Black plays ...e5. You would like to play Bc4 to support your dominating knight.   11...Bxd5?  The most popular move at the beginner level eliminates your knight, but you will get pressure against Black's weak d6-pawn.  12.Qxd5  and Rad1 is coming. }
*

