{ You go for the Knight Domination Setup! } 8... O-O 9. Bxf6 Bxf6 10. O-O Be6
11. Nd5 { You reach the Knight Domination Setup. } 11... Rc8
{ Black's critical move! They ignore your knight and activate the rook. } 12.
c3
{ A thematic move in this structure, restricting Black's knight.  There is also nothing wrong with grabbing the pawn with  12.Nxf6  Qxf6  13.Qxd6  , but you give up your knight domination, and Black gains a tempo with  13...Rfd8 }
12... Ne7
{ Black's best reply to your knight domination, aiming to trade the knight. }
13. Nxf6+
{ You have to give up Knight Domination, so in return weakens Black's kingside. }
13... gxf6 14. Qc2
{ You open the d-file for the rooks!  After  14...d5  , you can trade  15.exd5  , and after any recapture, bring the rook to the open d-file. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3d) Sicilian Scheveningen and Classical Variations"]
[Black "Sicilian: Classical Sicilian #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5
{ This move marks the Sicilian Defense. Black does not put a pawn directly in the center but controls it instead with a flank pawn. }
2. Nf3
{ You play in the same fashion as in the Open Games after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...e5  2.Nf3  You develop the knight and control the center.  Wait to put your other pawn in the center with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...c5  2.d4  because after  2...cxd4  3.Qxd4  Black can develop with tempo and attack your queen with  3...Nc6  . }
2... d6
{ Black opens up the diagonal for the light-squared bishop and controls the e5-square. }
3. d4
{ Here you go for the most principled variation: the Open Sicilian. White aims for quick and active development of his pieces. You follow the first golden move rule and place your pawn in the center.  The difference is that after  3...cxd4  , you can recapture with the knight and play  4.Nxd4  .  You saw before why you didn't play @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.d4  because after  2...cxd4  3.Qxd4  Nc6  Black gained a tempo in development by attacking your queen. }
3... cxd4
{ Black's best move is to capture the pawn.  After  3...Nc6  , you can start harassing the knight with  4.d5  .  When Black plays  3...Nf6  , you develop and defend the pawn with  4.Nc3  . }
4. Nxd4
{ Here, you recapture with the knight. You have opened the diagonals for both bishops. You can continue with Nc3, Be2, Be3, and castle kingside.  One move Black could play to disturb your plan is  4...e5  here, you can immediately go for  5.Bb5+  when after  5...Bd7  6.Bxd7+  Nxd7  7.Nf5  is strong, and you are attacking the d6-pawn.  Instead, you can also play  5.Nf3  and you will transpose to one of the other variations you will learn in the course most likely the Najdorf variation }
4... Nf6 5. Nc3 { Defending the pawn and developing the other knight. } 5...
Nc6
{ This is the Classical Sicilian. Black gets his knight out quickly and attacks the d4 knight. Also, Black remains flexible with the rest of his pawns. }
6. Be2 { White can safely continue developing as before. } 6... e5
{ Black plays ...e5, so you switch to the Knight Domination Setup.  The most-played move.  6...g6  7.O-O  Bg7  8.Be3  transposes to the Dragon.  6...e6  7.Be3  Be7  transposes to the Scheveningen }
7. Nf3 { You go back to the natural square for the knight! } 7... h6
{ The most popular move to stop the exchange with Bg5-Bxf6, giving you knight domination. }
8. O-O
{ You continue development and have another plan to reach knight domination. }
8... Be7 9. Re1
{ 9.Nd5  loses the pawn now  9...Nxe4!  You slowly want to protect this pawn to prepare for Knight Domination, so you move the rook to the e-file. }
9... O-O { Black castles! } 10. h3
{ 10.Bf1  would protect the e4-pawn to allow Black to pin you with  10...Bg4  , when are they going for knight domination on d4 So you avoid that first. }
10... Be6 11. Bf1
{ You continue with the plan and are ready for Nd5 next move. The most-played move for Black is  11...Nb8  , but this is rarely played at the club level. }
11... Rc8
{ Black activates the rook! But this doesn't stop your knight Domination.   11...a6  is a popular move at the Club Player level, but it doesn't stop your play. You reach Knight Domination  12.Nd5   @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pp2bpp1/2npbn1p/4p3/4P3/2N2N1P/PPP2PP1/R1BQRBK1 b - - 2 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Qa5  is possible, but you can play  12.Bd2  threatening the Knight Domination with  12...Nd5  when the best move is for the queen to retreat  12...Qd8  You have to repeat with  13.Bc1  Qa5  14.Bd2  or play on with  14.Nd2 }
12. Nd5 Bxd5 { Black captures your knight. This gives you the bishop pair. }
13. exd5 Nb4
{ Double attack with ...Nxc2 and ...Nxd5, but don't worry, you can defend against both. }
14. c4
{ You support your center! You plan to continue with a3 and b4 shutting down the knight.  Therefore, Black will most likely play  14...a5  when after  15.a3  Na6  16.Rb1  you are ready to play b4 next! }
