{ This pawn move marks the Najdorf Sicilian, named after Polish/ Argentinian grandmaster Miguel Najdorf. This is one of the most popular openings at the highest level. Black prevents any piece from moving to b5 and remains flexible with the rest of his pawns. }
6. Be2 { You follow the robust development strategy. } 6... e5
{ A typical move in the Najdorf. Black aims to develop his dark-squared bishop and forces White's central knight to retreat. The disadvantage for Black is that the d6-pawn becomes backward, and the d5-square can't be defended by a pawn anymore. }
7. Nf3 { Your knight goes back to the natural square! } 7... h6 8. Nd2
{ There would be nothing wrong with  8.O-O  either.  You plan to play for the Knight Domination in a different way. Nc4-Ne3-Ncd5. This plan doesn't work well in Classical Sicilian since it is there after  8.Nd2  Be6  9.Nc4  Black can play  9...d5  and avoid the Knight Domination.  10.exd5  Nxd5  11.Nxd5  Qxd5  12.Qxd5  Bxd5  , and White only made some useless knight jumps without accomplishing anything.  In the Najdorf after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p3pp1/p2p1n1p/4p3/4P3/2N2N2/PPP1BPPP/R1BQK2R w KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Nd2  Be6  9.Nc4  d5?  10.exd5  Nxd5  11.Nxd5  the b6-square is weak  11...Bxd5  12.Be3  threatens a fork with Nb6.  Also, after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p3pp1/p2p1n1p/4p3/4P3/2N5/PPPNBPPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8...d5  9.exd5  Nxd5  10.Nxd5  Qxd5  White can make use of the weak b6-square  11.Nc4  Qxd1+  12.Bxd1  Nc6  13.Nb6  Rb8  14.Nxc8  Rxc8  White gets the bishop pair and plays  15.c3  to prevent ... Nd4 jumps.  After  11...Qxg2  12.Bf3  Qg6  13.Qe2  White will win back the e5-pawn. }
8... b5 9. a4 b4 10. Nd5 Nxd5 11. exd5
{ Black prevented your Knight Domination plan on d5 but couldn't develop anything. You have a plan for another knight domination. a5 Nc4-Nb6.  When Black plays  11...a5  to prevent that, your bishop has an outpost  12.Bb5+ }
