{ There would be nothing wrong with  8.O-O  either.  You plan to play for the Knight Domination in a different way. Nc4-Ne3-Ncd5. This plan doesn't work well in Classical Sicilian since it is there after  8.Nd2  Be6  9.Nc4  Black can play  9...d5  and avoid the Knight Domination.  10.exd5  Nxd5  11.Nxd5  Qxd5  12.Qxd5  Bxd5  , and White only made some useless knight jumps without accomplishing anything.  In the Najdorf after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p3pp1/p2p1n1p/4p3/4P3/2N2N2/PPP1BPPP/R1BQK2R w KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Nd2  Be6  9.Nc4  d5?  10.exd5  Nxd5  11.Nxd5  the b6-square is weak  11...Bxd5  12.Be3  threatens a fork with Nb6.  Also, after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p3pp1/p2p1n1p/4p3/4P3/2N5/PPPNBPPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8...d5  9.exd5  Nxd5  10.Nxd5  Qxd5  White can make use of the weak b6-square  11.Nc4  Qxd1+  12.Bxd1  Nc6  13.Nb6  Rb8  14.Nxc8  Rxc8  White gets the bishop pair and plays  15.c3  to prevent ... Nd4 jumps.  After  11...Qxg2  12.Bf3  Qg6  13.Qe2  White will win back the e5-pawn. }
8... Be6 9. Nc4 { You continue with your plan. } 9... b5 10. Ne3 Nbd7
{ When Black goes for  10...b4  11.Ncd5  , the e4-pawn is again poisoned  11...Nxe4  12.Bf3  controls an important diagonal and eyes the rook in the corner. }
11. a4
{ When Black captures with  11...bxa4  when after  12.Rxa4  Nc5  13.Ra1  , again, it will be dangerous for Black to capture the e4-pawn. }
11... b4 12. Ncd5
{ After  12...Nxe4  , you don't have to go for the direct attack with  13.Bf3  since after  13...Ndf6  14.Nxf6  Nxf6  15.Bc6+  Nd7  16.Bxa8  Qxa8  Black has sufficient compensation for the exchange. }
12... a5 13. O-O Be7
{ After  13...Nxe4  , you have the ideas with  14.Bf3  Nc5  15.Nc7+  discovered check winning the exchange.  But also you can play it slowly with @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/3nbpp1/3pbn1p/p2Np3/Pp2P3/4N3/1PP1BPPP/R1BQ1RK1 w kq - 2 14@@EndFEN@@  14.f4  activating the rook or  14.Bb5  , placing your bishop on an outpost. }
14. c3
{ It's time to activate your dark-squared bishop. You want to go to a3 and trade the b4-pawn. }
14... bxc3 15. bxc3
{ Your pawn is not weak since the knight supports it. Your bishop has beautiful prospects with Ba3 and Bb5.  After  15...O-O  16.Ba3  you are already threatening Nxe7+ to win the d6-pawn.  @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/3nbpp1/3pbn1p/p2Np3/P3P3/2P1N3/4BPPP/R1BQ1RK1 b kq - 0 15@@EndFEN@@  15...Nxe4?  will be punished with  16.Bf3  is dominating the diagonal when after  16...Ndc5  17.Qc2  attacks again  17...Ng5  opens the diagonal for  18.Nc7+  discovered check when  18...Qxc7  19.Bxa8  , you get the rook and are up in material. }
