[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3e) Sicilian Najdorf Variation"]
[Black "Sicilian: Najdorf Variation #10"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5
{ This move marks the Sicilian Defense. Black does not put a pawn directly in the center but controls it instead with a flank pawn. }
2. Nf3
{ You play in the same fashion as in the Open Games after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...e5  2.Nf3  You develop the knight and control the center.  Wait to put your other pawn in the center with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...c5  2.d4  because after  2...cxd4  3.Qxd4  Black can develop with tempo and attack your queen with  3...Nc6  . }
2... d6
{ Black opens up the diagonal for the light-squared bishop and controls the e5-square. }
3. d4
{ Here you go for the most principled variation: the Open Sicilian. White aims for quick and active development of his pieces. You follow the first golden move rule and place your pawn in the center.  The difference is that after  3...cxd4  , you can recapture with the knight and play  4.Nxd4  .  You saw before why you didn't play @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.d4  because after  2...cxd4  3.Qxd4  Nc6  Black gained a tempo in development by attacking your queen. }
3... cxd4
{ Black's best move is to capture the pawn.  After  3...Nc6  , you can start harassing the knight with  4.d5  .  When Black plays  3...Nf6  , you develop and defend the pawn with  4.Nc3  . }
4. Nxd4
{ Here, you recapture with the knight. You have opened the diagonals for both bishops. You can continue with Nc3, Be2, Be3, and castle kingside.  One move Black could play to disturb your plan is  4...e5  here, you can immediately go for  5.Bb5+  when after  5...Bd7  6.Bxd7+  Nxd7  7.Nf5  is strong, and you are attacking the d6-pawn.  Instead, you can also play  5.Nf3  and you will transpose to one of the other variations you will learn in the course most likely the Najdorf variation }
4... Nf6 5. Nc3 { Defending the pawn and developing the other knight. } 5... a6
{ This pawn move marks the Najdorf Sicilian, named after Polish/ Argentinian grandmaster Miguel Najdorf. This is one of the most popular openings at the highest level. Black prevents any piece from moving to b5 and remains flexible with the rest of his pawns. }
6. Be2 { You follow the robust development strategy. } 6... e5
{ A typical move in the Najdorf. Black aims to develop his dark-squared bishop and forces White's central knight to retreat. The disadvantage for Black is that the d6-pawn becomes backward, and the d5-square can't be defended by a pawn anymore. }
7. Nf3 { Your knight goes back to the natural square! } 7... Be7
{ Black continues development. } 8. Bg5
{ You go for the Knight Domination Setup. } 8... Be6
{ Black has three options. After  8...Be6  and  8...O-O  , you want to eliminate the knight with  9.Bxf6  before Black again plays ...Nbd7 supporting the knight.  When Black plays @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/1p2bppp/p2p1n2/4p1B1/4P3/2N2N2/PPP1BPPP/R2QK2R b KQkq - 3 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Nbd7  , it doesn't make sense to play  9.Bxf6  anymore since Black renews the knight with the other knight  9...Nxf6!  In this position, you want to wait with the trade until Black moves the knight on d7. }
9. Bxf6
{ You eliminate the knight and don't give Black the chance to support it with ...Nbd7. }
9... Bxf6 10. O-O O-O 11. Nd5 { You reach the Knight Domination Setup. } 11...
Bxd5
{ The most popular move at the club level is to eliminate the knight immediately! This gives you pressure against the d6-pawn. }
12. Qxd5 Nc6 13. c3
{ You prevent ...Nd4 and ...Nb4 ideas and get ready to play Rfd1 attacking the d6-pawn. }
13... Qc7 { Black prepares to bring Rad8! } 14. Rfd1
{ You go with your rook to the semi-open d-file and pressure the d6-pawn. In this structure, you want to get the bishop on the a2-g8 diagonal and reroute your knight to attack d6 and get closer to the outpost for a possible Knight Domination. }
