Nd7 12. Bc4 Rc8 13. Bb3 { You retreat the bishop. } 13... Nc5
{ Black immediately starts to target your bishop and e4-pawn. The computer also suggested  13...g6  , which Black has never played, and you can play in the same fashion with  14.Nxf6+  Qxf6  15.Qxd6 }
14. Nxf6+
{ You capture the bishop and go for the direct battle.   14.Re1  is an alternative, but it's likely that after massive exchange, an equal endgame without much play left will appear on the board  14...Nxb3  15.axb3  Bxd5  16.Qxd5  runs into  16...Rxc2  17.Qxb7  Rxb2  18.Rxa6  and now Black could opt for  18...Qb8  when after  19.Qxb8  Rxb8  20.Rxd6  R2xb3  , the remaining endgame looks drawish and boring. }
14... gxf6
{ Black could capture back with the pawn. This is a risky decision from the Black side but a decision Black can likely take when they want to complicate the game. }
15. Re1 { You bring the rook to the center. } 15... f5
{ Black challenges your center. } 16. Bxe6
{ You capture the bishop and go for the direct battle! } 16... fxe6 17. exf5
{ You trade the pawns. } 17... exf5
{ Black captures back with the pawn. After  17...Rxf5  18.Qd2  Black's center is in danger as Rad1 is coming. }
18. Qd5+ { You go for the check. Black's pawns move forward a lot. } 18... Kh8
19. Rad1 { It's time to include the rook in the game. } 19... Ne4
{ The only good move for Black go for a counterattack. } 20. Qxb7
{ You are the first one to grab a pawn. } 20... Rxc2
{ Grabbing the c2-pawn back is risky for Black. } 21. Nxe5
{ You capture the pawn and threaten the fork on f7. } 21... Qf6 22. Qb3
{ This move may look strange. The idea is that you force the rook to capture your pawn and then almost trap it to force Black's knight away from its powerful outpost. }
22... Rxf2 23. Nd3 { This almost traps the rook, and only Rd2 can escape. }
23... Rd2 24. Rxd2
{ By trading the rooks, you get Black's knight away from the powerful e4-square. }
24... Nxd2 25. Qd5
{ Now your queen controls the d5-square. As Black has four pawn islands, your pawns are a bit safer than Black's pawns. After  25...Ne4  26.Rf1  , you have so much pressure that Black can't do anything better than offer a trade of queens with  26...Qf7  and after  27.Qxf7  Rxf7  it will be a position where you can push risk-free for the win. }
