{ This pawn move marks the Najdorf Sicilian, named after Polish/ Argentinian grandmaster Miguel Najdorf. This is one of the most popular openings at the highest level. Black prevents any piece from moving to b5 and remains flexible with the rest of his pawns. }
6. Be2 { You follow the robust development strategy. } 6... e5
{ A typical move in the Najdorf. Black aims to develop his dark-squared bishop and forces White's central knight to retreat. The disadvantage for Black is that the d6-pawn becomes backward, and the d5-square can't be defended by a pawn anymore. }
7. Nf3 { Your knight goes back to the natural square! } 7... Be7
{ Black continues development. } 8. Bg5
{ You go for the Knight Domination Setup. } 8... Be6
{ Black has three options. After  8...Be6  and  8...O-O  , you want to eliminate the knight with  9.Bxf6  before Black again plays ...Nbd7 supporting the knight.  When Black plays @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/1p2bppp/p2p1n2/4p1B1/4P3/2N2N2/PPP1BPPP/R2QK2R b KQkq - 3 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Nbd7  , it doesn't make sense to play  9.Bxf6  anymore since Black renews the knight with the other knight  9...Nxf6!  In this position, you want to wait with the trade until Black moves the knight on d7. }
9. Bxf6
{ You eliminate the knight and don't give Black the chance to support it with ...Nbd7. }
9... Bxf6 10. O-O O-O 11. Nd5 { You reach the Knight Domination Setup. } 11...
Nd7 12. Bc4 Rc8 13. Bb3 { You retreat the bishop. } 13... Nc5
{ Black immediately starts to target your bishop and e4-pawn. The computer also suggested  13...g6  , which Black has never played, and you can play in the same fashion with  14.Nxf6+  Qxf6  15.Qxd6 }
14. Nxf6+
{ You capture the bishop and go for the direct battle.   14.Re1  is an alternative, but it's likely that after massive exchange, an equal endgame without much play left will appear on the board  14...Nxb3  15.axb3  Bxd5  16.Qxd5  runs into  16...Rxc2  17.Qxb7  Rxb2  18.Rxa6  and now Black could opt for  18...Qb8  when after  19.Qxb8  Rxb8  20.Rxd6  R2xb3  , the remaining endgame looks drawish and boring. }
14... Qxf6 15. Qxd6 { This leads to a forcing sequence of captures } 15... Bxb3
16. Qxf6 gxf6 17. axb3 Nxe4 18. Rfe1 { You attack the knight! } 18... Nc5 19.
b4 Nd7 20. c3
{ You solidify your pawn chain. In this structure, f5 is a strong square for your knight. You can go for Red1 to get the rook to the open file. }
*

