{ Black can't do much! After  10...Nc5  Black can't recapture with the knight anymore, so you can go for the trade  11.Bxf6  , getting one step closer to knight domination. }
11. Be3
{ Black played perfectly from a defensive point of view and did well to prevent the Knight domination plan for now. You have to be patient when your opponent plays well. You can ask Black now what they aim to do. You can improve your position with Bc4- Qd3 and Rfd1 and still aim to support Nd5 with your other bishop, queen, and rook. You can always keep fighting for the Knight domination.   11.Bh4  keeps an eye on the knight, but after  11...g5  12.Bg3  , your bishop looks at a wall of pawns, and Black's kingside is not so much weakened. The computer suggests it's still fine for White, but I don't recommend burying the bishop. }
11... Ng4 { Black goes after your bishop but loses track of the d5-square } 12.
Bc1
{ You go back to the starting square but are ready for Nd5 with the knight domination. }
12... Ngf6 { Black should also retreat to avoid Knight domination. } 13. Nd2
{ 13.Be3  would repeat the position. But you aim for Nc4-Ne3-Nd5 with Knight domination. }
13... Nc5 { Black prevents Nc4 by attacking the e4-pawn. } 14. b4
{ You kick the knight back. } 14... Ne6 15. Nc4
{ You are ready for the last two steps for Knight domination. Ne3-Ncd5. Giri and Vachier-Lagrave played this with White. The best chess players in the world don't just memorize computer moves but play the game with a plan. It's fine to forget some variations if you understand the plans and ideas.  After  15...Nd4  , you are not in a rush and can first move the bishop out of the way  16.Bd3   Black can also go for @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/1p2bpp1/p2pnn1p/4p3/PPN1P3/2N5/2P1BPPP/R1BQ1RK1 b - - 2 15@@EndFEN@@  15...Nxe4  , a tactic when after  16.Nxe4  d5  Black forks the knights  17.Bb2  develops, and after  17...dxc4  18.Bxe5  regains the e5-pawn.  18...Bxb4  19.Bxc4  You have a slight lead in development. }
