[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3f) Sicilian O'Kelly, Grievas and Löwenthal Variations"]
[Black "Sicilian: O'Kelly Variation #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5
{ This move marks the Sicilian Defense. Black does not put a pawn directly in the center but controls it instead with a flank pawn. }
2. Nf3 a6
{ The O'Kelly variation. You will understand the idea behind this pawn after discussing the Lowental variation  2...Nc6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  e5  Black attacks the knight, and we will play  5.Nb5!  The knight is ready to jump to d6 after  5...a6  6.Nd6+  Bxd6  7.Qxd6  White has the bishop pair and a better pawn structure.  With the O'Kelly variation, Black prevents your knight from jumping to b5. For most White players, this is a reason to completely abandon their strategy and not play @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/1p1ppppp/p7/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.d4  on the next move. You will still play  3.d4  .  I like sticking to the same moves to build a repertoire for you that is easy to remember and play. }
3. d4 cxd4 { Black should capture our center pawn. } 4. Nxd4
{ The position looks very good for you! You have your knight in the center and are ready to develop both the bishops, whereas Black's bishops are still stuck. Black's strategy is that they have a strategic advantage by having an extra center pawn. Also, they can gain a tempo on the knight with ...e5. }
4... Nf6 5. Nc3
{ You develop the knights and defend the pawn. Typically, you develop knights before you develop bishops, and you will stick with that strategy. This is because c3 and f3 are the natural development squares for knights, and for the bishops, the best squares depend on Black's play. By first developing knights, you gain more insight into Black's play, allowing you to choose the best squares for the bishops.  Unlike the Nimzowitch-Rubenstein variation, you can't attack the knight with  5.e5?  this time, as Black plays  5...Qa5+  double attack to win the e5-pawn. }
5... e5
{ Black's main idea! They pin the knight and want to play Bb4 pinning your knight and preventing the Knight Domination Setup. }
6. Nde2
{ When you play  6.Nf3?  , like in the Najdorf and Classical Sicilian, you won't be able to reach Knight Domination.  6...Bb4  Black pins your knight  7.Bg5  you can try to eliminate the knight on f6, but your knight won't be dominating  7...Bxc3  8.bxc3  and your strategy failed.  That's why you need to use your other knight to reinforce your knight on c3 @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p1p1ppp/p4n2/4p3/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq e6 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Nde2  You still go for the Knight Domination Setup! }
6... Bb4 { Black pins your knight! } 7. Bg5
{ You continue with your plan to reach the Knight Domination! } 7... O-O 8. a3
Ba5
{ Keeping the pin is the only option for Black not to allow you direct knight domination.  After  8...Be7  9.Bxf6  Bxf6  10.Nd5  you reach Knight Domination. }
9. Qd6
{ You stop all Black's play and get ready for O-O-O unpinning the knight and knight domination with Nd5*   9.b4  to unpin the knight is a sound alternative but makes things difficult! After  9...Bb6  , you can't play  10.Nd5  yet as it runs into  10...Nxe4  when you are unable to capture the queen  11.Bxd8  since  11...Bxf2#  finishes the game with a spectacular mate.  After @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/1p1p1ppp/p2Q1n2/b3p1B1/4P3/P1N5/1PP1NPPP/R3KB1R b KQ - 2 @@EndFEN@@  9.b4  Bb6  10.Ng3  , you would be doing great but you would rather avoid the unnecessary complications. }
