[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3f) Sicilian O'Kelly, Grievas and Löwenthal Variations"]
[Black "Sicilian: Löwenthal Variation #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5
{ This move marks the Sicilian Defense. Black does not put a pawn directly in the center but controls it instead with a flank pawn. }
2. Nf3
{ You play in the same fashion as in the Open Games after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...e5  2.Nf3  You develop the knight and control the center.  Wait to put your other pawn in the center with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...c5  2.d4  because after  2...cxd4  3.Qxd4  Black can develop with tempo and attack your queen with  3...Nc6  . }
2... Nc6
{ Black develops the knight and remains flexible with his pawns for the time being. The most popular move at the beginner and club player level, and the second-most popular move at the top level. }
3. d4
{ The Open Sicilian. Many White players are scared to play Open Silician because they think it's a heavy theoretical battleground. Black has many setups, and we must learn how to play against all of them. This course will teach you that it's possible to do well in the open Sicilian without learning a massive amount of theory. We will use a robust development setup that works versus almost all Sicilians. }
3... cxd4 4. Nxd4 { You capture with the knight as usual } 4... e5
{ This is the Kalashnikov Sicilian, in which Black quickly attacks White's central knight.  Black gives you control over the d5-square in return.  4...e6  5.Nc3  transposes to the Taimanov covered here. }
5. Nb5
{ White jumps in with his knight, with the possibility of jumping to d6.  Notice the difference with the Najdorf Sicilian @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...d6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  a6  , after which the pawn on a6 prevents the knight from jumping to b5 in that variation. }
5... a6
{ The Löwenthal Variation. Black attacks the knight, but White can jump in. }
6. Nd6+ Bxd6 7. Qxd6
{ White has gained the bishop pair, and Black has a worse pawn structure. On the other hand, Black is currently better developed. Yet, that is not a problem at all. }
7... Qe7
{ When you trade with  8.Qxe7  Ngxe7  , the Knight Domination setup no longer works since the knight came to e7 instead of f6. }
8. Qd1 { You go back and keep the plan of the Knight Domination Setup. } 8...
Nf6 9. Nc3 { Let's go for the Knight Domination setup. } 9... O-O 10. Bg5
{ And Black is already in trouble. Since Black's main problem is the d6-pawn, it makes a lot of sense to castle queenside to put a rook on the d-file. }
*

