{ You play in the same fashion as in the Open Games after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...e5  2.Nf3  You develop the knight and control the center.  Wait to put your other pawn in the center with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...c5  2.d4  because after  2...cxd4  3.Qxd4  Black can develop with tempo and attack your queen with  3...Nc6  . }
2... Nc6
{ Black develops the knight and remains flexible with his pawns for the time being. The most popular move at the beginner and Club player level, and the second most popular move at the top level. }
3. d4
{ The Open Sicilian. Many White players are scared to play Open Silician because they think it's a heavy theoretical battleground. Black has many setups, and we must learn how to play against all of them. This course will teach you that it's possible to do well in the open Sicilian without learning a massive amount of theory. You will use a robust development setup that works versus almost all Sicilians. }
3... cxd4 4. Nxd4 { You capture with the knight as usual } 4... e5
{ This is the Kalashnikov Sicilian, in which Black quickly attacks White's central knight.  Black gives you control over the d5-square in return.  4...e6  5.Nc3  transposes to the Taimanov covered here. }
5. Nb5
{ White jumps in with his knight, with the possibility of jumping to d6.  Notice the difference with the Najdorf Sicilian @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...d6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  a6  , after which the pawn on a6 prevents the knight from jumping to b5 in that variation. }
5... d6 { Black prevents the b5 knight from jumping to d6. } 6. N1c3
{ White continues developing and controls the d5 square. } 6... a6
{ Black kicks our knight away!  6...Nf6  7.Bg5  brings us to the Sveshnikov variation covered here. }
7. Na3 b5 { Black threatens ...b4 forking the knights } 8. Nd5
{ We take the outpost for our knight. An outpost is a square where a pawn protects you, and none of your opponent's pawns can attack you. Black can never kick away your knight with a pawn. }
8... Nge7
{ Black avoids your pin with the bishop by putting the knight on e7. } 9. Bd3
{ You can use the same rule as in the Scotch that pinning the knight when it's on e7 is not useful.  The knight is better protected here, and one big downside is that after  9.Bg5  h6  10.Bxe7  doesn't give you the knight domination since Black still has the other knight with  10...Nxe7  to exchange your dominating knight. }
9... Nxd5 { Black trades your dominating knight! } 10. exd5 Ne7 11. c4
{ You protect your center! } 11... g6
{ Black continues development and doesn't want to activate your knight. } 12.
O-O
{ You castle!  You would still be happy about it if Black plays  12...bxc4  13.Nxc4  with similar ideas as before. }
12... Bg7 13. cxb5
{ It's time to claim the advantage of the pawn, and Black has nothing to show for it. }
13... O-O 14. Re1
{ You get your rook to the center.   14.bxa6  wouldn't win you another pawn since Black takes it back with  14...Bxa6  . }
14... f5
{ The only try for Black to get some counterplay, but this allows you to get your knight activated.  After  14...Bb7  either playing  15.Bc4  to support the pawn or  15.bxa6  is strong for you. }
15. bxa6 { Now, after you capture, you can activate your knight. } 15... Bxa6
16. Nb5
{ The drawback from @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/4npbp/p2p2p1/1P1Pp3/8/N2B4/PP3PPP/R1BQR1K1 b - - 2 14@@EndFEN@@  14...f5  for Black is that in the current position after  15.bxa6  Bxa6  16.Nb5  Nxd5?  is not possible since you go for the pin with  17.Bc4  .  You plan Bf1 to strengthen your center pawn and can start pushing your pawns with a4 and b4. Black has no compensation for the sacrificed pawn. }
