[White "3g) Sicilian Kalashnikov and Sveshnikov Variations"]
[Black "Sicilian: Sveshnikov Variation #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5
{ This move marks the Sicilian Defense. Black does not put a pawn directly in the center but controls it instead with a flank pawn. }
2. Nf3
{ You play in the same fashion as in the Open Games after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...e5  2.Nf3  You develop the knight and control the center.  Wait to put your other pawn in the center with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...c5  2.d4  because after  2...cxd4  3.Qxd4  Black can develop with tempo and attack your queen with  3...Nc6  . }
2... Nc6
{ Black develops the knight and remains flexible with his pawns for now. The most popular move at the beginner and Club player level, and the second most popular move at the top level. }
3. d4
{ The Open Sicilian. Many White players are scared to play Open Silician because they think it's a heavy theoretical battleground. Black has many setups, and we must learn how to play against all of them. This course will teach you that it's possible to do well in the open Sicilian without learning a massive amount of theory. We will use a robust development setup that works versus almost all Sicilians. }
3... cxd4 4. Nxd4 { You capture with the knight as usual. } 4... Nf6 5. Nc3 e5
{ This is the Sveshnikov Sicilian, named after the Soviet grandmaster Evgeny Sveshnikov. The ideas are similar to the Kalashnikov variation. Black quickly attacks White's central knight, but his pawn formation gets slightly weakened.  After  5...e6  , we can continue with  6.Be2  followed by Be3 and the same after  5...d6  6.Be2 }
6. Ndb5
{ White jumps in with his knight, just like against the Kalashnikov Sicilian. }
6... d6 { Black prevents the b5-knight from jumping in. } 7. Bg5
{ White develops his bishop and pins the f6-knight. Your knights can become very threatening on b5 and d5. Black has to be careful now and can't just continue development. Next move, you will capture the knight. }
7... Be7 8. Bxf6 gxf6
{ 8...Bxf6  has also been played frequently, but we can immediately win the d6-pawn with  9.Qxd6  preventing Black from castling. }
9. Nd5
{ You are threatening Nbc7+ forking the king and rook. Also, Black's pawn structure on the kingside is weakened.  After  9...O-O  , there are multiple good ways to continue. The most straightforward one is to win a pawn with  10.Nxe7+  Qxe7  11.Qxd6 }
