{ A precise move! Black kicks back your knight before they continue development. }
8. Na3 { You retreat the knight! } 8... b5
{ Threatening a fork with ...b4 so you should move the knight. } 9. Nd5
{ Reaching Knight Domination and attacking the pinned knight on f6. } 9... Be7
{ Black develops and threatens to win a piece with @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/4bppp/p1np1n2/1p1Np1B1/4P3/N7/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 2 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Nxd5  when they open up the attack against our bishop and after  11.Bxe7  , their knight can escape back to safety with  11...Ndxe7  . }
10. Bxf6
{ You eliminate the knight and keep our knight on a powerful outpost.  After  10...Bxf6  , you don't want to trade with  11.Nxf6  Qxf6!  Your knight is powerful on the outpost, and you want to keep it there. }
10... Bxf6 11. c3
{ You get ready to bring your knight back into the game with Nc2 and can play a4 next to undermine Black's pawns on the queenside and get your bishop to c4.  Don't play  11.Be2  , it's the Knight Domination Setup, and your bishop belongs on c4. You want to get ready to support your dominating knight with your friends. }
11... Ne7 { Black directly challenges your knight on the outpost. } 12. Nxf6+
{ You grab the chance to destroy Black's pawn structure. Black will try to claim that opening up the g-file also has some benefits, which is true. }
12... gxf6 13. Nc2 { You bring the knight back to the game. } 13... Bb7
{ Black pressure the e4-pawn. } 14. Bd3 { You develop and support the pawn. }
14... d5
{ Black opens the center.   14...f5  is not dangerous!  15.exf5  Bxg2  16.Rg1  activates your rook along the g-file. }
15. exd5
{ You accept the trade.  15.Qe2  is also a sound alternative. In general, you only want to be defending in chess if you have to. Defending ties your pieces down and doesn't give them the freedom to fight somewhere else. }
15... Qxd5 { After  15...Nxd5  16.Be4  pins the knight. } 16. Ne3
{ You get the knight to e3 with tempo and defend the g2-pawn. } 16... Qe6 17.
a4
{ Black is unable to capture your pawn.  17...bxa4  18.Qxa4+  Qd7  19.Qxd7+  Kxd7  20.Bc4  gives you a fantastic endgame. You attack the f7-pawn and can play Ke2, and double the rooks on the a-file, and target the a6-pawn.  @@StartFEN@@r3k2r/1b2np1p/p3qp2/1p2p3/P7/2PBN3/1P3PPP/R2QK2R b KQkq a3 0 17@@EndFEN@@  17...Rd8  is the critical reply when  18.Qe2  unpins the bishop. Black should play  18...e4  to chase your bishop to a worse square but it also blocks Black's bishop.  19.Bc2  b4  is the best defense for Black when after  20.Rd1  , you aim to trade rooks to weaken Black's king. A sample variation is  20...f5  21.Rxd8+  to weaken Black's king  Kxd8  22.Qd1+  Kc7  23.Qd4  forks the rook and b4-pawn  23...Rd8  24.Qxb4  , this looks riskier for Black since you should be able to give a perpetual check once Black's attack gets strong. }
