{ You play in the same fashion as in the Open Games after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...e5  2.Nf3  You develop the knight and control the center.  Wait to put your other pawn in the center with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...c5  2.d4  because after  2...cxd4  3.Qxd4  Black can develop with tempo and attack your queen with  3...Nc6  . }
2... Nc6
{ Black develops the knight and remains flexible with his pawns for now. The most popular move at the beginner and Club player level, and the second most popular move at the top level. }
3. d4
{ The Open Sicilian. Many White players are scared to play Open Silician because they think it's a heavy theoretical battleground. Black has many setups, and we must learn how to play against all of them. This course will teach you that it's possible to do well in the open Sicilian without learning a massive amount of theory. We will use a robust development setup that works versus almost all Sicilians. }
3... cxd4 4. Nxd4 { You capture with the knight as usual. } 4... Nf6 5. Nc3 e5
{ This is the Sveshnikov Sicilian, named after the Soviet grandmaster Evgeny Sveshnikov. The ideas are similar to the Kalashnikov variation. Black quickly attacks White's central knight, but his pawn formation gets slightly weakened.  After  5...e6  , we can continue with  6.Be2  followed by Be3 and the same after  5...d6  6.Be2 }
6. Ndb5
{ White jumps in with his knight, just like against the Kalashnikov Sicilian. }
6... d6 { Black prevents the b5-knight from jumping in. } 7. Bg5
{ White develops his bishop and pins the f6-knight. Your knights can become very threatening on b5 and d5. Black has to be careful now and can't just continue development. Next move, you will capture the knight. }
7... a6
{ A precise move! Black kicks back your knight before they continue development. }
8. Na3 { You retreat the knight! } 8... b5
{ Threatening a fork with ...b4 so you should move the knight. } 9. Nd5
{ Reaching Knight Domination and attacking the pinned knight on f6. } 9... Be7
{ Black develops and threatens to win a piece with @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/4bppp/p1np1n2/1p1Np1B1/4P3/N7/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 2 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Nxd5  when they open up the attack against our bishop and after  11.Bxe7  , their knight can escape back to safety with  11...Ndxe7  . }
10. Bxf6
{ You eliminate the knight and keep our knight on a powerful outpost.  After  10...Bxf6  , you don't want to trade with  11.Nxf6  Qxf6!  Your knight is powerful on the outpost, and you want to keep it there. }
10... Bxf6 11. c3
{ You get ready to bring your knight back into the game with Nc2 and can play a4 next to undermine Black's pawns on the queenside and get your bishop to c4.  Don't play  11.Be2  , it's the Knight Domination Setup, and your bishop belongs on c4. You want to get ready to support your dominating knight with your friends. }
11... Bg5 12. Nc2 Rb8
{ Black can also go for this setup to delay castling. This can also be reached by the @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/5ppp/p1np1b2/1p1Np3/4P3/N1P5/PP3PPP/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Rb8  12.Nc2  Bg5  move order. }
13. a4 { Your plans don't change. } 13... bxa4
{ Black is threatening ...Rxb2 so you should prevent that. } 14. Rxa4
{ You recapture with the rook and stay consistent.   14.Ncb4  also makes it possible to save the b2-pawn. }
14... Rxb2 { Black captures the pawn. } 15. Bxa6
{ You win the pawn back and propose a trade of light-squared bishops. } 15...
O-O
{ The most played move for club players. You happily trade the bishops since it strengthens your Knight Domination. }
16. Bxc8 Qxc8 17. O-O Ne7 { Black counters your Knight Domination. } 18. Nxe7+
{ You trade the knights. } 18... Bxe7 19. Ne3
{ Your other knight is quick to reclaim the Knight Domination.   19...Qxc3?  is not possible since  20.Nd5!  gets the Knight Domination with a fork on the queen and bishop. }
