{ Black secures the pawn. } 15. Bc4
{ You develop the bishop and support the knight on the outpost. } 15... Rb8
{ Black attacks your b2-pawn. } 16. b3 { You also safeguard the pawn. } 16...
Kh8
{ Black's only good option in the position is to play ... f5 either in one go or with first g6 and f5. Therefore, the king has to sidestep to safety first. }
17. Nce3
{ You bring your knight over to support your dominating knight and to slow down Black's ...f5 idea. 17.O-O would be a solid alternative. }
17... g6
{ After 17...Ne7, you can trade with 18.Nxe7 Qxe7 and reinforce the Knight Domination with 19.Nd5 }
18. O-O
{ 18.h4  is a big theoretical debate where White sacrifices material with to open up the h-file  18...Bxh4  19.g3  Bg5  20.f4  exf4  21.gxf4  Bh4+  22.Kf1  g5!   The position looks more pleasant for White, but Black should be able to hold the balance. Both sides need to remember lots of theory there. I like to keep it simple and avoid going for these complications. }
18... f5 19. Qd3
{ Did you notice that all the pieces in your position are defended? This is the trademark of a healthy position. You don't want to trade with  19.exf5  gxf5  when Black gets more control over the center.  You would be happy to see @@StartFEN@@1rbq1r1k/7p/2np2p1/p2Nppb1/R1B1P3/1PPQN3/5PPP/5RK1 b - - 1 19@@EndFEN@@  19...f4  20.Nc2  f3  21.g3  when the on f3 is more a weakness than a strength. After  21...Qd7?  22.Rfa1  Qh3  23.Ne1  , you defend against the mate, and Black cannot continue the attack. You can chase the knight away with Bb5 and start marching your b-pawn forward.  Black's best strategy is to stay patient with @@StartFEN@@1rbq1r1k/7p/2np2p1/p2Nppb1/R1B1P3/1PPQN3/5PPP/5RK1 b - - 1 19@@EndFEN@@  19...Be6  when you can play  20.Rd1  going to the semi-open d-file. Since all your pieces are protected, you are not rushing to change the position. You can aim for Ra2 to prepare to defend the f2-pawn and swing over to the d-file. }
