[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4a) French Defense"]
[Black "French Exchange: 3...Qxd5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6
{ The French! The third most popular opening. A lot of White players don't like facing the French. This is because you can end up in a closed French pawn structure after  2.d4  d5  3.e5  or this structure from another move order.  Black will try to break down your center with  3...c5  followed by ... Nc6 ...Qb6 and feel comfortable in that pawn structure. What French players often dislike to face is the exchange variation. They often think that this variation is boring and drawish.  There is certainly ground for these claims. If you look in the database, a lot of games go something like: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq d6 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.exd5  exd5  4.Nf3  Nf6  5.Bd3  Bd6  6.O-O  O-O  7.Bg5  Bg4  8.c3  c6  9.Qc2  Qc7  , and in this symmetrical position, the percentage of games that ended in draw is enormous.  I recommend you play the French exchange ambitiously and with  3.exd5  exd5  4.c4  when the symmetrical pawn structure will disappear after a trade on c4. This way, you avoid the complex strategical French pawn structures and get an open battle with lightning-fast development and similar plans as in the Panov Attack versus the Caro-Kann. }
2. d4 d5 { Black strikes back in the center. } 3. exd5
{ You go for the exchange variation. You will play this against both the French and Caro-Kann. In both cases, you position where you can play for lightning-fast development and place your pieces on the natural squares.  There are three other main options against the French:  3.Nc3  the Classical variation.  3.Nd2  is the Tarrasch variation, and  3.e5  is the Advanced variation. You must usually be ready to play the typical closed French pawn structure with your pawn on e5. }
3... Qxd5 4. Nc3
{ You develop the knight with a tempo! This is the standard move after the queen captures, which you also play in the Scandinavian opening. }
4... Bb4 { Black starts pinning your knight! } 5. Nf3
{ As usual, you continue with development! Castling is typically the strongest way to reinforce the threat on the queen. }
5... Nf6 6. Be2
{ You develop the bishop! When you castle, you manage to unpin the knight. }
6... Ne4
{ Black takes the chance to attack your pinned knight.  If Black doesn't attack your pinned knight, then you can castle on the next move  6...O-O  7.O-O  unpins your knight when you threaten the queen. You will be happy to trade your knight for the bishop with  7...Bxc3  8.bxc3 }
7. O-O { You ignore the attack and castle. You are happy to sacrifice a pawn. }
7... Bxc3 8. Qd3
{ A brilliant move! Let's slow down a bit to understand the idea.  If you captured the bishop with  8.bxc3  , Black would capture back  8...Nxc3  and after  9.Qe1  Nxe2+  10.Qxe2  Black is a pawn-up, and even though you have better development, with this move, you show that you are not in a rush to recapture since when the bishop moves away, you can still win the knight. }
8... Bb4
{ The bishop moves away, and Black is a piece up. But you are still attacking the other knight and can chase away the defending queen. }
9. c4 { You chase the queen and aim to win the knight in the center. } 9... Qf5
{ The queen moves away to the only square where it can defend the knight. } 10.
Nh4 { You target the queen again to win the knight on the next move. } 10...
Qf6 { The queen drops back. } 11. Qxe4
{ You win the piece back and have a lead in development. Also, you threaten to trap the bishop with c5, followed by a3 and b4. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4a) French Defense"]
[Black "French Exchange: 3...Qxd5 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6
{ The French! The third most popular opening. A lot of White players don't like facing the French. This is because you can end up in a closed French pawn structure after  2.d4  d5  3.e5  or this structure from another move order.  Black will try to break down your center with  3...c5  followed by ... Nc6 ...Qb6 and feel comfortable in that pawn structure. What French players often dislike to face is the exchange variation. They often think that this variation is boring and drawish.  There is certainly ground for these claims. If you look in the database, a lot of games go something like: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq d6 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.exd5  exd5  4.Nf3  Nf6  5.Bd3  Bd6  6.O-O  O-O  7.Bg5  Bg4  8.c3  c6  9.Qc2  Qc7  , and in this symmetrical position, the percentage of games that ended in draw is enormous.  I recommend you play the French exchange ambitiously and with  3.exd5  exd5  4.c4  when the symmetrical pawn structure will disappear after a trade on c4. This way, you avoid the complex strategical French pawn structures and get an open battle with lightning-fast development and similar plans as in the Panov Attack versus the Caro-Kann. }
2. d4 d5 { Black strikes back in the center. } 3. exd5
{ You go for the exchange variation. You will play this against both the French and Caro-Kann. In both cases, you position where you can play for lightning-fast development and place your pieces on the natural squares.  There are three other main options against the French:  3.Nc3  the Classical variation.  3.Nd2  is the Tarrasch variation, and  3.e5  is the Advanced variation. You must usually be ready to play the typical closed French pawn structure with your pawn on e5. }
3... Qxd5 4. Nc3
{ You develop the knight with a tempo! This is the standard move after the queen captures, which you also play in the Scandinavian opening. }
4... Qd8 5. Nf3
{ You develop the other knight! Both your bishops are free to develop, and then you can castle. At this point, you have a clear lead in development. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4a) French Defense"]
[Black "French Monte Carlo Variation 4...dxc4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6
{ The French! The third most popular opening. A lot of White players don't like facing the French. This is because you can end up in a closed French pawn structure after  2.d4  d5  3.e5  or this structure from another move order.  Black will try to break down your center with  3...c5  followed by ... Nc6 ...Qb6 and feel comfortable in that pawn structure. What French players often dislike to face is the exchange variation. They often think that this variation is boring and drawish.  There is certainly ground for these claims. If you look in the database, a lot of games go something like: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq d6 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.exd5  exd5  4.Nf3  Nf6  5.Bd3  Bd6  6.O-O  O-O  7.Bg5  Bg4  8.c3  c6  9.Qc2  Qc7  , and in this symmetrical position, the percentage of games that ended in draw is enormous.  I recommend you play the French exchange ambitiously and with  3.exd5  exd5  4.c4  when the symmetrical pawn structure will disappear after a trade on c4. This way, you avoid the complex strategical French pawn structures and get an open battle with lightning-fast development and similar plans as in the Panov Attack versus the Caro-Kann. }
2. d4 d5 { Black strikes back in the center. } 3. exd5
{ You go for the exchange variation. You will play this against both the French and Caro-Kann. In both cases, you position where you can play for lightning-fast development and place your pieces on the natural squares.  There are three other main options against the French:  3.Nc3  the Classical variation.  3.Nd2  is the Tarrasch variation, and  3.e5  is the Advanced variation. You must usually be ready to play the typical closed French pawn structure with your pawn on e5. }
3... exd5 4. c4
{ You challenge Black's center before you develop the knights. You always want to develop the knight into natural squares with Nc3 and Nf3.  In this pawn structure, the knight would be poorly placed with a direct  4.Nc3  , since this knight can't put much pressure on the center with the pawn still on c2. You also propose a trade to an isolated pawn structure instead of a symmetrical pawn structure. The symmetrical pawn structure has a drawish reputation. }
4... dxc4
{ Black immediately captures the pawn. Typically, Black waits to capture the pawn until you move the bishop so that they can then capture and gain a tempo. You will be one tempo up, but the advantage for Black is that they can directly get their bishop to d6.   After the direct  4...Bd6  5.cxd5  , it can be difficult for Black to win back the pawn, as covered here. Black immediately captures the pawn. Typically, Black waits to capture the pawn until you move the bishop so that they can then capture and gain a tempo. You will be one tempo up, but the advantage for Black is that they can directly get their bishop to d6. }
5. Bxc4 { You capture and develop the bishop. } 5... Nf6
{ Black develops the knight! This transposes to  4...Bd6  5.Nf3  Nf6 } 6. Nf3
{ 6.Qb3  is an alternative that forces a good endgame after  6...Qe7+  7.Ne2  Qb4+  8.Nbc3  Qxb3  9.Bxb3  I don't like this option much since it's inconsistent with the style of the course and in the opening. In every position, you develop the knights to the most natural squares c3 and f3.  Also, it suddenly changes the natural plan of developing the knights first. Black can avoid this as well by starting with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/8/8/2BP4/8/PP3PPP/RNBQK1NR b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Bd6 }
6... Bd6
{ Black's best square for the bishop and the way to justify why Black would play 4...dxc4 and let your bishop recapture in the way.   5...Bb4+  wouldn't make much sense for Black since after  6.Nc3  you transpose to the mainline with a tempo up. }
7. O-O { You castle! Also  7.Nc3  would be just as good } 7... O-O 8. Nc3
{ As usually, you develop your other knight. } 8... Bg4 9. h3
{ You immediately challenge and start harassing the bishop to stop the pin. }
9... Bh5
{ The trade with  9...Bxf3  10.Qxf3  would be strong for you. You have the bishop pair and target the b7-pawn. }
10. g4
{ You insist on it that Black stop the pin. There is no danger in this position since you have the initiative. It is an important move! You don't want your knight to be pinned, so you unpin the knight. Pushing the pawns in front of your king may seem dangerous, but you will take the initiative when you can bring your knight to the center. }
10... Bg6 11. Ne5
{ Your knight is free and jumps to the central outpost. Also, you threaten to trap Black's light-squared bishop with f4 and f5.  If Black decides to capture your knight with  11...Bxe5  , you start harassing the knight with  12.dxe5  Your position is dominating, and after the knight moves, you keep the plan to start trapping the bishop. }
11... Nbd7
{ Black is in a tough situation. Striking back in the center with  11...c5?  is too dangerous for Black. You strike with  12.Nxg6  hxg6  13.dxc5  Bxc5  14.Bxf7!  The rook can't recapture it as it's protecting the queen and after  14...Kxf7  15.Qb3++-   You have a devastating attack. Black also tried @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pppn1ppp/3b1nb1/4N3/2BP2P1/2N4P/PP3P2/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 3 12@@EndFEN@@  11...Ne4  when after  12.f4  Nxc3  13.bxc3  the bishop can escape with  13...Be4  , but after  14.Qe2  Bc6  15.g5+-  you have a dominating knight in the center and are pinning the f7-pawn. }
12. f4 { You support your knight and plan to trap the bishop with f5. } *

