{ 6.Qb3  is an alternative that forces a good endgame after  6...Qe7+  7.Ne2  Qb4+  8.Nbc3  Qxb3  9.Bxb3  I don't like this option much since it's inconsistent with the style of the course and in the opening. In every position, you develop the knights to the most natural squares c3 and f3.  Also, it suddenly changes the natural plan of developing the knights first. Black can avoid this as well by starting with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/8/8/2BP4/8/PP3PPP/RNBQK1NR b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Bd6 }
6... Bd6
{ Black's best square for the bishop and the way to justify why Black would play  4...dxc4  and let your bishop recapture in way go.   5...Bb4+  wouldn't make much sense for Black since after  6.Nc3  you transpose to the mainline with a tempo up. }
7. O-O { You castle! Also  7.Nc3  would be just as good } 7... O-O 8. Nc3
{ As usually, you develop your other knight. } 8... Nc6 9. Bg5
{ You start pinning the knight. } 9... h6 { Black kicks your bishop back! } 10.
Bh4 { You keep the knight pinned. } 10... Bg4 11. h3
{ Your standard reaction is to break the pin! } 11... Bxf3 12. Qxf3 g5
{ Black can also choose to start chasing away your bishop. } 13. Bg3 Bxg3 14.
Qxg3
{ You capture back with the queen!  14.fxg3  is also a sound alternative! The downside is that this allows Black to capture  14...Qxd4+  with a check, but the upside is that you open the f-file. }
14... Qxd4 15. Bb5
{ You move your bishop out of the way! You keep an attack on the c7-pawn. }
15... Qd6
{ In this position with the weaker king, it would be wise for Black to go for a queen trade. }
16. Qxd6
{ Trading the queens also gives you an advantage as Black's d6-pawn becomes weak. }
16... cxd6 17. Rad1 Rad8 18. f4
{ You aim to activate your rook on the f-file! You are a pawn down, but Black has many weaknesses in the position, and all your pieces are active.  After  18...g4  19.hxg4  Nxg4  20.Rf3  , you can aim for a pin with Rg3, and when Black plays ...h5 to defend, you can continue with Rh3 targetting the h5-pawn. }
