2. d4 d5 { Black strikes back in the center. } 3. exd5
{ You go for the exchange variation. You will play this against both the French and Caro-Kann. In both cases, you position where you can play for lightning-fast development and place your pieces on the natural squares.  There are three other main options against the French:  3.Nc3  the Classical variation.  3.Nd2  is the Tarrasch variation, and  3.e5  is the Advanced variation. You must usually be ready to play the typical closed French pawn structure with your pawn on e5. }
3... exd5 4. c4
{ You challenge Black's center before you develop the knights. You always want to develop the knight into natural squares with Nc3 and Nf3.  In this pawn structure, the knight would be poorly placed with a direct  4.Nc3  , since this knight can't put much pressure on the center with the pawn still on c2. You also propose a trade to an isolated pawn structure instead of a symmetrical pawn structure. The symmetrical pawn structure has a drawish reputation. }
4... c5 { What happens if Black tries to create chaos in the center. } 5. cxd5
{ First, you let Black's queen come forward. } 5... Qxd5 6. Nc3
{ You develop and attack the queen. } 6... Qxd4
{ You are happy to sacrifice the pawn and want to develop all your pieces as quickly as possible. }
7. Bb5+ { Developing with a check. } 7... Bd7
{ After  7...Nc6  , you continue in the same fashion with  8.Qe2+  Be7  9.Nf3  gaining a tempo on the queen. }
8. Qe2+ { Developing with another check. } 8... Be7 9. Nf3
{ You develop and gain a tempo on the queen. } 9... Qb4 10. O-O
{ You castle and have a massive lead in development! } *

