[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4a) French Defense"]
[Black "French Monte Carlo Variation 4...c6 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6
{ The French! The third most popular opening. A lot of White players don't like facing the French. This is because you can end up in a closed French pawn structure after  2.d4  d5  3.e5  or this structure from another move order.  Black will try to break down your center with  3...c5  followed by ... Nc6 ...Qb6 and feel comfortable in that pawn structure. What French players often dislike to face is the exchange variation. They often think that this variation is boring and drawish.  There is certainly ground for these claims. If you look in the database, a lot of games go something like: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq d6 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.exd5  exd5  4.Nf3  Nf6  5.Bd3  Bd6  6.O-O  O-O  7.Bg5  Bg4  8.c3  c6  9.Qc2  Qc7  , and in this symmetrical position, the percentage of games that ended in draw is enormous.  I recommend you play the French exchange ambitiously and with  3.exd5  exd5  4.c4  when the symmetrical pawn structure will disappear after a trade on c4. This way, you avoid the complex strategical French pawn structures and get an open battle with lightning-fast development and similar plans as in the Panov Attack versus the Caro-Kann. }
2. d4 d5 { Black strikes back in the center. } 3. exd5
{ You go for the exchange variation. You will play this against both the French and Caro-Kann. In both cases, you position where you can play for lightning-fast development and place your pieces on the natural squares.  There are three other main options against the French:  3.Nc3  the Classical variation.  3.Nd2  is the Tarrasch variation, and  3.e5  is the Advanced variation. You must usually be ready to play the typical closed French pawn structure with your pawn on e5. }
3... exd5 4. c4
{ You challenge Black's center before you develop the knights. You always want to develop the knight into natural squares with Nc3 and Nf3.  In this pawn structure, the knight would be poorly placed with a direct  4.Nc3  , since this knight can't put much pressure on the center with the pawn still on c2. You also propose a trade to an isolated pawn structure instead of a symmetrical pawn structure. The symmetrical pawn structure has a drawish reputation. }
4... c6
{ Black wants to be solid in the center! The downside is that it takes away the natural square for their knight. }
5. Nc3
{ You keep developing the knight and put more pressure on the center. As learned in the opening rules. This is a flank pawn facing a center pawn, so you typically don't trade. }
5... Nf6 6. Nf3 { You develop the other knight as usual. } 6... Be7 7. Be2
{ You develop your bishop as usual. } 7... dxc4 8. Bxc4 O-O 9. O-O Nbd7
{ Black typically has in mind that they can go for ...Nb6 and place a knight on d5 with a solid position. The problem for Black is that there is no good square for their light-squared bishop in this setup. }
10. Re1 Nb6 11. Bb3
{ This same position could also be reached from the @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp2bppp/2p2n2/8/2BP4/2N2N2/PP3PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Nbd7  9.O-O  Nb6  10.Bb3  O-O  11.Re1  move order. }
11... Nbd5
{ A much safer move for Black would be placing the knight directly in the center. }
12. Bd2
{ You develop the bishop! This position looks innocent, and it seems like Black is doing just fine! But still, Black has no good square to develop the light-squared bishop in this structure.   12.Bg5  is much more popular and a good move, but you would like to keep this square free for your knight after  12.Bd2  Be6  , you can go for  13.Ng5  and harass that bishop. }
12... Be6 { When the bishop goes to e6, you will hit it with a tempo! } 13. Ng5
Bg4 14. Qb1
{ A bold move aiming for mating ideas! The knight on f6 is an important defender now, and White could move again  15.Bxd5  cxd5  16.Rxe7  Qxe7  17.Nxd5  would be crushing  @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pp2bppp/2p2n2/3n2N1/3P2b1/1BN5/PP1B1PPP/R2QR1K1 w - - 11 14@@EndFEN@@  14.Qc2?  is imprecise as it allows Black to chase away your queen with  14...Nb4 }
14... h6
{ Black will likely kick away your knight, but you won't go away!  The best move for Black would be  14...Bd6  as Black doesn't have to kick away your knight. After this, you have many ways to continue  15.Qd3  and  15.Nxd5  are possible, but you can also opt for  15.Nge4  attacking the bishop. }
15. h3 { In return for the knight, you would like to get the bishop. } 15...
hxg5 { Taking the knight may look logical for Black! } 16. hxg4
{ You capture the light-squared bishop! Black's position is riskier without the h-pawn. }
16... Nxg4 17. Nxd5
{ You capture the knight! Now that Black can only capture back with the pawn, they will get a weak pawn on d5. You didn't play this capture earlier because Black's knight on f6 first could capture back. }
17... cxd5 18. Qd1 { You chase the knight back. } 18... Nf6 19. Bxg5
{ You win the pawn back! With the bishop pair, you have a dominating position and a powerful attacking plan because the h-file is open and Re5-Qf3-g3-Kg2-Rh1 prepares to eliminate the knight and give mate on the h-file. }
