[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6
{ The French! The third most popular opening. A lot of White players don't like facing the French. This is because you can end up in a closed French pawn structure after  2.d4  d5  3.e5  or this structure from another move order.  Black will try to break down your center with  3...c5  followed by ... Nc6 ...Qb6 and feel comfortable in that pawn structure. What French players often dislike to face is the exchange variation. They often think that this variation is boring and drawish.  There is certainly ground for these claims. If you look in the database, a lot of games go something like: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq d6 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.exd5  exd5  4.Nf3  Nf6  5.Bd3  Bd6  6.O-O  O-O  7.Bg5  Bg4  8.c3  c6  9.Qc2  Qc7  , and in this symmetrical position, the percentage of games that ended in draw is enormous.  I recommend you play the French exchange ambitiously and with  3.exd5  exd5  4.c4  when the symmetrical pawn structure will disappear after a trade on c4. This way, you avoid the complex strategical French pawn structures and get an open battle with lightning-fast development and similar plans as in the Panov Attack versus the Caro-Kann. }
2. d4 d5 { Black strikes back in the center. } 3. exd5
{ You go for the exchange variation. You will play this against both the French and Caro-Kann. In both cases, you position where you can play for lightning-fast development and place your pieces on the natural squares.  There are three other main options against the French:  3.Nc3  the Classical variation.  3.Nd2  is the Tarrasch variation, and  3.e5  is the Advanced variation. You must usually be ready to play the typical closed French pawn structure with your pawn on e5. }
3... exd5 4. c4
{ You challenge Black's center before you develop the knights. You always want to develop the knight into natural squares with Nc3 and Nf3.  In this pawn structure, the knight would be poorly placed with a direct  4.Nc3  , since this knight can't put much pressure on the center with the pawn still on c2. You also propose a trade to an isolated pawn structure instead of a symmetrical pawn structure. The symmetrical pawn structure has a drawish reputation. }
4... Bb4+
{ Black gives a check! This move will likely transpose to the main variation with  5.Nc3  Nf6  , which will be covered here. Black also has another option to place the knight on e7. }
5. Nc3 Ne7
{ This looks like a strange move for Black, developing the knight to an unnatural square.  But there is a clear point to this move. After  5...Qe7  , you also continue with  6.Be2  , you don't mind that after  6...dxc4  you can't capture the pawn back yet because after  6.Nf3  followed by castling, you are ready to get the pawn back with a better position. }
6. Nf3 O-O 7. Be2 { You develop as planned. } 7... dxc4
{ Black delays the trade until this moment.  After  7...Nbc6  8.O-O  Bg4  , you can win the bishop pair with  9.a3  and after  9...Bxc3  10.bxc3  Black can't win a pawn with  10...Bxf3?  11.Bxf3  dxc4  since  12.Qa4  will win back the c4-pawn, and you will then have two bishops versus two knights. }
8. Bxc4 Bg4
{ 8...Nd5?  attacks the pinned knight, but Black ignores development. After  9.O-O  Nxc3  10.bxc3  Bxc3  11.Rb1  , you have an overwhelming lead in development for the pawn, and Ba3, Ng5 Qb3 will ruthlessly target the weak f7-square, the defending rook, and the undefended bishop. }
9. O-O Nbc6
{ You can also reach this position from the @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1nppp/8/8/1bBP4/2N2N2/PP3PPP/R1BQK2R b KQ - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Nbc6  9.O-O  Bg4  move order. }
10. Be3 { You develop and defend the d4-pawn. } 10... Nf5
{ Black's point behind playing 5...Ne7! They add another attacker to the d4-pawn. }
11. h3
{ You are happy to sacrifice a pawn to trade a knight for a bishop in this position. }
11... Bxf3
{ 11...Bh5  has never been played yet, but is a cunning move to keep the pin.  12.g4  doesn't win the piece yet since Black has the intermediate  12...Nxe3  13.fxe3  and then saves the bishop with  13...Bg6  here, you can't strengthen your center yet with  14.e4?  because Black can eliminate the defender knight  14...Bxc3  15.bxc3  Bxe4  .  That's why I like to include @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/ppp2ppp/2n5/5n1b/1bBP4/2N1BN1P/PP3PP1/R2Q1RK1 w - - 1 12@@EndFEN@@  12.a3  first, then after  12...Bd6  13.g4  Nxe3  14.fxe3  Bg6  , you have a strong center with  15.e4   When Black plays  12...Bxc3  instead, you get the bishop and defend your central pawn with  13.bxc3 }
12. Qxf3 Nfxd4
{ After  12...Ncxd4  13.Bxd4  Qxd4  14.Bb3  , you still have a double attack on the knight and b7-pawn. Also  13.Qxb7  would be a sound alternative.  @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/ppp2ppp/2n5/5n2/1bBP4/2N1BQ1P/PP3PP1/R4RK1 b - - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12...Nxe3?  13.fxe3  would be fantastic for you when your rook joins the attack on the f7-pawn. }
13. Qh5
{ You keep targeting the f7-pawn and get ready to pin the knight with Rad1. }
13... g6 { Black kicks away your queen to realease the pressure on f7. } 14.
Qg4
{ You target the knight and prepare to pin the knight with Rad1.  Black has to play  14...Ne5  when you win back the pawn with  15.Bxf7+  Rxf7  16.Qxd4  Alternatively, Black could go first for @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/ppp2p1p/2n3p1/8/1bBn2Q1/2N1B2P/PP3PP1/R4RK1 b - - 1 14@@EndFEN@@  14...Bxc3  15.bxc3  and then go for the fork with  15...Ne5  16.Bxf7+  Rxf7  17.Qxd4  is when you win back the pawn similarly. }
