2. d4 d5 { Black strikes back in the center. } 3. exd5
{ You go for the exchange variation. You will play this against both the French and Caro-Kann. In both cases, you position where you can play for lightning-fast development and place your pieces on the natural squares.  There are three other main options against the French:  3.Nc3  the Classical variation.  3.Nd2  is the Tarrasch variation, and  3.e5  is the Advanced variation. You must usually be ready to play the typical closed French pawn structure with your pawn on e5. }
3... exd5 4. c4
{ You challenge Black's center before you develop the knights. You always want to develop the knight into natural squares with Nc3 and Nf3.  In this pawn structure, the knight would be poorly placed with a direct  4.Nc3  , since this knight can't put much pressure on the center with the pawn still on c2. You also propose a trade to an isolated pawn structure instead of a symmetrical pawn structure. The symmetrical pawn structure has a drawish reputation. }
4... Nf6
{ The main move! Black develops the knight to defend the central pawn. In this position, you follow the rule of developing the knights first. It's important to note that. Black can play in different ways, too, and start, for example, with  4...Nc6  or  4...Bb4+  instead. Usually, the position will transpose into each other since you start developing your knights first. You will return to a position you studied a few moves later. }
5. Nc3 { Development as usual. You develop the knight! } 5... Be7
{ Black develops the bishop and gets ready to castle. } 6. Nf3
{ You develop the other knight. } 6... O-O 7. Be2
{ You also develop and get ready to castle. You are fine giving up a tempo and moving the bishop twice to recapture the pawn on c4 since c4 is such a good square for your bishop. }
7... dxc4
{ Black captures the pawn now that you move the bishop.   7...Be6  is answered similarly to the other variation,  8.Ng5  kicks the bishop away, and after  8...Bf5  9.O-O  Nc6  , you go back with  10.Nf3  and most likely transpose back to the mainline after  10...dxc4  11.Bxc4  Bg4  12.Be3 }
8. Bxc4 { You capture back and get the bishop to the powerful square. } 8...
Bg4 9. Be3
{ You develop the bishop and defend the pawn.  Going for  9.O-O  first is a sound alternative. }
9... Nbd7 10. h3
{ You start to get rid of the pin and want to place your knight in the center. }
10... Bh5 11. g4
{ You make sure your knight is no longer pinned. In other variations where Black played ...Bb4 you were aiming for an idea with Be2, Qb3, Ne5, but when you can no longer attack Black's dark-squared bishop, this makes less sense.   11.Be2  Nb6  12.Qb3  Nfd5  Would be a bit better for Black as they have a solid structure. }
11... Bg6 12. Ne5 { As usual, you firmly place your knight in the center. }
12... Nb6 { Black aims to block your isolated pawn with a knight on d5. } 13.
Bb3 Nbd5
{ On the eye, it looks like Black's position is solid. However, Black has one problematic piece: the light-squared bishop. You will aim to trap it. }
14. h4
{ You continue your plan to trap the bishop! In other variations, you did this with f4-f5, but in this position, your bishop on e3 is under attack, so it's better to use the h-pawn. }
14... Nxc3
{ Black will trade the knights to make an escape square for the bishop. } 15.
bxc3 Be4 { The bishop escapes but is still unsafe. } 16. O-O
{ You castle! You have multiple strong threats such as f3 kicking away the bishop, as it still doesn't have a good square, or you can also start with g5 chasing the knight back. }
*

