Bg4 9. Be3
{ You develop the bishop and defend the pawn.  Going for  9.O-O  first is a sound alternative. }
9... Nc6 { Black develops the knight. } 10. O-O
{ You castle. At this point, the most played move in the database is @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/ppp1bppp/2n2n2/8/2BP2b1/2N1BN2/PP3PPP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 4 10@@EndFEN@@  10...a6?  Black doesn't know how to make progress in this position. You plan to unpin the knight with  11.h3  Bh5  12.g4  Bg6  and place your knight on a powerful square in the center with  13.Ne5  .   If Black captures your knight with @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/ppp1bppp/2n2n2/8/2BP2b1/2N1BN2/PP3PPP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 4 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Bxf3  11.Qxf3  Black can capture your center pawn with  11...Nxd4  , but you win back a pawn with  12.Qxb7   Notice that in the opening, many move transpositions are possible @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/5n2/3p4/2PP4/2N5/PP3PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nc6  6.Nf3  Bg4  7.Be2  dxc4  8.O-O  Be7  9.Bxc4  O-O  10.Be3  would be another way to reach this position. Don't get confused when your opponent starts out with another move; by sticking to your plan, you will reach back to a position you already know! }
10... a6 { The most popular move, but that doesn't do much. } 11. h3 Bh5 12. g4
{ You continue with your plan to unpin your knight. } 12... Bg6 13. Ne5
{ You place the knight in the center and prepare for f4-f5! } 13... Nxe5
{ Club players often decide to capture the knight immediately. } 14. dxe5
{ You start harassing the knight! } 14... Ne4 15. Qxd8
{ You trade the queen, which is defending the bishop! } 15... Raxd8
{ If Black instead plays  14...Bxd8  , it is very passive and  15.f4  prepares to trap the bishop with f5. }
16. Nd5
{ You bring the knight in the attack and target the bishop! You don't aim to win the c7-pawn, which will give Black counterplay. }
16... Bc5 17. Rad1
{ You bring the rook to the open file!  The idea is that at this point, you threaten @@StartFEN@@3r1rk1/1pp2ppp/p5b1/2bNP3/2B1n1P1/4B2P/PP3P2/3R1RK1 w - - 3 17@@EndFEN@@  18.Bxc5  Nxc5  19.Ne7+  Kh8  20.Nxg6+  hxg6  21.Rxd8  Rxd8  22.Bxf7  , which wins a pawn but also gets ready for e6-e7, which wins the game.  @@StartFEN@@3r1rk1/1pp2ppp/p5b1/2bNP3/2B1n1P1/4B2P/PP3P2/R4RK1 w - - 2 17@@EndFEN@@  17.Bxc5?  Nxc5  18.Nxc7  is too greedy. Black has multiple options for counterplay  18...Rd7  19.Nd5  b5  is annoying when both your bishop and knight are under attack. }
17... Bxe3
{ When Black takes the bishop, you can use the same tactic to win the f7-pawn. }
18. Ne7+ Kh8 19. Nxg6+ hxg6 20. Rxd8 Rxd8 21. fxe3
{ And you attack the f7-pawn twice! Black has to push the pawn forward to save it. }
21... f6 22. Bf7
{ You create a double threat of Bxg6 and e6-e7, and this gives you a decisive advantage in the endgame. }
