15. Bxf3 Nxd4 16. Bxd4 Qxd4 17. Rxe7
{ The important tactical point winning a piece because of the skewer on the d-file! }
17... Rxe7 18. Rd1 { And White wins because of the skewer! } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4a) French Defense"]
[Black "French Monte Carlo Variation 4...Nf6 and 5...Be7 #10"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6
{ The French! The third most popular opening. A lot of White players don't like facing the French. This is because you can end up in a closed French pawn structure after  2.d4  d5  3.e5  or this structure from another move order.  Black will try to break down your center with  3...c5  followed by ... Nc6 ...Qb6 and feel comfortable in that pawn structure. What French players often dislike to face is the exchange variation. They often think that this variation is boring and drawish.  There is certainly ground for these claims. If you look in the database, a lot of games go something like: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq d6 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.exd5  exd5  4.Nf3  Nf6  5.Bd3  Bd6  6.O-O  O-O  7.Bg5  Bg4  8.c3  c6  9.Qc2  Qc7  , and in this symmetrical position, the percentage of games that ended in draw is enormous.  I recommend you play the French exchange ambitiously and with  3.exd5  exd5  4.c4  when the symmetrical pawn structure will disappear after a trade on c4. This way, you avoid the complex strategical French pawn structures and get an open battle with lightning-fast development and similar plans as in the Panov Attack versus the Caro-Kann. }
2. d4 d5 { Black strikes back in the center. } 3. exd5
{ You go for the exchange variation. You will play this against both the French and Caro-Kann. In both cases, you position where you can play for lightning-fast development and place your pieces on the natural squares.  There are three other main options against the French:  3.Nc3  the Classical variation.  3.Nd2  is the Tarrasch variation, and  3.e5  is the Advanced variation. You must usually be ready to play the typical closed French pawn structure with your pawn on e5. }
3... exd5 4. c4
{ You challenge Black's center before you develop the knights. You always want to develop the knight into natural squares with Nc3 and Nf3.  In this pawn structure, the knight would be poorly placed with a direct  4.Nc3  , since this knight can't put much pressure on the center with the pawn still on c2. You also propose a trade to an isolated pawn structure instead of a symmetrical pawn structure. The symmetrical pawn structure has a drawish reputation. }
4... Nf6
{ The main move! Black develops the knight to defend the central pawn. In this position, you follow the rule of developing the knights first. It's important to note that. Black can play in different ways, too, and start, for example, with  4...Nc6  or  4...Bb4+  instead. Usually, the position will transpose into each other since you start developing your knights first. You will return to a position you studied a few moves later. }
5. Nc3 { Development as usual. You develop the knight! } 5... Be7
{ Black develops the bishop and gets ready to castle. } 6. Nf3
{ You develop the other knight. } 6... O-O 7. Be2
{ You also develop and get ready to castle. You are fine giving up a tempo and moving the bishop twice to recapture the pawn on c4 since c4 is such a good square for your bishop. }
7... dxc4
{ Black captures the pawn now that you move the bishop.   7...Be6  is answered similarly to the other variation,  8.Ng5  kicks the bishop away, and after  8...Bf5  9.O-O  Nc6  , you go back with  10.Nf3  and most likely transpose back to the mainline after  10...dxc4  11.Bxc4  Bg4  12.Be3 }
8. Bxc4 { You capture back and get the bishop to the powerful square. } 8...
Bg4 9. Be3
{ You develop the bishop and defend the pawn.  Going for  9.O-O  first is a sound alternative. }
9... Nc6 { Black develops the knight. } 10. O-O
{ You castle. At this point, the most played move in the database is @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/ppp1bppp/2n2n2/8/2BP2b1/2N1BN2/PP3PPP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 4 10@@EndFEN@@  10...a6?  Black doesn't know how to make progress in this position. You plan to unpin the knight with  11.h3  Bh5  12.g4  Bg6  and place your knight on a powerful square in the center with  13.Ne5  .   If Black captures your knight with @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/ppp1bppp/2n2n2/8/2BP2b1/2N1BN2/PP3PPP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 4 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Bxf3  11.Qxf3  Black can capture your center pawn with  11...Nxd4  , but you win back a pawn with  12.Qxb7   Notice that in the opening, many move transpositions are possible @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/5n2/3p4/2PP4/2N5/PP3PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nc6  6.Nf3  Bg4  7.Be2  dxc4  8.O-O  Be7  9.Bxc4  O-O  10.Be3  would be another way to reach this position. Don't get confused when your opponent starts out with another move; by sticking to your plan, you will reach back to a position you already know! }
10... Qd7 11. h3 { You chase the bishop away! } 11... Bh5 12. Be2
{ You bring the bishop back to break the pin.  Note that playing  12.g4?  now is not possible since after  12...Nxg4  13.hxg4  Qxg4+  Black has a crushing attack, and you would be lost. }
12... Rad8 { Black brings the rook to the center! } 13. Re1
{ You make sure that Black can't go for liquidations!  The point is that now after  13...Bxf3  14.Bxf3  Nxd4  15.Bxd4  Qxd4  16.Qxd4  Rxd4  you pick up the bishop with  17.Rxe7 }
13... Rfe8
{ Black brings the other rook to the center!  This position can also be reached from the @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/pppqbppp/2n2n2/7b/3P4/2N1BN1P/PP2BPP1/R2Q1RK1 b - - 2 12@@EndFEN@@  12...Rfe8  13.Re1  Rad8  move order. }
14. Qb3 { Now you get ready for the plan with Ne5 again. } 14... Bd6 15. Ne5
{ You get the knight in the center aiming to leave one of Black's pieces misplaced on h5! }
15... Nxe5 16. dxe5
{ You capture back. After  16.Bxh5?  you would allow Black to escape with the knight and attack your rook with  16...Nd3 }
16... Bxe5 17. Bxh5 Nxh5 18. Qxb7
{ You win the pawn back and ruin Black's pawn structure on the queenside.  After  18...Nf4  , you can choose to either grab the pawn with  19.Bxa7  , or go for a safer option with  19.Bxf4  Bxf4  20.g3  followed by Kg2 when your king is very safe. }
*

