1. e4 c6 { The Caro-Kann opening. } 2. d4
{ You prioritize the first golden rule so also place your other pawn in the center. }
2... d5
{ The Caro-Kann is quite similar to the French. Black wants to strike back in the center on the second move with ...d5! As you know, you approach the opening in the same fashion as the French. }
3. exd5
{ The exchange variation! You keep the initiative and want to take down Black's pawns in the center. }
3... cxd5 4. c4
{ Like against the French opening, you immediately continue to put pressure on the center. You want to play your c-pawn in this structure before developing the knight with Nc3. If you would develop the knight first, it cannot put much pressure on Black's central pawn. You opened the diagonals for your bishops and queen in the first couple of moves. You know the plan already from other openings! The first step is to start developing the knights. }
4... dxc4
{ Black captures the pawn and allows you to develop your bishop in one go. } 5.
Bxc4 { You capture back and place your bishop on a powerful square. } 5... Nf6
6. Nf3
{ It's time to develop the knights like usual. Developing either knight is fine, but this one is more logical to play first as it allows you to castle. Whenever Black still has a pawn on d5, you can first develop the other knight to put pressure on the center. }
6... e6
{ The safest way to continue for Black is anticipating the knight hunt and the discovered attack in the previous variations. }
7. O-O Be7 8. Nc3 O-O 9. Re1
{ You bring your rook to the center! You want to open the position with d5 at some point, and then your rook dominates on the open e-file. An ideal moment to open the d-file is when Black pushes the b-pawn forward so that you can start to target the rook in the corner.  Also, you want to prevent Black from bringing the queenside knight to d5. A sample variation showing both ideas is:  9...Nc6  10.a3  preventing ...Nb4-Nd5  10...a6  11.Ba2  b5  12.d5  , now you open up the center  12...Nxd5  13.Nxd5  exd5  14.Qxd5  Black is under pressure, and  14...Qxd5?  would already lose a piece since  15.Bxd5  pins the knight  15...Bb7  16.Bxc6  Bxc6  17.Rxe7  wins the bishop. }
9... a6 10. Ne5
{ You want to prevent Black from playing ...b5 as you will be the first to control the important h1-a8 diagonal. }
10... b5 { Going for ...b5 is still the most played move. } 11. Qf3
{ You target the rook in the corner. } 11... Ra7 12. Bb3 b4 13. Ne4 Bb7
{ Whenever this bishop comes out, you sacrifice brutally on f7.  After  13...Nxe4  14.Qxe4  Bb7  now  15.Nxf7  is even stronger. You don't care that your queen is under attack because after  15...Bxe4  16.Nxd8  Rxd8  17.Bxe6+  Kh8  18.Rxe4  , you are two pawns up with a winning endgame. }
14. Nxf7 Bxe4 15. Rxe4 { Even  15.Qxe4  would be good } 15... Rxf7 16. Bxe6
{ With a dominating pin, you will win an exchange back. As usual, there is no rush to do this. At this point, the rook is in an absolute pin, not able to move, and your bishop is, for the time, more valuable than the rook. }
