[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5a) Caro-Kann Defense"]
[Black "Caro-Kann 4...dxc4 #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 { The Caro-Kann opening. } 2. d4
{ You prioritize the first golden rule so also place your other pawn in the center. }
2... d5
{ The Caro-Kann is quite similar to the French. Black wants to strike back in the center on the second move with ...d5! As you know, you approach the opening in the same fashion as the French. }
3. exd5
{ The exchange variation! You keep the initiative and want to take down Black's pawns in the center. }
3... cxd5 4. c4
{ Like against the French opening, you immediately continue to put pressure on the center. You want to play your c-pawn in this structure before developing the knight with Nc3. If you would develop the knight first, it cannot put much pressure on Black's central pawn. You opened the diagonals for your bishops and queen in the first couple of moves. You know the plan already from other openings! The first step is to start developing the knights. }
4... dxc4
{ Black captures the pawn and allows you to develop your bishop in one go. } 5.
Bxc4 { You capture back and place your bishop on a powerful square. } 5... Nf6
6. Nf3
{ It's time to develop the knights like usual. Developing either knight is fine, but this one is more logical to play first as it allows you to castle. Whenever Black still has a pawn on d5, you can first develop the other knight to put pressure on the center. }
6... e6
{ The safest way to continue for Black is anticipating the knight hunt and the discovered attack in the previous variations. }
7. O-O Be7 8. Nc3 O-O 9. Re1
{ You bring your rook to the center! You want to open the position with d5 at some point, and then your rook dominates on the open e-file. An ideal moment to open the d-file is when Black pushes the b-pawn forward so that you can start to target the rook in the corner.  Also, you want to prevent Black from bringing the queenside knight to d5. A sample variation showing both ideas is:  9...Nc6  10.a3  preventing ...Nb4-Nd5  10...a6  11.Ba2  b5  12.d5  , now you open up the center  12...Nxd5  13.Nxd5  exd5  14.Qxd5  Black is under pressure, and  14...Qxd5?  would already lose a piece since  15.Bxd5  pins the knight  15...Bb7  16.Bxc6  Bxc6  17.Rxe7  wins the bishop. }
9... Nc6 10. a3
{ You want to stop Black from playing ...Nb4-Nd5 when the knight would block your isolated pawn. }
10... a6 11. Ba2
{ You bring the bishop back to avoid that ...b5 would hit you with a tempo. }
11... b5 12. d5 { Now it's the perfect time for the pawn break! } 12... exd5
13. Nxd5
{ Your knight is coming in and putting pressure on the dark-squared bishop. }
13... Nxd5 { Eliminating the knight is already almost losing for Black. } 14.
Qxd5
{ You involve your queen in the fight! You are ready to either capture the knight or swing the queen over the kingside to attack with Qh5 }
14... Bb7
{ Black defends the knight with the bishop.  After  14...Qxd5?  15.Bxd5  Bb7  , you would already win a piece with  16.Bxc6  Bxc6  17.Rxe7 }
15. Qh5
{ You plan to exchange the dark-squared bishops with Bg5 and, after, go for the attack with Ng5!  Only in case Black plays  15...Qc7  a slower approach with  16.Bd2  followed by Rc1 is more effective. The idea of  15...Qc7  is that after  16.Bg5  Bxg5  17.Nxg5  , the queen is defending the f7-pawn, and Black can chase away your knight with  17...h6!  Even in that position, White is still significantly better. }
15... Qd6 { The most played move! Black wants to opt for a queentrade. } 16.
Bg5 Rad8 17. Bxe7 { You continue the plan and exchange the bishops. } 17...
Nxe7 18. Ng5 { This threatens Qh7# and also Nxf7! } 18... Qg6
{ Black's only move. } 19. Qxg6 Nxg6 20. Nxf7
{ Now it's time to strike! Usually, in a middle game with many pieces on the board, a knight and bishop are worth more than a rook and pawn, but in the endgame, the rook is very good in attacking pawns. }
20... Rxf7 21. Rad1
{ You keep the rook pinned and ensure you take control of the open d-file and will infiltrate Black's position. You are winning because you have this dominating pin.  21.Bxf7+?  Kxf7  would be a severe mistake, giving away all of your advantage.  Your bishop is much stronger than the rook because of the pin. After @@StartFEN@@3r2k1/1b3rpp/p5n1/1p6/8/P7/BP3PPP/3RR1K1 b - - 1 21@@EndFEN@@  21...Rxd1  22.Rxd1  Bc6  23.Rd8+  , also Black's knight will get into a pin  23...Nf8  White has a winning endgame, and Black is completely pinned down. }
*

