{ The exchange variation! You keep the initiative and want to take down Black's pawns in the center. }
3... cxd5 4. c4
{ Like against the French opening, you immediately continue to put pressure on the center. You want to play your c-pawn in this structure before developing the knight with Nc3. If you would develop the knight first, it cannot put much pressure on Black's central pawn. You opened the diagonals for your bishops and queen in the first couple of moves. You know the plan already from other openings! The first step is to start developing the knights. }
4... dxc4
{ Black captures the pawn and allows you to develop your bishop in one go. } 5.
Bxc4 { You capture back and place your bishop on a powerful square. } 5... Nf6
6. Nf3
{ It's time to develop the knights like usual. Developing either knight is fine, but this one is more logical to play first as it allows you to castle. Whenever Black still has a pawn on d5, you can first develop the other knight to put pressure on the center. }
6... e6
{ The safest way to continue for Black is anticipating the knight hunt and the discovered attack in the previous variations. }
7. O-O Be7 8. Nc3 O-O 9. Re1
{ You bring your rook to the center! You want to open the position with d5 at some point, and then your rook dominates on the open e-file. An ideal moment to open the d-file is when Black pushes the b-pawn forward so that you can start to target the rook in the corner.  Also, you want to prevent Black from bringing the queenside knight to d5. A sample variation showing both ideas is:  9...Nc6  10.a3  preventing ...Nb4-Nd5  10...a6  11.Ba2  b5  12.d5  , now you open up the center  12...Nxd5  13.Nxd5  exd5  14.Qxd5  Black is under pressure, and  14...Qxd5?  would already lose a piece since  15.Bxd5  pins the knight  15...Bb7  16.Bxc6  Bxc6  17.Rxe7  wins the bishop. }
9... Nc6 10. a3
{ You want to stop Black from playing ...Nb4-Nd5 when the knight would block your isolated pawn. }
10... b6 { Black gets ready to develop the bishop! } 11. d5
{ You open up the center and go for the attack.  A slower approach with  11.Ba2  would also be possible, but it doesn't put the same pressure. }
11... Na5 12. Ba2 Nxd5 13. Nxd5 { You capture back! } 13... exd5 14. Qxd5
{ As always, you capture with the queen!  If Black decides to trade queens with  14...Qxd5  15.Bxd5  , you win a material since the rook and bishop are both hanging. }
14... Be6 { Black's only move to survive. } 15. Rxe6
{ A novetly! The idea is that once Black captures your rook, aim to win back the exchange, trying to keep the pawn up that you won.   15.Qxd8  is more popular; however, after  15...Raxd8  Black is doing fine in the endgame.  16.Bxe6  fxe6  and  17.Rxe6  directly would be a bit imprecise as after  17...Rd1+  18.Re1  Rxe1  19.Nxe1  Rd8  Black will get an annoying initiative in exchange for the pawn. }
15... fxe6 16. Qxe6+ { So far, you lost an exchange for a pawn. } 16... Kh8 17.
Bd5
{ You attack the rook and want to win the exchange back!  You are threatening to take the rook because after  17...Bf6  18.Bxa8  Qd1+  , you still have  19.Qe1  to defend against the mate. Also, this move blocks the d-file, allowing you to play Ne5 next without getting mated on the back rank. }
17... Rc8
{ Black's move to escape with the rook still allows you to win an exchange in another way. }
18. Ne5
{ You even threaten a mate in two now with  18...--  19.Qg8+  Rxg8  20.Nf7#   You will aim for Nf7+ or Nd7 to win back the exchange. }
18... Qe8 19. Nd7
{ And the rook is trapped! You have a better position than White. Crazily enough, Black can play  19...Bxa3  with the idea that after  20.Nxf8  Qxf8  , you can't capture back with  21.bxa3  because  21...Re8  gives a skewer on the e-file with the threat of back rank mate. Therefore, playing  21.g3  is better for dealing with your problems, and you keep the bishop pair in an open position with a significant advantage.  Notice that the logical @@StartFEN@@2r1qr1k/p3b1pp/1p2Q3/n2BN3/8/P7/1P3PPP/R1B3K1 w - - 5 19@@EndFEN@@  19.Nf7+  does allow Black to win back the pawn with  19...Rxf7  20.Qxf7  Bxa3!  With the threat of back rank mate. }
