{ You prioritize the first golden rule so also place your other pawn in the center. }
2... d5
{ The Caro-Kann is quite similar to the French. Black wants to strike back in the center on the second move with ...d5! As you know, you approach the opening in the same fashion as the French. }
3. exd5
{ The exchange variation! You keep the initiative and want to take down Black's pawns in the center. }
3... cxd5 4. c4
{ Like against the French opening, you immediately continue to put pressure on the center. You want to play your c-pawn in this structure before developing the knight with Nc3. If you would develop the knight first, it cannot put much pressure on Black's central pawn. You opened the diagonals for your bishops and queen in the first couple of moves. You know the plan already from other openings! The first step is to start developing the knights. }
4... Nc6 5. Nc3
{ You develop the knight and put more pressure on the d5-pawn. } 5... dxc4
{ Black accepts the challenge and captures your pawn. Black is threatening to capture the d4-pawn now. Most games transpose back to the mainline with 5...Nf6 }
6. d5 { You hunt the knight. } 6... Ne5
{ Black's knight comes to the center and defends the c4-pawn. } 7. Nf3
{ A lovely move! You develop your knight to the natural square to attack the knight again. You would like to trade the knight to regain the c4-pawn. Technically, it is possible to capture the pawn back immediately with  7.Bxc4  Nxc4  and give a fork with  8.Qa4+  Bd7  9.Qxc4  You don't want to go for this variation because your light-squared bishop is powerful in this structure, and you don't want to give it up for the knight. }
7... Nxf3+ 8. Qxf3 Nf6 9. Bxc4
{ You have a lead in development! Next, you want to castle and develop your dark-squared bishop.  Note that when Black tries to develop with tempo with  9...Bg4  , you don't have to move your queen but can immediately bring the bishop back with  10.Bb5+  when Black admits the plan didn't work and plays  10...Bd7 }
