1. e4 c6 { The Caro-Kann opening. } 2. d4
{ You prioritize the first golden rule so also place your other pawn in the center. }
2... d5
{ The Caro-Kann is quite similar to the French. Black wants to strike back in the center on the second move with ...d5! As you know, you approach the opening in the same fashion as the French. }
3. exd5
{ The exchange variation! You keep the initiative and want to take down Black's pawns in the center. }
3... cxd5 4. c4
{ Like against the French opening, you immediately continue to put pressure on the center. You want to play your c-pawn in this structure before developing the knight with Nc3. If you would develop the knight first, it cannot put much pressure on Black's central pawn. You opened the diagonals for your bishops and queen in the first couple of moves. You know the plan already from other openings! The first step is to start developing the knights. }
4... Nf6 5. Nc3
{ As usual, you develop the knight! When Black still has a pawn on d5, you develop this knight first to attack in the center. }
5... e6
{ You can also get the same position after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/3p4/2PP4/8/PP3PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq c3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...e6  5.Nc3  Nf6   When Black goes for @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/3p4/2PP4/8/PP3PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq c3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...e6  5.Nc3  Bb4  , you can immediately challenge the bishop with  6.a3  and claim the bishop pair after  6...Bxc3  7.bxc3  . Next, you can get rid of your doubled c-pawn by trading with cxd5. }
6. c5
{ A very interesting idea that hasn't been played much. It's uncommon that you already play another pawn move at this point, but you want to shut down Black's dark-squared bishop and, as quickly as possible, play Bb5+ and trade your light-squared bishop.   6.Nf3  is much more popular, but if you play like in the French with  6...Be7  7.Bd3  dxc4  8.Bxc4  , you also spent two tempos to get here, but now that Black's pawn on e6 is blocking your bishop, the bishop is not as strong. This would still be a playable option, but I would suggest an alternative approach. I call this structure the Bishop Shutdown Structure, as you make it difficult for Black to activate the bishops. }
6... b6 { Black immediately to get rid of you c5-pawn. } 7. b4
{ You support the pawn! It's important to hold on to the d4 and c5-pawns and keep this better structure that restricts Black. }
7... a5
{ A logical and thematic move undermining the pawn structure. You cannot defend this pawn with your a-pawn because  8.a3?  axb4  9.axb4  drops the rook  9...Rxa1   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/p4ppp/1p2pn2/2Pp4/1P1P4/2N5/P4PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq b3 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Be7  is also possible and transposes to the variation after  8.Nf3  O-O  9.Rb1  , you are back in the mainline, which you will learn later in this chapter. }
8. Na4 { You get a strong counterattack on the b6-pawn. } 8... bxc5 9. bxc5
{ When Black goes for the trade, you keep your powerful structure and have a dominating advantage. Both bishops from Black are bad and also you can go for the direct attacks with Nb6 and Bb5+ }
