6. c5
{ A very interesting idea that hasn't been played much. It's uncommon that you already play another pawn move at this point, but you want to shut down Black's dark-squared bishop and, as quickly as possible, play Bb5+ and trade your light-squared bishop.   6.Nf3  is much more popular, but if you play like in the French with  6...Be7  7.Bd3  dxc4  8.Bxc4  , you also spent two tempos to get here, but now that Black's pawn on e6 is blocking your bishop, the bishop is not as strong. This would still be a playable option, but I would suggest an alternative approach. I call this structure the Bishop Shutdown Structure, as you make it difficult for Black to activate the bishops. }
6... Nc6
{ This is a poor move from Black and one that is played a lot! Black's knight can't put much pressure on the center. Also, later, you can trade eliminating this knight with your bishop so that your center becomes untouchable. }
7. Nf3 { You develop the knight first, as usual. } 7... Be7 8. Bb5
{ You pin the knight } 8... O-O 9. Bxc6
{ You immediately capture the knight and get a good structure. } 9... bxc6 10.
O-O Ne4 11. Qc2 { The standard reply! } 11... f5 12. b4
{ You strengthen your pawn structure now. } 12... a5 13. b5
{ You sacrifice a pawn to have the dominating c-pawn. } 13... Nxc3 14. Qxc3
cxb5 15. Bf4
{ Positionally speaking, you are dominating Black, who has two bad bishops. Also, the e6-pawn is weak. }
