{ By castling, Black prepares for their standard pawnbreak with ...b6 and ...a5! You need to anticipate it. }
8. Rb1
{ This is only the seventh move in terms of popularity, and your opponent has probably never seen it before. It has been played by Grandmaster Jobava who is known for his original play. The idea is straightforward: you want to keep your pawn construction that shuts down the dark-squared bishop and anticipate that Black will try to take it down.  Now, after  8...b6  , you can defend with  9.b4  , and after  10...a5  , you can defend with  11.a3  because after  11...axb4  12.axb4  , your rook is no longer hanging. }
