[White "5a) Caro-Kann Defense"]
[Black "Caro-Kann 4...Nf6 5...Nc6 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 { The Caro-Kann opening. } 2. d4
{ You prioritize the first golden rule so also place your other pawn in the center. }
2... d5
{ The Caro-Kann is quite similar to the French. Black wants to strike back in the center on the second move with ...d5! As you know, you approach the opening in the same fashion as the French. }
3. exd5
{ The exchange variation! You keep the initiative and want to take down Black's pawns in the center. }
3... cxd5 4. c4
{ Like against the French opening, you immediately continue to put pressure on the center. You want to play your c-pawn in this structure before developing the knight with Nc3. If you would develop the knight first, it cannot put much pressure on Black's central pawn. You opened the diagonals for your bishops and queen in the first couple of moves. You know the plan already from other openings! The first step is to start developing the knights. }
4... Nf6 5. Nc3
{ As usual, you develop the knight! When Black still has a pawn on d5, you develop this knight first to attack in the center. }
5... Nc6 6. Nf3 g6
{ The move is slightly dubious! You can go with a forcing variation, also oblige Black to play ...e6 and the combination of both doesn't look pretty. }
7. cxd5 Nxd5 8. Qb3 { You increase the pressure! } 8... Nxc3
{ When Black captures your knight, you have a beautiful move! } 9. Bc4
{ This is powerful! You threaten Bxf7, and Black's knight can't escape.  After  9...Ne4?  10.Bxf7+  Kd7  11.Qe6+  would already win the knight back with a fork! Despite that, the computer suggests that  11.O-O  is even more winning for White. }
9... Nd5 { Jumping back with the knight is another option for Black. } 10. Bxd5
e6 11. Bxc6+ { You capture, and Black will get a weak pawn on c6! } 11... bxc6
12. O-O Qd5 13. Bg5
{ You take control of the f6-square, making sure to profit from Black's weak dark-squares. Moving the queen away with, for example,  13.Qc2  is also a sound alternative. }
13... Bg7 14. Qe3
{ You move the queen away and aim to trade the dark-squared bishops. } 14...
O-O 15. Bh6 { With the trade of bishops coming, Black is in trouble. } *

