{ You capture the pawn! Black should be able to win it back with  18...f6  19.Be3  Kxe7  when you can castle  20.O-O  . To be honest, the endgame looks very drawish, and you don't have an edge here as White.  If you don't like that possibility @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/pp1nppbp/3P2p1/1Q6/8/2N2P2/PP3P1P/R1B1K2R w KQkq - 1 15@@EndFEN@@  15.Nd5  would have been a better try to keep a more dynamic and fighting position. The advantage of this line is that you test out your opponent to find some challenging moves and can get a big advantage when they go wrong.  @@StartFEN@@r3k2r/1p1npp1p/1p1P2p1/6B1/8/2P2P2/P4P1P/R3K2R w KQkq - 0 18@@EndFEN@@  18.Bxe7  would also have been possible. This makes it easier to hold on to the pawn for longer, but the downside is that after  18...f6  , your bishop is a bit stuck. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5a) Caro-Kann Defense"]
[Black "Caro-Kann 4...Nf6 5...Nc6 #13"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 { The Caro-Kann opening. } 2. d4
{ You prioritize the first golden rule so also place your other pawn in the center. }
2... d5
{ The Caro-Kann is quite similar to the French. Black wants to strike back in the center on the second move with ...d5! As you know, you approach the opening in the same fashion as the French. }
3. exd5
{ The exchange variation! You keep the initiative and want to take down Black's pawns in the center. }
3... cxd5 4. c4
{ Like against the French opening, you immediately continue to put pressure on the center. You want to play your c-pawn in this structure before developing the knight with Nc3. If you would develop the knight first, it cannot put much pressure on Black's central pawn. You opened the diagonals for your bishops and queen in the first couple of moves. You know the plan already from other openings! The first step is to start developing the knights. }
4... Nf6 5. Nc3
{ As usual, you develop the knight! When Black still has a pawn on d5, you develop this knight first to attack in the center. }
5... Nc6 6. Nf3 Bg4
{ Black develops the bishop and pins your knight.  6...e6  has already been covered here. After  6...e6  , you will play  7.c5  and transpose. }
7. cxd5
{ In the Beginner version, I recommended  7.Bg5  , which is also a good move. I changed my mind after seeing the game between top GMs J. Van Foreest and Keymer, where Black got completely crushed. }
7... Nxd5 8. Qb3
{ You attack again and increase the pressure on the knight and b7-pawn. } 8...
Bxf3 9. gxf3 e6
{ Black supports the knight.  9...Nb6  10.d5  Nd4  transposes to the variation you learned with  11.Bb5+  . }
10. Qxb7 { You capture the pawn and target the knight. } 10... Nxd4
{ Black fights back to capture your pawn in the center. The knight is threatening some forks now so it's time to attack with your bishop. }
11. Bb5+ { You attack on the light-squares. } 11... Nxb5
{ Black has to eliminate the knight. } 12. Qc6+
{ A cunning check that forces Black to misplace the queen.  After  12.Qxb5+  Qd7  13.Qxd7+  Kxd7  14.Nxd5  exd5  Black is doing fine in the endgame. }
12... Ke7
{ Black's only move as  12...Qd7?  Would allow  13.Qxa8+  when you win the rook with a check. }
13. Qc5+
{ It's time to surprise your opponent now.  13.Qxb5  is the most popular move, but I feel that Black is generally better prepared against this and is less challenging for Black. The main variation with  13...Qd7  14.Nxd5+  Qxd5  15.Qxd5  exd5  leads to an equal endgame. }
13... Ke8 { Often, players already go wrong with this move! } 14. Qxb5+
{ There is a difference that now you can capture with a check. } 14... Qd7 15.
Nxd5
{ And a beautiful tactical point! You can exchange the knights and force them to capture back with the pawn.  You are not losing your queen because after  15...Qxb5  16.Nc7+  wins the queen back with the royal fork when after  16...Kd7  17.Nxb5  , you are a piece up. }
15... exd5 16. Qd3
{ Keeping the queen on the board is very powerful now! Remember that Black played ...Ke7-Ke8 and is no longer ready to castle. Because of that, your king is safer, and you should keep the queens on the board. }
16... Bb4+ 17. Kf1
{ You run with your king, and g2 would be a very safe square. You don't want to trade the bishops because your bishop could be very well placed on e3 when your king is on e2! Your bishop is a good defender, whereas Black's bishop doesn't do much. Also, you keep motifs alive with Qd4, which attacks the bishop and a couple of pawns. }
17... Qh3+ { Black gives a check and should stop you from playing Kg2 } 18. Ke2
{ Now you go to e2! Black's queen is now misplaced and must hurry back because you threaten to capture the d5-pawn. }
18... Qe6+ 19. Be3 { You block the attack with the bishop! } 19... Ke7
{ Black can no longer castle and must go forward with the king to connect the rooks. }
20. Rad1
{ You put pressure on the d5-pawn. White has a pleasant advantage here. With the bishop blocking the e-file Your position is safer. You can opt for Rg1, Qd4 to target the g7-pawn and bishop. Also, you have pressure against the d5-pawn. }
*

