[Round "?"]
[White "5a) Caro-Kann Defense"]
[Black "Caro-Kann 4...Nf6 5...Nc6 #19"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 { The Caro-Kann opening. } 2. d4
{ You prioritize the first golden rule so also place your other pawn in the center. }
2... d5
{ The Caro-Kann is quite similar to the French. Black wants to strike back in the center on the second move with ...d5! As you know, you approach the opening in the same fashion as the French. }
3. exd5
{ The exchange variation! You keep the initiative and want to take down Black's pawns in the center. }
3... cxd5 4. c4
{ Like against the French opening, you immediately continue to put pressure on the center. You want to play your c-pawn in this structure before developing the knight with Nc3. If you would develop the knight first, it cannot put much pressure on Black's central pawn. You opened the diagonals for your bishops and queen in the first couple of moves. You know the plan already from other openings! The first step is to start developing the knights. }
4... Nf6 5. Nc3
{ As usual, you develop the knight! When Black still has a pawn on d5, you develop this knight first to attack in the center. }
5... Nc6 6. Nf3 Bg4
{ Black develops the bishop and pins your knight.  6...e6  has already been covered here. After  6...e6  , you will play  7.c5  and transpose. }
7. cxd5
{ In the Beginner version, I recommended  7.Bg5  , which is also a good move. I changed my mind after seeing the game between top GMs J. Van Foreest and Keymer, where Black got completely crushed. }
7... Nxd5 8. Qb3
{ You attack again and increase the pressure on the knight and b7-pawn. } 8...
Bxf3 9. gxf3 e6
{ Black supports the knight.  9...Nb6  10.d5  Nd4  transposes to the variation you learned with  11.Bb5+  . }
10. Qxb7 { You capture the pawn and target the knight. } 10... Nxd4
{ Black fights back to capture your pawn in the center. The knight is threatening some forks now so it's time to attack with your bishop. }
11. Bb5+ { You attack on the light-squares. } 11... Nxb5
{ Black has to eliminate the knight. } 12. Qc6+
{ A cunning check that forces Black to misplace the queen.  After  12.Qxb5+  Qd7  13.Qxd7+  Kxd7  14.Nxd5  exd5  Black is doing fine in the endgame. }
12... Ke7
{ Black's only move as  12...Qd7?  Would allow  13.Qxa8+  when you win the rook with a check. }
13. Qc5+
{ It's time to surprise your opponent now.  13.Qxb5  is the most popular move, but I feel that Black is generally better prepared against this and is less challenging for Black. The main variation with  13...Qd7  14.Nxd5+  Qxd5  15.Qxd5  exd5  leads to an equal endgame that would make it difficult to crush your opponent in the opening phase. }
13... Nd6 { Black's best move is to block with the knight. } 14. Nxd5+
{ You capture the knight to open the d-file. } 14... exd5 15. Qxd5
{ A fantastic move!  15.O-O  has been played much more, so Black likely won't expect this. Black got crushed in the top GM battle between Van Foreest and Keymer. }
15... Rc8 16. O-O
{ You castle to include the rook!   16.Bf4?  would be wrong now as Black goes for  16...Nc4  and Black now proposes a trade of queens, which is annoying  17.Qe4+  Kf6  18.O-O  Bc5  and it turns out that Black's king is safe here, and they get ready for ...Rhe8 gaining a tempo on the queen.  @@StartFEN@@r2q1b1r/p3kppp/3n4/3Q4/8/5P2/PP3P1P/R1B1K2R b KQ - 0 15@@EndFEN@@  15...h6  is another move that Black could play, but it doesn't look so sensible, and you can continue with either  16.Bf4  and  16.O-O }
16... Qb6 17. Bf4 { Your bishop is always powerful on f4 in these positions. }
17... Rc5 18. Qd2
{ At this point, you are threatening to bring both rooks to the open e and d-file, harassing the king and the knight. Also, Be3 is a threat to give a skewer on the rook. }
*

