[White "6a) Scandinavian Defense"]
[Black "Scandinavian Modern: 2...Nf6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5
{ The Scandinavian opening. Black directly strikes back in the center. As explained in the Course Specific Rules chapter in the informational on pawns facing in the center, capturing the pawn is the only good option in this position. You lure Black's queen forward to gain a tempo in development. }
2. exd5 Nf6
{ Black doesn't capture the pawn back yet but attacks it with the knight instead. }
3. c4 { You defend the pawn! } 3... e6
{ Black challenges your central pawn and wants to lead development after  4.dxe6  Bxe6  when placing a pawn in the center can be problematic with  5.d4  since after  5...Bb4+  6.Nc3  Black can increase the pressure on your pinned knight with  6...Ne4 }
4. d4 { You refuse the pawn sacrifice and place your pawn in the center. } 4...
exd5 { Black captures back your central pawn. } 5. Nc3
{ Again, it's no problem for you! You transpose back to the French opening and have already studied these variations. You managed to trick your opponent in another opening. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6a) Scandinavian Defense"]
[Black "Scandinavian Modern 2...Nf6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5
{ The Scandinavian opening. Black directly strikes back in the center. As explained in the pawn structure sheet here, capturing the pawn is the only good option. You lure Black's queen forward to gain a tempo in development. }
2. exd5 Nf6
{ Black doesn't capture the pawn back yet but attacks it with the knight instead. }
3. c4 { You defend the pawn! } 3... c6
{ Black challenges your pawn in the center. If you capture, you would be a pawn up; however, Black after  4.dxc6  Nxc6  Black is ahead in development, and you can't place your pawn in the center with  5.d4  since Black wins it with  5...Qxd4  .  Therefore, you prefer to avoid capturing the pawn and go back to the first golden move rule, placing your pawn in the center. }
4. d4 cxd5
{ Black should capture back your pawn! No problem, you have transposed to the Caro-Kann opening. }
5. Nc3
{ You already studied these variations in the Caro-Kann opening in a previous chapter of this course. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6a) Scandinavian Defense"]
[Black "Scandinavian Valencian Variation 3...Qd8 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5
{ The Scandinavian opening. Black directly strikes back in the center. As explained in the pawn structure sheet here, capturing the pawn is the only good option. You lure Black's queen forward to gain a tempo in development. }
2. exd5 Qxd5 { Black's queen recaptures } 3. Nc3
{ You develop the knight and gain a tempo on the queen. This strategy is in line with the logic that you didn't play after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  you don't play  2.d4  because Black trades with  2...cxd4  3.Qxd4  and then gains the tempo on your queen with  3...Nc6 }
3... Qd8 { The queen retreats! } 4. d4
{ You follow the first golden rule and place your pawn in the center. } 4...
Nf6 5. Nf3 { You still follow the general logic and develop the other knight. }
5... e6 6. Bd3 Be7 7. Bg5
{ An interesting moment! With White, you prefer to castle queenside. This will make it easier to start an attack against Black's king later on. You are planning to play Qe2 and castle queenside  7.O-O  looks very logical and is also a fine alternative. }
7... Nbd7 8. Qe2 { Getting ready to castle queenside. } 8... O-O 9. O-O-O
{ A typical consolidating move is Kb1 in these positions where you castled queenside. Again, you can place your knight on the powerful e5-square. }
*

