{ The Scandinavian opening. Black directly strikes back in the center. As explained in the pawn structure sheet here, capturing the pawn is the only good option. You lure Black's queen forward to gain a tempo in development. }
2. exd5 Qxd5 { Black's queen recaptures } 3. Nc3
{ You develop the knight and gain a tempo on the queen. This strategy is in line with the logic that you didn't play after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  you don't play  2.d4  because Black trades with  2...cxd4  3.Qxd4  and then gains the tempo on your queen with  3...Nc6 }
3... Qd8 { The queen retreats! } 4. d4
{ You follow the first golden rule and place your pawn in the center. } 4...
Nf6 5. Nf3 { You still follow the general logic and develop the other knight. }
5... Bg4
{ Black pins your knight! Here, reacting in the same way as in the French opening is powerful. }
6. h3 { You target the bishop and force them to unpin the knight! } 6... Bh5
{ Black keeps the pin, but you can unpin the knight. } 7. g4
{ You chase the bishop back again. } 7... Bg6 8. Ne5
{ You control this powerful central position with the knight. The knight is almost on an outpost. An outpost is a square not occupied by a pawn, protected by your pawn, and no enemy pawn can ever attack it. e5 is technically not an outpost since Black's f-pawn can still attack it; however, practically speaking, it will be almost impossible for Black to move the knight out of the way and play ...f6! In this position, your light-squared bishop will be powerful on g2.   Also, you have the plan available to, at some point, trap Black's bishop with h4, h5 }
