2. exd5 Qxd5 { Black's queen recaptures } 3. Nc3
{ You develop the knight and gain a tempo on the queen. This strategy is in line with the logic that you didn't play after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  you don't play  2.d4  because Black trades with  2...cxd4  3.Qxd4  and then gains the tempo on your queen with  3...Nc6 }
3... Qd8 { The queen retreats! } 4. d4
{ You follow the first golden rule and place your pawn in the center. } 4...
Nf6 5. Nf3 { You still follow the general logic and develop the other knight. }
5... Bg4
{ Black pins your knight! Here, reacting in the same way as in the French opening is powerful. }
6. h3 { You target the bishop and force them to unpin the knight! } 6... Bxf3
{ Black should go for the trade to avoid the scenario where you get a dominating knight. You are happy to get the bishop pair. }
7. Qxf3 { You capture back with the queen and target the b7-pawn. } 7... c6
