[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6a) Scandinavian Defense"]
[Black "Scandinavian Gubinsky-Melts Defense 3...Qd6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5
{ The Scandinavian opening. Black directly strikes back in the center. As explained in the pawn structure sheet here, capturing the pawn is the only good option. You lure Black's queen forward to gain a tempo in development. }
2. exd5 Qxd5 { Black's queen recaptures } 3. Nc3
{ You develop the knight and gain a tempo on the queen. This strategy is in line with the logic that you didn't play after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  you don't play  2.d4  because Black trades with  2...cxd4  3.Qxd4  and then gains the tempo on your queen with  3...Nc6 }
3... Qd6 4. d4 { The same logic, you place your pawn in the center. } 4... Nf6
5. Nf3 Bg4
{ Whenever Black pins your knight, use the h-pawn to break the pin. } 6. h3
{ You kick the bishop to unpin the knight. } 6... Bh5 7. g4
{ You harass the bishop again. } 7... Bg6 8. Ne5
{ You place the knight on the powerful central square. } 8... Nbd7 9. Nc4
{ There are many moves to play in this position! The most consistent approach is to aim and trap the light-squared bishop at some point, so I don't recommend  9.Nxg6  , although it is a good option.   9.f4  is also possible but could be difficult to play since after  9...O-O-O  , you can't yet trap the bishop with  10.Nxd7  Nxd7  11.f5  as Black enters your position with  11...Qg3+   Therefore, with @@StartFEN@@r3kb1r/pppnpppp/3q1nb1/4N3/3P2P1/2N4P/PPP2P2/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 3 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Nc4  Qe6  10.Ne3  , you first misplace Black's queen and get ready for f4-f5 }
9... Qe6+ 10. Ne3
{ You are threatening f4-f5, which forks the queen and bishop and traps the bishop.  Also, Bg2 is coming when your light-squared bishop controls a fantastic diagonal.  10...h5  you can answer with  11.Bg2  keeping the option open to play f4-f5 }
