[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6a) Scandinavian Defense"]
[Black "Scandinavian Gubinsky-Melts Defense 3...Qd6 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5
{ The Scandinavian opening. Black directly strikes back in the center. As explained in the pawn structure sheet here, capturing the pawn is the only good option. You lure Black's queen forward to gain a tempo in development. }
2. exd5 Qxd5 { Black's queen recaptures } 3. Nc3
{ You develop the knight and gain a tempo on the queen. This strategy is in line with the logic that you didn't play after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  you don't play  2.d4  because Black trades with  2...cxd4  3.Qxd4  and then gains the tempo on your queen with  3...Nc6 }
3... Qd6 4. d4 { The same logic, you place your pawn in the center. } 4... Nf6
5. Nf3 c6
{ Black plays a slow move. At this point, you can get your knight into the center with  6.Ne5  so that Black can't comfortably develop the light-squared bishop.  @@StartFEN@@rnb1kb1r/ppp1pppp/3q1n2/8/3P4/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...a6  would be a cunning waiting move from Black! Your same plan to place the knight in the center hasn't worked this time since after  6.Ne5  Black can play  6...Nc6  and directly force a trade of your strong knight.  7.Nxc6  Qxc6  benefits Black since the queen pins your g2-pawn and developing the light-squared bishop is challenging. Therefore, you could reply with to @@StartFEN@@rnb1kb1r/ppp1pppp/3q1n2/8/3P4/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...a6  with  6.g3  and aim to place fianchetto your light-squared bishop. }
6. Ne5 { You place the knight in a powerful position! } 6... Nbd7
{ Black proposes to trade your strong knight! You don't want to go along with that. }
7. Nc4 { You kick away the queen! } 7... Qc7 8. Qf3
{ You develop the queen and prepare for Bf4 to develop and gain a tempo on the queen. }
8... Nb6
{ Black challenges your knight! A common mistake at the beginner level is  8...e6  when Black tries to continue development. You continue your plan  9.Bf4  developing with a tempo and after  9...Qd8  , you have  10.Nd6+  Bxd6  11.Bxd6  and your powerful bishop prevents Black from castling. }
9. Bf4 { You develop the bishop with tempo. } 9... Qd8 10. Be5
{ You place the bishop on the powerful square in the center and defend your central pawn. Next, you want to play Ne3 to prevent ideas with ...Bg4 from Black.  Avoid the trap that after  10.O-O-O  Black has a skewer with  10...Bg4  to win an exchange. }
10... Be6 11. Ne3 Nbd5 { Black often goes with the knight to the center! } 12.
Ncxd5 Nxd5
{ You traded a pair of knights so that Black can't play ...g6 and develop the dark-squared bishop to g7 anymore. }
13. Bd3
{ You develop your bishop and get ready to castle kingside. As Black has ideas with ...Nb4, this is now better than castling queenside. Black is still stuck with the development of the dark-squared bishop. }
