[Round "?"]
[White "6a) Scandinavian Defense"]
[Black "Scandinavian Main Line 3...Qa5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5
{ The Scandinavian opening. Black directly strikes back in the center. As explained in the pawn structure sheet here, capturing the pawn is the only good option. You lure Black's queen forward to gain a tempo in development. }
2. exd5 Qxd5 { Black's queen recaptures } 3. Nc3
{ You develop the knight and gain a tempo on the queen. This strategy is in line with the logic that after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  you don't play  2.d4  because Black trades with  2...cxd4  3.Qxd4  and then gains the tempo on your queen with  3...Nc6 }
3... Qa5 4. d4 { The standard move placing your pawn in the center. } 4... Nf6
5. Nf3 { You develop the knight as usual. } 5... Nc6
{ Black develops the knight and attacks your center. The queen is low on squares now. }
6. Bd2 { You develop your bishop and x-ray the queen along the diagonal. } 6...
Bg4 { Black keeps developing and pins your knight. } 7. d5
{ You start hunting the knight. It looks like you are giving up a pawn for nothing, but the pawn is poisoned. }
7... Nxd5 { Black captures the pawn. } 8. Nb5
{ You give a discovered attack on the queen and aim for the c7-square. } 8...
Qb6
{ Black moves the queen to the only safe square. The pawn on c7 is seemingly well protected, but you can chase away both defenders of the pawn in the next two moves. }
9. c4 { You chase away the knight first. } 9... Nf6 10. c5
{ A fantastic move since you chase away the queen, and Black cannot defend the c7-pawn. }
10... Qxc5 11. Nxc7+
{ You strike and fork the king and rook.  After  11...Kd7  , you can win the rook with  12.Nxa8  , but it would also be just as strong to go for the queen with a discovered attack and play  12.Bb4+ }
