[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6a) Scandinavian Defense"]
[Black "Scandinavian Main Line 3...Qa5 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5
{ The Scandinavian opening. Black directly strikes back in the center. As explained in the pawn structure sheet here, capturing the pawn is the only good option. You lure Black's queen forward to gain a tempo in development. }
2. exd5 Qxd5 { Black's queen recaptures } 3. Nc3
{ You develop the knight and gain a tempo on the queen. This strategy is in line with the logic that after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  you don't play  2.d4  because Black trades with  2...cxd4  3.Qxd4  and then gains the tempo on your queen with  3...Nc6 }
3... Qa5 4. d4 { The standard move placing your pawn in the center. } 4... Nf6
5. Nf3 { You develop the knight as usual. } 5... c6 6. Bc4
{ You develop the bishop. If you play  6.Ne5  first, that allows Black to play  6...Be6  which, after  7.Bc4  , allows them to trade light-squared bishops with  7...Bxc4  . And although  8.Nxc4  is a good line for White, it should be noted that, in the Scandinavian structure, Black's light-squared bishop is problematic for Black, so you want to keep it on the board. }
6... Bg4
{ If Black plays  6...Bf5  , then you play  7.Ne5  and go to the mainline with  7...e6  8.g4 }
7. h3 { You immediately attack the bishop to break the pin. } 7... Bxf3 8. Qxf3
{ A trade would be good for White. You like to castle queenside in these positions. }
8... e6 9. Bd2 Qc7 10. O-O-O Nbd7 11. Kb1
{ Getting the king to b1 is a standard move when you castle queenside to make your king safer. }
11... O-O-O 12. Bb3
{ You drop the bishop back and anticipate the threat of ...Nb6, which would be a double attack both on your bishop and the d4-pawn. }
12... Bd6 13. g4 { You can aim for g5 going after the f7-pawn. } 13... h6
{ Black defense against the threat. } 14. h4
{ You reinforce the threat of g5.  White has a fantastic position, and the best move Black can play is the passive  14...Nf8  to make sure the queen defends the f7-pawn. You can continue with  15.Na4  which has the idea to play c4 and get more control in the center. }
