3... Qa5 4. d4 { The standard move placing your pawn in the center. } 4... Nf6
5. Nf3 { You develop the knight as usual. } 5... c6 6. Bc4
{ You develop the bishop. If you play  6.Ne5  first, that allows Black to play  6...Be6  which, after  7.Bc4  , allows them to trade light-squared bishops with  7...Bxc4  . And although  8.Nxc4  is a good line for White, it should be noted that, in the Scandinavian structure, Black's light-squared bishop is problematic for Black, so you want to keep it on the board. }
6... Bg4
{ Black pins your knight! Like Black plays  6...Bf5  instead when you opt for  7.Ne5  and go to the mainline with  7...e6  8.g4 }
7. h3 { You immediately attack the bishop to break the pin. } 7... Bh5
{ Usually, the bishop keeps the pin. } 8. g4
{ You attack and chase the bishop further back. } 8... Bg6 9. Bd2
{ You develop the bishop and line up towards Black's queen! Next, you want to play h4-h5 and threaten to trap Black's light-squared bishop. }
9... e6 10. h4 { You go ahead with your plan! } 10... Nxg4 11. h5
{ Now that Black has already played ...e6, it is stronger to push the pawn first. }
11... Bf5
{ Capturing the pawn with  11...Bxh5  would be too dangerous for Black; you have multiple good ways to punish that and  12.Ng5  would be an option to threaten Rxh5. }
12. Qe2
{ You get the queen out and get ready to castle! Black has no good plan to keep developing. Castling kingside would be quite suicidal for Black. But castling queenside leaves the f7-pawn vulnerable.  12.Nh4  would also be a good alternative. }
12... Nd7 13. O-O-O O-O-O
{ Black managed to castle, but now the f7-pawn is vulnerable. } 14. Ng5
{ You aim for the fork. } 14... Nh6 { Black's only move to defend. } 15. Nd5
{ Now, also, Black's queen is vulnerable. } 15... Qa4 16. Ne3
{ The knight will be overloaded defending the f7-pawn and the bishop. Soon, you will win back the pawn while keeping a strong lead in development. }
*

