[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7a) Sidelines: Alekhine, Nimzowitsch and Owen Defenses "]
[Black "Alekhine Defense 1...Nf6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ Get ready to tackle the sidelines! What's going to be super helpful here is everything you've learned from the course. It's good to get your pawns in the middle. Remember, you usually develop the knights first, and hunting your opponents' knights can be smart. Sometimes, you'll play against opponents who don't know their openings well and do something offbeat. If that happens, stay calm. Use the concepts you've learned to take advantage of their unusual start. }
1... Nf6 2. e5 { You hunt the knight! A concept you have seen before. } 2...
Nd5 3. c4
{ You strengthen your center and chase the knight again.  Placing your other pawn in the center with  3.d4  is equally good and will likely result in the same position after  3...d6  4.c4 }
3... Nb6 { The knight jumps back! } 4. d4
{ You place your other pawn in the center.  Kicking the knight again with  4.c5  is not useful. The knight returns to a central position with  4...Nd5  , and your c-pawn can become weak when it's too far advanced. }
4... d6 { Black attacks your central pawn. } 5. exd6
{ You trade the pawns!  Supporting the center with  5.f4  is an alternative, but in this case, after  5...dxe5  6.fxe5  Nc6  , the standard plan was to develop the knights first with  7.Nf3  works less well as you immediately get pinned with  7...Bg4!  That's why, in this variation,  7.Be3  first is a better move. }
5... cxd6
{ Black can also go for  5...exd6  , but this doesn't change your plan much. The game could continue with  6.Nf3  Be7  7.Nc3  , and you want to develop the bishops on e2 and e3 and play h3 to prevent Black from playing ...Bg4 }
6. Nf3 Bg4 { Black can aim for the direct pin! } 7. h3
{ You immediately challenge the bishop! } 7... Bxf3
{ Black takes the knight!  After  7...Bh5  , there are several good ways to play. You can immediately play  8.g4  or keep developing as usual with  8.Nc3  the main problem here for Black is they can no longer get a strong fianchetto dark-squared bishop because after  8...g6?  9.g4  the bishop is trapped. }
8. Qxf3 Nc6 { Black plays aggressively and hits the center! } 9. d5
{ You go for the attack on the knight! } 9... Ne5 10. Qd1
{ You drop the queen back! The pawn is poisoned as  10...Ne5xc4  11.Bxc4  Nxc4  loses the knight after  12.Qa4+ }
10... g6
{ Black wants to get a powerful bishop on the dark squares, which can be dangerous. You opt for a cunning strategy to remove all potential targets off the long diagonal. }
11. a4
{ A multiple-purpose move! You aim to either kick the knight back with a5 or bring your rook to a safe square with b3, Ra2! }
11... a5
{ Black has to prevent you from playing a5 and kick the knight back.   11...Nb6xc4?  would have lost the knight because of  12.f4  and @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/pp2pp1p/1n1p2p1/3Pn3/P1P5/7P/1P3PP1/RNBQKB1R b KQkq a3 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Ne5xc4?  losing the knight after  12.a5 }
12. b3 { You support your strong pawnchain! } 12... Bg7 13. Ra2
{ Your rook moves away from the dangerous diagonal! Now, you have a positionally dominating position. The knight on b6 is bad, and the dark-squared bishop has no targets on the diagonal! You can continue developing with Be2, O-O, Be3, Qd2, and Nc3. Don't rush with playing Nc3 as you will run into discovered attacks with Black's dangerous bishop on the dark squares. }
*

