1. e4
{ Get ready to tackle the sidelines! What's going to be super helpful here is everything you've learned from the course. It's good to get your pawns in the middle. Remember, you usually develop the knights first, and hunting your opponents' knights can be smart. Sometimes, you'll play against opponents who don't know their openings well and do something offbeat. If that happens, stay calm. Use the concepts you've learned to take advantage of their unusual start. }
1... Nc6 2. d4 { You take the center! } 2... d5 3. exd5 { You trade as always }
3... Qxd5 4. Nf3 { You develop the knight and defend your central pawn. } 4...
Bg4 5. Nc3 { You develop the other knight and attack the queen. } 5... Bxf3
{ The most played move at the Club Level! Black allows you to capture the queen. }
6. Nxd5 Bxd1 7. Nxc7+
{ You keep capturing and fork the king and rook. Black saves the bishop and captures a pawn }
7... Kd7 8. Nxa8 Bxc2 { Black saves the bishop. } 9. d5
{ You hunt the knight. All the strategies implemented were aligned with the basic principles you studied earlier in the course. At this point, you already have a significant advantage. You hunt the knight!  After  9...Nb4  , you can develop with a tempo  10.Bb5+  Also after  9...Nd4  , you can develop with a tempo and attack the knight again with  10.Be3 }
