1. e4
{ Get ready to tackle the sidelines! What's going to be super helpful here is everything you've learned from the course. It's good to get your pawns in the middle. Remember, you usually develop the knights first, and hunting your opponents' knights can be smart. Sometimes, you'll play against opponents who don't know their openings well and do something offbeat. If that happens, stay calm. Use the concepts you've learned to take advantage of their unusual start. }
1... Nc6 2. d4 { You take the center! } 2... d5 3. exd5 { You trade as always }
3... Qxd5 4. Nf3 { You develop the knight and defend your central pawn. } 4...
Bg4 5. Nc3 { You develop the other knight and attack the queen. } 5... Qh5
{ The only good move for Black! } 6. d5 { You start hunting the knight } 6...
O-O-O 7. Be2
{ You develop the bishop and support the knight!  After  7...e6  , there are two good options you can attack with  8.Ng5  is another option I recommend in my attacking repertoire for Club Players after  8...Bxe2  9.Qxe2  Qxe2+  10.Kxe2  , you are still attacking the f7-pawn. }
7... e6 8. O-O
{ You sacrifice the pawn and castle, but will soon win the pawn back. } 8...
exd5 9. h3 { You start chasing away the bishop! } 9... Bxf3
{ Black should capture the bishop.  When Black retreats with  9...Be6  , then  10.Bf4  prepares for Nb5 with powerful pressure against the c7-pawn }
10. Bxf3 Qg6
{ The only good move as  10...Qe5  allows you to gain a tempo with  11.Re1 }
11. Bh5
{ You attack the queen again and put pressure on the f7-pawn.  The idea is that after  11...Qf6  , you can play  12.Nxd5  winning the pawn and also gaining another tempo on the queen. }
11... Qe6 12. Re1 { You gain another tempo on the queen! } 12... Qd7
{ Black seems to have defended everything! } 13. Bg5
{ There is no good way for Black to deal with the attack on the rook! } 13...
Be7
{ Blocking with the bishop loses the f7-pawn for Black but is the best they have because  13...f6  allows  14.Bg4  pinning the queen and this wins an exchange after  14...f5  15.Bxd8 }
14. Bxf7 { You win the pawn and threaten the pin with Be6 } 14... Kb8 15. Bf4
{ You calmly retreat the bishop! You are not interested in trading with  15.Bxe7  Ngxe7  as this helps Black to develop }
15... Qf5
{ The double attack is not dangerous as you have a beautiful countertactic. }
16. Qf3
{ And you support both bishops because of the discovered attack.  16...Qxf7?  now loses the queen after  17.Bxc7+  Kxc7  18.Qxf7   White has a fantastic position, and Black should opt for @@StartFEN@@1k1r2nr/ppp1bBpp/2n5/3p1q2/5B2/2N2Q1P/PPP2PP1/R3R1K1 b - - 4 16@@EndFEN@@  16...Bd6  when after  17.Bxd6  Qxf3  18.gxf3  cxd6  19.Bxd5  , you have an endgame with a pawn up. }
