1. e4
{ Get ready to tackle the sidelines! What's going to be super helpful here is everything you've learned from the course. It's good to get your pawns in the middle. Remember, you usually develop the knights first, and hunting your opponents' knights can be smart. Sometimes, you'll play against opponents who don't know their openings well and do something offbeat. If that happens, stay calm. Use the concepts you've learned to take advantage of their unusual start. }
1... b6 { Black aims to attack from the flank. } 2. d4 { The common strategy! }
2... Bb7 3. Nc3 { You develop the knight and defend the central pawn. } 3... e6
{ Black gets ready to pin your knight. This is nothing to be worried about. }
4. Nf3 { You develop the other knight. } 4... Bb4
{ Black pins your knight! This means that Black threatens to capture your central pawn on e4 on the next move. }
5. Bd3 { You develop and defend the pawn. } 5... Nf6 6. e5
{ You start hunting the knight!  6.Qe2  is an alternative, and also  6.Nd2  is a cunning move to break the pin and defend the e4-pawn. }
6... Ne4
{ The knight goes towards the center and puts pressure on your pinned knight. You are happy to sacrifice the pawn. If Black plays  6...Nd5  , you can get the same by going for  7.O-O }
7. O-O { You follow the golden rule to castle and unpin the knight. } 7... Nxc3
8. bxc3 Bxc3 { Black wins the pawn, but the bishop can be in trouble on c3. }
9. Rb1 { You sidestep with the rook. Black is in a difficult situation now. }
9... Nc6 10. Be4
{ You centralize the bishop and pin the knight. GM Sevian quickly went wrong here with Black and played  10...d5  11.exd6  Qxd6?  when after  12.Rb3  , the bishop is in trouble.  When Black goes for @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/pbpp1ppp/1pn1p3/4P3/3PB3/2b2N2/P1P2PPP/1RBQ1RK1 b kq - 3 10@@EndFEN@@  10...O-O  , now the Greek Gift tactic with  11.Bxh7+  still works well. }
10... d5 11. exd6 cxd6
{ Black should capture back with the pawn to break the pin on the knight with ...d5 later! }
12. Rb3 { You continue in the same way and attack the bishop. } 12... Ba5 13.
d5 { And now this is just crushing! } 13... Ne7
{ The critical move! And after an early  12.d5  Ne7  would have been the refutation. }
14. dxe6 Bxe4 15. exf7+
{ You sacrifice the piece for a dominating attack!  Black has no good squares for the king after  15...Kf8  16.Ng5  , you are threatening the royal fork and  16...Bd5  is answered with  17.Re3  when you are threatening to capture the knight on e7 with a winning attack. }
15... Kf8 16. Ng5 { You opt for the royal fork! } 16... Bd5 17. Re3
{ You threaten to capture the knight, and after that, this bishop is hanging.  An important difference to the variation @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/pb3ppp/1pnpp3/8/3PB3/2b2N2/P1P2PPP/1RBQ1RK1 w kq - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12.d5?  Ne7  13.dxe6  Bxe4  14.exf7+  Kf8  15.Ng5  Bd5  , you can't bring a rook to the e-file, and Black has a winning position there  That's why you first played @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/pb3ppp/1pnpp3/8/3PB3/2b2N2/P1P2PPP/1RBQ1RK1 w kq - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12.Rb3  Ba5  and only now  13.d5! }
*

