1. e4
{ Get ready to tackle the sidelines! What's going to be super helpful here is everything you've learned from the course. It's good to get your pawns in the middle. Remember, you usually develop the knights first, and hunting your opponents' knights can be smart. Sometimes, you'll play against opponents who don't know their openings well and do something offbeat. If that happens, stay calm. Use the concepts you've learned to take advantage of their unusual start. }
1... d6 2. d4
{ You follow the first golden rule and place the other pawn in the center. }
2... Nf6 3. Nc3
{ You develop your knight and defend the pawn.  It would be wrong to hunt the knight now with  3.e5?  since after  3...dxe5  4.dxe5  , Black can trade queens and break your right to castle with  4...Qxd1+  5.Kxd1  , and also fork your two pawns with  6...Ng4 }
3... e5 4. dxe5
{ As usual, you opt for the trade when the pawns are facing in the center. In this particular case, going for  4.Nf3  first is also a good alternative. }
4... dxe5 5. Qxd8+ { You trade the queen and break Black's right to castle. }
5... Kxd8 6. Nf3
{ You keep the rules in the course to develop the knight first and the bishops after. }
6... Bd6 7. Bg5
{ As the d-file is already open, you would like to opt for a queenside castle! You pin the knight and also get ready to castle.   7.Bc4  would be an alternative targeting the f7-pawn. }
7... Be6 8. O-O-O Ke7 9. Nh4
{ Again, Nh4 is a powerful move, and Nf5 is unstoppable! } 9... h6 10. Nd5+
{ First, you want to chase away the bishop! } 10... Bxd5 11. Nf5+
{ The knight again enters f5 with great power! } 11... Ke8
{ Black could also go for  11...Kf8  , but then after  12.Bxf6  gxf6  13.Rxd5  , the bishop has no escape square. }
12. Bxf6
{ You trade the bishop and weaken Black's pawn structure before you capture back the bishop. }
12... gxf6 13. Rxd5 Bf8 14. Rb5
{ One more final touch: you want to force Black to play ...b6 and weaken the light-squares. }
14... b6 15. Rd5
{ Your mission is completed, and you move the rook back. Positionally speaking, White is winning. The pawn structure from Black is horrible, and all its pieces are still in the starting position. You would like to double your rook on the open d-file. }
