6. e5 { You go for the plan and chase the knight away. } 6... Nfd7 7. Qe2
{ Again, you get your queen to e2 so that you protect the e5-pawn and get ready to castle queenside! }
7... dxe5 8. O-O-O
{ A powerful move! The idea is that you have the e5-pawn pinned either way, so you don't need to rush to capture it back.  The downside of  8.dxe5  is that after  8...Nb6  Black can stop you from castling. }
8... h6
{ The only good move for Black! Black should give back the pawn with ...e4, but after the direct  8...e4  9.Qxe4  Nf6  , you can play  10.Qh4  That's why Black first wants to chase your bishop to h4 }
9. Bh4 e4 10. Qxe4 Nf6 11. Bxf6 exf6
{ Black has to decide to double the pawns!  After  11...Bxf6?  12.Bc4  you pin the f7-pawn and after  12...e6  13.d5  you break open the position with a devastating effect }
12. Bc4
{ You develop the bishop and create the threat of Qxg6! When Black defends against this, you can also bring your other rook to the center. }
