{ Get ready to tackle the sidelines! What's going to be super helpful here is everything you've learned from the course. It's good to get your pawns in the middle. Remember, you usually develop the knights first, and hunting your opponents' knights can be smart. Sometimes, you'll play against opponents who don't know their openings well and do something offbeat. If that happens, stay calm. Use the concepts you've learned to take advantage of their unusual start. }
1... g6 2. d4 { You place your other pawn in the center as usual! } 2... Bg7 3.
Nc3 { You start developing your knights!  3.Nf3  is also possible } 3... d6 4.
Nf3 a6
{ The modern opening! The difference with the Pirc is that Black delays the move ...Nf6 Black would like to play ...b5 to gain more space on the queenside so it's good to avoid that. }
5. a4 { A standard reaction not allowing Black to play ...b5 } 5... Nf6
{ When Black plays ...Nf6, you can play in the same fashion as you played the Pirc. }
6. Bg5 { You play in a similar style as against the Pirc. } 6... O-O 7. Qd2
{ A typical plan! You will be able to exchange Black's dark-squared bishop with ...Bh6!  Your plan in the Pirc with  7.e5  works less well now because after  7...dxe5  8.dxe5  Qxd1+  9.Rxd1  Ng4  10.Nd5  Nc6  Black benefits from the inclusion of the moves a4 and ...a6 because in the Pirc opening, you now played the powerful @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/ppp1ppbp/2n3p1/3NP1B1/6n1/5N2/PPP2PPP/3RKB1R w K - 3 10@@EndFEN@@  10.Bb5 }
7... Nc6 8. d5 Nb4 9. a5
{ And Black's knight on b4 is out of play! Black should support it with  9...c5  when you can keep developing with  10.Bc4  followed by O-O!  If Black doesn't support the knight and goes for @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/1pp1ppbp/p2p1np1/P2P2B1/1n2P3/2N2N2/1PPQ1PPP/R3KB1R b KQ - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...e6  , you can even trap the knight with  10.Bxf6  Bxf6  11.Ne2  and the knight is trapped after  11...c5  12.c3 }
