1. e4
{ Get ready to tackle the sidelines! What's going to be super helpful here is everything you've learned from the course. It's good to get your pawns in the middle. Remember, you usually develop the knights first, and hunting your opponents' knights can be smart. Sometimes, you'll play against opponents who don't know their openings well and do something offbeat. If that happens, stay calm. Use the concepts you've learned to take advantage of their unusual start. }
1... g6 2. d4 { You place your other pawn in the center as usual! } 2... Bg7 3.
Nc3 { You start developing your knights!  3.Nf3  is also possible } 3... d6 4.
Nf3 a6
{ The modern opening! The difference with the Pirc is that Black delays the move ...Nf6 Black would like to play ...b5 to gain more space on the queenside so it's good to avoid that. }
5. a4 { A standard reaction not allowing Black to play ...b5 } 5... b6 6. Bg5
{ Let's play in the same style. } 6... Bb7 7. Qd2
{ This is a standard move to prepare for Bh6 ideas when Black develops the knight. Black will now have difficulties to finish development. }
7... Nd7
{ After  7...Nf6  , you have multiple good ways to reply, going for  8.Bd3  first to support your central pawn is strong, but you could also opt for the direct  8.Bh6  , which sacrifices a pawn after  8...Bxh6  9.Qxh6  Nxe4  , but the position is risky for Black since you can play  10.Nxe4  Bxe4  11.Ng5  , and when you enter Black's position with Qg7, you will keep a strong initiative }
8. Bd3 c5 { Black frequently tried to fight the center from the flank. } 9. d5
{ You shut down the light-squared bishop. } 9... Ngf6
{ Whenever the knight still develops, you are ready to play Bh6! } 10. Bh6 O-O
11. h4
{ This a typically attacking idea! Next, you want to play h5 and continue the checkmating attack. }
