[Black "Four Knights Italian: 4.Nc3 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 { Overwhelmingly the most popular move at the club player level. } 1...
e5
{ Prepare to begin with the Black pieces. Even though you haven't learned any moves from the Black side yet, you already understand the concepts from studying the moves from the White side. The principles of the opening stay the same. Your priority is controlling the center with pawns, and you do that from your first move. }
2. Nf3 { White develops and attacks your central pawn! } 2... Nc6
{ It's time to develop and defend the pawn. } 3. Bc4
{ This is the Italian Game, a very popular choice at all levels, from beginners to grandmasters. White plans to castle quickly and points the bishop towards your f7-pawn. }
3... Nf6
{ Applying what you've learned, you start by developing your knights before moving on to your bishops. }
4. Nc3 { White develops the other knight. A common move at the club level. }
4... Nxe4
{ You are going for a tactic! You don't give up the knight for free. If White captures, you can place your pawn in the center with a fork to regain the piece. Usually, when White goes for this, they are not too well-prepared, so you learn some fascinating variations and develop tactics to take your opponent down early on. }
5. Nxe4 d5 { Forking the bishop and knight } 6. Bb5
{ White pins your knight, and you can use your tactical knowledge from the pin variation you learned as White. }
6... dxe4 { You capture the pawn in the center. } 7. Nxe5 Qg5
{ The board is mirrored compared to the Sicilian pin variation, but the tactics work just as well. You skewer the knight and also target the g2-pawn. Because White wasted a tempo with the bishop, we transposed to this line, identical but with colors reversed, in the Petrov. }
8. d4 { White's best try is to attack your queen. } 8... Qxg2
{ You capture the pawn. } 9. Rf1 Bd6
{ A cold-blooded move!  A recurring theme in this repertoire is that when you have a pin like this one, you don't have to be too worried since you can counter  10.Nxc6  with  10...a6 }
10. Nxc6 a6 { You counterattack the bishop. } 11. Ba4 Bd7
{ You skewer the bishop and knight to win back the piece with a dominating advantage.   11...O-O  is also a good alternative. }
