[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8a) Italians Four Knights and Knight Attack Variations"]
[Black "Four Knights Italian: 4.Nc3 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 { Overwhelmingly the most popular move at the club player level. } 1...
e5
{ Prepare to begin with the Black pieces. Even though you haven't learned any moves from the Black side yet, you already understand the concepts from studying the moves from the White side. The principles of the opening stay the same. Your priority is controlling the center with pawns, and you do that from your first move. }
2. Nf3 { White develops and attacks your central pawn! } 2... Nc6
{ It's time to develop and defend the pawn. } 3. Bc4
{ This is the Italian Game, a very popular choice at all levels, from beginners to grandmasters. White plans to castle quickly and points the bishop towards your f7-pawn. }
3... Nf6
{ Applying what you've learned, you start by developing your knights before moving on to your bishops. }
4. Nc3 { White develops the other knight. A common move at the club level. }
4... Nxe4
{ You are going for a tactic! You don't give up the knight for free. If White captures, you can place your pawn in the center with a fork to regain the piece. Usually, when White goes for this, they are not too well-prepared, so you learn some fascinating variations and develop tactics to take your opponent down early on. }
5. Nxe4 d5 { Forking the bishop and knight } 6. Bd3
{ The best move for White, keeping the bishop alive. } 6... dxe4
{ You capture the knight. } 7. Bxe4 Bd6
{ You develop the bishop, defend your central pawn, and prepare to castle. With a pawn in the center, you have a comfortable position. }
8. O-O O-O 9. Re1
{ The only good move for White since the direct  9.c3  allows you to attack immediately with  9...f5  and get a good position. }
9... Bg4
{ You continue to pin the knight! Pinning the knight is only something you usually want to do when you can add an attacker. And you can do that with ...f5-e4! You can consider starting with ... Kh8 to prevent any bishop checks when you go for the attack. }
10. h3 { White somehow has to deal with the pin, so attacks your bishop. }
10... Bh5 { You keep the pin! } 11. g4 f5
{ It's a fascinating and crushing move that has rarely been played! And even in a top GM game between So and Mamedyarov, Mamedyarov missed the chance to play this brilliant move. You will sacrifice your knight, but it will be more than worth it, as your pin becomes deadly and White's king will become even more vulnerable. }
12. Bxc6 fxg4 13. hxg4 Bxg4 { You keep the pin and still attack the bishop. }
14. Bxb7 c6
{ The fun begins!  You block White's bishop and create a massive threat of ...Bxf3   14...Qf6?  would also look logical, however, after  15.d4  White can still survive the position. }
15. Bxc6 Rc8
{ You attack the bishop!  After  16.Bd5+  Kh8  , there is no way out of the problems for White. You still keep the powerful pin but want to keep attacking with brutal force and go for ...Bc5-Bxf2 and go for checkmate. }
16. Be4 { The bishop goes back! } 16... Rc4
{ A cool move, you want to eliminate the bishop to win the pinned knight. } 17.
Bd5+ Kh8
{ You don't care about the rook since  18.Bxc4  Bxf3  attacks the queen and threatens ...Qg5+ and mate follows soon after. }
18. d3 { White last attempt to prevent ...e4. } 18... e4
{ It didn't work! You play ...e4 anyway, and you are crushing your opponent here. This move interrupts the connection between the bishop and the knight.  After  19.Bxe4  , you take it  19...Rxe4  and after  20.Rxe4  , you have  20...Bxf3  next.  When White goes for  19.Rxe4  Rxe4  20.Bxe4  , you play  20...Qe8  and since ...Qh5 is coming next White's position collapses. }
*

