[White "8a) Italians Four Knights and Knight Attack Variations"]
[Black "Italian Knight Attack Variation: 4.Ng5 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 { Overwhelmingly the most popular move at the club player level. } 1...
e5
{ Prepare to begin with the Black pieces. Even though you haven't learned any moves from the Black side yet, you already understand the concepts from studying the moves from the White side. The principles of the opening stay the same. Your priority is controlling the center with pawns, and you do that from your first move. }
2. Nf3 { White develops and attacks your central pawn! } 2... Nc6
{ It's time to develop and defend the pawn. } 3. Bc4
{ This is the Italian Game, a very popular choice at all levels, from beginners to grandmasters. White plans to castle quickly and points the bishop towards your f7-pawn. }
3... Nf6
{ Applying what you've learned, you start by developing your knights before moving on to your bishops. }
4. Ng5
{ White directly targets your f7-pawn, aiming for a potential fork on your queen and rook. Your next move should block the bishop's diagonal to prevent White's plans. }
4... d5 { You block the bishop's diagonal to secure the f7-pawn. } 5. exd5
{ White has taken the pawn. Recapturing at this point would be risky, as it would reactivate White's strong bishop on the light squares. }
5... Na5
{ You aim at the light-squared bishop. You shouldn't play  5...Nxd5  , as this could lead to  6.Nxf7  Kxf7  7.Qf3+  , where White forks your king and knight.  In my 'Attacking Repertoire for Club Players for Black' course, I suggest @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/ppp2ppp/2n2n2/3Pp1N1/2B5/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...b5  , a move to counterattack the bishop. If  6.Bxb5  is played, then  6...Qxd5  forks the bishop and pawn. Both  5...b5  and  5...Na5  offer good opportunities for Black. While  5...b5  is likely be an option that surprises your opponent more,  5...Na5  is a more professional approach as it doesn't give White a slight objective edge. }
6. Bb5+
{ White relocates the bishop and delivers a check! Other moves aren't great, as guarding the bishop doesn't protect White's central pawn.  For instance,  6.Qe2  lets you take the strong bishop  6...Nxc4  7.Qxc4  , and then take back the central pawn with  7...Qxd5 }
6... c6
{ You start harassing the bishop!   6...Bd7  is a possible alternative. A trade of bishops would be good for you, but after  7.Qe2  , White can back up the bishop and has a strong chance for an opening advantage. }
7. dxc6 bxc6 { You capture back with the pawn and attack the bishop again. } 8.
Be2 { The bishop drops back! } 8... h6
{ You push the knight away! This is the key. After the knight retreats with  9.Nf3  , you can keep the pressure up with  9...e4  . }
9. Nf3 e4
{ You keep hunting the knight! An idea that you also have seen a lot from the White side. }
10. Ne5 Bc5
{ You develop your bishop and prepare for ...Qd4, which threatens the knight and checkmate.  After  10.O-O  , I suggest you continue with  10...Qd4  to keep hunting the knight and prevent White from setting up a pawn in the center. Another valid option would be  10...Bd6  to chase the knight again. However, White can still protect the knight with  11.d4  , and after  11...exd3  , the knight can get away with  12.Nxd3 }
11. c3 { The most popular move, which is not scary. } 11... O-O
{ Don't be scared by the threat of b4 since you can get your bishop back with ...Bd6 to counterattack the knight. }
12. b4
{ The fork is not dangerous since you can counterattack the knight.  Also, after  12.d4  exd3  13.Nxd3  Bb6  Black keeps a strong initiative. }
12... Bd6 { You counterattack the knight! } 13. f4
{ White can support with either pawn, but you can capture en-passant also after  13.d4  exd3 }
13... exf3 14. Nxf3 Re8
{ A cool idea! Your attack is so strong that you don't bother about your knight.  Also, if the opponent had played @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/p4pp1/2pb1n1p/n3N3/1P2p3/2P5/P2PBPPP/RNBQK2R w KQ - 1 13@@EndFEN@@  13.d4  exd3  14.Nxd3  , it would be strong to go for the same idea and play  14...Re8   @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/p4pp1/2pb1n1p/n7/1P6/2PN4/P3BPPP/RNBQK2R b KQ - 0 14@@EndFEN@@  14...Nb7  still would keep a slightly better position for you, but this is much more crushing. }
15. bxa5
{ If White plays it safer with  15.O-O  , you don't have to back down and retreat your knight  15...Qe7  keeps the attack on the bishop, and after  16.Re1  Bg4  White would lose with  17.bxa5  because you go for  17...Bxf3  18.gxf3  Qe5  with a devastating attack. }
15... Ba6 { You attack the pinned bishop! } 16. d3 Bc5
{ You threaten ...Bxd3 and also prevent White from castling. Apart from that ...Ng4-Nf2 is also an overwhelming threat. Your position is winning, and White has no way to deal with all threats. }
