{ You develop your bishop and prepare for ...Qd4, which threatens the knight and checkmate.  After  10.O-O  , I suggest you continue with  10...Qd4  to keep hunting the knight and prevent White from setting up a pawn in the center. Another valid option would be  10...Bd6  to chase the knight again. However, White can still protect the knight with  11.d4  , and after  11...exd3  , the knight can get away with  12.Nxd3 }
11. O-O O-O
{ You also castle, and here  12.c3  is the most popular move, which transposes to lines you already learned. }
12. Kh1
{ The best move for White is to place the king in the corner and unpin the f2-pawn to play f4 next and support the knight.   12.Nc3  has also been played, but here you have multiple good replies, and White's position is shaky. After  12...Qd4  13.Ng4  Bxg4  14.Bxg4  e3!  gives a discovered attack on the bishop and attacks the f2-pawn. }
12... Re8 13. f4 exf3 14. Nxf3 Bb6 { Intending ...c5 next. } 15. Nc3 c5
