{ White should first develop the knight. } 10... O-O
{ You castle and get your king to safety. } 11. Be2
{ White could keep postponing castling and attack your knight. } 11... Qh4
{ It's time to increase the pressure and involve the queen! } 12. d3
{ White threatens Bg5, hitting your queen. } 12... h6 { You prevent Bg5. } 13.
O-O Nxh2
{ You sacrifice the knight directly.  Unfortunately, the plan with  13...e4  first, like before, doesn't work as well since White now has the idea that after  14.Nxe4  Bxh2  15.Kh1  Bc7  the move  16.Qe1  is useful in the defensive, so that after  16...f5  17.f3  White forces the trades of queens and will get a better endgame. }
14. Kxh2 e4+ 15. Kg1
{ The king drops back!   15.Kh1  looks crazy, but it is also possible, and after  15...Bxh3  White can play  16.g3  Qe7  17.Re1  f5  and here your bishop can never get trapped because after  18.Kh2  , you can defend with  18...Qh4  as the g3-pawn is pinned. White's best play is to make a repetition with  19.Kh1  Qe7  20.Kh2  Qh4  . }
