{ The bishop seems out of place here, as it blocks White's d-pawn and prevents the other bishop from developing. However, White has a clear strategy of moving the knight to e4 and bringing the misplaced knight back into the center. }
8... Ng4
{ You once again start harassing the knight, but this time you attack it with your queen. }
9. Ne4 { The knight goes to the center. } 9... f5
{ You attack the knight again } 10. Nec3
{ At the beginner level, it's common to move the knight!  After  10.Ng3  , you attack with the same idea. }
10... Bc5
{ You move your bishop and target White's weak f2-pawn. Now, the tables have turned. Your bishop and knight are attacking in the same way as White's bishop and knight were on the fourth move. }
11. O-O { White castles to defend the pawn. } 11... Qh4
{ You bring in your queen to threaten mate with ...Qxh2 and also attack the f2-pawn one more time. }
12. h3 { White has to push forward the pawn to prevent mate. } 12... Bxf2+
{ You strike with devastating power. } 13. Kh1 Qg3
{ A cunning move, threatening mate with ...Qh2. } 14. hxg4
{ White could have only prevented the mate by giving up the queen  14.Qxg4  fxg4 }
14... Qh4#
{ Greco's mate. This is a mate to a king in the corner by a rook or queen. The bishop or queen covers its only escape square. }
