[White "8b) Italian Giuoco Pianissimo"]
[Black "Italian Giuoco Pianissimo: 4.d3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 { Overwhelmingly the most popular move at the club player level. } 1...
e5
{ Prepare to begin with the Black pieces. Even though you haven't learned any moves from the Black side yet, you already understand the concepts from studying the moves from the White side. The principles of the opening stay the same. Your priority is controlling the center with pawns, and you do that from your first move. }
2. Nf3 { White develops and attacks your central pawn! } 2... Nc6
{ It's time to develop and defend the pawn. } 3. Bc4
{ This is the Italian Game, a very popular choice at the beginner level. White plans to castle quickly and points the bishop towards your f7-pawn. }
3... Nf6
{ Applying what you've learned, you start by developing your knights before moving on to your bishops. }
4. d3 { This is a slower move that White often plays to support the pawn. }
4... Bc5
{ You develop the bishop as usual!   4...Be7  is a sound alternative. } 5. Bg5
{ This should often transpose to  5.O-O  O-O  6.Bg5  . Yet White tries to castle long in certain moments. }
5... h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. Nc3 Be7
{ The anti-pin setup! And here, White players almost always play  8.O-O  , and you transpose to the mainline you will study here. }
8. Qd2
{ White players often go for this, try to castle long and create a kingside attack. Yet, this is a mistake!   8.Bg3  is not dangerous because after  8...d6  you can pin the knight with ...Bg4 next. }
8... Nxe4 { And Black wins a pawn. For example: } 9. dxe4
{ The best move yet, out of the three options for White, the least often played on club level.  9.Bxe7?  would dig a bigger hole for White, since after  9...Nxd2  10.Bxd8  , you have the intermediate  Nxf3+  11.gxf3  Rxd8   Also, after @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppppbpp1/2n4p/4p3/2B1n2B/2NP1N2/PPPQ1PPP/R3K2R w KQ - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Nxe4  , you play  9...Bxh4 }
9... Bxh4 { You won an important pawn. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8b) Italian Giuoco Pianissimo"]
[Black "Italian Giuoco Pianissimo: 4.d3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 { Overwhelmingly the most popular move at the club player level. } 1...
e5
{ Prepare to begin with the Black pieces. Even though you haven't learned any moves from the Black side yet, you already understand the concepts from studying the moves from the White side. The principles of the opening stay the same. Your priority is controlling the center with pawns, and you do that from your first move. }
2. Nf3 { White develops and attacks your central pawn! } 2... Nc6
{ It's time to develop and defend the pawn. } 3. Bc4
{ This is the Italian Game, a very popular choice at the beginner level. White plans to castle quickly and points the bishop towards your f7-pawn. }
3... Nf6
{ Applying what you've learned, you start by developing your knights before moving on to your bishops. }
4. d3 { This is a slower move that White often plays to support the pawn. }
4... Bc5
{ You develop the bishop as usual!   4...Be7  is a sound alternative. } 5. O-O
O-O
{ In this position, White can play a lot of moves that do not involve the c3 move for White. This makes it harder to go for the Pin setup in certain cases. }
6. Re1 { The only move that doesn't allow Black to play ...d5 } 6... Ng4
{ You can immediately target the f2-pawn and go for the attack.   6...h6  or  6...d6  would be good alternatives.  6...d5?  wouldn't work because after  7.exd5  Nxd5  8.Nxe5  wins a pawn, and the tactic with  8...Nxe5  9.Rxe5  Bxf2+  doesn't work now because after  10.Kxf2  Qf6+  White can still block with  11.Qf3  when after  11...Qxe5  12.Bxd5  White has two pieces for the rook. }
7. Rf1 { White goes back and probably hopes for a draw! } 7... Na5
{ You will catch the light-squared bishop.  Alternatively, you could repeat with  7...Nf6  , but why not play for a win? }
