O-O
{ In this position, White can play a lot of moves that do not involve the c3 move for White. This makes it harder to go for the Pin setup in certain cases. }
6. h3 { A useful move that doesn't give away White's intentions yet. } 6... d5
{ Whenever you can, play ...d5! } 7. exd5 Nxd5 8. Re1
{ White is aiming for the e5-pawn. } 8... Be6
{ Setting a trap! It is the most-played move at the top level nowadays.   8...Re8  runs into a trap since White can go for  9.d4  Nxd4  10.Nxd4  and now White wins a piece either after  10...exd4  11.Rxe8  Qxe8  12.Bxd5  or after  10...Bxd4  11.c3 }
9. Nxe5 { By far the main move at club-level, but a huge mistake. } 9... Nxe5
10. Rxe5 Bxf2+
{ You win back the pawn with a good position. The tactical point is that your bishop can't be safely captured. }
11. Kxf2 Qf6+ { You fork the king and rook. } 12. Kg1 Qxe5
{ Black is an exchange up. } *

