O-O
{ In this position, White can play a lot of moves that do not involve the c3 move for White. This makes it harder to go for the Pin setup in certain cases. }
6. Bg5 { The most played move after c3. } 6... h6 7. Bh4 Be7
{ Introducing: The anti-pin setup! An idea that many top Grandmasters implemented to solve the problem of the pin. The idea is to solve the pin on your knight by moving the bishop back. This ensures you don't have to weaken your position with ...g5.  Therefore, moving the dark-squared bishop twice is warranted! @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pppp1pp1/2n2n1p/2b1p3/2B1P2B/3P1N2/PPP2PPP/RN1Q1RK1 b - - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7...d6  is an alternative but after  8.c3  White keeps the pin on your knight and playing ...g5 could be risky to break the pin. On the other hand, it would also be annoying if your knight stays pinned. }
8. Nc3 { White develops the knight towards the center. } 8... d6 9. Qd2 Nxe4
{ This is a good trick to remember! You win a pawn with the discovered attack.  The point is that after  10.Bxe7  Nxd2  11.Bxd8  Nxf3+  comes with a check, and after  12.gxf3  Rxd8  , you are a pawn up with a fantastic position. }
10. Nxe4 Bxh4 { And Black is a pawn up. } *

