1. e4 { Overwhelmingly the most popular move at the club player level. } 1...
e5
{ Prepare to begin with the Black pieces. Even though you haven't learned any moves from the Black side yet, you already understand the concepts from studying the moves from the White side. The principles of the opening stay the same. Your priority is controlling the center with pawns, and you do that from your first move. }
2. Nf3 { White develops and attacks your central pawn! } 2... Nc6
{ It's time to develop and defend the pawn. } 3. Bc4
{ This is the Italian Game, a very popular choice at the beginner level. White plans to castle quickly and points the bishop towards your f7-pawn. }
3... Nf6
{ Applying what you've learned, you start by developing your knights before moving on to your bishops. }
4. d3 { This is a slower move that White often plays to support the pawn. }
4... Bc5
{ You develop the bishop as usual!   4...Be7  is a sound alternative. } 5. Nc3
{ Let's now look at ideas where White develops the knight.  This can also happen after  5.O-O  O-O  and  6.Nc3 }
5... O-O 6. O-O d6
{ This can be an exciting variation! Now, you should be really careful because the pin can be dangerous for you. The pin can also be very dangerous for White.   6...h6  is also an alternative to stop the pin! }
7. Bg5 h6 { You kick the bishop back as usual. } 8. Bh4 Bg4
{ You can't drop your bishop back anymore to block the pin! But you can counter with a pin. }
9. h3 { White attacks your bishop! A critical moment in the game. } 9... Bxf3
{ You capture the knight, and this is something that you usually don't like to do.  However, keeping the pin with  10...Bh5  would be bad here since White continues with  11.g4  and after  11...Bg6  White starts attacking your pinned knight with  12.Nd5  , and you also don't have the ...g5 resource available to unpin your knight.  This would be a terrible position. @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/ppp2pp1/2np1n1p/2b1p3/2B1P2B/2NP1b1P/PPP2PP1/R2Q1RK1 w - - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Be6  would be an alternative, but it is a little strange move to drop back. }
10. Qxf3 Nd4
{ You attack the queen directly. Notice here that although  11.Bxf6  would attack your queen; you have the intermediate  11...Nxf3+  , and you capture White's queen with a check. }
11. Qd1 { The queen is forced to go back. } 11... a5
{ A sneaky move! In this position, you always have ...g5 available to unpin your knight! But there is no need to commit to that too early }
12. Nd5
{ White falls the temptation to attack your pinned knight! This attack can often give White a crushing attack, but this time it's you who will benefit. }
12... g5 { The only move. You have to break the pin directly. } 13. Bg3 b5
{ And now, suddenly, the point behind the ...a5 move is revealed. You want to trap the light-squared bishop. }
14. Nxf6+
{ White could try to trade the knight to get another square for the bishop, but it doesn't help.   Instead, White could also opt for a direct  14.c3  but also after  14...bxc4  15.cxd4  Bxd4  Black has a significant advantage because of the powerful bishop. }
14... Qxf6 15. Bd5 c6 { You attack the bishop! } 16. Bb3 a4
{ And the bishop is trapped. } 17. c3
{ White can still counterattack your knight and make sure not to lose a full piece. }
17... axb3 { You capture and still keep a dominating advantage. } 18. cxd4 Bxd4
19. Qxb3 Qe6
{ You offer a trade of queens! Even though the material is equal, this position is winning for Black. Your bishop is on a dominating outpost putting pressure on b2-pawn, whereas White's bishop is useless and out of the game. The a2 and b2-pawns are vulnerable. }
