6. Bb3
{ Played quite often at the club level as well. The idea is that if you play ...d5, then White doesn't have to take on d5.  Carlsen made this move popular a few years ago, and many top-level and club-level players started adopting this as well. The idea is quite simple: Qe2, Nbd2, Nf1, and Ng3 either with h3-g4 or without given the circumstances.   6.Nbd2  d5  usually transposes to the mainline after  7.exd5  Nxd5  8.O-O }
6... d5 7. Qe2
{ The point: White does not want to be forced to take on d5. Leaving the d5-pawn gives Black a lot of interesting ideas }
7... dxe4 { You trade the pawns as usual. } 8. dxe4 Qe7
{ You move the queen to support the f7-pawn and free the d8-square. Now you are ready for ...Nh5 next. Going for ...Nh5 is a common plan to attack.  The direct  8...Nh5  doesn't work yet because after  9.Ng5  Nf4  10.Bxf4  exf4  11.Qh5  attacks both the h7 and f7-pawn.  White has a crushing attack now. @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp2ppp/2n2n2/2b1p3/4P3/1BP2N2/PP2QPPP/RNB1K2R b KQ - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Bg4?  wouldn't do much, as you are not ready yet to put more pressure on the pinned knight. }
9. O-O Nh5
{ With great play! You can continue with ...Qf6. ...Bg4 is also useful with pressure on the pinned knight, and ...Nf4 is also strong. You are the one who is attacking here. }
