1. e4 { Overwhelmingly the most popular move at the club player level. } 1...
e5
{ Prepare to begin with the Black pieces. Even though you haven't learned any moves from the Black side yet, you already understand the concepts from studying the moves from the White side. The principles of the opening stay the same. Your priority is controlling the center with pawns, and you do that from your first move. }
2. Nf3 { White develops and attacks your central pawn! } 2... Nc6
{ It's time to develop and defend the pawn. } 3. Bc4
{ This is the Italian Game, a very popular choice at the beginner level. White plans to castle quickly and points the bishop towards your f7-pawn. }
3... Nf6
{ Applying what you've learned, you start by developing your knights before moving on to your bishops. }
4. d3 { This is a slower move that White often plays to support the pawn. }
4... Bc5
{ You develop the bishop as usual!   4...Be7  is a sound alternative. } 5. c3
{ The slow Italian or Giuoco Pianissimo. } 5... O-O
{ You castle!  Don't rush with  5...d5  here, since after  6.exd5  Nxd5  7.Qb3  , you have an issue since your knight, f7-pawn, and b7-pawn are under attack. }
6. Bg5
{ Often played at club level. If you compare this to @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pppp1ppp/2n2n2/2b1p3/2B1P3/3P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.O-O  O-O  6.Bg5  , you'll notice that White can not put a knight on d5 anymore.  White wants to develop with Nbd2 now.  That makes a big difference. Your pin with ...Bg4 is less effective now as the f3-knight is well-guarded. }
6... h6 7. Bh4 { White wants to keep the pin. } 7... Be7
{ You go for the anti-pin setup! An idea that many top Grandmasters implemented to solve the problem of the pin. You move the bishop twice, but otherwise, Black would have to play ...g5 in order to solve the pin, and that is something don't wait to commit to too quickly.   7...g5  is also an alternative. }
8. Nbd2 d6
{ Your dark-squared bishop is boxed in, but that doesn't mean it has no future. }
9. O-O Nh5 { Solving the problem of the pin! } 10. Bg3
{ Hardly played, yet the idea is sound. White would rather trade the bishop for an active knight than for the boxed-in bishop on e7. }
10... Nxg3 { Don't mind if I do } 11. hxg3 Na5
{ A common move in this Italian repertoire. Let's go for the other bishop as well! }
12. Bb5
{ Now you can push the bishop away to c2 with a6-b5 and then get more control in the center with c5. Your position is very healthy! }
12... a6 { You attack the bishop to get more space! } 13. Ba4 b5 14. Bc2 c5
{ A typical move to gain more space in the center. } 15. d4
{ Pushing the pawn in the center is a common mistake from White. It's in your favor when the position opens up with the bishop pair. }
15... exd4 { You trade pawns in the center as usual. } 16. cxd4 Bg4
{ You pin the knight, and with ...Nc6, you can aim for the powerful squares on d4 and b4.  When White pushes the pawn forward with  17.d5  , you have the powerful  17...Bf6 }
