{ You castle!  Don't rush with  5...d5  here, since after  6.exd5  Nxd5  7.Qb3  , you have an issue since your knight, f7-pawn, and b7-pawn are under attack. }
6. O-O d5
{ You go for the Pin setup! The pin setup is where you play d5 in the center, followed by Bg4. If you have studied the White repertoire for club players, this setup should be quite familiar! The common difference is that you have a bishop on c5 instead of on e7, but that is not a bad thing at all. }
7. exd5 { White needs to trade on d5. } 7... Nxd5 8. b4
{ White is aiming to play b5 and win the e5-pawn. Yet, this once again leads to a lot of weak pawns for White! }
8... Be7
{ The rule of thumb: When White plays b4, you put the bishop on e7!  When you play  8...Bb6?  White has a cunning tactic to trap your bishop with  9.Bxd5  Qxd5  10.c4  Qd8  11.c5  and the bishop is trapped. }
9. b5 { White goes for the e5-pawn. } 9... Na5 { Targeting the c4-bishop. } 10.
Nxe5
{ White almost always takes immediately on e5.   10.Bxd5  is an alternative move for White, and after  10...Qxd5  11.c4  , you have multiple good options, but the strongest one is  11...Qd7  to keep the d8-square available for your rook and after  12.Bb2  e4  is a powerful counterattack on the knight. }
10... Nxc4 { And White has a difficult choice to make. How to recapture best? }
11. Nxc4
{ The most played move. Yet now White will remain with a weak d3 pawn which is very hard to protect in the next couple of moves. }
11... a6 12. bxa6 Rxa6
{ And you have an overwhelming position! Ideas are to aim for all White weak pawns with moves like ...c5 @@StartBracket@@to make sure White can not play d4@@EndBracket@@, ...b5 @@StartBracket@@to make sure White can not play a4@@EndBracket@@, followed by ...Bb7-...Qa8 to target a lot of White's weaknesses. }
