1. e4 { Overwhelmingly the most popular move at the club player level. } 1...
e5
{ Prepare to begin with the Black pieces. Even though you haven't learned any moves from the Black side yet, you already understand the concepts from studying the moves from the White side. The principles of the opening stay the same. Your priority is controlling the center with pawns, and you do that from your first move. }
2. Nf3 { White develops and attacks your central pawn! } 2... Nc6
{ It's time to develop and defend the pawn. } 3. Bc4
{ This is the Italian Game, a very popular choice at the beginner level. White plans to castle quickly and points the bishop towards your f7-pawn. }
3... Nf6
{ Applying what you've learned, you start by developing your knights before moving on to your bishops. }
4. d3 { This is a slower move that White often plays to support the pawn. }
4... Bc5
{ You develop the bishop as usual!   4...Be7  is a sound alternative. } 5. c3
{ The slow Italian or Giuoco Pianissimo. } 5... O-O
{ You castle!  Don't rush with  5...d5  here, since after  6.exd5  Nxd5  7.Qb3  , you have an issue since your knight, f7-pawn, and b7-pawn are under attack. }
6. O-O d5
{ You go for the Pin setup! The pin setup is where you play d5 in the center, followed by Bg4. If you have studied the White repertoire for club players, this setup should be quite familiar! The common difference is that you have a bishop on c5 instead of on e7, but that is not a bad thing at all. }
7. exd5 { White needs to trade on d5. } 7... Nxd5 8. h3
{ Quite often played, what do you do now that you can't play Bg4? } 8... Nb6
{ The other strong recommended move, let's target the bishop on c4 and the pawn on d3! }
9. Bb5
{ White attacks your knight and keep the d3-pawn defended.  9.Bb3  allows  9...Bf5  when the d3-pawn is weak. }
9... Bd6 { As usual, when White plays Bb5, you play ...Bd6 to protect e5! } 10.
Re1 Re8
{ You can no longer pin the knight so now you can use your rook to support the central pawn. }
11. Nbd2 a6 { You can force White to give up the bishop! } 12. Bxc6 bxc6 13.
Ne4 Bf5
{ You develop the bishop and start putting more pressure on the d3-pawn. Note that whenever you move your a-pawn forward, you should be more careful with playing ...f5!  This is because you would like to use the c-pawn to recapture your bishop, and here after  13...f5  14.Bg5  Qd7  15.Nxd6  cxd6  , you run into the issue that after  16.Qb3+  , your knight is no longer defended. This doesn't lose a piece yet, as you can still block the check with the knight, but it would still lead to a problematic position. }
