1. e4 { Overwhelmingly the most popular move at the club player level. } 1...
e5
{ Prepare to begin with the Black pieces. Even though you haven't learned any moves from the Black side yet, you already understand the concepts from studying the moves from the White side. The principles of the opening stay the same. Your priority is controlling the center with pawns, and you do that from your first move. }
2. Nf3 { White develops and attacks your central pawn! } 2... Nc6
{ It's time to develop and defend the pawn. } 3. Bc4
{ This is the Italian Game, a very popular choice at the beginner level. White plans to castle quickly and points the bishop towards your f7-pawn. }
3... Nf6
{ Applying what you've learned, you start by developing your knights before moving on to your bishops. }
4. d3 { This is a slower move that White often plays to support the pawn. }
4... Bc5
{ You develop the bishop as usual!   4...Be7  is a sound alternative. } 5. c3
{ The slow Italian or Giuoco Pianissimo. } 5... O-O
{ You castle!  Don't rush with  5...d5  here, since after  6.exd5  Nxd5  7.Qb3  , you have an issue since your knight, f7-pawn, and b7-pawn are under attack. }
6. O-O d5
{ You go for the Pin setup! The pin setup is where you play d5 in the center, followed by Bg4. If you have studied the White repertoire for club players, this setup should be quite familiar! The common difference is that you have a bishop on c5 instead of on e7, but that is not a bad thing at all. }
7. exd5 { White needs to trade on d5. } 7... Nxd5 8. a4
{ This is also a popular move at the top level! Here, you can play ...a5 and use similar ideas. But in lines where White opts for Bb5, you can also try to attack the bishop with ...Na7 }
8... a5 9. Nbd2 Nb6 10. Bb5 Bd6
{ You move the bishop back as usual to support the pawn. } 11. Re1
{ White ads an attacker. } 11... Bg4
{ You neutralize the attack of the knight by creating the pin. } 12. Ne4
{ White could also first play  12.h3  Bh5  13.Ne4  , but you can play in the same style with  13...Na7 }
12... Na7
{ Go for ...Na7 in these lines to attack White's light-squared bishop.   12...f5?  would be very bad since after  13.Nxd6  cxd6  14.Qb3+  Kh8  15.Ng5  is crushing with the threat of Nf7+ and Ne6, and the big downside now of having  a4  and  ...a5  included is that  15...Qf6  loses to  16.Bxc6  bxc6  17.Qxb6  , as your knight, is no longer defended. }
13. h3 { White attacks your bishop. } 13... Bh5 { You drop back as usual. } 14.
d4 { Many top level games went like this. } 14... exd4
{ You trade as usual.   14...Nxb5  is an alternative and will likely transpose. }
15. Nxd6 Qxd6 16. Qxd4 Nxb5
{ It's time to eliminate the bishop.   16...Bxf3  would transpose and is also good! }
17. axb5 Bxf3 { You destroy the pawn structure. } 18. Qxd6
{ White will also trade and break your pawn structure. } 18... cxd6 19. gxf3
Rfd8
{ You build up a solid defense and can play ...a4 next to control White's pawns.  Games that reach this position typically continued with  20.Re7  Rd7  21.Rxd7  Nxd7  22.Bf4  Nb6  , and the endgame is balanced. After  23.Bxd6  Black has a double attack with  23...Nc4  and after  24.Ba3  a4  Black will win back the b5-pawn with a comfortable endgame. }
