{ You target the bishop on c4 and, with that, the pawn on d3! } 11. Bb3
{ A new move White has been trying out on the top level. White gives the pawn on e5 but gets the e5-pawn in return without having to play g4. }
11... a5
{ You like to chase the bishop away! This will unpin your f7-pawn and make it possible to go for the ...f5 plan again.   11...Qxd3  is also possible and much more popular, but after  12.Nxe5  Qf5  13.Nef3  , the position is complex, and you are under some severe pressure. After  13...Rad8  White has the option to fork you with  14.g4  , which eventually after  14...Bxg4  15.hxg4  Qxg4+  16.Kh1  Qh3+  17.Nh2  Bd6  18.f4  Bxf4  19.Re2  will go to an endgame where White has a piece for three pawns. It's much more practical to sidestep these long forcing variations and go for a plan where you also play for ...f5, which will be familiar from other variations. }
12. a4 { White could stop your pawn! } 12... Kh8
{ So White wants to keep the bishop on the diagonal and stop you from playing  ...f5  . Either way, you can still prepare for ...f5 now!  Instead  12...Qxd3  is also an alternative but leads to the same complications as discussed. }
13. Ne4 { White attacks your bishop! } 13... Nd7
{ A great countermove! You don't want to drop the bishop back now, as it's passive there. Keeping the bishop on this diagonal and playing ...Bb6 back is strong.  Capturing the bishop with  14.Nxc5  wouldn't be good for White since  14...Nxc5  attacks the bishop and the d3-pawn.  The inclusion of a5 and a4 improved your position because if White plays @@StartFEN@@r2q1r1k/1ppn1ppp/2n5/p1b1p2b/P3N3/1BPP1N1P/1P3PP1/R1BQR1K1 w - - 3 14@@EndFEN@@  14.Bd5  now they are not threatening b4 }
14. Ng3 Bxf3
{ You can trade your bishop for the knight now and follow it up with ...f5 }
15. Qxf3 f5
{ You get in your ...f5 move now with an excellent position.  Grandmaster Kobo had this position twice with Black and managed to score 1.5 out of 2 against two top Grandmasters.  16.Nxf5?  would blunder the knight after  16...g6 }
