{ You develop the bishop as usual!   4...Be7  is a sound alternative. } 5. c3
{ The slow Italian or Giuoco Pianissimo. } 5... O-O
{ You castle!  Don't rush with  5...d5  here, since after  6.exd5  Nxd5  7.Qb3  , you have an issue since your knight, f7-pawn, and b7-pawn are under attack. }
6. O-O d5
{ You go for the Pin setup! The pin setup is where you play d5 in the center, followed by Bg4. If you have studied the White repertoire for club players, this setup should be quite familiar! The common difference is that you have a bishop on c5 instead of on e7, but that is not a bad thing at all. }
7. exd5 { White needs to trade on d5. } 7... Nxd5 8. Re1
{ White attacks the e5-pawn twice.   8.Nbd2  is answered with  8...Nb6  when after  9.Bb5  Bd6  10.Re1  , you transpose to the mainline. }
8... Bg4
{ Pinning the knight on f3. White can still win the pawn on e5, but you will make sure that White has to open his whole kingside for this to happen! }
9. h3 Bh5 10. Nbd2 Nb6
{ You target the bishop on c4 and, with that, the pawn on d3! } 11. Bb3
{ A new move White has been trying out on the top level. White gives the pawn on e5 but gets the e5-pawn in return without having to play g4. }
11... a5
{ You like to chase the bishop away! This will unpin your f7-pawn and make it possible to go for the ...f5 plan again.   11...Qxd3  is also possible and much more popular, but after  12.Nxe5  Qf5  13.Nef3  , the position is complex, and you are under some severe pressure. After  13...Rad8  White has the option to fork you with  14.g4  , which eventually after  14...Bxg4  15.hxg4  Qxg4+  16.Kh1  Qh3+  17.Nh2  Bd6  18.f4  Bxf4  19.Re2  will go to an endgame where White has a piece for three pawns. It's much more practical to sidestep these long forcing variations and go for a plan where you also play for ...f5, which will be familiar from other variations. }
12. Ne4 { White attacks your dark-squared bishop. } 12... a4
{ The light-squared bishop is the strongest minor piece for White in this position. You are more than happy to sacrifice a pawn to trade the bishops. }
13. Nxc5 { Capturing your bishop would be inaccurate from White. } 13... axb3
14. Nxb3 Qd5
{ You put more pressure on the pinned knight.  If White releases the pressure with  15.g4  Bg6  , you will win the d3-pawn. }
