[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9a) Ruy Lopez Four Knights Variation and Sidelines "]
[Black "Four Knights Ruy Lopez: 4.Nc3 #1 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ The Ruy Lopez! A major opening in chess. White develops the bishop, targets your knight, and gets ready to castle. }
3... Nf6
{ You stick to the principles and develop your knight first. This is known as the Berlin Defense. I suggest playing the Berlin in a modern and aggressive way.  Moving your pawn to the center with  3...d5?  wouldn't work for the usual reason: after  4.exd5  Qxd5  , White gains a tempo on the queen with  5.Nc3  . Another problem with  3...d5?  is that your knight is pinned, so  4.Nxe5  would lose a pawn.   3...a6  is the Spanish opening and an alternative move. }
4. Nc3 { The four knights Ruy Lopez! } 4... Bc5
{ You develop the bishop as usual. } 5. Nxe5
{ White immediately goes for the trick you also use against the Four Knights Italian. }
5... Nxe5 { You capture back. } 6. d4 { White forks the bishop and knight. }
6... Bd6 { You prefer to keep the bishop. } 7. dxe5 Bxe5
{ This is not so threatening for you. } 8. O-O O-O
{ You can safely castle before you aim to win the e4-pawn. } 9. Bd3
{ In this variation, White first plays Bb5, and now the bishop goes back to d3, so it is as if White is playing as Black.  After the bishop retreat, you have seen this same position before with Black against the Four Knights Italian, but there the position was mirrored. With Black you learned a cool novelty later with the ...f5 move. Usually, it's great news if you achieve a theoretical variation in which you would usually be White when you are Black, but because your opponent could try and play for the same opening idea as you learned, it's good to know how to avoid that.  To make sure White can't use the same opening novelty as you learned with Black you shouldn't play  9...Re8  10.Bg5  h6  11.Bh4  g5?  when White can strike with the powerful  12.f4 }
9... Re8 { You bring the rook to the center } 10. Bg5
{ White goes for the pin } 10... c6
{ You play a careful move and avoid the trap with  10...h6  11.Bh4  g5?  when White strikes with  12.f4 }
11. Kh1
{ A useful move for White to prepare to f4 without running in any checks. }
11... Bxc3
{ You first eliminate the knight before you want to get rid of the pin. } 12.
bxc3 h6 13. Bh4 g5 { By breaking the pin you will be able to win the e4-pawn. }
14. Bg3 Nxe4
{ You win the pawn in the center back. Your pawn structure will still be weak so the position will be balanced. }
*

