[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9a) Ruy Lopez Four Knights Variation and Sidelines "]
[Black "Berlin Sidelines: 4.Bxc6 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ The Ruy Lopez! A major opening in chess. White develops the bishop, targets your knight, and gets ready to castle. }
3... Nf6
{ You stick to the principles and develop your knight first. This is known as the Berlin Defense. I suggest playing the Berlin in a modern and aggressive way.  Moving your pawn to the center with  3...d5?  wouldn't work for the usual reason: after  4.exd5  Qxd5  , White gains a tempo on the queen with  5.Nc3  . Another problem with  3...d5?  is that your knight is pinned, so  4.Nxe5  would lose a pawn.   3...a6  is the Spanish opening and an alternative move. }
4. Bxc6 { White eliminates your knight. } 4... dxc6
{ You capture back and open up the diagonal for your bishop.  After  4.d3  , you can play  4...Bc5  and transpose to the variation covered here. }
5. Nxe5 { It's not dangerous when White captures your central pawn. } 5... Qd4
{ You attack the knight and the pawn in the center at the same time.  You could also play  5...Nxe4  , but be careful after  6.Qe2  .  Moving your knight back with  6...Nf6?  would be a mistake, as White could play a discovered check with  7.Nxc6+  and win your queen:  7...Be7  8.Nxd8  . }
6. Nf3 { The knight moves back. } 6... Qxe4+
{ You capture the pawn with a check. } 7. Qe2 { The queen blocks. } 7... Qxe2+
{ You trade queens and break White's right to castle. } 8. Kxe2 Bg4
{ You move your bishop and pin the knight. You're ready to castle queenside, and you have a good setup with your two bishops. When White stops shielding the knight with the king, it's a good time to take the knight and mess up White's pawn structure.  Many club-level games continue with  9.Re1  O-O-O  10.Kf1  , and you can play  10...Bxf3  to disrupt the pawn structure. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9a) Ruy Lopez Four Knights Variation and Sidelines "]
[Black "Berlin Sidelines 4.d3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ The Ruy Lopez! A major opening in chess. White develops the bishop, targets your knight, and gets ready to castle. }
3... Nf6
{ You stick to the principles and develop your knight first. This is known as the Berlin Defense. I suggest playing the Berlin in a modern and aggressive way.  Moving your pawn to the center with  3...d5?  wouldn't work for the usual reason: after  4.exd5  Qxd5  , White gains a tempo on the queen with  5.Nc3  . Another problem with  3...d5?  is that your knight is pinned, so  4.Nxe5  would lose a pawn.   3...a6  is the Spanish opening and an alternative move. }
4. d3
{ White defends the central pawn.   4.Nc3  would transpose to the Four Knights Ruy Lopez.   4.Qe2  is an uncommon sideline, after which you can play in your regular style with  4...Bc5  5.c3  O-O  and ...Re8, ...a6, ...h6, ...d5 are the natural next moves. }
4... Bc5
{ Your standard development move. This prevents White's plan to capture your knight and win your central pawn. }
5. Bxc6 dxc6 6. Nxe5 { The pawn is poisoned. } 6... Qd4
{ Double attack! You threaten mate as well as the knight. } 7. Be3 Qxe5
{ You capture the knight. } 8. d4
{ White tries to win back the piece with a fork but runs into other problems. }
8... Qxe4 { You capture the central pawn. } 9. dxc5 Qxg2
{ It's time to strike; you grab the pawn and target the rook in the corner, which can't escape. }
10. Rf1 { The rook moves to the only save square. } 10... Bh3
{ You target the rook again.  If White defends the rook with  11.Nd2  , you can play  11...O-O-O  and prepare to capture the defending knight. }
*

