[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9a) Ruy Lopez Four Knights Variation and Sidelines "]
[Black "Berlin Sidelines 4.d3 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ The Ruy Lopez! A major opening in chess. White develops the bishop, targets your knight, and gets ready to castle. }
3... Nf6
{ You stick to the principles and develop your knight first. This is known as the Berlin Defense. I suggest playing the Berlin in a modern and aggressive way.  Moving your pawn to the center with  3...d5?  wouldn't work for the usual reason: after  4.exd5  Qxd5  , White gains a tempo on the queen with  5.Nc3  . Another problem with  3...d5?  is that your knight is pinned, so  4.Nxe5  would lose a pawn.   3...a6  is the Spanish opening and an alternative move. }
4. d3
{ White defends the central pawn.   4.Nc3  would transpose to the Four Knights Ruy Lopez.   4.Qe2  is an uncommon sideline, after which you can play in your regular style with  4...Bc5  5.c3  O-O  and ...Re8, ...a6, ...h6, ...d5 are the natural next moves. }
4... Bc5
{ Your standard development move. This prevents White's plan to capture your knight and win your central pawn. }
5. Bxc6 dxc6 6. O-O { White castles and threatens to capture the pawn. } 6...
Nd7
{ You support the e5-pawn with the knight. The long-term plan is to castle and centralize the rook. You can play ...f6 to support your center more and get ready to start improving your pieces after. }
7. Nbd2 O-O
{ This position is also often reached from the @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/ppp2ppp/2p2n2/2b1p3/4P3/3P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Nbd2  Nd7  7.O-O  O-O  move order }
8. Nc4 Re8 9. Bd2 f6 { You fully support the central pawn. } 10. Nh4 Bf8
{ The standard plan is to bring the bishop back in a good defensive position and get ready to reroute your knight with ... Nc5-Ne6 }
11. Ne3 Nc5 12. g3 b5 { You gain more space on the queenside. } 13. f4
{ White gains a strong pawn structure, so it's a good idea to destroy it and sacrifice your knight. }
13... exf4 14. gxf4 Nxd3 { And you blow away White's pawn structure! } 15. cxd3
Qxd3 16. e5 Bc5 17. Qe1 fxe5 { You gain another pawn back. } 18. f5
{ White should keep the e-file closed. } 18... Rd8
{ A nice move to put pressure on the bishop. The e-file is blocked now, so it's an excellent time to switch to the open d-file. }
19. Rd1 { Defending with the rook would be imprecise. } 19... Qe4
{ You sidestep and threaten ...Rxd2!  White should give up another pawn with  20.Nhg2  when after  20...Bxf5  Black is doing well. }
