1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ The Ruy Lopez! A major opening in chess. White develops the bishop, targets your knight, and gets ready to castle. }
3... Nf6
{ You stick to the principles and develop your knight first. This is known as the Berlin Defense. I suggest playing the Berlin in a modern and aggressive way.  Moving your pawn to the center with  3...d5?  wouldn't work for the usual reason: after  4.exd5  Qxd5  , White gains a tempo on the queen with  5.Nc3  . Another problem with  3...d5?  is that your knight is pinned, so  4.Nxe5  would lose a pawn.   3...a6  is the Spanish opening and an alternative move. }
4. d3
{ White defends the central pawn.   4.Nc3  would transpose to the Four Knights Ruy Lopez.   4.Qe2  is an uncommon sideline, after which you can play in your regular style with  4...Bc5  5.c3  O-O  and ...Re8, ...a6, ...h6, ...d5 are the natural next moves. }
4... Bc5
{ Your standard development move. This prevents White's plan to capture your knight and win your central pawn. }
5. c3 { White pushes the pawn forward to control the center. } 5... O-O
{ You castle! } 6. O-O
{ When White plays  6.Bxc6  you can take towards the center with  6...bxc6  and after  7.Nxe5  d5  , you start putting pressure on White's center. }
6... d5 { You use the first golden rule and place your pawn in the center. } 7.
Nbd2
{ This can also be reached from the @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pppp1ppp/2n2n2/1Bb1p3/4P3/2PP1N2/PP3PPP/RNBQK2R w KQ - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Nbd2  d5  7.O-O  move order. }
7... dxe4 { As usual, you trade pawns when they are facing in the center. } 8.
dxe4
{ After  8.Nxe4  , you can trade one time with  8...Nxe4  9.dxe4  and then follow the same plan with  9...Qe7 }
8... Qe7
{ You clear the d8-square for your rook. At this stage, your light-squared bishop doesn't have a good square to develop yet.   8...Bg4?  would pin the knight, but since it is too well protected after  9.h3  and  9...Bh5  , you can't exert much pressure on the pinned knight, and your bishop is misplaced. Therefore, in this variation, you would like to wait to activate your bishop until White moves the knight on d2 away. }
9. b4 Bd6 { This keeps targeting the b4-pawn and supports the center. } 10. a3
{ White already anticipates ...a5 } 10... a5 11. Rb1 axb4
{ The trade opens the a-file for your rook. } 12. axb4 Rd8 13. Qc2 Bd7
{ You develop the bishop and threaten ...Nxb4 } 14. Bd3
{ White has to step back to avoid the tactics. } 14... Nh5
{ Your knight would be strong on f4, where it targets the kingside and pressures the bishop.  If White replies with  15.g3  , you can play  15...g4  , putting more pressure on the knight. }
