5... Nd6
{ You drop back and immediately harass the bishop.   5...d5?  would be awful placing your knight in a pin and after  6.d3  Nd6  7.Nxe5  both White's rook and bishops are eyeing your king, and White is winning. }
6. a4
{ A move that is not played so frequently but one that is trendy at the top level and that you should take seriously. White wants to keep the bishop in an active position. }
6... Be7 { You continue your development and get ready to castle. } 7. Nc3
{ White's idea is not to capture the pawn back but to develop quickly and get compensation for the pawn with active piece play. }
7... O-O
{ The fighting option! You continue your development and stay a pawn up.  A solid alternative would be to go for  7...a6  when after  8.Bf1  e4  , you can give back the pawn, and after  9.Nxe4  Nxe4  10.Rxe4  d5  11.Re1  , you can either go for  11...Bg4  or  11...d4  to avoid a position after  11...O-O?  12.d4  where your knight on c6 would be slightly misplaced. }
8. d4 { White aims to open up the game! } 8... exd4 { You capture as usual. }
9. Nd5
{ White is two pawns down but starts creating some threats. They threaten to eliminate your knight with Bxc6 and win your bishop. }
9... Re8 { You defend your bishop. } 10. Bf4
{ This move was almost always played. } 10... b6
{ You continue with the same plan. } 11. Bd3
{ The most ambitious move for White since they target the bishop towards your king. }
11... Bb7 { You develop as usual } 12. Qd2 Kh8
{ It's good to place your king in the corner where it's a bit safer. You make sure that attacks on the h7-square don't come with check. Also, as you will see later in this line, you will get chances to counterattack when White pushes the pawn to h6 by going for ...Rg8, and you start attacking White's king on the g-file. This happens in this line after 18. h6 Rg8! }
13. h4
{ This should be what White is aiming for, bringing also the pawn on the attack. When White gets so aggressive, you want to be looking for ways to activate your pieces and get one or both of the extra pawns back. }
13... a5
{ This prepares for ...Nb4 which trades White's annoying knight in the center and also activates your bishop. You can use your bishop to capture on f3 and damage the pawn structure. }
14. Ng5 { This knight is dangerous, so you need to eliminate it. } 14... Bxg5
15. Rxe8+ Nxe8 { You always capture back here with the knight. } 16. hxg5
{ White captures with the pawn to open the h-file. } 16... d6
{ You prepare to free yourself with ...Ne5 next. After you activate your bishop, your pieces come to life, and you are not running much danger.   16...Nb4  directly was also an alternative. }
