{ You take the pawn because it's undefended. This is the same strategy you use against the Italian when White leaves their pawn unprotected. }
5. Re1
{ White immediately attacks your knight!  This is a solid alternative for White, which will generally lead to a less crazy position than after  5.d4  exd4  6.Re1  f5  , which you will learn in the next chapter }
5... Nd6
{ You drop back and immediately harass the bishop.   5...d5?  would be awful placing your knight in a pin and after  6.d3  Nd6  7.Nxe5  both White's rook and bishops are eyeing your king, and White is winning. }
6. Nxe5 Be7
{ You block the e-file to defend against the discovered attack.   6...Nxe5  is a sound alternative, and after  7.Rxe5+  , you can also block the e-file with  7...Be7 }
7. Bd3
{ White places the bishop on a square that looks very bad. This blocks the d-pawn from moving forward. However, White has the idea of ​​using the bishop and attacking, and in some cases may sacrifice the bishop on h7. }
7... Nxe5 8. Rxe5 { You first trade the knights. } 8... O-O
{ It's safe to castle! } 9. Nc3 c6
{ You want to prevent Nd5 and like to keep your bishop. Next, you want to play ...Ne8 like in the other variation.  This makes it possible to use your knight as a defender and to activate your light-squared bishop.   9...Bf6  is also possible but can become more complex since after  10.Re3  Bd4  11.Bxh7+  is possible, and you rather want to avoid these complications. }
10. b3 Ne8 { You continue with your plan as usual. } 11. Bb2 d5
{ It's strong to place your pawn in the center. } 12. Qh5
{ The most common move! White goes all in for the attack, but the attack is luckily not dangerous.   12.Qf3  is better for White. You have multiple good ways to play both  12...Bf6  and  12...Bd6  are strong, and since  13.Ree1  is the best reply for White. It's clear that White is no longer having any dangerous attacks. }
12... Nf6 { Your knight nicely joins to defend and chase the queen away. } 13.
Qh4 Be6 { You can continue your development. } 14. Rg5 g6
{ White's attack didn't work out! Next, you can play ...d4 and ...c5 to block the dark-squared bishop. White's pieces are still misplaced here, and you have a harmonious position. }
