[White "9a) Ruy Lopez Four Knights Variation and Sidelines "]
[Black "Berlin Sidelines 4.O-O and 5.Re1 #13"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6
{ You stick to the principles and develop your knight first. This is known as the Berlin Defense. I suggest playing the Berlin in a modern and aggressive way.  Moving your pawn to the center with  3...d5?  wouldn't work for the usual reason: after  4.exd5  Qxd5  , White gains a tempo on the queen with  5.Nc3  . Another problem with  3...d5?  is that your knight is pinned, so  4.Nxe5  would lose a pawn.   3...a6  is the Spanish opening and an alternative move. }
4. O-O { White castles } 4... Nxe4
{ You take the pawn because it's undefended. This is the same strategy you use against the Italian when White leaves their pawn unprotected. }
5. Re1
{ White immediately attacks your knight!  This is a solid alternative for White, which will generally lead to a less crazy position than after  5.d4  exd4  6.Re1  f5  , which you will learn in the next chapter }
5... Nd6
{ You drop back and immediately harass the bishop.   5...d5?  would be awful placing your knight in a pin and after  6.d3  Nd6  7.Nxe5  both White's rook and bishops are eyeing your king, and White is winning. }
6. Nxe5 Be7
{ You block the e-file to defend against the discovered attack.   6...Nxe5  is a sound alternative, and after  7.Rxe5+  , you can also block the e-file with  7...Be7 }
7. Bf1
{ By far the most popular move! White gets the bishop back to the safe starting square. }
7... Nxe5
{ You trade the knights now!  A variation with  7...O-O  8.d4  Nf5  9.Nf3  could be slightly unpleasant as White has the well-protected  d4 -pawn, which means that your knight on c6 is misplaced. This is something you also wanted to avoid in all the d4-openings. }
8. Rxe5 O-O
{ You castle! This position is symmetrical. Usually, I like to avoid these types of positions as you tend to have fewer chances to outplay your opponent in the opening. There is no reason to get disappointed here, though, as you have a solid basis with Black, and there are still plenty of pieces on the board to have a fighting game. }
9. Nc3
{ Another option White could go for! Their goal is to grab the bishop pair with the knight, and this is something you can't avoid. You can get a position where you get more space and attacking chances in return for the bishop pair. }
9... Ne8
{ You stay consistent and get the knight back. This move often allows you to get the d-pawn forward and reroute your knight to a better position. }
10. Nd5
{ White goes after your bishop.  In case White plays  10.d4  then after  10...Bf6  11.Re1  d5  they can no longer get the bishop pair. }
10... Bd6 { For now, you still escape with the bishop. } 11. Re1 c6
{ You chase the knight back. } 12. Ne3 Bc7
{ You prepare to play ...d5 and activate the light-squared bishop.   12...Be7  is an alternative. }
13. Nf5
{ White wants to trade the bishop for the knight with Ne7+, and this is something you can't avoid. }
13... d5 { You place the pawn in the center as usual. } 14. Ne7+ Kh8 15. Nxc8
Rxc8
{ White has the bishop pair, no big deal, though at this point, you have more space, and you can try to reduce the square available for White's pieces.   15...Qxc8  is also possible. }
16. d3
{ This is more common than  16.d4  since White sometimes still wants to use the c4-pawnbreak to open up the position with the bishop pair. }
16... f5
{ This allows you to go ...Qf6-...g5-...Ng7, and you want to decide, depending on White's play, to continue with ...f4 or ...g4 }
17. Qf3
{ This position could also arise from the @@StartFEN@@2rqnr1k/ppb2ppp/2p5/3p4/8/8/PPPP1PPP/R1BQRBK1 w - - 0 16@@EndFEN@@  16.Qf3  f5  17.d3  move order. }
17... Qf6
{ You start pinning the b2-pawn. And also prepare for ...g5  17...Nf6  is a possible alternative. }
18. Rb1 g5
{ And you start to attack! When you get ...g4 and ...f4 in, the dark-squared bishop is not strong anymore, and you don't have to be afraid of White's bishop pair.   19.b3?  Ng7  20.Bb2  doesn't pose any issues, and after  20...d4  , the bishop is blocked. }
