[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9b) Berlin Mainline with 5...exd4 "]
[Black "Berlin Mainline 4.Re1 with 5...exd4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ The Ruy Lopez! A major opening in chess. White develops the bishop, targets your knight, and gets ready to castle. }
3... Nf6
{ You stick to the principles and develop your knight first. This is known as the Berlin Defense. I suggest playing the Berlin in a modern and aggressive way.  Moving your pawn to the center with  3...d5?  wouldn't work for the usual reason: after  4.exd5  Qxd5  , White gains a tempo on the queen with  5.Nc3  . Another problem with  3...d5?  is that your knight is pinned, so  4.Nxe5  would lose a pawn.   3...a6  is the Spanish opening and an alternative move. }
4. O-O { White castles } 4... Nxe4
{ You take the pawn because it's undefended. This is the same strategy you use against the Italian when White leaves their pawn unprotected. }
5. d4
{ White puts their other pawn in the center. Usually, when the pawns face each other in the center, you capture the pawn. This position is no exception, even though White can pin your knight.  Capturing the pawn is relatively rare, and most games continue with  5...Nd6  , which often leads to the Berlin endgame following  6.Bxc6  dxc6  7.dxe5  Nf5  8.Qxd8+  Kxd8  I recommend playing the Berlin in an attacking way and surprising the opponent. My main recommendation is to capture with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/3Pn3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq d3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...exd4  and this chapter present the alternative option to go for @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/3Pn3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq d3 0@@EndFEN@@  5...Be7 }
5... exd4
{ You capture in the center as usual and don't change your standard approach. This is a move that will likely surprise your opponent as it hasn't been played much. }
6. Nxd4 { White captures back the pawn in the center. } 6... Nxd4
{ You trade the knights. } 7. Qxd4
{ White captures back and targets your knight. } 7... Nc5
{ An important move. You will use your knight as a shield on e6 and keep a pawn up. }
8. Re1+ { White gives a check! } 8... Ne6
{ You use the knight as a blockade on the e-file, a good defensive strategy. Your subsequent plan includes pushing ...c6 to chase away the bishop, unpinning your knight with ...Be7, and preparing for castling. You also aim to centralize your pawn with ...d5.  Note that playing  8...Be7?  here would be a mistake. In that case, your bishop is pinned, and White can take your knight for free with  9.Qxc5 }
9. Nd2 c6 { You start chasing away the bishop! } 10. Bd3 d5
{ You get your pawn in the center. } 11. Nf3 Be7
{ You develop! If you consolidate, you will be a clean pawn up, so White must sacrifice the exchange.  Many other moves are also strong, like  11...h6  ,  11...Qf6  or  11...Qb6  .  However, developing the bishop puts more pressure on White as they must find the only good option. }
12. Rxe6 Bxe6 13. Qxg7 Bf6 { You kick the queen and defend the rook! } 14. Qh6
Qe7 { You prepare to castle queenside. } 15. c3 O-O-O 16. Bf4
{ White develops and wants to keep your king trapped! } 16... Rdg8
{ You prepare for ...Rg6! } 17. Re1 Rg6
{ A beautiful move, as after  18.Bxg6  hxg6  traps the queen. } 18. Qh5 Rhg8
{ You double the rooks!  After  19.Bxg6  hxg6  the queen can only go to h6 or h7 and after  20.Qh6  Rh8  , you trapped the queen again. }
19. Bg3 { It's a logical move to block with the bishop! } 19... Qf8
{ You get ready to trap the queen with ...Rh6 } 20. Nd4
{ The only way to create an escape for the queen. } 20... Rg5 21. Qf3 Bxd4 22.
cxd4 Qb4 { You have pressure on the d4 and b2-pawns. } 23. Qe3 h5
{ Getting ready for ...h4   23...Qxb2  is also playable but allows  24.Bxh7 }
24. h4 { White kicks the rook! } 24... Rxg3
{ It's a good moment to sacrifice the exchange back! White's dark-squared bishop was causing a lot of danger to your king. }
25. fxg3 Rg4 { Next, you will win the d4-pawn with a better endgame. } *

