5... exd4
{ You capture in the center as usual and don't change your standard approach. This is a move that will likely surprise your opponent as it hasn't been played much. }
6. Re1 { White pins your knight, and now you must be careful. } 6... f5
{ You back up your knight with the f-pawn! While it might seem logical to advance your pawn to the center and support your knight, it's a mistake.  After  6...d5?  your other knight becomes pinned, and White can then play  7.Nxd4  .  Now White threatens Nxc6 and f3, both targeting your pinned knights. You'll find yourself in significant trouble. If you play  7...Bd7  , then after  8.Bxc6  bxc6  9.f3  , White will gain material by winning your pinned knight. }
7. Ng5 { White adds an attacker to your pinned knight! } 7... Be7
{ You immediately kick the knight away. } 8. Qh5+
{ White gives a check to weaken your kingside pawn structure. } 8... g6 9. Qh6
{ White threatens to enter the position with Qg7! } 9... Nxg5 10. Bxg5 Kf7
{ Unpinning the bishop and defending against Qg7 } 11. Bxe7 Nxe7
{ White trades the bishops to keep the initiative. In this position, you are two pawns up but also have some weaknesses. It's important to follow a plan first to solidify your position. You want to get the knight to the natural square with ...Ng8-Nf6 and then go for an artificial castle with .. .Rf8 and ...Kg8! When you reach that, the position is becoming much safer. }
12. Nd2 Ng8
{ Gaining a tempo on the queen and getting ready to go to the natural square. }
13. Qf4 Nf6
{ The first part of the plan finishes with the knight back to its natural square. The next step is the artificial castle with ...Rf8 and ...Kg8 }
14. Qxd4
{ White catches back one of the pawns, but you still stay one pawn up.  If White plays something else like  14.Nf3  , the same plan with  14...Rf8  also works well. }
14... Rf8
{ You want to get the king as quickly as possible to a regular castle square, so that it is safe. }
15. Nf3 Kg8
{ You have reached the artificial castle setup and are still a pawn up! White has better piece activity, which compensates for the pawn, but they still have to prove that they keep an initiative. }
16. Rad1
{ When White plays this logical move, bringing the rook to the center, you can build a central pawn blockade, stopping all attacks. }
16... c6 { Kicking the bishop away! } 17. Ba4 b5
{ You want to prevent a c4-break when you will play ...d5  After  17...d5  White could still play  18.c4 }
18. Bb3+ d5
{ You have created a pawn wall which blocks out White's light-squared bishop. }
19. a4 { White can't break the wall down. } 19... a6
{ You support your wall of pawns! Next, you can opt for ...Qd6-...Bd7 and start bringing your rook to the open file. You are a pawn up. }
