{ White puts their other pawn in the center. Usually, when the pawns face each other in the center, you capture the pawn. This position is no exception, even though White can pin your knight.  Capturing the pawn is relatively rare, and most games continue with  5...Nd6  , which often leads to the Berlin endgame following  6.Bxc6  dxc6  7.dxe5  Nf5  8.Qxd8+  Kxd8  I recommend playing the Berlin in an attacking way and surprising the opponent. My main recommendation is to capture with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/3Pn3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq d3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...exd4  and this chapter present the alternative option to go for @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/3Pn3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq d3 0@@EndFEN@@  5...Be7 }
5... exd4
{ You capture in the center as usual and don't change your standard approach. This is a move that will likely surprise your opponent as it hasn't been played much. }
6. Re1 { White pins your knight, and now you must be careful. } 6... f5
{ You back up your knight with the f-pawn! While it might seem logical to advance your pawn to the center and support your knight, it's a mistake.  After  6...d5?  your other knight becomes pinned, and White can then play  7.Nxd4  .  Now White threatens Nxc6 and f3, both targeting your pinned knights. You'll find yourself in significant trouble. If you play  7...Bd7  , then after  8.Bxc6  bxc6  9.f3  , White will gain material by winning your pinned knight. }
7. Nxd4
{ White captures your pawn in the center. The knight attacks your f5-pawn, so you should trade knights. }
7... Nxd4 { You trade the knights to secure the f5-pawn } 8. Qxd4 c6
{ You're eager to advance your other pawn to the center, but the d-pawn is still pinned. It's essential to remove this pin now. Remember that your knight remains pinned, and moving it would be illegal because it's an absolute pin.  Therefore, playing  8...Bc5?  would result in losing the bishop after  9.Qxc5 }
9. Bd3
{ The bishop retreats, putting pressure on your knight. This is a common move in games at the beginner level, despite White having other promising options.   9...Bc5?  would again not work here, as your knight is pinned. Thus, White can capture your bishop for free with  10.Qxc5  . }
9... d5
{ You apply the first golden rule and position your pawn in the center! But haven't you walked into a trap? Isn't your knight pinned? }
10. f3
{ White assumes you've made a blunder. They target your pinned knight, aiming to capture it on their next turn. }
10... Bd6
{ You develop your bishop like nothing happened. You set up a great trap for your opponent. }
11. fxe4
{ White grabs the knight and falls for the trap. Now it's time to strike. }
11... Bxh2+
{ You capture the pawn! When White captures back, you will win the rook with a fork. }
12. Kf1
{ White stops the tactic and sidesteps with the king. The king is not safe here, though. }
12... fxe4
{ You capture the central pawn and get ready to castle with a check. You have a dominating position, but the next move can still be critical for the game. If White goes  13.Bxe4  , it's fine to capture back, but I like to go for  13...O-O+  when after  14.Bf3  , you have a pin on the bishop and can sacrifice a pawn with  14...c5  15.Qxc5  and attack the pinned bishop with  15...Bg4   On the other hand, if @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pp4pp/2p5/3p4/3Qp3/3B4/PPP3Pb/RNB1RK2 w kq - 0 13@@EndFEN@@  13.Qxg7  is played, White would be targeting your rook, which allows you to make a rook move to f8 with check  13...Rf8+  .  After  14.Ke2  , it's important to avoid capturing the bishop immediately as  14...exd3?  would permit White to recapture via a discovered check  15.Kxd3  , thereby unleashing the rook's devastating power. Instead, you should play  14...Qh4  , creating a threat of developing with tempo through ...Bg4+ and a queenside castle. }
13. Bxe4 O-O+ { You castle and give a check! } 14. Bf3
{ White block with the bishop! You want to add an attacker with ...Bg4, but now the queen is still defending, so you first chase away the queen. }
14... c5 15. Qxc5 Bg4 { You attack the pinned bishop once more. } 16. Nd2 Rc8
{ Another piece joins the attack with tempo. } 17. Qf2 Rxc2
{ White is completely pinned down, both the bishop and knight are pinned, and Black is simply winning. }
