1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ The Ruy Lopez! A major opening in chess. White develops the bishop, targets your knight, and gets ready to castle. }
3... Nf6
{ You stick to the principles and develop your knight first. This is known as the Berlin Defense. I suggest playing the Berlin in a modern and aggressive way.  Moving your pawn to the center with  3...d5?  wouldn't work for the usual reason: after  4.exd5  Qxd5  , White gains a tempo on the queen with  5.Nc3  . Another problem with  3...d5?  is that your knight is pinned, so  4.Nxe5  would lose a pawn.   3...a6  is the Spanish opening and an alternative move. }
4. O-O { White castles } 4... Nxe4
{ You take the pawn because it's undefended. This is the same strategy you use against the Italian when White leaves their pawn unprotected. }
5. d4
{ White puts their other pawn in the center. Usually, when the pawns face each other in the center, you capture the pawn. This position is no exception, even though White can pin your knight.  Capturing the pawn is relatively rare, and most games continue with  5...Nd6  , which often leads to the Berlin endgame following  6.Bxc6  dxc6  7.dxe5  Nf5  8.Qxd8+  Kxd8  I recommend playing the Berlin in an attacking way and surprising the opponent. My main recommendation is to capture with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/3Pn3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq d3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...exd4  and this chapter present the alternative option to go for @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/3Pn3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq d3 0@@EndFEN@@  5...Be7 }
5... exd4
{ You capture in the center as usual and don't change your standard approach. This is a move that will likely surprise your opponent as it hasn't been played much. }
6. Re1 { White pins your knight, and now you must be careful. } 6... f5
{ You back up your knight with the f-pawn! While it might seem logical to advance your pawn to the center and support your knight, it's a mistake.  After  6...d5?  your other knight becomes pinned, and White can then play  7.Nxd4  .  Now White threatens Nxc6 and f3, both targeting your pinned knights. You'll find yourself in significant trouble. If you play  7...Bd7  , then after  8.Bxc6  bxc6  9.f3  , White will gain material by winning your pinned knight. }
7. Nxd4
{ White captures your pawn in the center. The knight attacks your f5-pawn, so you should trade knights. }
7... Nxd4 { You trade the knights to secure the f5-pawn } 8. Qxd4 c6
{ You're eager to advance your other pawn to the center, but the d-pawn is still pinned. It's essential to remove this pin now. Remember that your knight remains pinned, and moving it would be illegal because it's an absolute pin.  Therefore, playing  8...Bc5?  would result in losing the bishop after  9.Qxc5 }
9. f3
{ The best move for White is to target your knight immediately and not retreat the bishop. You will unlikely face this much at the beginner level, but knowing how to reply is good. }
9... cxb5 { You capture the bishop. } 10. fxe4
{ White captures your knight. In the current position, your king is in danger and still in the middle. Therefore, you must force a trade of queens. }
10... Qb6 { You pin White's queen to force a trade of queens. } 11. exf5+
{ White can capture the pawn with a discovered check. } 11... Kf7
{ You go forward with the king. On the light-squares, you are safe and hide from any check from the dark-squared bishop. Remember that you are pinning White's queen, which is not allowed to move and can't pose any danger to your king. Since the queens will get traded, this is safe.  Blocking with  11...Be7  would leave your bishop in a pin when White first trades queens with  12.Qxb6  axb6  and then adds an attacker to the pinned piece with  13.Bg5 }
12. Be3 { White defends the queen. } 12... Qxd4
{ You trade queens: When your king is less safe, trading queens is good! } 13.
Bxd4 b6
{ You get ready to develop your light-squared bishop with . .. Bb7 Since the queens are traded, your king is pretty safe where it is. }
14. Nc3 b4 { You kick the knight! } 15. Ne4 { White threatens Ng5+ } 15... h6
{ Preventing Ng5+   15...Be7  is dangerous since after  16.f6  gxf6  17.Nxf6  Bxf6  18.Rf1  White will get the piece back, and your king is more exposed. }
16. Nf2 { White gets ready to jump with Ng4-Ne5, so you should prevent that. }
16... h5 { You prevent the knight from jumping to g4! } 17. Ne4
{ The move you wanted to provoke! For White, it seems logical to try and go back to g5 now that your h-pawn can no longer defend it. But it's no longer dangerous now. }
17... Bb7
{ Now that you have played ... h5 the check on g5 is no longer dangerous. } 18.
Ng5+ Kg8 19. f6
{ This would have been a disaster when your pawn would still have been on h7, but now! }
19... gxf6 20. Bxf6 Bc5+ { Develops the bishop with a check! } 21. Kh1 Rh6
{ And suddenly Black is doing fantastic, chasing away the bishop. } 22. Be7 Rg6
{ Your bishops are monsters, and after  23.Bxc5  Rxg5  Black has a double threat on c5 and g2! This is how strong Black's bishops can be if White misplays the endgame. }
