{ The main suggestion of  5...exd4  is a good move, but it's also risky. It follows the usual idea of capturing when pawns face each other in the center. Playing  5...exd4  is a strong choice if you've studied all the variations well. However, the price of a mistake in this variation is higher than in the other openings, and a single mistake can lead to a nearly lost position.  Therefore, I also suggest an alternative move that's steady and secure. Pick the move that fits your chess style the best. The alternative suggested is  5...Be7  to anticipate White's attack along the e-file and get ready to castle. }
6. Re1
{ White targets your knight! This is a frequently chosen move at the club level, but it's not the most threatening one. }
6... Nd6
{ You attack the bishop. Placing your pawn in the center with  6...d5?  would be a mistake because it pins your knight, and White can quickly snatch a pawn and attack your pinned knight with  7.Nxe5  . }
7. Bxc6
{ White needs to give up on the powerful light-squared bishop to regain the central pawn. }
7... dxc6 { You capture back and open up the diagonal for your bishop. } 8.
dxe5 { White captures the pawn back and targets your knight. } 8... Nf5
{ You move your knight to safety. } 9. Qxd8+
{ White takes your queen! But luckily, you don't have to lose your right to castle when you recapture it. }
9... Bxd8
{ You've arrived at a comfortable endgame with the bishop pair. A strong strategy could be to start aiming at White's central pawn. This can be achieved by castling and using the rook to attack, followed by ...Ne7-Ng6. Additionally, you can play ...Bg4 to target the defending knight. }
10. Bg5 Bxg5 11. Nxg5 Nd4
{ You threaten the fork with ...Nxc2, forcing White to defend awkwardly. } 12.
Na3 h6
{ You chase the knight away and stop all White hopes of getting in ...e6! } 13.
Ne4 Bf5
{ Carlsen also played this as Black and was already clearly better against top GM Vachier Lagrrave, and Carlsen went on to win the game. }
