{ You stick to the principles and develop your knight first. This is known as the Berlin Defense. I suggest playing the Berlin in a modern and aggressive way.  Moving your pawn to the center with  3...d5?  wouldn't work for the usual reason: after  4.exd5  Qxd5  , White gains a tempo on the queen with  5.Nc3  . Another problem with  3...d5?  is that your knight is pinned, so  4.Nxe5  would lose a pawn.   3...a6  is the Spanish opening and an alternative move. }
4. O-O { White castles } 4... Nxe4
{ You take the pawn because it's undefended. This is the same strategy you use against the Italian when White leaves their pawn unprotected. }
5. d4
{ White puts their other pawn in the center. Usually, when the pawns face each other in the center, you capture the pawn. This position is no exception, even though White can pin your knight.  Capturing the pawn is relatively rare, and most games continue with  5...Nd6  , which often leads to the Berlin endgame following  6.Bxc6  dxc6  7.dxe5  Nf5  8.Qxd8+  Kxd8  I recommend playing the Berlin in an attacking way and surprising the opponent. My main recommendation is to capture with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/3Pn3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq d3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...exd4  and this chapter present the alternative option to go for @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/3Pn3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq d3 0@@EndFEN@@  5...Be7 }
5... Be7
{ The main suggestion of  5...exd4  is a good move, but it's also risky. It follows the usual idea of capturing when pawns face each other in the center. Playing  5...exd4  is a strong choice if you've studied all the variations well. However, the price of a mistake in this variation is higher than in the other openings, and a single mistake can lead to a nearly lost position.  Therefore, I also suggest an alternative move that's steady and secure. Pick the move that fits your chess style the best. The alternative suggested is  5...Be7  to anticipate White's attack along the e-file and get ready to castle. }
6. Qe2 { The critical response from White is rarely seen at the club level. }
6... Nd6 { You move the knight back to target the bishop. } 7. Bxc6
{ White captures your knight. } 7... bxc6
{ You should only capture back with the b-pawn at this moment, while in all other situations, you should capture with the d-pawn.  This is because with the move @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/ppppbppp/2n5/1B2p3/3Pn3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Qe2  , White opens the d-file for the rook, and here, after  6...Nd6  7.Bxc6  dxc6?  8.dxe5  Nf5  , White can utilize it to attack your queen with  9.Rd1  .  This forces  9...Bd7  , keeping your bishop stuck in an unpleasant pin. }
8. dxe5 Nb7 { You can use the b7-square to safeguard your knight. } 9. Nc3 O-O
{ You follow the third golden rule and castle. A solid way to play this position is to reposition your knight with ... Nc5-Ne6. After that, it's safe to play ...d5 and open up the center. Rerouting your knight on e6 helps you block for White's pressure along the e-file when the center opens up. }
10. Nd4 { A tricky move. White aims to go for Rd1 followed by Nxc6. } 10... Bc5
{ You immediately put pressure on the knight. I also tried to make  10...f6  work but after  11.Bf4  fxe5  12.Bxe5  , the position is more pleasant for White.  @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pnppbppp/2p5/4P3/3N4/2N5/PPP1QPPP/R1B2RK1 b - - 4 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Nc5  involving the knight is a standard idea, but a strong reply for White would be  11.Rd1  threatening Nxc6 and after  11...Qe8  White has the subtle  12.Re1  not allowing move the d-pawn forward and develop your light-squared bishop because  12...d5?  13.exd6  cxd6  14.Qxe7  would lose the bishop. }
11. Be3 Qe8
{ This move looks unnatural; however, the problem with  11...Re8  12.f4  f6  is that after  13.Rad1  White suddenly threatens Nxc6, so  13...fxe5  would run into  14.Nxc6  .   11...Qe7  12.f4  f6  allows White to attack the queen with  13.Nf5  and now after  13...Qe6  14.Bxc5  Nxc5  15.Qg4  is the deadly Qg4-Nf5 trick, and now it's not possible to block with the queen on g6 }
12. f4 f6 { You want to challenge and destroy White's center. } 13. Na4 Bb6
{ You bring the bishop back, and now  14.Nxb6  axb6  would improve your pawn structure and open the a-file for your rook. }
14. Rae1 { White brings the rook to the center! } 14... d5
{ You get ready to place your pawn in the center. } 15. Nf3 c5
{ You pawns start moving forward in the center! After  15...Bxe3?  16.Qxe3  , you would have a terrible position as White controls the dark squares and the c5-square, which means that your c-pawns would stay weak. }
16. b3 { White defends the knight! } 16... d4
{ You keep advancing and target the bishop. } 17. Bf2 fxe5
{ You don't want to give White time to move the queen and threaten exf6 when the e-file is open, and your queen is under attack. }
18. fxe5 Bd7 { You gain another tempo on the knight and have a good position. }
*

