6... Nd6 { You move the knight back to target the bishop. } 7. Bxc6
{ White captures your knight. } 7... bxc6
{ You should only capture back with the b-pawn at this moment, while in all other situations, you should capture with the d-pawn.  This is because with the move @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/ppppbppp/2n5/1B2p3/3Pn3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Qe2  , White opens the d-file for the rook, and here, after  6...Nd6  7.Bxc6  dxc6?  8.dxe5  Nf5  , White can utilize it to attack your queen with  9.Rd1  .  This forces  9...Bd7  , keeping your bishop stuck in an unpleasant pin. }
8. dxe5 Nb7 { You can use the b7-square to safeguard your knight. } 9. Nc3 O-O
{ You follow the third golden rule and castle. A solid way to play this position is to reposition your knight with ... Nc5-Ne6. After that, it's safe to play ...d5 and open up the center. Rerouting your knight on e6 helps you block for White's pressure along the e-file when the center opens up. }
10. Re1
{ This same position can also arise from the @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pnppbppp/2p5/4P3/8/5N2/PPP1QPPP/RNB2RK1 w kq - 1 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Re1  O-O  10.Nc3  move order. }
10... Nc5 11. Be3 Ne6 12. Nd4 Nxd4
{ As the knight attacks your c6-pawn, you can't play  12...d5  since it runs into  13.Nxc6  .  Therefore, you first trade the knight. }
13. Bxd4 c5
{ You kick the bishop back.  13...d5  would be bad because after  14.Na4   White would control the c5-square, and your doubled c-pawn would be a weakness }
14. Be3 d5 { You place the pawn in the center! } 15. exd6 Bxd6
{ You have to capture with the bishop and accept a doubled pawn. You gain the bishop pair, though, in an open position.  After  15...cxd6  16.Bxc5  dxc5  17.Qxe7  immediately wins a pawn for White. }
16. Ne4 { White needs to fight against your bishop pair. } 16... Bb7 17. Nxd6
{ White needs to take your bishop! } 17... cxd6
{ You can undouble your pawn again. } 18. Rad1
{ White brings the rook to the center. White scored well in this position because Black's backward d6-pawn is a bit weaker. That's why you need to get rid of that weakness quickly. }
18... Qb6
{ You play energetic target the b2-pawn and prepare to play ...d5 and solve the backward pawn. }
19. c4
{ A cunning move from White, both stopping ...d5 and supporting the b2-pawn. }
19... Rad8 { You prepare to play ... d5 next. } 20. f3 d5 21. cxd5 Rxd5
{ You get rid of the backward pawn and solve your problems. The game could continue with  22.Rxd5  Bxd5  23.Rc1  attacking your c5-pawn, but after  23...Qe6  ,  you are ready to win the a2-pawn back. As Black's pawns are split, the pawns on the queenside are a bit weaker than White's pawns.   In a worst-case scenario, the game could continue something along the lines of  @@StartFEN@@5rk1/pb3ppp/1q6/2pr4/8/4BP2/PP2Q1PP/3RR1K1 w - - 0 22@@EndFEN@@  22.Qf2  going after the c5-pawn.  22...Rxd1  Controlling the d-file  23.Rxd1  Rd8  24.Rxd8  Qxd8  25.Bxc5  Qd1+  26.Qf1  Qd2  27.Bxa7  Qxb2  28.Qc4  Qd2  29.h3  Qd7  30.Bd4  Bc6  and Black would be a pawn down, however with the opposite color bishops, it should be a dead draw as the a-pawn could never surpass the a4-square, and White has no way to make progress. }
*

