[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10a) Scotch and Göring Gambits and Schmidt Variation"]
[Black "Scotch Gambit: 4.Bc4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4
{ The Scotch opening! White uses the same strategy as you. } 3... exd4
{ You capture the central pawn. } 4. Bc4
{ The Scotch Gambit! A dangerous opening weapon from White, which I recommend for the White pieces in my Attacking Repertoire for Club Players: 1.e4!. White is quick with development and is already ready to castle. }
4... Nf6 { You follow the opening principles and develop the knight first. } 5.
O-O { White follows the third golden rule and castles. } 5... Nxe4
{ You capture the central pawn! There is no need to fear the pin on the e-file since you can defend and place your pawn in the center with ...d5. }
6. Re1 { White pins your knight! } 6... d5
{ You keep following the opening concepts and place your pawn in the center to defend the knight and attack the bishop. }
7. Bxd5
{ White captures your pawn! White has some tactics now to regain the sacrificed material. }
7... Qxd5 { You capture back with the queen. } 8. Nc3
{ An excellent move from White exploiting the fact that your knight and central pawn are both pinned. Therefore, you should avoid capturing the knight. }
8... Qd7
{ Currently, you possess the bishop pair and are ahead by a pawn! Nonetheless, your king remains central. Your main goal should be to castle quickly and stabilize the situation. Giving back your central pawn for this would be a worthwhile exchange. I suggest a move that might seem unconventional as it obstructs your light-squared bishop with your queen. The idea is that defending the e7-square proves beneficial as White is attacking the e-file. Furthermore, shielding your c6-knight with the queen is useful in anticipating White's potential Nxd4 followed by the Nxc6 maneuver. }
9. Nxe4
{ White threatens a discovered attack along the e-file. So, it's time to develop and block the attack.  After  9.Rxe4+  , you also block with  9...Be7  , and when White captures the central pawn back with  10.Nxd4  f5  is strong chasing the rook away to unpin your bishop }
9... Be7 10. Bg5
{ White aims to trade your bishop on the e-file! You can consolidate now and reach a safe position. }
10... O-O
{ You follow the third golden rule and castle to reach a safe position.  At this point, White still needs to make some effort to regain the pawn and should play  11.Bxe7  Qxe7  12.Nxd4  when after  12...Bd7  , you have a convenient position with the bishop on an open board. }
11. Bxe7 Qxe7 12. Nxd4 Bd7
{ This position can only be a bit better for Black since Black has a bishop on the open board. }
13. Nb3 Rae8
{ It is important to use this rook because after  14.Nec5  , you go  14...Qxe1+  15.Qxe1  Rxe1+  16.Rxe1  Bc8!   With a better endgame because of the strong bishop @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/pppbqppp/2n5/8/4N3/1N6/PPP2PPP/R2QR1K1 b - - 2 13@@EndFEN@@  13...Rfe8  would run into the problem that after  14.Nec5  Qxe1+  15.Qxe1  Rxe1+  16.Rxe1  Bc8  is no longer possible because of  17.Re8# }
14. Qd2 Bc8
{ You should not allow White to trade your powerful bishop. The bishop can become very powerful later when you go ...b6, ...Bb7 }
15. Rad1 Rd8 { Black is doing great as the bishop is strong! } *

