12. Nxc6 Qxc6 13. Nd5 Bd6 14. Rd4 Be6 15. c4 Bxd5
{ You can eliminate the knight now because White will get other problems. } 16.
cxd5 Qb6 { A great position since White has weak pawns on b2 and f2. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10a) Scotch and Göring Gambits and Schmidt Variation"]
[Black "Scotch Gambit: 4.Bc4 #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4
{ The Scotch opening! White uses the same strategy as you. } 3... exd4
{ You capture the central pawn. } 4. Bc4
{ The Scotch Gambit! A dangerous opening weapon from White, which I recommend for the White pieces in my Attacking Repertoire for Club Players: 1.e4!. White is quick with development and is already ready to castle. }
4... Nf6 { You follow the opening principles and develop the knight first. } 5.
e5
{ White starts hunting your knight! I also recommend this for White in the Scotch Gambit. }
5... d5
{ You can follow the first golden rule and place the pawn in the center. You would be more than happy to trade your knight for White's powerful bishop. }
6. Bb5 { White moves the bishop out of the way and pins your knight. } 6... Ne4
{ Your knight goes forward. } 7. Nxd4 Bd7
{ You defend the knight with the bishop. } 8. Bxc6 bxc6 9. O-O Bc5
{ You develop the bishop and are ready to castle on the next move! } 10. f3
{ White kicks your knight! } 10... Ng5 11. f4
{ White attacks your knight!  11.Be3  has also been played, but after  11...O-O  12.f4  Ne4  , you are back to the mainline. }
11... Ne4 12. Be3 O-O { You keep playing healthy moves and castle. } 13. Nd2
Nxd2 { You trade knight as you prefer not to allow a trade on e4. } 14. Qxd2
Bb6
{ An important move! You get ready to start marching your c and d-pawns forward.  When you fight in the center with  14...f6  White could get an unpleasant initiative after  15.Rae1  . }
15. Nb3 { White wants to restrain your c and d-pawns! } 15... f6
{ It's time to fight in the center! } 16. Nc5
{ White could try to block your c-pawn by placing a piece on c5. You will aim for active counterplay in the center! }
16... fxe5 17. fxe5 Qe7 { Targeting the central pawn. } 18. Qc3 Rf5
{ You start doubling your rook on the f-file!  If White plays  19.Rxf5  , it activates your bishop  19...Bxf5  . }
*

