[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10a) Scotch and Göring Gambits and Schmidt Variation"]
[Black "Göring Gambit: 4.c3 #1 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4
{ The Scotch opening! White uses the same strategy as you. } 3... exd4
{ You capture the central pawn. } 4. c3 Nf6
{ You develop the knight and attack White's central pawn.  Placing your pawn in the center with  4...d5  is an alternative. Usually, you don't do that when White can force your queen about with  5.exd5  Qxd5  , but in this case, White can't attack your queen yet with the knight since there is still a pawn on the c3-square. After  6.cxd4  , White is ready to start hunting your queen with Nc3 next.  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/8/3pP3/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...dxc3  is also an option, but it can be risky to accept White's pawn sacrifice and give them a big lead in development. White typically wants to sacrifice another pawn with  5.Bc4  when  5...cxb2  6.Bxb2  is objectively still fine, but I wouldn't recommend playing against White's monster bishops. }
5. e5 { White hunts your knight. } 5... Nd5
{ You place your knight on a safe central square. } 6. cxd4
{ White recaptures the central pawn. White also tried a couple of other moves, but they were not so dangerous.   6.Bc4  is met with  6...Nb6  when after  7.Bd3  d5  places the pawn in the center and blocks the bishop's diagonal. White could capture en-passant with  8.exd6  to open it, but in that case, after  8...Bxd6  , you are ready to castle on the next move.  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pppp1ppp/2n5/3nP3/3p4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Bb5  leads to more or less the same position after  6...a6  7.Ba4  Nb6  8.Bb3  and  8...d5  blocking the bishop. }
6... d6
{ It's time to break down White's pawn center immediately.   6...Bb4+  is an alternative, but it doesn't accomplish much when White blocks with  7.Bd2 }
7. Bc4 dxe5 { You capture the pawn and defend your knight. } 8. dxe5 Be6
{ You develop the bishop and support the knight. } 9. O-O Qd7
{ Black prepares to castle queenside with a great position.  After  10.Nc3  , even stronger than Castling, is  10...Nxc3  when after the trades with  11.Qxd7  Kxd7  12.Bxe6+  Kxe6  13.bxc3  Be7  , your king is already doing a great job attacking the e5-pawn in the endgame. }
*

