[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10a) Scotch and Göring Gambits and Schmidt Variation"]
[Black "Scotch Schmidt Variation: 5.Bg5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4
{ The Scotch opening! White uses the same strategy as you. } 3... exd4
{ You capture the central pawn. } 4. Nxd4
{ The mainline Scotch. White captures back the pawn in the center. } 4... Nf6
{ As is typical, you start by developing your knights and quickly exerting pressure on the center.  You're already familiar with the Scotch from playing as White and know that trading with  4...Nxd4?  5.Qxd4  isn't a good move because it helps White by letting their queen occupy a strong spot in the center. }
5. Bg5
{ Creating an early pin on the knight is not good for White as White depends on the pin to defend the e4-pawn. }
5... h6
{ You immediately want to break the pin. White needs to give up either the strong bishop or the central pawn. }
6. Bh4
{ White keeps the pin  6.Bxf6  Qxf6  would activate your queen and put pressure on the knight in the center. }
6... g5 { You break the pin to win the central pawn. } 7. Bg3 Nxe4
{ You are a pawn up! When you develop with ...Bg7 your bishop is strong! } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10a) Scotch and Göring Gambits and Schmidt Variation"]
[Black "Scotch Schmidt Variation Four Knights: 5.Nc3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4
{ The Scotch opening! White uses the same strategy as you. } 3... exd4
{ You capture the central pawn. } 4. Nxd4
{ The mainline Scotch. White captures back the pawn in the center. } 4... Nf6
{ As is typical, you start by developing your knights and quickly exerting pressure on the center.  You're already familiar with the Scotch from playing as White and know that trading with  4...Nxd4?  5.Qxd4  isn't a good move because it helps White by letting their queen occupy a strong spot in the center. }
5. Nc3 { White develops the knight and supports the central pawn. } 5... Bb4
{ You pin the knight and pressure White's central pawn. } 6. Nxc6
{ White captures your knight. } 6... bxc6 { You recapture towards the center. }
7. Bd3 { White supports the central pawn. } 7... d5
{ You follow the first golden rule and place your pawn in the center. } 8. e5
{ Advancing the pawn won't be dangerous for you! } 8... Ng4
{ You attack in the center. } 9. O-O
{ White castled!  You don't want to capture the central pawn as you after  9...Nxe5  , you get pinned with  10.Re1  and after  10...f6  11.f4  White wins the knight. }
9... O-O { You also castle and are now threatening ...Nxe5. } 10. f4
{ This move is played surprisingly often at the club level put opens up White's vulnerable king even more. }
10... Bc5+ { You give a check first.  10...Qh4  was also very powerful. } 11.
Kh1 Qh4
{ You go for ...Qxh2#! Don't be sanctified here by just winning the exchange after  11...Nf2+  12.Rxf2  Bxf2 }
12. h3 Qg3
{ You go for ...Qxh2! White cannot stop the mate without giving up the queen. }
13. hxg4
{ Only  13.Qxg4  would stop, mate, for now, but this loses the queen after  13...Bxg4 }
13... Qh4# { Greco's mate! } *

