[Round "?"]
[White "10a) Scotch and Göring Gambits and Schmidt Variation"]
[Black "Scotch Schmidt Variation Four Knights: 5.Nc3 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4
{ The Scotch opening! White uses the same strategy as you. } 3... exd4
{ You capture the central pawn. } 4. Nxd4
{ The mainline Scotch. White captures back the pawn in the center. } 4... Nf6
{ As is typical, you start by developing your knights and quickly exerting pressure on the center.  You're already familiar with the Scotch from playing as White and know that trading with  4...Nxd4?  5.Qxd4  isn't a good move because it helps White by letting their queen occupy a strong spot in the center. }
5. Nc3 { White develops the knight and supports the central pawn. } 5... Bb4
{ You pin the knight and pressure White's central pawn. } 6. Nxc6
{ White captures your knight. } 6... bxc6 { You recapture towards the center. }
7. Bd3 { White supports the central pawn. } 7... d5
{ You follow the first golden rule and place your pawn in the center. } 8. O-O
{ Whenever White exchanges the pawns in the center you aim to win the central pawn. }
8... Bxc3 { First you eliminate the knight! } 9. bxc3 dxe4
{ You capture the pawn when they are facing in the center! You are a pawn up now. }
10. Re1 { Pinning the pawn wouldn't mean White can win it back. } 10... O-O
{ You get out of the pin.   11.Bxe4?  would lose the bishop after  11...Qxd1  12.Rxd1  Nxe4 }
11. Bc4 Qd6
{ A nice move! You would like to benefit from trading the queen as after  12.Qxd6  cxd6  , your pawn structure would be great, also you have a strong idea if White doesn't want to trade queens as shown in this line. }
12. Bg5 Bf5 13. Qe2
{ If White avoids the queen trade and wants to attack you with Rad1, your queen is strong in the attack now. }
13... Ng4 { Going for ...Qxh2# } 14. g3
{ White has to defend with a weakening pawn move, creating an outpost for you on f3. }
14... Qc5
{ You put more pressure on the f2-pawn and bishop and prepare for ...Ne5, which is hitting the light-squared bishop as well as threatening ...Nf3+ forking the king rook and dark-squared bishop. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10a) Scotch and Göring Gambits and Schmidt Variation"]
[Black "Scotch Schmidt Variation Four Knights: 5.Nc3 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4
{ The Scotch opening! White uses the same strategy as you. } 3... exd4
{ You capture the central pawn. } 4. Nxd4
{ The mainline Scotch. White captures back the pawn in the center. } 4... Nf6
{ As is typical, you start by developing your knights and quickly exerting pressure on the center.  You're already familiar with the Scotch from playing as White and know that trading with  4...Nxd4?  5.Qxd4  isn't a good move because it helps White by letting their queen occupy a strong spot in the center. }
5. Nc3 { White develops the knight and supports the central pawn. } 5... Bb4
{ You pin the knight and pressure White's central pawn. } 6. Nxc6
{ White captures your knight. } 6... bxc6 { You recapture towards the center. }
7. Bd3 { White supports the central pawn. } 7... d5
{ You follow the first golden rule and place your pawn in the center. } 8. Bd2
{ A better move from White! You keep the same strategy to go after the e4-pawn. }
8... Bxc3 { First you eliminate the knight. } 9. Bxc3 dxe4
{ You get the central pawn. } 10. Bxf6
{ Also  10.Bc4  has sometimes been played, and White has sacrificed a pawn to have a better pawn structure and the bishop pair. I recommend to castle with  10...O-O  and with ...Be6, you get ready to trade White's light-squared bishop. }
10... Qxf6 11. Bxe4 Ba6
{ A powerful move! Before you secure your king, you make sure that White doesn't do the same. }
12. Qf3
{ White wants to exchange queens too, as the king is less safe.  Retreating with  12.Bd3  is an alternative for White, but  12...Bxd3  13.Qxd3  Black is doing well. You can either castle safely with  13...O-O  or capture the pawn with  13...Qxb2 }
12... Qxf3 13. Bxf3
{ A big mistake that is made in most of the club-level games. } 13... O-O-O
{ The king is stuck in the and ...Rhe8 is a devastating check which is coming up. }
14. Bxc6
{ White can capture a pawn and stop the check for now, but this only postpones its fate! }
14... Rd6 { You kick that bishop back. } 15. Ba4 Rhd8
{ You bring the other rook over and threaten the same devastating check with ...Re6 Black is winning! }
*

