1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4
{ The Scotch opening! White uses the same strategy as you. } 3... exd4
{ You capture the central pawn. } 4. Nxd4
{ The mainline Scotch. White captures back the pawn in the center. } 4... Nf6
{ As is typical, you start by developing your knights and quickly exerting pressure on the center.  You're already familiar with the Scotch from playing as White and know that trading with  4...Nxd4?  5.Qxd4  isn't a good move because it helps White by letting their queen occupy a strong spot in the center. }
5. Nc3 { White develops the knight and supports the central pawn. } 5... Bb4
{ You pin the knight and pressure White's central pawn. } 6. Nxc6
{ White captures your knight. } 6... bxc6 { You recapture towards the center. }
7. Bd3 { White supports the central pawn. } 7... d5
{ You follow the first golden rule and place your pawn in the center. } 8. exd5
cxd5 { The pawns in the center are traded. } 9. O-O O-O { Both sides castle. }
10. h3 { This is a slower move from White that has also been tried. } 10... Be6
{ You play in the same style and get ready to play ...c5 next. } 11. Qf3 c5
{ You play your pawn to ...c5 in one go and go for the active option. } 12. Bg5
{ The idea of playing ...c5 works well if White would trade to the endgame. }
12... h6 { You kick the bishop away. } 13. Bh4
{ White drops the bishop back. Black has a good version of the endgame after  13.Bxf6  Qxf6  14.Qxf6  gxf6  because the pawns are already on d5 and c5. }
13... c4 { You start targeting the light-squared bishop. } 14. Bf5 Rb8
{ You have many good ways to play with Black. Bringing the rook to the b-file is active. }
15. Rfe1 Re8
{ You can support the bishop, and White runs out of options to increase the pressure. }
16. Rad1 { White tries to increase the pressure. } 16... Bxc3
{ Going for all the trades is a good option for Black. } 17. bxc3 Bxf5 18. Qxf5
Rxe1+ 19. Rxe1 Qd7
{ And with this counterattack, you safely get out of the pin.  Black is doing fine in the endgame, and it would even be wrong for White to go for  20.Qxd7  Nxd7  21.Re7  since after  21...Nc5  22.Rxa7  Ne4  , you are about to pick up the pawns on the c-file after ...Rb2 when your pawns are more powerful, then White's a-pawn. }
