1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4
{ The Scotch opening! White uses the same strategy as you. } 3... exd4
{ You capture the central pawn. } 4. Nxd4
{ The mainline Scotch. White captures back the pawn in the center. } 4... Nf6
{ As is typical, you start by developing your knights and quickly exerting pressure on the center.  You're already familiar with the Scotch from playing as White and know that trading with  4...Nxd4?  5.Qxd4  isn't a good move because it helps White by letting their queen occupy a strong spot in the center. }
5. Nc3 { White develops the knight and supports the central pawn. } 5... Bb4
{ You pin the knight and pressure White's central pawn. } 6. Nxc6
{ White captures your knight. } 6... bxc6 { You recapture towards the center. }
7. Bd3 { White supports the central pawn. } 7... d5
{ You follow the first golden rule and place your pawn in the center. } 8. exd5
cxd5 { The pawns in the center are traded. } 9. O-O O-O { Both sides castle. }
10. h3 { This is a slower move from White that has also been tried. } 10... Be6
{ You play in the same style and get ready to play ...c5 next. } 11. Qf3 c5
{ You play your pawn to ...c5 in one go and go for the active option. } 12. Rd1
{ Te main move for White! White stops your ...c4 idea. } 12... Qe7
{ You get out of the way with the queen. } 13. Bg5
{ White is going for the pin now!   13...h6  would be fine, but it has the small downside that White can play  14.Nxd5  , which forces  14...Bxd5  15.Bxf6  Bxf3  16.Bxe7  Bxd1  17.Bxf8  Bxc2  18.Bxc5  Bxc5  19.Bxc2  and with the opposite colored bishops, this endgame should be easy to hold, but of course, White is still a pawn up and is the only one who can try to play for a win. I would rather avoid that line. }
13... Bxc3
{ By taking the knight first, you avoid the line where you have to defend the opposite color bishop endgame. }
14. bxc3 h6 { Only now you go for ... h6 } 15. Be3
{ In case White captures your knight, both sides would have doubled pawn with a balanced position. }
15... c4 { You can chase the bishop away again. } 16. Bf1 Ne4
{ The knight is well-placed. White has the bishop pair, though, but the light-squared bishop is passive. You can aim to get control of the open b-file and start attacking White's pawns. }
