{ You safeguard your knight by pinning the pawn. Generally, it's not ideal to position your queen in front of your bishop on an awkward square, but doing so forces White to make a similar move. Given that your queen will be attacking and White's queen will be defending, these moves work to your advantage. }
7. Qe2
{ White unpins the pawn to attack your knight again. White threatens to capture your knight again. }
7... Nd5 { You move the knight to the center. } 8. h4
{ A modern move! White includes ideas to develop the bishop with Bg5 and possibly activate the rook with Rh3. Your primary focus is to eliminate White's central pawn to further your development. }
8... f6 { You challenge White's center. } 9. c4 Ba6 { Your standard reaction. }
10. Rh3 fxe5 { You capture the pawn! } 11. Bg5 Qd6
{ A novelty!  It's an alternative to drop back the knight with  11...Nf6  as well, but this allows White to attack with  12.Re3  could be unpleasant as after  12...O-O-O  now suddenly  13.Ra3  comes with more power.  @@StartFEN@@r3kb1r/p1ppq1pp/b1p5/3np1B1/2P4P/7R/PP2QPP1/RN2KB2 b Qkq - 1 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Qb4+  is not good because  12.Nd2  , you can't counterattack White's dark-squared bishop with  12...h6  because  13.Qh5+  g6  14.Qxg6#  is mate. }
12. Nd2 h6
{ The important point is that now after  13.Qh5+  g6  wins a piece. } 13. Be3
{ Now that White's bishop blocks the third rank its impossible for White to still swing the rook over to the other side. }
13... Rb8 { You start targeting the b2-pawn. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10b) Scotch Mieses Variation "]
[Black "Scotch Mieses Variation: 5.Nxc6 #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4
{ The Scotch opening! White uses the same strategy as you. } 3... exd4
{ You capture the central pawn. } 4. Nxd4
{ The mainline Scotch. White captures back the pawn in the center. } 4... Nf6
{ As is typical, you start by developing your knights and quickly exerting pressure on the center.  You're already familiar with the Scotch from playing as White and know that trading with  4...Nxd4?  5.Qxd4  isn't a good move because it helps White by letting their queen occupy a strong spot in the center. }
5. Nxc6 bxc6
{ You recapture towards the center.   5...dxc6  would allow White to trade queens with  6.Qxd8+  Kxd8  when you lose your right to castle. }
6. e5
{ White starts hunting your knight!  White could also opt for  6.Nc3  when you can place your pawn in the center with  6...d5  and after  7.exd5  cxd5  8.Bg5  , you can stabilize the center with  8...c6 }
6... Qe7
{ You safeguard your knight by pinning the pawn. Generally, it's not ideal to position your queen in front of your bishop on an awkward square, but doing so forces White to make a similar move. Given that your queen will be attacking and White's queen will be defending, these moves work to your advantage. }
7. Qe2
{ White unpins the pawn to attack your knight again. White threatens to capture your knight again. }
7... Nd5 { You move the knight to the center. } 8. h4
{ A modern move! White includes ideas to develop the bishop with Bg5 and possibly activate the rook with Rh3. Your primary focus is to eliminate White's central pawn to further your development. }
8... f6 { You challenge White's center. } 9. c4 Ba6 { Your standard reaction. }
10. Rh3 fxe5 { You capture the pawn! } 11. Bg5 Qd6
{ A novelty!  It's an alternative to drop back the knight with  11...Nf6  as well, but this allows White to attack with  12.Re3  could be unpleasant as after  12...O-O-O  now suddenly  13.Ra3  comes with more power.  @@StartFEN@@r3kb1r/p1ppq1pp/b1p5/3np1B1/2P4P/7R/PP2QPP1/RN2KB2 b Qkq - 1 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Qb4+  is not good because  12.Nd2  , you can't counterattack White's dark-squared bishop with  12...h6  because  13.Qh5+  g6  14.Qxg6#  is mate. }
12. Nc3 { White offers a trade of knights! } 12... Nxc3
{ The upside for you is that you don't have to be worried that your knight is under attack in the case that White unpins the c4-pawn. }
13. Rxc3
{ If White plays  13.bxc3  , it weakens the pawn structure, and you can play  13...Be7  getting ready to castle. }
13... Qe6 { You step out of the way with your queen! } 14. O-O-O h6
{ You kick away the bishop. } 15. Re3 Bxc4 { Leads to big exchanges. } 16. Qxc4
hxg5 17. Qxe6+ dxe6 18. Rxe5 Bd6 19. Rxe6+ Kf7 20. Bc4 Rxh4
{ A beautiful move, and White can't use the discovered attack as  21.Rexd6+  runs into  21...Rxc4+  countercheck and Black wins a rook.  @@StartFEN@@r7/p1p2kp1/2pbR3/6p1/2B4r/8/PP3PP1/2KR4 w - - 0 21@@EndFEN@@  21.Re4+  is not problematic as the rook on h4 is protected }
21. Bb3 Kf8
{ The endgame is balanced with the opposite color bishops. With Black, you have the ugly doubled pawns, but you also a pawn up, so there is nothing to be worried about. }
