6. e5
{ White starts hunting your knight!  White could also opt for  6.Nc3  when you can place your pawn in the center with  6...d5  and after  7.exd5  cxd5  8.Bg5  , you can stabilize the center with  8...c6 }
6... Qe7
{ You safeguard your knight by pinning the pawn. Generally, it's not ideal to position your queen in front of your bishop on an awkward square, but doing so forces White to make a similar move. Given that your queen will be attacking and White's queen will be defending, these moves work to your advantage. }
7. Qe2
{ White unpins the pawn to attack your knight again. White threatens to capture your knight again. }
7... Nd5 { You move the knight to the center. } 8. h4
{ A modern move! White includes ideas to develop the bishop with Bg5 and possibly activate the rook with Rh3. Your primary focus is to eliminate White's central pawn to further your development. }
8... f6 { You challenge White's center. } 9. c4 Ba6 { Your standard reaction. }
10. Rh3 fxe5 { You capture the pawn! } 11. Bg5 Qd6
{ A novelty!  It's an alternative to drop back the knight with  11...Nf6  as well, but this allows White to attack with  12.Re3  could be unpleasant as after  12...O-O-O  now suddenly  13.Ra3  comes with more power.  @@StartFEN@@r3kb1r/p1ppq1pp/b1p5/3np1B1/2P4P/7R/PP2QPP1/RN2KB2 b Qkq - 1 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Qb4+  is not good because  12.Nd2  , you can't counterattack White's dark-squared bishop with  12...h6  because  13.Qh5+  g6  14.Qxg6#  is mate. }
12. Ra3 Qb4+
{ The big difference is now that after  13.Nd2  Qxb2  would fork both the rooks. }
