1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4
{ The Scotch opening! White uses the same strategy as you. } 3... exd4
{ You capture the central pawn. } 4. Nxd4
{ The mainline Scotch. White captures back the pawn in the center. } 4... Nf6
{ As is typical, you start by developing your knights and quickly exerting pressure on the center.  You're already familiar with the Scotch from playing as White and know that trading with  4...Nxd4?  5.Qxd4  isn't a good move because it helps White by letting their queen occupy a strong spot in the center. }
5. Nxc6 bxc6
{ You recapture towards the center.   5...dxc6  would allow White to trade queens with  6.Qxd8+  Kxd8  when you lose your right to castle. }
6. e5
{ White starts hunting your knight!  White could also opt for  6.Nc3  when you can place your pawn in the center with  6...d5  and after  7.exd5  cxd5  8.Bg5  , you can stabilize the center with  8...c6 }
6... Qe7
{ You safeguard your knight by pinning the pawn. Generally, it's not ideal to position your queen in front of your bishop on an awkward square, but doing so forces White to make a similar move. Given that your queen will be attacking and White's queen will be defending, these moves work to your advantage. }
7. Qe2
{ White unpins the pawn to attack your knight again. White threatens to capture your knight again. }
7... Nd5 { You move the knight to the center. } 8. c4
{ White chases away your knight. } 8... Ba6
{ Developing the bishop and pinning the c4-pawn.  The alternative is to retreat the knight with  8...Nb6  is also fine. }
9. b3
{ After  9.Nd2  you can also play  9...g6  to develop the dark-squared bishop. }
9... g6 { You prepare to develop the dark-squared bishop. } 10. Bb2
{ White develops the bishop! } 10... Bg7
{ You develop the bishop and apply pressure on the center. } 11. Nd2 d6
{ You immediately fight in the center. This fresh approach has yet to be played much and likely surprises your opponent. The mainline with  11...O-O  has a significant downside after  12.O-O-O  Rfe8  White could force a draw with  13.Qf3  unpinning the pawn  13...Nb6  14.Ne4  , when would you have to capture with  14...Bxe5  15.Bxe5  Qxe5  and now  16.Nf6+  Kf8  17.Nxe8  wins the exchange for White when you would have to give a perpetual check with  17...Qa1+  18.Kc2  Qxa2+  19.Kc1  Qa1+  .  Apart from forcing this draw, White would have other options to keep the game going, like @@StartFEN@@r3r1k1/p1ppqpbp/b1p3p1/3nP3/2P5/1P6/PB1NQPPP/2KR1B1R w - - 0 13@@EndFEN@@  13.Nf3  . }
12. Nf3 { White can support the pawn in the center. } 12... O-O-O
{ You castle queenside as you like the possibility to get both rooks to the center quickly. }
13. O-O-O { castling queenside doesn't end well for White. } 13... dxe5
{ You capture and win the central pawn. } 14. Bxe5
{ White can't just recapture! } 14... Nf4 15. Rxd8+
{ White first trades the rooks before capturing the knight!  After  15.Bxf4  , it's immediately game over since you play  15...Qa3+  and after  16.Kb1  , then you trade with  16...Rxd1  17.Qxd1  leading to  17...Qb2#  . }
15... Rxd8 16. Bxf4 Qa3+ 17. Kb1 Bxc4
{ A beautiful strike! This bishop can't be captured because of the impending checkmate.   17...Rd1+  is an alternative; however, it only works if it is after  18.Kc2  , you play  18...Rd5  , and when the king goes back with  19.Kb1  you should play  19...Bxc4  either way, so it's much more logical to play directly strike with @@StartFEN@@2kr4/p1p2pbp/b1p3p1/8/2P2B2/qP3N2/P3QPPP/1K3B1R b - - 2 17@@EndFEN@@  17...Bxc4 }
18. bxc4 { The bishop can't be captured! } 18... Rd1+ 19. Kc2 Qa4#
{ A stunning checkmate! } *

