{ White unpins the pawn to attack your knight again. White threatens to capture your knight again. }
7... Nd5 { You move the knight to the center. } 8. c4
{ White chases away your knight. } 8... Ba6
{ Developing the bishop and pinning the c4-pawn.  The alternative is to retreat the knight with  8...Nb6  is also fine. }
9. b3
{ After  9.Nd2  you can also play  9...g6  to develop the dark-squared bishop. }
9... g6 { You prepare to develop the dark-squared bishop. } 10. f4 g5
{ Smashing White's center with an unexpected move!  10...Bg7  seems like a logical continuation after g6 however, with White's pawn on f4, you cannot exert much pressure on the center, and White will get a pleasant position after unpinning the c4-pawn with  11.Qf2  . }
11. f5
{ White advances the pawn! It's a common move, but Black is already doing very well here. }
11... O-O-O 12. Bb2
{ White develops the bishop. After  12.f6  , you would reply similarly with  12...Qc5  and have a much better version. }
12... Qc5
{ You want to place your knight on e3 and avoid that Black can castle in either direction. }
13. Nd2
{ After  13.Nc3  , you can play  13...Nf4  and White's queen has no good way to defend the e5-pawn since after  14.Qe4  , you get in  14...d5  with tempo.  Note that after @@StartFEN@@2kr1b1r/p1pp1p1p/b1p5/2qnPPp1/2P5/1P6/PB2Q1PP/RN2KB1R w KQ - 3 13@@EndFEN@@  13.Nc3  Ne3  doesn't work because after  14.Na4  , your queen is no longer able to keep defending the knight. }
13... Ne3 { The knight is strong here, keeping White's king in the middle. }
14. Ne4 Qb6 15. Qf2 { White's needs to untangle the king! } 15... g4
{ You want more support for your strong knight and prepare to defend it with ...Bh6 as well. }
16. Bd3
{ White continues development. They could also try to trap your knight with Ke2 and Bc1, so you should start giving more support to the knight. }
16... Bh6 { Supporting your knight once more. } 17. c5
{ White now can block your queen from the defense of the knight, but you don't mind this. }
17... Qb4+ 18. Bc3 Qxc3+
{ You sacrifice the queen as you get two pieces, and White's king keeps on being stuck in the center.  Also  18...Qa3  is a sound alternative }
19. Nxc3 Bxd3 20. Qg3 f6
{ You break open the center!  It was already possible to force a draw with  20...Bf4  21.Qf2  Bh6  , but as Black is already better, you prefer to keep the game going. }
