[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11a) Wayward Queen Attack, Vienna & Danish Gambits"]
[Black "Scholar's Mate #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Qh5
{ The Wayward Queen Attack. It's a common choice among beginners who aim to win with the Scholar's Mate.  What White hopes that after  2...Nc6  3.Bc4  , you'd miss the mate threat and make the move  3...Nf6  , leading to  4.Qxf7#  .  It's the right moment to surprise those using this tactic, ensuring you are on the offensive. }
2... Nf6
{ Right away, you target the queen and sacrifice a pawn in exchange for rapid piece development. }
3. Qxe5+ Be7
{ You are ready to castle and can also gain another tempo on the queen with ...Nc6 }
4. d3
{ This is one of the moves White can play but also after  4.Bc4  or  4.Nc3  it is strong to continue with  4...Nc6  developing with tempo and after  5.Qg3  , you can place your pawn in the center with  5...d5 }
4... Nc6 { You develop with tempo. } 5. Qg3 d5
{ You follow the first golden rule and position your pawn in the center. You don't need to worry about White capturing your g7-pawn, as it will only lead to activating more of your pieces. }
6. exd5 { White trades the pawn in the center. } 6... Nxd5
{ You capture back the pawn!  An alternative was to go for  6...Nd4  threatening a fork on the king and rook. }
7. Qxg7 { White takes your pawn, but you have a strong move to counter. } 7...
Bf6
{ You attack the queen and defend your rook! Next, you will continue to develop with lightning speed.   You can play ...Bf5 followed by ...Qe7+ and ... O-O-O, and also you can go for ...Nd4 threatening the fork with ...Nxc2+. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11a) Wayward Queen Attack, Vienna & Danish Gambits"]
[Black "Scholar's Mate #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Qh5
{ The Wayward Queen Attack. It's a common choice among beginners who aim to win with the Scholar's Mate.  What White hopes that after  2...Nc6  3.Bc4  , you'd miss the mate threat and make the move  3...Nf6  , leading to  4.Qxf7#  .  It's the right moment to surprise those using this tactic, ensuring you are on the offensive. }
2... Nf6
{ Right away, you target the queen and sacrifice a pawn in exchange for rapid piece development. }
3. Qxe5+ Be7
{ You are ready to castle and can also gain another tempo on the queen with ...Nc6 }
4. d3
{ This is one of the moves White can play but also after  4.Bc4  or  4.Nc3  it is strong to continue with  4...Nc6  developing with tempo and after  5.Qg3  , you can place your pawn in the center with  5...d5 }
4... Nc6 { You develop with tempo. } 5. Qg3 d5
{ You follow the first golden rule and position your pawn in the center. You don't need to worry about White capturing your g7-pawn, as it will only lead to activating more of your pieces. }
6. Qxg7 Rg8 { You harass the queen and activate your rook. } 7. Qh6 dxe4
{ You capture back your pawn in the center. } 8. dxe4 Nd4
{ An excellent move! Your next objective is to fork the king and rook. White lacks an effective strategy to defend against the fork.   8...Nxe4  wouldn't result in a pawn advantage as White can respond with  9.Qxh7  , reclaiming the pawn and putting your rook and knight in a fork. You can still protect both of them using either  9...Nf6  or  9...Rg6  . }
9. Qd2
{ One option to defend! But now you can grab the central pawn and harass the queen again. }
9... Nxe4
{ You capture the pawn and attack the queen. White has not developed a single piece except the queen. }
10. Qd3 Bf5
{ You develop your last minor piece and threaten a discovered attack on the queen. Next move ...Nxf2 is a powerful threat when you target the queen and the rook in the corner. With the massive lead in development, you have a dominating advantage. }
*

