[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11a) Wayward Queen Attack, Vienna & Danish Gambits"]
[Black "Vienna Gambit #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. f4
{ The Vienna Gambit!  Unlike the King's Gambit, accepting the sacrifice isn't smart because, after  3...exf4  , White will begin chasing your knight with  4.e5  , leaving you with no good squares to relocate to. The only safe spot is to return to the start position with  4...Ng8  , but reversing your development isn't desirable. }
3... d5 { You place your pawn in the center to counter the gambit. } 4. fxe5
{ White takes your pawn and starts to chase your knight. However, this time, you can move forward and recapture a pawn. }
4... Nxe4 5. d3
{ A poor move since White should be able to defend the e5-pawn with another pawn to keep a powerful pawn structure. }
5... Nxc3
{ You trade knights.  5...Qh4+  may look appealing, but White hopes for the complication after  6.g3  Nxg3  when  7.Nf3  gains a tempo on the queen and after  7...Qh5  8.Nxd5  the position becomes very messy, and White also threatens Nxc7+. }
6. bxc3 d4 { You stop White from playing d4! } 7. Nf3 dxc3 8. d4 Qd5
{ You stop White from playing Bc4 and prepare to develop with ...Nc6, ...Be6 and castle queenside.   8...Be6  would also have prevented the bishop from coming and is strong. I recommend  8...Qd5  because after  8...Be6  9.Rb1  could be slightly annoying when White targets the b7-pawn. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11a) Wayward Queen Attack, Vienna & Danish Gambits"]
[Black "Vienna Gambit #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. f4
{ The Vienna Gambit!  Unlike the King's Gambit, accepting the sacrifice isn't smart because, after  3...exf4  , White will begin chasing your knight with  4.e5  , leaving you with no good squares to relocate to. The only safe spot is to return to the start position with  4...Ng8  , but reversing your development isn't desirable. }
3... d5 { You place your pawn in the center to counter the gambit. } 4. fxe5
{ White takes your pawn and starts to chase your knight. However, this time, you can move forward and recapture a pawn. }
4... Nxe4 5. Qf3
{ White targets your knight and applies pressure in the center. } 5... Nc6
{ As usual, start by developing the knights! I also recommend this line in my course 'Attacking Repertoire for Club Players for Black'. }
6. Nxe4 Nd4
{ A brilliant intermediate move! You target the queen and threaten the fork on the king and rook. }
7. Qd3
{ A typical blunder! White continues to protect the pawn and knight.  Instead, White should opt for  7.Qc3  , which would allow you to capture the knight with  7...dxe4 }
7... dxe4 8. Qxe4 Bf5 { You skewer the queen! } 9. Qxb7 Rb8
{ A cunning move! The sequence of  9...Nxc2+  10.Kd1  Nxa1  offers White an opportunity for an irritating counterplay with  11.Bb5+  .  The text move deals with this particular issue. }
10. Qxa7 Nxc2+ { You can confidently create a fork to capture the rook. } 11.
Kd1 Nxa1
{ Your rook protects the b5-square, and White has no room for a counterattack! You're leading by a rook. }
*

