3... d5 { You place your pawn in the center to counter the gambit. } 4. fxe5
{ White takes your pawn and starts to chase your knight. However, this time, you can move forward and recapture a pawn. }
4... Nxe4 5. Qf3
{ White targets your knight and applies pressure in the center. } 5... Nc6
{ As usual, start by developing the knights! I also recommend this line in my course 'Attacking Repertoire for Club Players for Black'. }
6. Bb5 Nxc3
{ You trade the knight now because otherwise, White will capture you. } 7. bxc3
Qh4+ { You are going for the check! } 8. g3 Qe4+
{ By trading the queens, White's e5-pawn will become more vulnerable. } 9. Qxe4
dxe4
{ After this trade, it's difficult for White to keep defending the e5-pawn! }
10. Bxc6+ bxc6 11. Ne2 Bc5 { You get ready for ...O-O and ... Re8! } 12. d4
{ White can place the pawn in the center, which opens up the position more. }
12... exd3
{ You want to capture en passant and trade your pawn on e4, which otherwise could become vulnerable. }
13. cxd3 O-O 14. d4
{ White's center may look strong, but it doesn't restrict your bishops much. }
14... Be7 15. O-O Rb8
{ You gain control of the open file! Black is already clearly better. Your doubled pawns are not weak because White has no way to attack them.   Going for...c5 soon is unnecessary and could be inaccurate as White can pin your pin with Ba3. It's a position where White can't do much, and you would like to restrict White more! Playing ...g5 could be an idea to take away the f4-square. When White moves the bishop away, your rook will get ready to enter White's position. }
*

