[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11a) Wayward Queen Attack, Vienna & Danish Gambits"]
[Black "Vienna Gambit #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. f4
{ The Vienna Gambit!  Unlike the King's Gambit, accepting the sacrifice isn't smart because, after  3...exf4  , White will begin chasing your knight with  4.e5  , leaving you with no good squares to relocate to. The only safe spot is to return to the start position with  4...Ng8  , but reversing your development isn't desirable. }
3... d5 { You place your pawn in the center to counter the gambit. } 4. fxe5
{ White takes your pawn and starts to chase your knight. However, this time, you can move forward and recapture a pawn. }
4... Nxe4 5. Qf3
{ White targets your knight and applies pressure in the center. } 5... Nc6
{ As usual, start by developing the knights! I also recommend this line in my course 'Attacking Repertoire for Club Players for Black'. }
6. Bb5 Nxc3
{ You trade the knight now because otherwise, White will capture you. } 7. dxc3
{ When White captures back with the other pawn  7.bxc3  , you can either go for the same strategy and play  7...a6  , or you can play  7...Qh4+  when after  8.g3  Qe4+  you force a trade of queens  9.Qxe4  dxe4  , and you want to pick up White's central pawn with ...Bd7 followed by ...Nxe5. }
7... Qh4+
{ You go for a check, after which you again get ready to trade the queens. } 8.
g3 Qe4+ { You go for the same queen trade. } 9. Qxe4 dxe4 10. Bxc6+
{ The most popular move is to trade and double the pawns. } 10... bxc6 11. Be3
{ White continues development and gets ready to castle queenside. } 11... h5
{ You want to activate the rook on the h-file and weaken White's pawn structure with ...h4! In this position, both your bishops are already quite active on the starting squares; the a8-rook also has a task to defend the a7-pawn. That's why activating the other rook is a logical step. }
12. Ne2 h4 { You keep going forward with the pawn. } 13. gxh4 Rxh4
{ Your rook is active, targeting the h2-pawn and ensuring White's rook stays passive. You can aim for ...Bg4-Bf3, which chases away the rook or for ...Rh5, targeting the e5-pawn. }
*

