[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11a) Wayward Queen Attack, Vienna & Danish Gambits"]
[Black "Vienna Gambit #8"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. f4
{ The Vienna Gambit!  Unlike the King's Gambit, accepting the sacrifice isn't smart because, after  3...exf4  , White will begin chasing your knight with  4.e5  , leaving you with no good squares to relocate to. The only safe spot is to return to the start position with  4...Ng8  , but reversing your development isn't desirable. }
3... d5 { You place your pawn in the center to counter the gambit. } 4. fxe5
{ White takes your pawn and starts to chase your knight. However, this time, you can move forward and recapture a pawn. }
4... Nxe4 5. Nf3 Nc6
{ You stick to the classic opening principle of initially developing your knights.  Exchanging knights with  5...Nxc3  benefits White because after  6.bxc3  , White's center becomes more robust, or after  6.dxc3  , White can develop their dark-squared bishop. White doesn't wish to take your knight, as when you capture in return, you begin pressuring the knight on f3. }
6. Bb5
{ White pins your knight! Similar to the previous variation, you'd be satisfied with a trade of the bishop for the knight. }
6... Bc5 { You develop the bishop as usual! } 7. d4
{ White can gain a tempo on your bishop! } 7... Bb6
{ You keep pressuring the d4-pawn, and in the next move, you also get ready to increase the pressure with ...O-O unpinning the knight and playing ...Bg4 pinning the knight. }
8. O-O O-O { You castle and unpin the knight! } 9. Be3
{ White develops and supports the central pawn! } 9... Bg4
{ You create a pin on the knight. } 10. Bxc6
{ White could capture the knight immediately! } 10... bxc6 11. Qd3
{ White develops the queen and targets the knight. } 11... Qd7
{ This ensures White can't win a pawn by introducing a tactic. You want to avoid trading with  11...Nxc3  12.Qxc3  because now your dark-squared will be poorly placed and can't put much pressure on the center. }
12. Nxe4
{ White captures your knight! When White doesn't trade it immediately, you can support your knight more with either ...Bh5-Bg6 or ...f5. }
12... dxe4 13. Qxe4 Bf5 { Skewer on the queen and c2-pawn! } 14. Qh4 Bxc2
{ Winning this pawn is important because White can never defend the center with c3. Also, you have the d5-square available as an outpost, and your queen would be well-placed there. }
*

