{ The Vienna Gambit!  Unlike the King's Gambit, accepting the sacrifice isn't smart because, after  3...exf4  , White will begin chasing your knight with  4.e5  , leaving you with no good squares to relocate to. The only safe spot is to return to the start position with  4...Ng8  , but reversing your development isn't desirable. }
3... d5 { You place your pawn in the center to counter the gambit. } 4. fxe5
{ White takes your pawn and starts to chase your knight. However, this time, you can move forward and recapture a pawn. }
4... Nxe4 5. Nf3 Nc6
{ You stick to the classic opening principle of initially developing your knights.  Exchanging knights with  5...Nxc3  benefits White because after  6.bxc3  , White's center becomes more robust, or after  6.dxc3  , White can develop their dark-squared bishop. White doesn't wish to take your knight, as when you capture in return, you begin pressuring the knight on f3. }
6. Bb5
{ White pins your knight! Similar to the previous variation, you'd be satisfied with a trade of the bishop for the knight. }
