1. e4 e5 2. d4
{ White immediately places the pawn in the center! This is uncommon because after the trade you can gain a tempo on the queen. }
2... exd4 3. Qxd4 Nc6
{ Now you gain a tempo on the queen and this is why you didn't play this opening yourself from the White side. The White players who opt for this opening will try to prove that the tempo on the queen is not as big of an issue. }
4. Qe3
{ The only good square for the queen where White supports the pawn and prepare to develop with Nc3, Bd2 to castle queenside. }
4... Nf6 { You develop your knight as usual! Next you aim to go for ...Bb4 } 5.
Nc3 { The most common move! White continues the development. } 5... Bb4
{ You keep up the pressure by pinning the knight. } 6. Bd2 O-O 7. O-O-O Re8
{ This immediately puts pressure on the center. The e4-pawn is pinned and you are also ready to play ...d5 next attacking the pinned pawn.  The direct  7...d5?  would just blunder the pawn  8.Nxd5 }
8. Qg3
{ This is the main move, but it's not scary. You can safely capture the central pawn now. }
8... Nxe4 9. Nxe4 Rxe4
{ White doesn't have enough compensation for the pawn here. } *

