{ This immediately puts pressure on the center. The e4-pawn is pinned and you are also ready to play ...d5 next attacking the pinned pawn.  The direct  7...d5?  would just blunder the pawn  8.Nxd5 }
8. Bc4 { White should develop the bishop instead. } 8... d6
{ This is a nice way to neutralize White's play since you are aiming for ...Be6 to trade off the light-squared bishops. }
9. Nf3 Be6 10. Bxe6 Rxe6 { You still keep pressure against the e4-pawn now. }
11. Ng5 Re8
{ White's attack is not going anywhere and you still have pressure on the e4-pawn. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11b) Center Game, Bishop Opening and King's Gambit"]
[Black "Center game #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. d4
{ White immediately places the pawn in the center! This is uncommon because after the trade you can gain a tempo on the queen. }
2... exd4 3. Qxd4 Nc6
{ Now you gain a tempo on the queen and this is why you didn't play this opening yourself from the White side. The White players who opt for this opening will try to prove that the tempo on the queen is not as big of an issue. }
4. Qe3
{ The only good square for the queen where White supports the pawn and prepare to develop with Nc3, Bd2 to castle queenside. }
4... Nf6 { You develop your knight as usual! Next you aim to go for ...Bb4 } 5.
Bd2 { This move is much less popular but a better practical try. } 5... Bb4
{ It's strong to still play in the same fashion. Likely, you will transpose to the lines you learned after White plays  6.Nc3 }
6. a3 { This is another move White could play. } 6... Bxd2+ 7. Nxd2 O-O 8.
O-O-O d5
{ You can comfortably get your pawn in the center now and get a good position.   8...Re8!?  It is slightly inaccurate since White could opt for  9.f4  when after  9...d5  White can put some pressure with  10.e5 }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11b) Center Game, Bishop Opening and King's Gambit"]
[Black "Bishop opening #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Bc4
{ The Bishop Opening! This opening will likely transpose back to the Italian opening. }
2... Nf6 { You develop and attack White's central pawn. } 3. d3 Nc6
{ You develop the other knight! } 4. Nc3 Bc5
{ An alternative is  4...Na5  immediately after White's light-squared bishop. }
5. f4 O-O { You castle and continue your development! } 6. Nf3 d6
{ You push the pawn forward and get ready to develop your light-squared bishop. }
7. Na4 { White can go after you, bishop! } 7... Bb6
{ You would like to trade it on your terms and keep your pawns connected. } 8.
Nxb6 axb6 9. O-O Na5
{ You go for the same idea! Trading of White's light-squared bishop.  The point is to defend with the tactic  10.fxe5  dxe5  11.Nxe5  Qd4+  forking the king and knight. }
10. Bd5 c6 { You keep chasing the bishop away. } 11. Bb3
{ Going back with the bishop allows you to trade and even force White to take back with the c-pawn. }
11... Nxb3 12. cxb3
{ White has to take back with the c-pawn now and has two pawn islands, whereas you only have one. }
12... Re8
{ You bring the rook to the center! ...h6 is typically a useful move to avoid that you get pinned. When White moves the bishop, you can trade on f4 and develop your bishop to e6. }
