[Black "Bishop opening #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Bc4
{ The Bishop Opening! This opening will likely transpose back to the Italian opening. }
2... Nf6 { You develop and attack White's central pawn. } 3. d3 Nc6
{ You develop the other knight! } 4. Nc3 Bc5
{ An alternative is  4...Na5  immediately after White's light-squared bishop. }
5. f4 O-O { You castle and continue your development! } 6. Nf3 d6
{ You push the pawn forward and get ready to develop your light-squared bishop. }
7. Na4 { White can go after you, bishop! } 7... Bb6
{ You would like to trade it on your terms and keep your pawns connected. } 8.
Nxb6 axb6 9. O-O Na5
{ You go for the same idea! Trading of White's light-squared bishop.  The point is to defend with the tactic  10.fxe5  dxe5  11.Nxe5  Qd4+  forking the king and knight. }
10. Bd5 c6 { You keep chasing the bishop away. } 11. fxe5
{ White can go for a small tactic to avoid the worse pawn structure. } 11...
dxe5 12. Bxf7+ { White sacrifices the bishop to trap your knight. } 12... Rxf7
13. b4
{ White traps the knight.  Note that  13.Nxe5?  still runs into  13...Qd4+  when you win the knight with a double attack. }
13... Nxe4
{ As you will either way lose one of the knights, you still grab a pawn.   13...Bg4  is an alternative move! }
14. dxe4 { When White captures back, your knight has an escape square now. }
14... Qxd1 15. Rxd1 Nc4
{ Your knight is suddenly in a beautiful position where it can't be chased away and it can support your central pawn. }
