[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11b) Center Game, Bishop Opening and King's Gambit"]
[Black "Bishop opening #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Bc4
{ The Bishop Opening! This opening will likely transpose back to the Italian opening. }
2... Nf6 { You develop and attack White's central pawn. } 3. d3 Nc6
{ You develop the other knight! } 4. Nc3 Bc5
{ An alternative is  4...Na5  immediately after White's light-squared bishop. }
5. f4 O-O { You castle and continue your development! } 6. Nf3 d6
{ You push the pawn forward and get ready to develop your light-squared bishop. }
7. f5
{ White tries to shut down your bishop. You have to be a bit careful now because White plans to go for Bg5, pinning your knight followed by the attack with Nd5! }
7... Nd4
{ You move your knight forward, get ready to play ...c6, and take control of the d5-square. }
8. Bg5 { By far the most-played move, but already a big mistake! } 8... c6
{ Black stops the knight from coming to d5, and now White's light-squared bishop is in trouble. }
9. a3 h6 { You kick the bishop back. } 10. Bh4 d5 11. exd5
{ After  11.Ba2  , you keep the strong center and can play  11...Re8  or even go for the sacrifice with  11...Bxf5  12.exf5  Nxf5  since White's dark-squared bishop will be in trouble. }
11... Nxf5 { You start targeting Black's bishop. } *

