[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11b) Center Game, Bishop Opening and King's Gambit"]
[Black "King's Gambit #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. f4 { The King's Gambit. } 2... exf4
{ You capture the pawn and accept the challenge. } 3. Nf3
{ White develops the knight. } 3... g5
{ You support your f4-pawn and threaten to attack with ...g4 followed by ...Qh4+.  Placing the pawn in the center is an alternative but causes difficulties since after  3...d5  4.exd5  if you recapture with  4...Qxd5?  White gains a tempo with  5.Nc3  .  Developing the knight with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppp1ppp/8/8/4Pp2/5N2/PPPP2PP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  is possible, too, but White can hunt your knight with  4.e5  when you have to go to the edge of the board with  4...Nh5  . }
4. Bc4
{ White's most popular move at the beginner level. White aims to sacrifice a knight after  4...g4  5.O-O  gxf3  6.Qxf3  , and even though this sacrifice is dubious, White gets a powerful attack, and I wouldn't recommend going there. You already have a good position with Black and are a pawn up. You can develop all pieces without trouble, and White doesn't have any attack. }
4... Nc6 5. d4 Bg7
{ You are targeting the d4-pawn. You plan to play ...h6 protecting the g5-pawn and then ...d6 avoiding White's knight hunt with e5 when you can play ...Nf6 and are ready to castle. }
6. c3 h6 7. O-O d6 { You follow the plan. } 8. Nbd2 Nf6
{ The knight develops again to the natural square, and next move, you are ready to castle. One important thing in the King's Gambit is that you want to hold on to your f4-pawn. First of all, this ensures that you are a pawn up, but secondly, it will mean that White's dark-squared bishop remains passive, and White's doesn't have much of an attack. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11b) Center Game, Bishop Opening and King's Gambit"]
[Black "King's Gambit #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. f4 { The King's Gambit. } 2... exf4
{ You capture the pawn and accept the challenge. } 3. Nf3
{ White develops the knight. } 3... g5
{ You support your f4-pawn and threaten to attack with ...g4 followed by ...Qh4+.  Placing the pawn in the center is an alternative but causes difficulties since after  3...d5  4.exd5  if you recapture with  4...Qxd5?  White gains a tempo with  5.Nc3  .  Developing the knight with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppp1ppp/8/8/4Pp2/5N2/PPPP2PP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  is possible, too, but White can hunt your knight with  4.e5  when you have to go to the edge of the board with  4...Nh5  . }
4. h4
{ White attacks your pawn! It's an interesting situation.  When you push the pawn with  4...g4  White can attack with  5.Ne5  and get ready to win the pawn on the next move.  Capturing with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppp1p1p/8/6p1/4Pp1P/5N2/PPPP2P1/RNBQKB1R b KQkq h3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...gxh4?  would leave all your pawns weak, and White would play  5.d4  to dominate the center and win back your f4-pawn. }
4... g4
{ You immediately attack the knight!  For those of you who had the Beginner version of this course there, I recommended  4...d5  , which is also a sound alternative. I changed the recommendation because I thought this new approach is easier to play, and practice shows that White can easily go very wrong in this line in the next couple of moves. }
5. Ne5 Nc6
{ You develop your knight as usual and challenge White's knight in the center! White only has one good option. }
6. Nxg4
{ Grabbing the pawn would be a significant mistake. Your pieces can start developing fast now. }
6... d5 { Getting your pawn in the center and activating the bishop! } 7. exd5
Qxd5 8. Nc3
{ This is usually why...d5 won't be good! But now you can continue attacking. }
8... Qe6+ { Double attack on the king and knight. } 9. Be2
{ White supports with the bishop! } 9... Nd4
{ You bring in the knight, threaten to eliminate the bishop, and win White's knight on g4. }
10. Nf2 { The knight drops back to safety. } 10... Bd7
{ You get ready to castle queenside. All your pieces can start attacking with great power. ...Nf6, the natural square for your knight, is available. ...Rg8 and ...Bc6 increases the pressure against Black's vulnerable g2-pawn. Also, with ...Bc5 your bishop is placed excellently for the attack. White is busted, and you have a winning position. }
