6... d6 { You immediately kick White's knight away from the center. } 7. Nxc6
{ White should trade the knights. } 7... bxc6 8. Bxf4 Nf6
{ You continue development and get ready to kick the bishop away with ...Nh5! }
9. Nc3 Nh5 { You start attacking! } 10. Bg5 f6 11. Be3 Ng3
{ You keep moving the knight! You don't want to trade it for the light-squared bishop yet, but the idea of placing your knight here is that when White plays Be2 and targets your vulnerable g4-pawn, then you are ready to capture the bishop. }
12. Rg1 Rb8 { You keep the attack going and put more pressure. } 13. b3
{ White shouldn't move the pawn forward to defend it as you can start creating a pin on the knight! }
13... d5 14. exd5 Bb4 { You immediately pin the knight. } 15. Qd2
{ After  15.Qd3  Bf5  is very strong! Followed by ...Ne4 on the next move. }
15... Ne4
{ You add an attacker to the pinned knight, and White has nothing better than  16.Nxe4  giving up the queen  16...Bxd2+  17.Kxd2 }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11b) Center Game, Bishop Opening and King's Gambit"]
[Black "King's Gambit #7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. f4 { The King's Gambit. } 2... exf4
{ You capture the pawn and accept the challenge. } 3. Nf3
{ White develops the knight. } 3... g5
{ You support your f4-pawn and threaten to attack with ...g4 followed by ...Qh4+.  Placing the pawn in the center is an alternative but causes difficulties since after  3...d5  4.exd5  if you recapture with  4...Qxd5?  White gains a tempo with  5.Nc3  .  Developing the knight with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppp1ppp/8/8/4Pp2/5N2/PPPP2PP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  is possible, too, but White can hunt your knight with  4.e5  when you have to go to the edge of the board with  4...Nh5  . }
4. h4
{ White attacks your pawn! It's an interesting situation.  When you push the pawn with  4...g4  White can attack with  5.Ne5  and get ready to win the pawn on the next move.  Capturing with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppp1p1p/8/6p1/4Pp1P/5N2/PPPP2P1/RNBQKB1R b KQkq h3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...gxh4?  would leave all your pawns weak, and White would play  5.d4  to dominate the center and win back your f4-pawn. }
4... g4
{ You immediately attack the knight!  For those of you who had the Beginner version of this course there, I recommended  4...d5  , which is also a sound alternative. I changed the recommendation because I thought this new approach is easier to play, and practice shows that White can easily go very wrong in this line in the next couple of moves. }
5. Ne5 Nc6
{ You develop your knight as usual and challenge White's knight in the center! White only has one good option. }
6. d4 { The only good move for White is to support the knight in the center. }
6... d6 { You immediately kick White's knight away from the center. } 7. Nxc6
{ White should trade the knights. } 7... bxc6 8. Bxf4 Nf6
{ You continue development and get ready to kick the bishop away with ...Nh5! }
9. Nc3 Nh5 { You start attacking! } 10. Bg5 f6 11. Be3 Ng3
{ You keep moving the knight! You don't want to trade it for the light-squared bishop yet, but the idea of placing your knight here is that when White plays Be2 and targets your vulnerable g4-pawn, then you are ready to capture the bishop. }
12. Rg1 Rb8 { You keep the attack going and put more pressure. } 13. Kf2
{ White's best move is to attack your knight and force the trade. } 13... Nxf1
14. Rxf1 Bg7
{ Now you are not greedy with the direct  14...Rxb2  because after  15.Kg1  Bg7  16.Ne2  O-O  17.Ng3  White is in time to stop your ... f5-break, and your dark-squared bishop is very bad. }
15. Kg1 O-O 16. Qd2 f5
{ Both bishops will become active when you get in the f5-pawn break, and Black has a good position. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12a) Queens Gambit Declined"]
[Black "Queen Gambit Declined: 3.cxd5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 { It's to learn how to fight against d4! } 1... d5
{ As usual you place your pawn in the center first. } 2. c4
{ The Queen's Gambit. White challenges your center. Capturing the pawn is possible, but not what you will learn in this course. }
2... e6
{ You reinforce your pawn to support the center.  A common mistake is to play  2...Nf6?  , supporting the center with your knight, but after  3.cxd5  Nxd5  , White can gain complete control of the center with  4.e4 }
3. cxd5
{ White goes for the early exchange variation. This variation is challenging to face, and you have to be precise to still be able to develop your pieces in your regular setup. This is because you usually aim to capture back with the knight on d5 and trade White's knight on c3, or in some cases, you also capture the pawn on ...dxc4 at a later stage.  When White exchanges one move later  3.Nc3  Nf6  4.cxd5  there you capture back with  4...Nxd5  5.e4  Nxc3  6.bxc3  , and you can go for your standard development plan with  6...c5  when you want to trade the pawns on d4 and continue with ...Nc6  Also, in the early exchange variation, you still want to get in the moves  ...c5  and  ...Nc6  , and therefore, you want to play after  3.cxd5  exd5  4.Nc3  Bb4  pinning the knight and follow it up with ...c5 and ...Nc6.  Going for  4...Nf6?  would no longer allow you to go for your usual setup since after  5.Bg5  c5?  is no longer possible  6.Bxf6  leaves you would a sad decision to either play  6...gxf6  with a horrible pawn structure, or  6...Qxf6  loses a pawn with  7.Nxd5 }
3... exd5 4. Nc3
{ White develops the knight. Now, you have to be careful not to run into unfamiliar theory. }
4... Bb4
{ You pin White's knight! This is a special moment when you make an exception to the rule of developing knights first. This is strong to do since White's move already allowed an appealing option for your bishop to pin the knight.  After  4...Nf6  , White can pin you with  5.Bg5  and your standard plans with  5...c5?  won't work anymore because after  6.Bxf6  , you don't have a good way to recapture:  6...exf6  ruins your pawn structure, and  6...Qxf6  allows  7.Nxd5  , losing your central pawn.  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/8/3p4/3P4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...c5  to prepare for ...Nc6 is possible and aligns with the course ideas. But, as a Semi-Tarrasch player, you generally avoid these pawn structures, and  4...c5  leads towards the Tarrasch, which is another big theoretical variation you would rather avoid. }
5. Nf3 c5
{ This move has only been played in six classical games, so it could be surprising for your opponent. You keep delaying the ...Nf6 move. }
6. g3 Nc6 { It's good to develop the knight and put pressure on the center. }
7. Bg2 Nf6 { Now going for ...Nf6 is fine. } 8. Bg5 cxd4
{ You first trade to avoid that White captures your pawn. } 9. Nxd4 h6
{ You can immediately challenge the bishop now. The strategy worked well to wait with playing...Nf6 because now that White already played g3, it's no longer possible for them to keep the pin since  10.Bh4?  just loses the bishop after  10...g5 }
10. Bxf6 { White has to your knight now. } 10... Qxf6
{ You are putting more pressure on the d4-knight. } 11. Nb5 O-O
{ You can castle! It would be way too risky for White to capture your central pawn now. }
12. O-O Bxc3 { You eliminate the knight now. } 13. Nxc3 Rd8
{ You have consolidated the position with Black.   14.Nxd5  can be met with  14...Qxb2  capturing the pawn back. }
*

