1. d4 { It's to learn how to fight against d4! } 1... d5
{ As usual you place your pawn in the center first. } 2. c4
{ The Queen's Gambit. White challenges your center. Capturing the pawn is possible, but not what you will learn in this course. }
2... e6
{ You reinforce your pawn to support the center.  A common mistake is to play  2...Nf6?  , supporting the center with your knight, but after  3.cxd5  Nxd5  , White can gain complete control of the center with  4.e4 }
3. cxd5
{ White goes for the early exchange variation. This variation is challenging to face, and you have to be precise to still be able to develop your pieces in your regular setup. This is because you usually aim to capture back with the knight on d5 and trade White's knight on c3, or in some cases, you also capture the pawn on ...dxc4 at a later stage.  When White exchanges one move later  3.Nc3  Nf6  4.cxd5  there you capture back with  4...Nxd5  5.e4  Nxc3  6.bxc3  , and you can go for your standard development plan with  6...c5  when you want to trade the pawns on d4 and continue with ...Nc6  Also, in the early exchange variation, you still want to get in the moves  ...c5  and  ...Nc6  , and therefore, you want to play after  3.cxd5  exd5  4.Nc3  Bb4  pinning the knight and follow it up with ...c5 and ...Nc6.  Going for  4...Nf6?  would no longer allow you to go for your usual setup since after  5.Bg5  c5?  is no longer possible  6.Bxf6  leaves you would a sad decision to either play  6...gxf6  with a horrible pawn structure, or  6...Qxf6  loses a pawn with  7.Nxd5 }
3... exd5 4. Nc3
{ White develops the knight. Now, you have to be careful not to run into unfamiliar theory. }
4... Bb4
{ You pin White's knight! This is a special moment when you make an exception to the rule of developing knights first. This is strong to do since White's move already allowed an appealing option for your bishop to pin the knight.  After  4...Nf6  , White can pin you with  5.Bg5  and your standard plans with  5...c5?  won't work anymore because after  6.Bxf6  , you don't have a good way to recapture:  6...exf6  ruins your pawn structure, and  6...Qxf6  allows  7.Nxd5  , losing your central pawn.  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/8/3p4/3P4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...c5  to prepare for ...Nc6 is possible and aligns with the course ideas. But, as a Semi-Tarrasch player, you generally avoid these pawn structures, and  4...c5  leads towards the Tarrasch, which is another big theoretical variation you would rather avoid. }
5. Nf3 c5
{ This move has only been played in six classical games, so it could be surprising for your opponent. You keep delaying the ...Nf6 move. }
6. Bg5
{ White attacks your queen and hopes that you still go for ...Nf6 getting back into the pin.  You want to avoid the position after  6...Nf6?  7.dxc5  , where White keeps pressure on your center. }
6... Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 Qa5
{ You immediately counter with pressure against the c3-pawn. } 8. Bd2
{ The bishop drops back to support the pawn. } 8... Nc6
{ You can keep developing. } 9. c4
{ The discovered attack is not problematic. } 9... Qd8
{ You support your central pawn. } 10. cxd5 Qxd5 11. dxc5 Nf6
{ You develop your knights to the natural squares as always. There was no need to rush with capturing the c5-pawn back, but also  11...Qxc5  would have been fine. }
12. Rc1 { White can try to hold on to the pawn. } 12... Ne4
{ You put more pressure on the bishop and the c5-pawn. } 13. Qb3
{ White can try to exchange queens to hold on to the bishop, but it doesn't work out well for them. }
13... Qxb3 14. axb3 Be6
{ You develop and attack the b3-pawn.  You will win back the pawn since White has no way to defend it.  15.b4  wouldn't keep the extra pawn for White because you can play  15...Nxd2  16.Kxd2  Nxb4 }
