[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12a) Queens Gambit Declined"]
[Black "Queens Gambit Declined: 3.cxd5 #9"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 { It's to learn how to fight against d4! } 1... d5
{ As usual you place your pawn in the center first. } 2. c4
{ The Queen's Gambit. White challenges your center. Capturing the pawn is possible, but not what you will learn in this course. }
2... e6
{ You reinforce your pawn to support the center.  A common mistake is to play  2...Nf6?  , supporting the center with your knight, but after  3.cxd5  Nxd5  , White can gain complete control of the center with  4.e4 }
3. cxd5
{ After learning the lines, you know that you usually like to take back with the knight when White takes your d5-pawn. If White trades right away, this isn't possible. }
3... exd5 { Without the c4-pawn, the pressure on your center decreases. } 4.
Nc3
{ White develops the knight. Now, you have to be careful not to run into unfamiliar theory. }
4... Bb4
{ You pin White's knight! This is a special moment when you make an exception to the rule of developing knights first. This is strong to do since White's move already allowed an appealing option for your bishop to pin the knight.  After  4...Nf6  , White can pin you with  5.Bg5  and your standard plans with  5...c5  won't work anymore because after  6.Bxf6  , you don't have a good way to recapture:  6...exf6  ruins your pawn structure, and  6...Qxf6  allows  7.Nxd5  , losing your central pawn.  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/8/3p4/3P4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...c5  to prepare for ...Nc6 is possible and aligns with the course ideas. But, as a Semi-Tarrasch player, you generally avoid these pawn structures, and  4...c5  leads towards the Tarrasch, which is another big theoretical variation you would rather avoid. }
5. Bf4 { White develops the bishop. } 5... c5
{ You immediately start putting pressure on the center. You would like to get the bishop shutdown setup you also have with White in the Panov against the Caro-Kann after  6.e3  c4  .  Therefore, I recommend playing c5 as fast as possible to give your opponent only one chance to capture the pawn.   5...Nf6  is also an alternative. }
6. e3 c4
{ You use the bishop shutdown structure as you did with White in the Panov Attack against the Caro-Kann. This time, your pin could even be more dangerous for White since the dark-squared bishop is already out of the pawn change. }
7. Bxb8
{ The most popular move, and White is only playing for a cheap trick. Other moves from White are also not dangerous. You want to develop your knight to the natural squares as usual and have a better pawn structure because White's light-squared bishop is stuck. }
7... Bxc3+
{ You exchange the bishop with an intermediate check.   7...Rxb8?  would lose the bishop after  8.Qa4+  with a fork. }
8. bxc3 Rxb8 { You capture the bishop back! } 9. Qa4+
{ White can win a pawn with the fork but won't have any pieces developed. }
9... Bd7 { 9...b5 is also a strong alternative. } 10. Qxa7 Nf6
{ This is a fantastic position for Black. You are ready to castle and can opt for ...Ne4 to put pressure on the weak c3-pawn. }
