[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12a) Queens Gambit Declined"]
[Black "Queens Gambit Declined: 4.Bg5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 { It's to learn how to fight against d4! } 1... d5
{ As usual you place your pawn in the center first. } 2. c4
{ The Queen's Gambit. White challenges your center. Capturing the pawn is possible, but not what you will learn in this course. }
2... e6
{ You reinforce your pawn to support the center.  A common mistake is to play  2...Nf6?  , supporting the center with your knight, but after  3.cxd5  Nxd5  , White can gain complete control of the center with  4.e4 }
3. Nc3 { White develops the knight! } 3... Nf6
{ You also develop the knight and support the center. } 4. Bg5
{ White develops the bishop and pins your knight! } 4... c5 5. e3 cxd4
{ This time, you trade the flank pawn for the central pawn because you need your bishop to block the pin; therefore, it cannot also fulfill the task of defending the pawn.  After  5...Nc6  you get into trouble after  6.cxd5  exd5  and  7.Bxf6  when you need to decide if you want to have a bad pawn structure or lose a pawn. }
6. exd4 Be7
{ You develop the bishop first because you always want to be able to capture with ...Nxd5 back! }
7. Nf3 O-O { You can continue your development and castle! } 8. c5
{ This doesn't establish anything like a bishop shutdown structure, which you played with White against the Caro-Kann. }
8... b6 { First, you aim to weaken the pawn structure! } 9. b4 Ne4
{ You force White to trade your bishop that was blocked and get rid of your problems. Since Black has to capture your knight here, you also free the d5-square, which can be an outpost later on for your light-squared bishop. }
10. Bxe7 Qxe7 11. Nxe4 dxe4 12. Ne5 Rd8
{ You put pressure on the central pawn and aim to follow it up with ... Bb7 and ...Nc6 }
