[Black "Queens Gambit Declined: 4.Bg5 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 { It's to learn how to fight against d4! } 1... d5
{ As usual you place your pawn in the center first. } 2. c4
{ The Queen's Gambit. White challenges your center. Capturing the pawn is possible, but not what you will learn in this course. }
2... e6
{ You reinforce your pawn to support the center.  A common mistake is to play  2...Nf6?  , supporting the center with your knight, but after  3.cxd5  Nxd5  , White can gain complete control of the center with  4.e4 }
3. Nc3 { White develops the knight! } 3... Nf6
{ You also develop the knight and support the center. } 4. Bg5
{ White develops the bishop and pins your knight! } 4... c5 5. Nf3 cxd4
{ You capture the pawn in the center! You generally don't do this when White has the pawn supported with another pawn.  In this situation, after  6.Nxd4  , you can opt for  6...e5  and after  6.Qxd4  , you can attack with  6...Nc6 }
6. Qxd4 Nc6 7. Bxf6
{ White should take your knight immediately to destroy the pawn structure because after  7.Qh4  , you can support the knight with  7...Be7 }
7... gxf6 8. Qh4 { The queen moves to safety. } 8... dxc4
{ Going for  8...d4  now is risky since White can pin you with  9.O-O-O } 9.
Rd1 Bd7
{ You block with the bishop because you want to keep defending the f6-pawn with your queen. Next you can opt for ...f5 and ...Bg7 and also with ...Qb6 you can start putting pressure on the b2-pawn. }
