[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12a) Queens Gambit Declined"]
[Black "Queens Gambit Declined: 4.Bg5 #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 { It's to learn how to fight against d4! } 1... d5
{ As usual you place your pawn in the center first. } 2. c4
{ The Queen's Gambit. White challenges your center. Capturing the pawn is possible, but not what you will learn in this course. }
2... e6
{ You reinforce your pawn to support the center.  A common mistake is to play  2...Nf6?  , supporting the center with your knight, but after  3.cxd5  Nxd5  , White can gain complete control of the center with  4.e4 }
3. Nc3 { White develops the knight! } 3... Nf6
{ You also develop the knight and support the center. } 4. Bg5
{ White develops the bishop and pins your knight! } 4... c5 5. cxd5 cxd4
{ You take the central pawn, tempting White's queen to advance.   5...exd5?  is less ideal since White can respond with  6.Bxf6  . If you retake with your queen,  6...Qxf6  , White wins the central pawn with  7.Nxd5 }
6. Qa4+
{ Surpringly, this check has been given quite frequently, but it only helps you. }
6... Qd7
{ You block with the queen! Your queen may look misplaced, but you get out of the pin of your knight. }
7. Qxd4 Nc6 { Using the pinned pawn, you gain a tempo on the queen. } 8. Qd1
{ White's queen has no good squares and has to retreat to the starting square.   8.Qd2  is more common, but now after  8...Nxd5  9.Nxd5  exd5  , you suddenly are threatening ...Bb4 to pin the queen }
8... Nxd5 9. Nxd5 exd5
{ Trading queens would also be fine, but let's keep them on the board. } 10.
Nf3 Bc5
{ In this structure, White's dark-squared bishop is misplaced and has no target to attack.  Eventually, you can chase the bishop back to d2, where it blocks the queen. Therefore, going for your standard Semi-Tarrasch approach with  10...Bb4  11.Bd2  Bxd2+  12.Qxd2  would be a slight inaccuracy, although, in that position, Black also has nothing to be worried about. }
*

[Event "?"]
