[White "12a) Queens Gambit Declined"]
[Black "Queens Gambit Declined: 4.Bg5 #11"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 { It's to learn how to fight against d4! } 1... d5
{ As usual you place your pawn in the center first. } 2. c4
{ The Queen's Gambit. White challenges your center. Capturing the pawn is possible, but not what you will learn in this course. }
2... e6
{ You reinforce your pawn to support the center.  A common mistake is to play  2...Nf6?  , supporting the center with your knight, but after  3.cxd5  Nxd5  , White can gain complete control of the center with  4.e4 }
3. Nc3 { White develops the knight! } 3... Nf6
{ You also develop the knight and support the center. } 4. Bg5
{ White develops the bishop and pins your knight! } 4... c5 5. cxd5 cxd4
{ You take the central pawn, tempting White's queen to advance.   5...exd5?  is less ideal since White can respond with  6.Bxf6  . If you retake with your queen,  6...Qxf6  , White wins the central pawn with  7.Nxd5 }
6. Qxd4 Be7
{ You develop your bishop, breaking the pin on your knight.   6...Nc6?  seems reasonable, but it doesn't work out well. While White can't take your knight because you pin the central pawn, White can play  7.Bxf6  and launch a counterattack on your queen. After  7...gxf6  is played, then  8.Qe3  creates a pin on the e-pawn, and you can't recapture the central pawn. }
7. e4 { White tries to hold on to the central pawn. } 7... Nc6
{ You attack the queen and use the pin on the central pawn. } 8. Qe3 Nxd5
{ You capture with the knight opening the attack on the bishop.  This time,  8...exd5  doesn't work well after  9.Bxf6  Bxf6  10.exd5+  comes with a check and after  10...Ne7  White has the powerful  11.d6  sacrificing the pawn so that after  11...Qxd6  12.Bb5+  Black can't block with  12...Bd7  because of  13.Rd1!  You want to avoid this. }
9. exd5 { White takes the challenge and grabs your knight. } 9... Bxg5 10. f4
{ White goes for a double attack on your bishop and knight! Time to counterattack. }
10... Nb4 { Threatening the royal fork with ...Nc2+ } 11. O-O-O
{ White castles and defends against the fork! } 11... Be7
{ You move your bishop back to safety and secure your knight!   11...Bf6  may look more active, however, after  12.Bb5+  Kf8  13.Qc5+  would win the knight with a fork since now  13...Be7  would be too late as  14.d6  cuts off the defense. }
12. Bb5+ Kf8
{ You have to sidestep with the king!   12...Bd7?  would end badly when  13.dxe6  also, pin your bishop to your queen. }
13. d6
{ White could try to sacrifice the pawn to open the d-file.  After  13.dxe6  , you have a similar counterplay with  13...Qc7 }
13... Bxd6 14. Nf3 Qc7
{ The same idea for counterplay stepping out of the pin and threatening ... Bxf4 }
15. Kb1 e5
{ With energetic play ...Bf5 becomes a big threat, and White has to be careful.  White could still defend with  16.Nd4  , the knight can't be captured because of checkmate  16...Bc5  pins the knight when White has to start going into an equal endgame after  17.Qxe5  Qxe5  18.fxe5  Bg4 }
*

