12. dxe6
{ The main move is to grab the pawn! This is not as dangerous as it looks. When the board opens up, it favors the side with the bishop pair. }
12... Qc7 { You sidestep with the queen and pin the knight. } 13. exf7+ Kxf7
{ There is no need to hide your king, and you can safely recapture the pawn. At this point, you threaten ...Nxa2 since you are pinning the knight. White has no good way to defend against the threat. }
14. Nf3
{ White develops the knight and allows the threat.   14.a3  would result in the same situation  14...Na2+  15.Kb1  Nxc3+  16.Qxc3  Qxc3  17.bxc3  and now Black could already grab the pawn back with  17...Bxa3  , although other moves would also give Black a good endgame. }
14... Nxa2+ 15. Kb1 Nxc3+ 16. Qxc3
{ Now White is the one who wants to trade queens as after  16.bxc3  Bf5+  17.Kb2  Rhd8  Black's king starts looking more safe than White's king. }
16... Qxc3 17. bxc3 Rd8 { Black has a good endgame with the bishop pair. } *

