{ You bring your queen in the attack and eye for ...Qa3+ } 14. Kb2 Bd7
{ You develop the bishop and get ready to involve the rooks in the attack. }
15. Ne2 Rac8 { This threatens ...Nc4+ } 16. Ng3 Rfd8
{ You ensure all your pieces participate in the attack. } 17. Ne4 Qc7
{ White's king remains weak, and White is not yet ready to develop the bishop with  18.Be2  because you have  18...Be6  targeting the pinned d5-pawn. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12a) Queens Gambit Declined"]
[Black "Queens Gambit Declined Exchange Variation: 7.Rb1 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 { It's to learn how to fight against d4! } 1... d5
{ As usual you place your pawn in the center first. } 2. c4
{ The Queen's Gambit. White challenges your center. Capturing the pawn is possible, but not what you will learn in this course. }
2... e6
{ You reinforce your pawn to support the center.  A common mistake is to play  2...Nf6?  , supporting the center with your knight, but after  3.cxd5  Nxd5  , White can gain complete control of the center with  4.e4 }
3. Nc3 { White develops the knight! } 3... Nf6
{ You also develop the knight and support the center. } 4. cxd5
{ White directly exchanges the pawns, a cunning move. } 4... Nxd5
{ Like in earlier scenarios, you recapture using the knight. Your goal is to transition to known positions and cleverly sidestep extensive theory.  Taking with the pawn is more common, but the problem now is that after  4...exd5  5.Bg5  , you can't opt for your usual setup with  5...c5  , as White can strike with  6.Bxf6  , and  6...Qxf6  would lead to the loss of your central pawn after  7.Nxd5 }
5. e4 { White places the pawn in the center. } 5... Nxc3
{ You go for the standard trade! } 6. bxc3 c5
{ You pressure White's center as usual. } 7. Rb1
{ White tries to capitalize on your different move order.  The idea is that after  7...cxd4  8.cxd4  , you can't play ...Bb4+ anymore. In most games, If White continues with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp3ppp/4p3/2p5/3PP3/2P5/P4PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Nf3  , you get back to the Semi-Tarrasch. You've successfully avoided the Queen's Gambit Exchange variation without studying extra theory. }
7... cxd4
{ You trade the center pawns as usual.   7...Nc6?  first would run into  8.d5 }
8. cxd4 Nc6 { You put pressure on the center with your knight. } 9. Bb5
{ White pins your knight!  When you have an absolute pin, you can't move, so  9...Bb4+?  would be a horrible blunder since White would capture the bishop for free with  10.Rxb4 }
9... a6
{ A common motif in your repertoire, you want to get rid of the pin immediately. }
10. Bxc6+
{ White is obligated to trade the bishop. Otherwise, you would win the d4-pawn. }
10... bxc6 11. Nf3 c5
{ You make a daring move and immediately aim to get rid of your isolated pawn. You challenge the center. As usual, you want to avoid capturing it immediately when you have a flank pawn that attacks the center.  Developing immediately with  11...Be7?  gives White the chance to attack your weak pawn with  12.Ne5  and now  12...c5  is no longer possible since White goes for  13.Qa4+  and can stop you from castling. }
12. Bg5
{ This move I faced myself in a classical game against FM Tomaszewski in Riga 2023, and the game continued crazily with  12...Qa5+?  13.Kf1?  Eventually, I won quickly after my opponent missed a beautiful way to defend the position. White could have punished my check  12...Qa5?  with  13.Bd2  when after  13...Qc7  14.Rc1  White has a powerful pin on the c-pawn. }
12... f6
{ Chasing the bishop back is a good option, and in the game Adhiban- Xiang, Black managed to get a better position out of the opening and win the game after  13.Be3  cxd4  14.Nxd4  e5  Black has a beautiful pawn structure restricting White's knight.   12...Be7  is a valid alternative; however, after  13.Bxe7  Qxe7  14.Qc2  Black needs to sacrifice the c5-pawn temporarily and can only hope to get an equal position by winning it back. The move 12...f6 is more ambitious. }
13. Bf4 cxd4 14. O-O Bc5 { Holding on to the pawn White gave you! } 15. Rc1 Ba7
16. e5 f5
{ White can only hope to gain back the pawn. After  17.Qa4+  Qd7  18.Qxd7+  Kxd7  19.Nxd4  Bxd4  20.Rfd1  Bb7  21.Rxd4  Bd5  , Black has a very comfortable endgame. }
*

