10... bxc6 11. Nf3 c5
{ You make a daring move and immediately aim to get rid of your isolated pawn. You challenge the center. As usual, you want to avoid capturing it immediately when you have a flank pawn that attacks the center.  Developing immediately with  11...Be7?  gives White the chance to attack your weak pawn with  12.Ne5  and now  12...c5  is no longer possible since White goes for  13.Qa4+  and can stop you from castling. }
12. O-O Be7
{ It's time to start developing! As usual you don't trade the flank pawn for the central pawn since after  13.dxc5  Qxd1  14.Rxd1  Bxc5  your bishop is well-placed on c5. }
13. dxc5 Qxd1
{ You first trade the queens to recapture the pawn without losing the right to castle. }
14. Rxd1 Bxc5 15. Bf4 f6
{ The most flexible way to solve the minor issues in the position. If White allows you, you would love to play ...e5, gaining a strong pawn structure restricting White's bishop. }
16. e5
{ White counters your plan, not allowing you to get a strong pawn structure. }
16... O-O
{ With the bishop pair, you have a dynamic endgame. You can play ...Ra7 to control your seventh rank and start developing your light-squared bishop, and ...Kf7 to activate your king and control the pawn. }
