{ The critical move where White challenges your knight. } 12... Qd6
{ A multi-purpose move. You support the knight and double on the d-file. } 13.
O-O Rd8 { You increase the pressure and immediately go after the d4-pawn. } 14.
Rfd1
{ White supports the central pawn.   14.Bxc6  is also possible, but after  14...Qxc6  15.Qf4  h6  16.Rfc1  Qd6  it's not problematic that after the trade of queens with  17.Qxd6  Rxd6  White can enter the seventh rank with  18.Rc7  because after  18...b6  you have counterplay with ...Ba6-Be2-Bxf3 when White's center is shaky, and this way you can maintain the balance. }
14... h6
{ A prophylactic move. Often, White could aim to advance with e5 and start a kingside attack; therefore, it's useful to safeguard the g5-square. }
15. Qe3 Bd7
{ You develop your bishop, and White has difficulties pushing their central pawns forward.   16.d5  exd5  17.exd5  Ne7  would be great for Black, as the d5-pawn is safely blockaded  16.e5  Qf8 }
16. e5 Qf8
{ White is left with some weaknesses in the position, and ...Ne7 next is appealing, getting ready to jump to f5 or d5. }
