[White "12a) Queens Gambit Declined"]
[Black "Queens Gambit Declined 3.Nf3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Bg5
{ White goes for the pin now. This creates the threat that White wants to capture the pawn and go to a position where your standard ...c5 and ...Nc6 plan no longer works. Therefore, you capture White's c4-pawn now.  This strategy is similar to the Catalan, which you will learn later. So after  4.g3  you also first capture with  4...dxc4  before you continue with your usual setup. }
4... dxc4
{ Next move, you are ready to play ...c5 and go for the standard development move. }
5. Qa4+ { White forks the king and pawn. } 5... Bd7
{ The usual reply, you keep the c6-square free for your knight. } 6. Qxc4 c5
{ The standard break still works. } 7. dxc5 Qc8
{ This will make sure to win back the c5-pawn. Defending it with 8.b4 would only make things worse for Black because you go for the thematic pawnbreak with 8... a5, and White can't hold on to the pawn formation. Note that 7...Qa5? would be wrong because now 8.b4 supports the pawn and also gains a tempo on the queen. }
8. Nbd2 { White can't hold on to the pawn. } 8... Qxc5 9. Qxc5 Bxc5
{ You have won the pawn back with a comfortable position. } *

