1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Bg5
{ White goes for the pin now. This creates the threat that White wants to capture the pawn and go to a position where your standard ...c5 and ...Nc6 plan no longer works. Therefore, you capture White's c4-pawn now.  This strategy is similar to the Catalan, which you will learn later. So after  4.g3  you also first capture with  4...dxc4  before you continue with your usual setup. }
4... dxc4
{ Next move, you are ready to play ...c5 and go for the standard development move. }
5. Nc3
{ White develops the knight!   5.e4  is also possible and usually transposes after  5...c5  6.Nc3 }
5... c5 { You go for your standard pawnbreak. } 6. e4 cxd4
{ Capturing the pawn is useful to continue your development. } 7. Nxd4 Bc5
{ You develop the bishop first to avoid getting doubled pawns. White is already under pressure and struggles here to keep an equal position. }
8. Nf3 { It would be best for White to retreat with the knight. } 8... Qxd1+
{ You trade the queens to make sure that White's can't capture you. } 9. Rxd1
h6 { You attack the bishop since you would love to trade it for your knight. }
10. Bf4 Nc6
{ You develop and are doing well in the endgame. You have no weaknesses, and with ...Bb4, you can put some pressure on White's e4-pawn. }
