1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Bg5
{ White goes for the pin now. This creates the threat that White wants to capture the pawn and go to a position where your standard ...c5 and ...Nc6 plan no longer works. Therefore, you capture White's c4-pawn now.  This strategy is similar to the Catalan, which you will learn later. So after  4.g3  you also first capture with  4...dxc4  before you continue with your usual setup. }
4... dxc4
{ Next move, you are ready to play ...c5 and go for the standard development move. }
5. Nc3
{ White develops the knight!   5.e4  is also possible and usually transposes after  5...c5  6.Nc3 }
5... c5 { You go for your standard pawnbreak. } 6. e3 cxd4
{ You first capture the pawn before you keep developing.   6...Nc6  would allow White to go for  7.Bxf6  a move that has never been played yet, but a very strong one. Because after  7...Qxf6  8.d5  puts pressure on your knight, and  8...exd5  runs into another problem that  9.Nxd5  attacks your queen. }
7. exd4 Qc7
{ You have won the c4-pawn, and you don't want to give it up so easily.   7...Nc6?  would allow White to win back the pawn with  8.Bxc4 }
8. Qa4+ { White could still win the pawn back with the fork. } 8... Bd7
{ This gives you a tempo in development. } 9. Qxc4 Qxc4
{ Trading queens is also good when your opponent has the isolated pawn. } 10.
Bxc4 Bb4
{ You pin the knight! In this position it's good to wait a bit with playing ...Nc6 because you can put pressure by ...O-O followed by ...Rc8 since White's pieces are vulnerable on the c-file. Black has an excellent endgame. }
11. O-O O-O { And ...Rc8 is a powerful threat. } *

