[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12b) Semi-Tarrasch Defense "]
[Black "Semi-Tarrasch Mainline: 4...Nf3 and 5.e3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ The second-most popular move at the beginner level. You should stop White from dominating the center. }
1... d5 { You apply the first golden rule and place your pawn in the center. }
2. c4
{ The Queen's Gambit. White challenges your center. While you can accept the Queen's Gambit, I don't recommend it because after  2...dxc4  3.e4  , White establishes a strong pawn center and threatens to retake your pawn. }
2... e6
{ You reinforce your pawn to support the center.   2...c6  is also a viable option, leading to the Slav opening. A common error among beginners is to play  2...Nf6?  , supporting the center with your knight, but after  3.cxd5  Nxd5  , White can gain complete control of the center with  4.e4 }
3. Nc3 { White develops the knight! } 3... Nf6
{ You also develop the knight and support the center. } 4. Nf3
{ White brings out the other knight! This is one of the main moves.  It could be tempting to play  4...Nc6?  in line with the opening principles you learned earlier. However, in the d4-variations, your knight can only exert a little bit of pressure on the center if your pawn is behind it. Therefore, you first play  4...c5  and aim to increase the pressure on the center with ...Nc6 next. }
4... c5 { You always this pawn and get ready to develop your knight next. } 5.
e3 { A slow move from White to defend the central pawn. } 5... Nc6
{ You develop the knight.  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp3ppp/4pn2/2pp4/2PP4/2N1PN2/PP3PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...cxd4  is another option, but the drawback is that after  6.exd4  , it opens up a diagonal for White's light-squared bishop. }
6. cxd5 Nxd5 { You capture back with the knight as usual. } 7. Nxd5
{ White also has alternatives and is not obliged to trade the knights.  After  7.Bd3  , you can play  7...cxd4  8.exd4  Be7  and get ready to castle. }
7... Qxd5 { your queen would be strong in the center after the trades! } 8. Bb5
{ White would run into trouble when they pin your knight. } 8... cxd4
{ You capture with a discovered attack on the bishop. } 9. Bxc6+ bxc6
{ You take back using the pawn, with the idea to play ...Ba6 next, preventing White from castling. }
10. Qxd4 Ba6
{ A clever move that stops White from castling.  You won't mind if White decides to exchange queens with  11.Qxd5  , because after  11...cxd5  , your pawns would be linked together once again. }
*

