{ You develop the knight.  The most challenging move for White would be  6.a3  , but it's rarely seen among beginner-level play. Next, you aim to exchange your flank pawn for White's central pawn and develop the bishop and castle.  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp3ppp/4pn2/2pp4/2PP4/2N1PN2/PP3PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...cxd4  is another option, but the drawback is that after  6.exd4  , it opens up a diagonal for White's light-squared bishop. }
6. a3 Ne4
{ You free the f6-square for your bishop. Also, White has the idea to capture on c5 and play b4, and you also stop those. }
7. Qc2 { White can attack your knight with the queen. } 7... Nxc3
{ You trade the knights. } 8. Qxc3
{ White can also capture with pawn  8.bxc3  , and you can develop with  8...Bd6 }
8... cxd4
{ You trade in the center! White was putting pressure on your c-pawn with the queen on the c-file. }
9. exd4 dxc4
{ You also capture the other pawn to give White an isolated d-pawn. } 10. Bxc4
Be7
{ You are ready to castle. Your bishop will be strong on f6, putting pressure on the central pawn. }
