12... b5 { You offer a poisoned pawn to the bishop. } 13. Ba2 Qa5+
{ A classy move! You first want to make the bishop block the d-file so that White's queen doesn't defend the d4-pawn anymore and subsequently starts attacking the central pawn.  At this point, the plan with  13...Na5  doesn't work well since White can go for the direct  14.d5 }
14. Bd2 Qb6
{ Now you attack the pawn and threaten to capture it.  15.d5  is not dangerous. You can capture it with  15...exd5  16.Bxd5  Kh8  and continue development with ...Bb7  After @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/p3b1pp/1qn1p3/1p2Pp2/3P4/P4N2/B2B1PPP/R2QK2R w KQ - 4 15@@EndFEN@@  15.Be3  , there are two strong options: attack the bishop with  15...f4  or give another check with  15...Qa5+ }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12b) Semi-Tarrasch Defense "]
[Black "Semi-Tarrasch Mainline: 4...Nf3 and 5.cxd5 #16"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ The second most popular move at the Beginner level. You should stop White from dominating the center. }
1... d5 { You apply the first golden rule and place your pawn in the center. }
2. c4
{ The Queen's Gambit. White challenges your center. While you can accept the Queen's Gambit, I don't recommend it because after  2...dxc4  3.e4  , White establishes a strong pawn center and threatens to retake your pawn. }
2... e6
{ You reinforce your pawn to support the center.   2...c6  is also a viable option, leading to the Slav opening. A common error among beginners is to play  2...Nf6?  , supporting the center with your knight, but after  3.cxd5  Nxd5  , White can gain complete control of the center with  4.e4 }
3. Nc3 { White develops the knight! } 3... Nf6
{ You also develop the knight and support the center. } 4. Nf3
{ White brings out the other knight! This is one of the main moves.  It could be tempting to play  4...Nc6?  in line with the opening principles you learned earlier. However, in the d4-variations, your knight can only apply little pressure on the center if your pawn is behind it. Therefore, you first play  4...c5  and aim to increase the pressure on the center with ...Nc6 next. }
4... c5
{ You always push this pawn and get ready to develop your knight next. } 5.
cxd5 { White goes for the trade } 5... Nxd5
{ As always you capture back with your knight. } 6. e4
{ White places the pawn in the center. } 6... Nxc3 { You trade the knights. }
7. bxc3 cxd4
{ It's important to trade pawns in the center before developing the knight.  If you play  7...Nc6  too early, White can push  8.d5  and your knight has no good squares. }
8. cxd4 Nc6
{ Trading pawns makes it safe to develop the knight.  You could also play  8...Bb4+  , but it's your common strategy to develop the knight first, which sets some nasty traps for White. }
9. a3
{ A cunning move from White not allowing you to give the check with ...Bb4. }
9... Be7 { You develop your bishop and get ready to castle. } 10. Bd3
{ The best square for the bishop, keeping the option open for a kingside attack. }
10... O-O 11. Bb2
{ White has a healthy position, although they have one problem: the king is still in the middle. Let's make use of that. }
11... Qa5+ { You throw in a powerful check. } 12. Kf1
{ White gives up on the right to castle. } 12... b6
{ You aim for ... Ba6 trading off White's light-squared bishop. } 13. Qe2
{ White stops your plan! With the light-squared bishop, White could start a dangerous attack. }
13... Nb8
{ A brilliant move; by retreating the knight, you force a trade of the light-squared bishop with ...Ba6 next }
14. Rc1 Ba6
{ Trades are about to happen, and as you know, this benefits you since you have flank pawns versus White's central pawns. }
*

