[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "13a) Catalan "]
[Black "Catalan Open Defense: 7.Na3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3
{ The Catalan! An opening where White aims to create a powerful light-squared bishop.  This position can also be reached from the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.g3  Nf6  4.Nf3  move order }
4... dxc4 { You capture the pawn. } 5. Bg2 c5
{ As typical for the d4-openings. You want to play your c-pawn first before placing your knight on c6 so that you can apply pressure on the center. }
6. O-O { White castles and is quick with development. } 6... Nc6
{ You develop the knight as usual. } 7. Na3
{ To go for Na3 quickly, it's a bit unknown move, but this has also been played by Carlsen and Caruana and is definitely a serious option. }
7... cxd4 8. Nxc4 Bc5
{ Against this system, I recommend the active bishop move defending the pawn, although in the same position without the Ne5 and ...Bd7 inclusion. I recommend placing the bishop on e7:  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp3ppp/2n1pn2/2p5/2pP4/5NP1/PP2PPBP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Ne5  Bd7  8.Na3  cxd4  9.Naxc4  line I recommend  9...Be7  Because if you play  9...Bc5  the ideas with  10.Qb3  could be annoying. Whereas in this particular position, you still have your bishop on c8. In this early Na3 line, White, could you use the same setup with the bishop on e7 @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp3ppp/2n1pn2/8/2Np4/5NP1/PP2PPBP/R1BQ1RK1 b kq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Be7  White still has the knight on f3 and could opt for  9.b3  and start winning back the d4-pawn while keeping standard pressure with the Catalan bishop. }
9. Bf4 Nd5 { The standard reaction after Bf4! } 10. Be5 Nxe5
{ You can take the bishop. } 11. Ncxe5 O-O 12. Nxd4 Qb6
{ You start putting pressure on the knight. } 13. Nb3 Be7
{ You threaten tactics with ...Ne3 } 14. Bxd5
{ Capturing the knight doesn't win a pawn for White. } 14... Rd8
{ With the pin, Black wins the Catalan bishop and is doing great with the bishop pair. }
*

