{ Against this system, I recommend the active bishop move defending the pawn, although in the same position without the Ne5 and ...Bd7 inclusion. I recommend placing the bishop on e7:  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp3ppp/2n1pn2/2p5/2pP4/5NP1/PP2PPBP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Ne5  Bd7  8.Na3  cxd4  9.Naxc4  line I recommend  9...Be7  Because if you play  9...Bc5  the ideas with  10.Qb3  could be annoying. Whereas in this particular position, you still have your bishop on c8. In this early Na3 line, White, could you use the same setup with the bishop on e7 @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp3ppp/2n1pn2/8/2Np4/5NP1/PP2PPBP/R1BQ1RK1 b kq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Be7  White still has the knight on f3 and could opt for  9.b3  and start winning back the d4-pawn while keeping standard pressure with the Catalan bishop. }
9. a3 a5 10. b3 Nd7 { A novely! You aim for ...e5, keeping the extra pawn. }
11. Bg5 Nf6
{ Going back is fine! White's bishop would have to go to b2 to target the d4-pawn. }
12. Bc1 { Going back to the starting position is the best option for White. }
12... Nd7 { Again preparing for ...e5 } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "13a) Catalan "]
[Black "Catalan Open Defense: 7.Ne5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3
{ The Catalan! An opening where White aims to create a powerful light-squared bishop.  This position can also be reached from the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.g3  Nf6  4.Nf3  move order }
4... dxc4 { You capture the pawn. } 5. Bg2 c5
{ As typical for the d4-openings. You want to play your c-pawn first before placing your knight on c6 so that you can apply pressure on the center. }
6. O-O { White castles and is quick with development. } 6... Nc6
{ You develop the knight as usual. } 7. Ne5
{ White places the knight in the center.  The idea from White is that after  7...Nxe5?  8.dxe5  Qxd1  9.Rxd1  Nd5  White can trade off your central knight with  10.Nc3  when after  10...Nxc3  11.bxc3  White has a monster bishop on g2, which is pinning the b7-pawn, and it's challenging for you to develop your light-squared bishop. }
7... Bd7 { You develop the bishop and support your knight. } 8. Nxc6
{ It wouldn't be an ambitious choice for White to capture your knight since you can immediately neutralize White's strong, light-squared bishop. }
8... Bxc6
{ The bishops are equally strong now, and White should capture your bishop to give the triple pawns. }
9. Bxc6+ bxc6 10. Qa4 { Attacking both the c6 and c4-pawns. } 10... cxd4
{ You capture in the center. } 11. Qxc6+ Nd7 { The check must be blocked. } 12.
Qxc4 Bc5
{ You firmly hold on to the center pawn and are ready to castle. With the light-squared bishop exchanged you are doing great against the Catalan. White didn't achieve its goal of establishing an influential light-squared bishop. }
13. b4 Be7
{ A powerful move! The point is that you still have the pawn protected with the tactic  14.Qxd4?  Bf6  when you win the rook in the corner with a skewer. Your bishop is better placed on e7 than on b6 because you still keep attacking the b4-pawn. }
14. Bb2 e5 { You consolidate your strong pawn center and are ready to castle. }
*

