[White "13a) Catalan "]
[Black "Catalan Open Defense: 7.Ne5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3
{ The Catalan! An opening where White aims to create a powerful light-squared bishop.  This position can also be reached from the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.g3  Nf6  4.Nf3  move order }
4... dxc4 { You capture the pawn. } 5. Bg2 c5
{ As typical for the d4-openings. You want to play your c-pawn first before placing your knight on c6 so that you can apply pressure on the center. }
6. O-O { White castles and is quick with development. } 6... Nc6
{ You develop the knight as usual. } 7. Ne5
{ White places the knight in the center.  The idea from White is that after  7...Nxe5?  8.dxe5  Qxd1  9.Rxd1  Nd5  White can trade off your central knight with  10.Nc3  when after  10...Nxc3  11.bxc3  White has a monster bishop on g2, which is pinning the b7-pawn, and it's challenging for you to develop your light-squared bishop. }
7... Bd7 { You develop the bishop and support your knight. } 8. Nxc4
{ White sacrifices a pawn in the center and wants to get counterplay with Bf4 and Nd6+ }
8... cxd4 { You capture the pawn. } 9. Bf4 Nd5
{ The idea is that you can use your knight later to make it possible to castle again. }
10. Nd6+ Bxd6 11. Bxd6 Nde7 { You block the bishop and get ready to castle. }
12. Nd2 O-O 13. Qb3 { White pressures your b7-pawn. } 13... b6
{ You push the pawn forward to safeguard the pawn.  13...Bc8  is also an option to defend, but this looks very passive to me. }
14. Rac1 Rc8 { Steps out of the pin and supports the knight. } 15. Ba3
{ White is a pawn down but wants to play Ne4 Nd6 with good counterplay. } 15...
e5 { You consolidate your pawn advantages and build a solid center. } 16. Ne4
Be6 17. Qd3 Qd7
{ It's not possible to prevent White from jumping to d6 with the knight. Your queen nicely supports your knight and makes ...Bh3 ideas are possible to exchange White's powerful bishop. }
18. Nd6 Rc7 19. Nb5 Rcc8
{ White could repeat with  20.Nd6  , and there is no good way to avoid repetition. Although from a theoretical viewpoint, a draw with Black is, of course, a good result. }
20. f4 { White could try to target the center. } 20... Bh3
{ You exchange the Catalan bishop and will exchange one of White's powerful bishops. You are still a pawn up, but with the powerful bishop on a3, White should be able to win a pawn back, keeping the position in balance. }
*

