[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3
{ The Catalan! An opening where White aims to create a powerful light-squared bishop.  This position can also be reached from the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.g3  Nf6  4.Nf3  move order }
4... dxc4 { You capture the pawn. } 5. Bg2 c5
{ As typical for the d4-openings. You want to play your c-pawn first before placing your knight on c6 so that you can apply pressure on the center. }
6. O-O { White castles and is quick with development. } 6... Nc6
{ You develop the knight as usual. } 7. Ne5
{ White places the knight in the center.  The idea from White is that after  7...Nxe5?  8.dxe5  Qxd1  9.Rxd1  Nd5  White can trade off your central knight with  10.Nc3  when after  10...Nxc3  11.bxc3  White has a monster bishop on g2, which is pinning the b7-pawn, and it's challenging for you to develop your light-squared bishop. }
7... Bd7 { You develop the bishop and support your knight. } 8. Na3
{ White develops the knight and is ready to regain the c4-pawn. } 8... cxd4
{ You capture in the center. } 9. Naxc4 { White wins back your c4-pawn. } 9...
Be7 { You develop the bishop and get ready to castle. } 10. Qb3
{ The typical move in this position that White tries to bring you in trouble. }
10... Qc7
{ You use the aggressive approach, defending the pawn and attacking the knight in the center. }
11. Nxc6 Bxc6 12. Bf4 { White gains a tempo in development. } 12... Qd8
{ You retreat to the starting square because  12...Qd7  runs into a fork with  13.Ne5 }
13. Bxc6+ bxc6 14. Ne5 Rc8
{ You defend the pawn with the rook! A novelty, and all of the 29 games continued with  14...c5  when after  15.Qa4+  Kf8  a complicated theoretical battle arises where Black is up pawn up but has misplaced king. I instead recommend something else to avoid this defense and surprise the opponent. }
15. Rac1
{ White can add pressure with the rook, but now the situation is different. }
15... c5 16. Qa4+ Nd7
{ You can block with the knight now. And it would have also been possible to play the main move with @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/p3bppp/2p1pn2/4N3/3p1B2/1Q4P1/PP2PP1P/R4RK1 b kq - 1 14@@EndFEN@@  14...c5  , and after  15.Qa4  block with  15...Nd7  , which Peter Leko played.  Included the moves Rc1 and ...Rc8 gives White fewer options, though, as Black is better prepared for White's plans connected with Nc6. }
17. Rfd1 g5
{ You want to unpin your knight by forcing White's knight to capture you, so you first chase away the bishop. }
18. Bd2
{ The bishop moves back!   18.Be3  looks strange, but it is also possible when after  18...Rc7  19.Nc6  you can counterattack with  19...Nb6 }
18... Qc7 { You target the knight to stop the pin. } 19. Be3 Qxe5 20. Bxd4
{ Suddenly, there is a skewer on the queen and rook, and your c5-pawn is pinned. }
20... Qe4 { You counter with a pin on the bishop and the queen. } 21. f3
{ White kicks away your queen but weakens the king. } 21... Qxe2 22. Bxh8 Qe3+
{ White's only option to avoid perpetual check is running to h3. } 23. Kg2 Qe2+
24. Kh3 f5 25. Qxd7+
{ Grabbing the rook with check loses for White in brilliant fashion } 25... Kf7
{ Threatens checkmate with ...g4 } 26. Qa4
{ White goes back with the queen and defends against the mate.  After  26.Qxc8  h5!  It's also game over }
26... h5 { You have another pawn to reinforce the unstoppable mate. } *

