{ A typical move going after the bishop. } 16. Rac1
{ White increases the pressure on the pawn.   16.Qxa7  would be dangerous for White since you can castle  16...O-O  and the queen is out of play  17.Qxd4?  is not possible because  17...f6  followed by ...e5 next wins a piece. }
16... Nxf4 { It's time to take down the bishop. } 17. gxf4 O-O 18. Nxc6 Qd6
{ The most active square for the queen! } 19. Nxe7+
{ White can reach a position with a pawn-up. } 19... Qxe7 20. Qxd4 Rcd8
{ There is no danger here for Black. White's king is weak, and the pawns on f4 and b2 are vulnerable. Soon, Black should be able to win back a pawn, and the case is likely to head towards a draw. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "13a) Catalan "]
[Black "Catalan Open Defense: 7.Ne5 #10"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3
{ The Catalan! An opening where White aims to create a powerful light-squared bishop.  This position can also be reached from the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.g3  Nf6  4.Nf3  move order }
4... dxc4 { You capture the pawn. } 5. Bg2 c5
{ As typical for the d4-openings. You want to play your c-pawn first before placing your knight on c6 so that you can apply pressure on the center. }
6. O-O { White castles and is quick with development. } 6... Nc6
{ You develop the knight as usual. } 7. Ne5
{ White places the knight in the center.  The idea from White is that after  7...Nxe5?  8.dxe5  Qxd1  9.Rxd1  Nd5  White can trade off your central knight with  10.Nc3  when after  10...Nxc3  11.bxc3  White has a monster bishop on g2, which is pinning the b7-pawn, and it's challenging for you to develop your light-squared bishop. }
7... Bd7 { You develop the bishop and support your knight. } 8. Na3
{ White develops the knight and is ready to regain the c4-pawn. } 8... cxd4
{ You capture in the center. } 9. Naxc4 { White wins back your c4-pawn. } 9...
Be7 { You develop the bishop and get ready to castle. } 10. Qb3
{ The typical move in this position that White tries to bring you in trouble. }
10... Qc7
{ You use the aggressive approach, defending the pawn and attacking the knight in the center. }
11. Bf4 Nd5
{ The same move as in the other line directly targeting the bishop.  @@StartFEN@@r3k2r/ppqbbppp/2n1pn2/4N3/2Np1B2/1Q4P1/PP2PPBP/R4RK1 b kq - 4 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Nh5  is much more common, and it gives White an extra option of playing  12.Bxc6  Bxc6  13.Nxc6  Qxc6  14.Be5   This is not necessarily problematic @@StartFEN@@r3k2r/ppqbbppp/2n1pn2/4N3/2Np1B2/1Q4P1/PP2PPBP/R4RK1 b kq - 4 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Nd5  also gives White an extra option of playing  12.Bxd5  exd5  When both options are about equally good, I like to pick one that your opponent is likely less familiar with. }
12. Bxd5 { White can take down your knight and give up the powerful bishop. }
12... exd5 13. Nxf7
{ The position gets very tactical now as White attacks your queen. } 13... dxc4
{ You capture the knight and attack White's queen. } 14. Qxc4 Qc8
{ It's time to step back with the queen. } 15. Nxh8 Be6 16. Qd3 Bf5
{ White should allow a move repetition. A game between GM Kunin and GM Stern continued with  17.e4?  when after  17...Be6!  Black is much better. White's knight will not get safely out of the corner, and you can slowly start collecting the knight with ...Kf8, ...Kg8, ...Kxh8 }
17. Qc4 { White goes back and makes a significant mistake. } 17... Qe6
{ You block with the queen, and Black suddenly has a winning position as the knight in the corner will be lost. }
18. Qb5 g5
{ The crucial move to keep a winning position for Black. After kicking the bishop, it is safe to castle queenside and collect the knight.   18...O-O-O  is not safe yet since after  19.Rac1  Rxh8  20.Rxc6+  is devastating when  20...bxc6  is followed up with  21.Qb8+  and  20...Qxc6  would lose the queen because of  21.Rc1 }
19. Bd2 O-O-O
{ The knight is trapped.  After  20.Rac1  , you can capture the knight with  20...Rxh8  and the sacrifice with  21.Rxc6  bxc6  is not dangerous. }
