[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "13a) Catalan "]
[Black "Catalan Open Defense: 7.dxc5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3
{ The Catalan! An opening where White aims to create a powerful light-squared bishop.  This position can also be reached from the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.g3  Nf6  4.Nf3  move order }
4... dxc4 { You capture the pawn. } 5. Bg2 c5
{ As typical for the d4-openings. You want to play your c-pawn first before placing your knight on c6 so that you can apply pressure on the center. }
6. O-O { White castles and is quick with development. } 6... Nc6
{ You develop the knight as usual. } 7. dxc5 { White captures the pawn! } 7...
Qxd1
{ You trade the queen. When you recapture the pawn with  7...Bxc5  White will trade queens with  8.Qxd8+  and you have to make a concession either by retreating with  8...Nxd8  or by giving up your right to castle with  8...Kxd8 }
8. Rxd1 Bxc5
{ You recapture the pawn! At this point, you are a pawn up, but White can win the pawn back. }
9. Nbd2 { White develops and threatens to capture back the c4-pawn. } 9... Ng4
{ An aggressive move immediately going after the f2-pawn.  A much more popular move is  9...c3  , giving back the pawn and forcing White to concede with their pawn structure after  10.bxc3  . It's good to avoid the most played variation once you have a good alternative. }
10. e3
{ White blocks the bishop diagonal and wants to capture on c4 next. It's time to continue the energetic play. }
10... Bxe3 { You will get an exchange and a couple of pawns for the piece. }
11. fxe3 Nxe3 { White's rook can't escape to a safe square. } 12. Re1
{ The rook can't escape here because of the knight fork. } 12... Nc2
{ You fork the rooks! } 13. Rb1 Nxe1 { It's time to win an exchange back. } 14.
Nxe1 Na5
{ Only now that the other knight went back to e1, it's good to defend the pawn. }
15. Nc2 { White can try to reroute the knight to win the c4-pawn. } 15... O-O
{ You continue with your development. It's fine to give the pawn back when you can manage to castle and play ...e5 }
16. Ne3 e5 { You will make sure to activate your bishop. } 17. Nexc4 Nxc4 18.
Nxc4 Be6 { It's time to develop and attack. } 19. Nxe5 f6
{ A clever move! You first chase the knight back to f3 where it blocks White's light-squared bishop. After that, you can win the a2-pawn. }
20. Nf3
{ The only square for the knight is  20.Nd3  runs into a skewer with  20...Bf5 }
20... Bxa2 { You win a pawn! } 21. Ra1 Bd5
{ Your bishop nicely neutralizes White's bishop, and Black is comfortable in the endgame. }
