[Black "Jobava London 2.Nc3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Bf4
{ The Jobava London! White typically aims for attacking plans with Nb5-Nc7 early on. Now you still play ...c5 as usual. }
3... c5
{ The usual move! Notice here that White isn't ready yet for  4.Nb5?  since  4...Qa5+  forks the king and knight. White would have to retreat the knight when you get a strong initiative. }
4. e4 { White immediately break open the center. } 4... Nxe4
{ Capturing with the knight is safe and proposes a trade of knights. } 5. Nxe4
dxe4 6. dxc5 Qxd1+
{ You can trade queens to make sure White doesn't capture you.  6...Qa5+  doesn't win a pawn because after  7.c3  Qxc5  White will also fork you with  8.Qa4+  and win back the e4-pawn. }
7. Rxd1 Nc6 8. Bb5
{ The most common move for White, but this is not so dangerous. } 8... f6
{ You prepare for ...e5 and want to get a strong center. } 9. Ne2 e5 10. Be3
Be6 { Black has a more central pawns and a comfortable endgame. } *

