[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "14a) London and Jobava London"]
[Black "Jobava London 2.Nc3 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Bf4
{ The Jobava London! White typically aims for attacking plans with Nb5-Nc7 early on. Now you still play ...c5 as usual. }
3... c5
{ The usual move! Notice here that White isn't ready yet for  4.Nb5?  since  4...Qa5+  forks the king and knight. White would have to retreat the knight when you get a strong initiative. }
4. e3
{ The main move and now White is threatening Nb5-Nc7+.  It would be very bad now to immediately develop the knight as you usually do with  4...Nc6  since after  5.Nb5  you don't have a good way to stop the fork. }
4... Bg4
{ You change your strategy and play a move that likely surprises White. The idea is that you attack the queen and you want to force White to play f3 so that they no longer can develop there knight to the natural square.   With Black against the d4-openings, in the exceptions where you are not developing your knights first you are always playing ...Bb4 or ...Bg4!   The exceptions 1 and 2 were in the Queens Gambit Declined and 3 in the Jobava London.  Exception 1: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.cxd5  exd5  4.Nc3  Bb4  Exception 2: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nf3  Nf6  4.cxd5  exd5  5.Nc3  Bb4   Exception 3: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p4/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq d6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nc3  Nf6  3.Bf4  c5  4.e3  Bg4 }
5. f3
{ White attacks your bishop, but this also takes away the natural square for the knight. }
5... Bd7
{ When you drop back you have to control the b5-square to be able to capture the knight when White goes there. }
6. Nb5 { This move is no challenging anymore. } 6... Bxb5
{ You take down the knight. } 7. Bxb5+ Nc6
{ After developing the knight you immediately threaten ...Qa5+ to fork the king and bishop. }
8. c3 { White prevents the fork. } 8... e6
{ You continue your development as usual. } 9. Ne2 Be7
{ You develop the bishop. In the regular London variation you will opt for ...Bd6 to neutralize White's London bishop but not in this case. This is because you would like to use your queen to go ...Qb6 and put pressure on the light-squared bishop and b2-pawn.  Also you can neutralize the London bishop by going for ...Nh5 and capturing the bishop. After  10.Bd3  it would be safe for you to go for  10...Nh5  11.Bg3  Nxg3  12.hxg3  when you can reply with  12...h6  and aim for a ...Qb6 and a queenside castle. Black already be doing clearly better there. In the regular London position which you will learn move about later activating White's rook on h-file could be dangerous, but in the position where White couldn't develop the knight to f3 they don't have a good attack anymore. }
10. O-O Qb6
{ You can put pressure on the light-squared bishop and also aim for ...Nh5 to target the dark-squared bishop. Black is doing very well here. }
