5. f3
{ White attacks your bishop, but this also takes away the natural square for the knight. }
5... Bd7
{ When you drop back you have to control the b5-square to be able to capture the knight when White goes there. }
6. dxc5 Qa5
{ I recommend this move to make sure you can win the pawn back later.   6...Nc6!?  also looked like an interesting option but after  6...Nc6  7.Nxd5  e5  8.Bg5  Qa5+  9.Nc3  Bxc5  10.a3  Be7  you have some compensation for the pawn but it feels like it's not enough. }
7. Qd2 Nc6
{ You can develop your knight! There is no rush to capture the pawn back immediately. }
8. Rd1 { Another move White could try. } 8... e5
{ You can attack the bishop and gain a tempo again. } 9. Bg5 Qxc5
{ You capture the pawn back with the queen.  Don't go for  9...O-O-O?  since White can capture with  10.Nd5 }
10. Bxf6 gxf6 11. Nxd5
{ At this piont White is a pawn up! You will get counterplay on the d-file. }
11... O-O-O { You threaten ...Be6 } 12. Qc3
{ White wants to trade the queens and aim to be a pawn up. } 12... Be6
{ You only agree to a trade on your terms. When White captures you now your bishop would get activated. }
