1. d4 d5 2. Bf4
{ The London opening! White typically develops the pieces in a similar setup. They aim to get the dark-squared bishop out of the pawn chain and solidly develop all the other pieces. }
2... Nf6 { As usual, you develop the knights first. } 3. e3 c5
{ You follow the general strategy in d4-variations, before you develop the other knight, you want to advance your c-pawn. }
4. dxc5 Nc6
{ You develop your knight and get ready to take control of the center with ...e5 next. }
5. Bb5
{ White creates a pin on your knight to prevent ...e5   5.Nf3  is not a challenging move since after  5...e6  , you win back the c5-pawn and have a strong center. }
5... Qa5+ { You fork the king and the bishop. } 6. Nc3 a6
{ You kick away the bishop and want to make sure that you regain the c5-pawn. }
7. Bxc6+ bxc6 { White should trade if they want to hold on to the c5-pawn. } 8.
Qd4 { The most popular move defending the pawn. } 8... e6
{ You threaten to win back the pawn with ...Bxc5! } 9. Bd6
{ White could try to defend the pawn this way. } 9... Bxd6
{ After the trade, White's pawn on d6 will be weak. } 10. cxd6 Rb8
{ You are targeting the b2-pawn. Black has a strong center and will eventually win back the pawn on d6. }
