{ You kick away the bishop and want to make sure that you regain the c5-pawn. }
7. Bxc6+ bxc6 { White should trade if they want to hold on to the c5-pawn. } 8.
Nf3 Ne4
{ You add an attacker to White's pinned knight. And this plan also prepares to prevent White from attacking with Ne5 or Nd4 later on.   8...e6?  will now allow White to unpin the knight with  9.O-O  and after  9...Bxc5  10.Nd4  White can start putting pressure on the c6-pawn.  In the @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/4pppp/p1p2n2/q1Pp4/5B2/2N1P3/PPP2PPP/R2QK1NR w KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Qd4  variation  8...Ne4?  wouldn't have worked because after  9.b4  White unpins the knight, and after  9...Qa3  10.Nxe4  dxe4  , your pawn structure is destroyed. White can even play  11.Qxe4  because after  11...Qc3+  12.Ke2  Qxa1?  13.Qxc6+  is a deadly strike, and you will get mated. }
9. Qd4
{ White keeps the extra pawn, but you can now destroy their pawn structure. }
9... Nxc3 10. Qxc3 { White should go for a trade of queens. } 10... Qxc3+ 11.
bxc3 f6
{ You want to build a strong center with ...e5! And you also stop White's Ne5 and Nd4 moves avoiding that White can put pressure on your c6-pawn.   12.Nd4  runs into  12...e5  forking the knight and bishop }
12. Bc7 { The only move for White to hold on to the c5-pawn. } 12... e5
{ You get the strong center and threaten ...Bxc5! Your c6-pawn will stay safe now, and White no longer has a way to attack it. }
13. Bb6 g5
{ You start gaining more space on the queenside. You are a pawn down, but White has the ugly triple pawn, so it's basically balanced. You can go for ...h5 and play ...Be7, ...Kf7! After that, you can aim to trade the dark-squared bishops and try to target pawns on the queenside.   ...Kf7 can help activate the rook h8! When you play ...Bd8 the rook defends the bishop. These are the positions where you should not memorize other moves or continue with the move trainer, because many different moves will be just as good! }
