[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4
{ The London opening! White typically develops the pieces in a similar setup. They aim to get the dark-squared bishop out of the pawn chain and solidly develop all the other pieces. }
2... Nf6 { As usual, you develop the knights first. } 3. e3 c5
{ You follow the general strategy in d4-variations, before you develop the other knight, you want to advance your c-pawn. }
4. c3 Nc6 { You develop the other knight! } 5. Nd2 e6
{ Your usual setup. You are ready to neutralize White's London bishop on the next move with ...Bd6 }
6. Ngf3 { This position can come from multiple move orders. } 6... Bd6
{ You develop the bishop to neutralize the London bishop. A trade would be beneficial for you. Because White has the pawn setup with c3, d4, and e3, your bishop doesn't have any other good options. }
7. Bg3
{ A cunning move from White. White only wants to trade the bishop on their terms, and the h-file will open up for the rook after a trade. I don't recommend trading the bishops.   At this point, you have already neutralized the influence of White's dark-squared bishop so you don't need to capture it. }
7... O-O 8. Bb5
{ This move is much less common than the main move  8.Bd3  , but it's quite tricky if you are unprepared for it. }
8... Be7
{ You drop the bishop back now, and this move looks odd. The idea is that you want to play ...Qb6 to start putting pressure on White's bishop. That's why dropping your bishop back is useful to free your queen from the task of defending it.  Also, you didn't want to solve it by going for  8...Bxg3  either because after  9.hxg3  , White's rook gets activated on the h-file. }
9. Bd3
{ The main idea for White is to bring the bishop back now and claim that they have tricked your bishop away from d6, so now they can keep the London bishop. At this point, it may be better for White to try another move, but in that case, they should admit that the strategy was the Bb5 idea was unsuccessful. }
9... Nh5
{ This is a cold shower for White's plans. You start attacking the London bishop, and it's important that you only want to capture it when White is castled so that you don't activate the rook. }
10. Ne5
{ White attacks your knight, but there is no rush to capture the bishop. You can defend your knight. }
10... g6
{ You protect your knight and only take the bishop when White is castled. } 11.
f4 { The most common move! Black is already doing very well. } 11... Qb6
{ You increase the pressure on the b2-pawn. A typical plan to improve your pieces is ...Bd6 and ...Ne7 protecting the g6-pawn, after which you can chase White's knight in the center away with ...f6. }
