2... Nf6 { As usual, you develop the knights first. } 3. e3 c5
{ You follow the general strategy in d4-variations, before you develop the other knight, you want to advance your c-pawn. }
4. c3 Nc6 { You develop the other knight! } 5. Nd2 e6
{ Your usual setup. You are ready to neutralize White's London bishop on the next move with ...Bd6 }
6. Ngf3 { This position can come from multiple move orders. } 6... Bd6
{ You develop the bishop to neutralize the London bishop. A trade would be beneficial for you. Because White has the pawn setup with c3, d4, and e3, your bishop doesn't have any other good options. }
7. Bg3
{ A cunning move from White. White only wants to trade the bishop on their terms, and the h-file will open up for the rook after a trade. I don't recommend trading the bishops.   At this point, you have already neutralized the influence of White's dark-squared bishop so you don't need to capture it. }
7... O-O { You follow the golden rules and castle. } 8. Bd3
{ White develops the light-squared bishop. } 8... a5
{ A waiting move that gains space on the queenside. You want to wait till White castles before you play ...b6  The most common move is  8...b6  , but now the problem is that after  9.e4  , you can't use the rule that when pawns are facing in the center, you capture because after  9...dxe4  10.Nxe4  Here the problem of White not being castled yet becomes clear.  10...Bxg3  11.hxg3  is too dangerous with White's rook still on the h-file but also @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/p4ppp/1pnbpn2/2p5/3PN3/2PB1NB1/PP3PPP/R2QK2R b KQ - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Nxe4  is problematic and after  11.Bxe4  White has a powerful pin on your knight.  The second most common move is @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp3ppp/2nbpn2/2pp4/3P4/2PBPNB1/PP1N1PPP/R2QK2R b KQ - 5 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Qe7  preparing ...e5, but White can stop the plans with  9.Ne5  and after  9...Nd7  challenging the knight, I don't like that White has a variation where they can force a draw but also can keep the game going. }
9. Ne5 { White often replies by placing the knight in the center. } 9... c4
{ In line with your previous move, you keep gaining more space and will prepare to go for ...b5-b4 later. You want to kick the knight in the center with  9...Qc7  , but first, you solve a minor issue that after  10.Nxc6  at this point  10...bxc6  opening the b-file is not possible because  11.dxc5  loses the c5-pawn, and this forces you to play  11...Bxg3  12.hxg3  , which opens up the h-file for White's rook. }
10. Bc2 Qc7 { You increase the pressure on the knight in the center. } 11. f4
{ White supports the knight! } 11... b5
{ You are ready now to advance on the queenside! } 12. O-O Ne7
{ You move the knight back, getting ready to reroute it to f5!  If you would immediately play  12...b4  White can go for  13.Bh4  Ne8  14.Nxc6  trading the knight that in other variations can get into trouble  14...Qxc6  and now White can get in  15.e4 }
13. Bh4 Ne8
{ You get the knight back because the trade could damage your pawn structure.  It's not powerful now for White to play  14.e4  as after  14...f6  , their knight can't retreat without losing the f4-pawn. }
14. Rf3 { White can also include the rook in the attack. } 14... f6
{ You can immediately start targeting the knight! } 15. Bxh7+
{ White needs to go all in for the attack because after  15.Ng4?  b4  there is no attack, and you slowly start destroying White's position. }
15... Kxh7 16. Rh3 Kg8 { You move out of any discovered attacks. } 17. Qh5 fxe5
{ Capturing the knight with  17...Bxe5  would also be a sound alternative. }
18. Bxe7 { White should trade to open the h-file. } 18... Qxe7
{ You capture back with the queen. After  19.Qh7+  Kf7  20.Qh5+  , you have a pleasant choice as after  20...g6  21.Qh7+  Ng7  , you can keep the game going with a fighting position that is slightly better for Black. Also,  20...Kg8  would have already repeated the position.  The most precise way to counter @@StartFEN@@r1b1nrk1/4q1p1/3bp3/pp1pp2Q/2pP1P2/2P1P2R/PP1N2PP/R5K1 w - - 0 19@@EndFEN@@  19.fxe5  is with  19...Nf6  and your king is safe. You will be more than happy to give the piece back for a safe position as you are up two pieces. }
