{ A waiting move that gains space on the queenside. You want to wait till White castles before you play ...b6  The most common move is  8...b6  , but now the problem is that after  9.e4  , you can't use the rule that when pawns are facing in the center, you capture because after  9...dxe4  10.Nxe4  Here the problem of White not being castled yet becomes clear.  10...Bxg3  11.hxg3  is too dangerous with White's rook still on the h-file but also @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/p4ppp/1pnbpn2/2p5/3PN3/2PB1NB1/PP3PPP/R2QK2R b KQ - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Nxe4  is problematic and after  11.Bxe4  White has a powerful pin on your knight.  The second most common move is @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp3ppp/2nbpn2/2pp4/3P4/2PBPNB1/PP1N1PPP/R2QK2R b KQ - 5 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Qe7  preparing ...e5, but White can stop the plans with  9.Ne5  and after  9...Nd7  challenging the knight, I don't like that White has a variation where they can force a draw but also can keep the game going. }
9. a4
{ So White says alright, you play a cunning waiting move; I will do the same and see what you will do. Now you will go for a variation that you previously couldn't go for where having the a4 and ...a5 inclusion benefits you. }
9... Qe7 { So you prepare for ...e5! } 10. Ne5
{ White places the knight in the center to stop that!  10.Bb5  is not dangerous since you can chase it away with  10...Na7  . }
10... g6
{ You defend the h5-square and prepare for plans with ...Nh5 to take down the bishop, which also makes White's knight in the center more vulnerable. Also, this move has a defensive function to block the light-squared bishop. Without this a4 and ...a5 inclusion, this wouldn't work well because after @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp3ppp/2nbpn2/2pp4/3P4/2PBPNB1/PP1N1PPP/R2QK2R b KQ - 5 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Qe7  9.Ne5  g6  10.O-O  Nh5  11.Nxc6  bxc6  12.Bxd6  Qxd6  13.Qa4  which puts pressure on both your c6 and c5 pawns because Qa3 is a threat to pin the c5-pawn.  It's quite a difference after @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp3ppp/2nbpn2/2pp4/3P4/2PBPNB1/PP1N1PPP/R2QK2R b KQ - 5 8@@EndFEN@@  8...a5  9.a4  Qe7  10.Ne5  g6  11.O-O  Nh5  12.Nxc6  bxc6  13.Bxd6  Qxd6  since the a4-square is not even available for the queen. }
11. O-O
{ After  11.Bh4  , you can capture the pawn with  11...Nxe5  12.dxe5  Bxe5   Next, you would like to unpin your knight, and different plans are possible for that, depending on how White plays. ...Qd8-...Qb6 with a counterattack against the b2-pawn and ...Nd7 is a good way to do that. }
11... Nh5 { You go after the dark-squared bishop. } 12. Nxc6
{ White doesn't want to trade the bishop for the knight, so they should exchange the knight and bishop. }
12... bxc6 13. Bxd6 Qxd6
{ This is the position where you are so happy with the inclusion of a4 and ...a5 because otherwise,  @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/p4p1p/2pqp1p1/2pp3n/3P4/2PBP3/PP1N1PPP/R2Q1RK1 w - - 0 13@@EndFEN@@  13.Qa4  would have been powerful, threatening the pin with Qa3! Black is doing well here, and you can play ...Ba6 to exchange the bishop since your bishop would otherwise be blocked by your pawns. }
