[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "14a) London and Jobava London"]
[Black "London Mainline #15"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4
{ The London opening! White typically develops the pieces in a similar setup. They aim to get the dark-squared bishop out of the pawn chain and solidly develop all the other pieces. }
2... Nf6 { As usual, you develop the knights first. } 3. e3 c5
{ You follow the general strategy in d4-variations, before you develop the other knight, you want to advance your c-pawn. }
4. c3 Nc6 { You develop the other knight! } 5. Nd2 e6
{ Your usual setup. You are ready to neutralize White's London bishop on the next move with ...Bd6 }
6. Ngf3 { This position can come from multiple move orders. } 6... Bd6
{ You develop the bishop to neutralize the London bishop. A trade would be beneficial for you. Because White has the pawn setup with c3, d4, and e3, your bishop doesn't have any other good options. }
7. Bg3
{ A cunning move from White. White only wants to trade the bishop on their terms, and the h-file will open up for the rook after a trade. I don't recommend trading the bishops.   At this point, you have already neutralized the influence of White's dark-squared bishop so you don't need to capture it. }
7... O-O { You follow the golden rules and castle. } 8. Bd3
{ White develops the light-squared bishop. } 8... a5
{ A waiting move that gains space on the queenside. You want to wait till White castles before you play ...b6  The most common move is  8...b6  , but now the problem is that after  9.e4  , you can't use the rule that when pawns are facing in the center, you capture because after  9...dxe4  10.Nxe4  Here the problem of White not being castled yet becomes clear.  10...Bxg3  11.hxg3  is too dangerous with White's rook still on the h-file but also @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/p4ppp/1pnbpn2/2p5/3PN3/2PB1NB1/PP3PPP/R2QK2R b KQ - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Nxe4  is problematic and after  11.Bxe4  White has a powerful pin on your knight.  The second most common move is @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp3ppp/2nbpn2/2pp4/3P4/2PBPNB1/PP1N1PPP/R2QK2R b KQ - 5 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Qe7  preparing ...e5, but White can stop the plans with  9.Ne5  and after  9...Nd7  challenging the knight, I don't like that White has a variation where they can force a draw but also can keep the game going. }
9. Qe2
{ White could also try not to commit to castling since it allows ...b6 and not to commit to Ne5 since it allows ...c4 and ...Qc7 }
9... Qe7 { You prepare for ...e5 } 10. Ne5 c4
{ You first attack the bishop and want to play ...Qc7 next.  The direct  10...Qc7  doesn't work well because after  11.Nxc6  bxc6  12.dxc5  wins the c5-pawn. Where  11...Qxc6  would make the  12.e4  break stronger for White.  The same plan with @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/1p2qppp/2nbpn2/p1ppN3/3P4/2PBP1B1/PP1NQPPP/R3K2R b KQ - 3 10@@EndFEN@@  10...g6  doesn't work well here because after  11.Bh4  Nxe5  12.dxe5  Bxe5  13.f4  Bd6  14.e4  is crushing since after  14...Bxf4  White has  15.e5  to win your pinned knight.  The big difference in the @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/1p3ppp/2nbpn2/p1pp4/3P4/2PBPNB1/PP1N1PPP/R2QK2R w KQ a6 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.a4  Qe7  variation is that after  10.Ne5  g6  11.Bh4  Nxe5  12.dxe5  Bxe5  13.f4  Bd6  14.e4  is countered with  14...Bxf4  and after  15.e5?  you take it  15...Bxe5 }
11. Bc2 Qc7 { It's time to harass the knight in the center. } 12. f4
{ White supports the knight.  Note that when White plays  12.e4  here, you should capture the knight with  12...Nxe5  to win a pawn and not trade the pawns in the center. Also, in this position, you didn't capture the pawn in the center directly because you won it with a cross pin. Whenever you are in a position that's no longer in the trainable lines, consider the rule to trade pawns when they face the center as a leading guideline but still calculate the continuations. }
12... b5
{ You continue your advance on the queenside and want to damage White's position. There is a beautiful way here to defend. }
13. e4 { White can play the pawn in the center! } 13... dxe4
{ It's fine to capture as usual. } 14. Nxe4 Nd5
{ Your knight is on an outpost here and can apply pressure on the c3-pawn. }
15. a4 { White can go for this and aim to win the c4-pawn. } 15... b4 16. Nxd6
{ White should first capture your bishop because  16.Nxc4?  allows  16...Bxf4 }
16... Qxd6 17. Nxc4 Qd7
{ Black is ready for ...Ba6 to pin White's knight while Black's knight puts pressure on the c3-pawn. White's dark-squared bishop has become a bad bishop blocked by the f4-pawn. Black has sufficient compensation for the pawn. }
