[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "15a) English Reti and Sidelines"]
[Black "English: Neo-Catalan 4.b3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 { The English opening. } 1... e6
{ Your opening strategy against @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  can be effectively utilized against  1.c4  and  1.Nf3  .  With Black, you adopt the same setup, and if White eventually plays d4, you can transpose back to the familiar variation. If White refrains from playing d4, the arising variations are generally not threatening, as White won't have any central pawns.  Moving your e-pawn to support ...d5 on the next move is crucial. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/2P5/8/PP1PPPPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq c3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...d5?  does not achieve the same setup and after  2.cxd5  Qxd5  3.Nc3  , White gains a tempo on your queen. }
2. Nf3 d5
{ You place your pawn in the center and go for the familiar Semi-Tarrasch setup }
3. g3
{ If White tries a setup with  3.b3  , you can play  3...d4  and after  4.Bb2  c5  makes the bishop look miserable on b2. }
3... Nf6
{ You keep applying the concepts as if you played against a d4 opening. So you develop the knight first. }
4. b3
{ This is not a critical try as you can block White's dark-squared bishop on b2. }
4... d4 { Immediately shutting down White's dark-squared bishop. } 5. Bg2 c5
{ You push your c-pawn, which you usually do in all the d4-openings.  You can also argue here that since your opponent doesn't have the pawn on d4, you can directly develop with  5...Nc6  which also would be an excellent option. }
6. O-O Nc6 { You develop the knight as usual. } 7. e3
{ White will try to fight back in the center. } 7... e5
{ You support your center and aim to take back with the e-pawn. Taking back with the c-pawn is also possible, but it is a more complex way to handle the position, as now you keep a space advantage in a symmetric position. As a general rule, with a space advantage, you like to avoid trading minor pieces, so the White's position stays cramped when its pieces take away square for either other. }
8. exd4 exd4 9. Re1+
{ White gives a check!   9.d3  is also as popular as  9.Re1  , and you reply with the same ideas. }
9... Be7 10. d3 O-O 11. Bg5 h6 { You force the bishop to capture your knight. }
12. Bxf6 Bxf6
{ You can continue with ...Qc7, ...Bf5, and you would like to avoid the trade of minor pieces, so when White plays Nd2-Ne4 ...Be7 back is a strong reply. White only managed to trade one pair of minor pieces, so you still have a space advantage. }
