{ White opts for a setup that looks like a Catalan. Therefore, you can treat it similarly.  This position could also be reached from the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppp1ppp/4p3/8/2P5/8/PP1PPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.g3  d5  3.Bg2  Nf3  4.Nf6  move order. }
4... dxc4 { You capture the pawn, like you do against the Catalan. } 5. Qa4+
Bd7
{ As usual, you want to play ...Nc6 eventually.  The direct  5...Nc6  runs into some trouble after  6.Ne5  when White targets your pinned knight three times. }
6. Qxc4 c5
{ As usual, before playing. ...Nc6, you push the pawn forward to put pressure on the center. }
7. Ne5
{ The main move! White opens the diagonal for the light-squared bishop and targets the b7-pawn. }
7... Qc8
{ You support the b7-pawn.  Playing  7...Nc6?  at this point could lead to doubled pawns on the c-file after  8.Nxc6  Bxc6  9.Bxc6  bxc6  .   Therefore, it's better to delay this move until your queen also provides control over the c6-square. @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/pp1b1ppp/4pn2/2p1N3/2Q5/6P1/PP1PPPBP/RNB1K2R b KQkq - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Qc7?  leaves the queen unprotected which means your c5-pawn is pinned so after  8.d4  you won't be able to capture with  8...cxd4?  since it drops the queen  9.Qxc7 }
8. Nxd7
{ White takes your bishop. In case White opts for  8.Qd3  , you can continue your development with  8...Nc6  .  Should White take your bishop with  9.Nxd7  , it would be beneficial to avoid a queen trade and play  9...Nxd7  .  From here, you can also proceed with ...Be7 and ...O-O. }
8... Qxd7
{ You take back with the queen to keep the option open to develop the knight to c6. }
9. O-O Nc6
{ You progress with your knight development. This move makes it challenging for White to establish a pawn in the center and shuts off the diagonal for White's powerful light-squared bishop.  You're now set to proceed with ...Be7 and castle kingside. After that, it's wise to play ...Rc88 and ...b6* to remove potential targets of White's bishop on the long diagonal. The same board setup could have also arisen via the moves:  8.O-O  Nc6  9.Nxd7  Qxd7  . }
10. Nc3 Rc8
{ Getting the rook of the bishop's diagonal. In the Catalan, you typically don't have to rush with castling as the pressure only comes from the bishop's diagonal. }
11. Rd1 Be7 12. b3 O-O 13. Bb2 Rfd8
{ And Black had no problem in the match Giri-Abasov and the World Cup game finished in a draw. }
