1. Nf3 { The Reti opening. } 1... d5
{ You have the opportunity to set your pawn in the middle of the board quickly. Following this, you can proceed with the usual strategy of developing your knights. However, prioritize playing ...c5 before bringing out your queenside knight. You only have to play ...e6 to solidify your pawn center in case White opts to play c4. }
2. g3
{ White aims to fianchetto the bishop. The move order with  2.b3  is covered in the sidelines chapter. }
2... Nf6 { You develop your knight. } 3. Bg2 { White fianchettos the bishop. }
3... c5
{ You again play like in a d4-opening.   3...Nc6?  would not apply much pressure on the center when White plays  4.d4 }
4. O-O Nc6
{ You develop the knight and aim to take control of the center with ...e5 } 5.
d4
{ White places the pawn in the center. 5.c4 d4 transposes to variations covered in the English. }
5... e6 6. b3
{ Most of the times it just goes 6.c4 dxc4 and you are back in your Catalan. }
6... Be7 { You keep developing! } 7. dxc5 Bxc5 8. Bb2 O-O 9. c4
{ White challenges your center! This position is still a little bit unpleasant, and it's important to be precise. I suggest capturing the pawn and preparing to activate the light-squared bishop with ...Qe7 and ...e5!  After  9...d4  10.a3  a5  11.b4  axb4  12.axb4  Rxa1  13.Bxa1  Bxb4  14.Nxd4  , the computer gives 0.00, but it feels like White's light-squared bishop is still a bit stronger than Black's light-squared bishop, and I would say it's practically speaking a bit better for White.  It's the same after @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp3ppp/2n1pn2/2bp4/2P5/1P3NP1/PB2PPBP/RN1Q1RK1 b - c3 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Qe7  10.exd5  Nxd5  When White still has some pressure due to the more powerful light-squared bishop.  White played @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp3ppp/2n1pn2/2bp4/8/1P3NP1/PBP1PPBP/RN1Q1RK1 w - - 2 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Nbd2  more often, but this move doesn't pose any danger  9...Qe7  prepares to include the rook with ...Rd8 }
9... dxc4 10. Qc2
{ White creates a pin on the c4-pawn.  Also  10.Qc1  is played sometimes, but this will result in the same position after  10...Qe7  11.Qxc4  e5 }
10... Qe7 11. Qxc4 e5
{ Once you get in ...e5 White's light-squared bishop is not dominating your bishop anymore! You have a strong grip on the center and a good position. }
