[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "15a) English Reti and Sidelines"]
[Black "Polish Opening: 1.b4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. b4
{ It's time to tackle the sidelines. These are the variations that you won't face that often, but you don't want to have a pleasant surprise when you face one of them. Generally, for all sidelines, you can go for your familiar Semi-Tarrasch setup or be even more aggressive and grab the full center with ...d5 and ...e5.  The Semi-Tarrasch is a robust option where you get a firm grip on the center and develop the knights quickly. Tackling the sidelines with ...e5 could be tricky because of the other variations learned in this repertoire. Let's start with the Solevsky opening  1.b4  and the Grob's attack  1.g4 }
1... d5 { As usual against all sidelines. } 2. Bb2 Nf6 3. e3 e5
{ The same strategy. You want to get rid of this b4-pawn, which prevents your knight from going to the natural square! Therefore, you offer to trade this pawn for the central pawn.  If you would have played  3...e6  , White could opt for  4.b5  , and even though the position is also slightly better for Black, the disadvantage here is that you can't develop your knight to the natural square with ...Nc6 }
4. Bxe5
{ White should accept the trade. If White plays  4.b5  after  4...Bd6  , you have established a strong pawncenter }
4... Bxb4 { You get rid of the b4-pawn! } 5. Nf3 O-O
{ You continue with castling. I don't recommend immediately gaining the tempo on the bishop with  5...Nc6  6.Bb2  because your knight is again a bit misplaced. }
6. Be2 c5 { You move your c-pawn forward before you develop the knight! } 7.
O-O Nc6 { You gain that tempo on the bishop. } 8. Bb2 Re8
{ You bring the rook to the center! Black has an excellent position.  You can get play ...Ba5 getting your dark-squared bishop to a safer square. If White goes for  9.d4  , then  9...c4  is strong, as White's dark-squared bishop would be blocked by its pawn. }
*

