{ It's time to tackle the sidelines. These are the variations that you won't face that often, but you don't want to have a pleasant surprise when you face one of them. Generally, for all sidelines, you can go for your familiar Semi-Tarrasch setup or be even more aggressive and grab the full center with ...d5 and ...e5.  The Semi-Tarrasch is a robust option where you get a firm grip on the center and develop the knights quickly. Tackling the sidelines with ...e5 could be tricky because of the other variations learned in this repertoire. Let's start with the Solevsky opening  1.b4  and the Grob's attack  1.g4 }
1... d5 { As usual against all sidelines. } 2. Bb2 Nf6 3. Nf3 e5
{ You want to get rid of this b4-pawn, which prevents your knight from going to the natural square! Therefore, you offer to trade this pawn for the central pawn.  If you would have played  3...e6  , White could opt for  4.b5  , and even though the position is also slightly better for Black, the disadvantage here is that you can't develop your knight to the natural square with ...Nc6 }
4. Nxe5 Bxb4 5. e3 O-O 6. Be2 Re8
{ You start putting pressure on the knight!  At this point, the downside of  6...c5  is that  7.Nd3  is annoying; it targets both the bishop and the c5-pawn.  As you know, you also don't want to play @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp2ppp/5n2/3pN3/1b6/4P3/PBPPBPPP/RN1QK2R b KQ - 2 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Nc6?  before moving the c-pawn forward. }
7. O-O Bd6 { You put more pressure on the knight and prepare to play ...c5! }
8. d4 c5 { You are ready now to play ... c5 next move! } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "15a) English Reti and Sidelines"]
[Black "Grob Opening: 1.g4 #1 "]
[Result "*"]

1. g4 d5 { As usual against the sidelines! } 2. Bg2 e5
{ You occupy the full center!   2...Bxg4  is also possible but is what White hopes for as after  3.c4  e6  , they could create an attack with  4.Qb3 }
3. d4 { Going for a direct break in the center would be best for White. } 3...
exd4 { You trade the pawns as usual! } 4. Qxd4 Be6
{ You defend the central pawn and develop the bishop! } 5. Nc3 Nc6
{ You develop the knight and gain a tempo on the queen. } 6. Qa4 Nf6
{ You develop the knight as usual to the natural square. } 7. g5
{ White kicks the knight! } 7... Nd7
{ You move back to unpin your other knight. } 8. Nxd5
{ White captures the pawn!   8.Bxd5  would already lose the piece for White after  8...Bxd5  9.Nxd5  Nc5  10.Qc4  b5  White has no way to keep defending the knight in the center. }
8... Nc5 { You attack the queen and give a discovered attack on the knight. }
9. Qc4 { White's only move is to defend the knight and run into a pin. } 9...
Qd7
{ You prepare to castle queenside and add another attacker to the pinned knight. }
10. Bf4 { White develops the bishop and prepares to castle queenside! } 10...
Nb4
{ You attack the pinned knight!  Your knight is defended with the discovered attack tactic since after  11.Qxb4  , you go for  11...Nd3+ }
11. e4 { White adds a defender. } 11... c6
{ You add an attacker to the pinned knight. } 12. Qxb4
{ White's only defense is to give up on the queen. } 12... Nd3+
{ Discovered check! } 13. cxd3 Bxb4+ 14. Nxb4
{ White has three pieces for the queen, which is quite a lot! However, you will still be able to win the d3-pawn and keep the initiative. }
14... a5 15. Nc2 Qxd3
{ You win the pawn and harass the knight. Also, your rook can join the attack with ...Rd8, and it will be challenging for White to survive this. }
*

