1. g4 d5 { As usual against the sidelines! } 2. Bg2 e5
{ You occupy the full center!   2...Bxg4  is also possible but is what White hopes for as after  3.c4  e6  , they could create an attack with  4.Qb3 }
3. c4 { White challenges the center } 3... dxc4
{ You capture the pawn immediately! } 4. Qa4+
{ The most played move by White! } 4... Bd7
{ You block with the bishop, leaving the c6-square open for the knight.   4...c6  would have been an excellent move as it blocks the light-squared bishop but is not in line with the opening strategy always to develop the knight to the natural squares. }
5. Qxc4 Nc6 { You get the knight to the natural square. } 6. Nc3
{ White develops the knight! } 6... h5
{ You want to get rid of the g4-pawn and free the natural square for the knight! }
7. gxh5 Rxh5
{ You recapture the pawn!  At this point, you also have a couple of good alternatives like  7...Qg5  or the immediate  7...Nf6 }
8. Nf3 Nf6
{ You develop your knight to the natural square! White is in a difficult situation. }
9. d3
{ White played this move in all of the Club Player games, but it overlooked a crucial tactic!  Also,  9.O-O  would be bad for White when you can start attacking with  9...Bd6 }
9... Na5 { You trapped the queen. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "15a) English Reti and Sidelines"]
[Black "Grob Opening: 1.g4 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. g4 d5 { As usual against the sidelines! } 2. Bg2 e5
{ You occupy the full center!   2...Bxg4  is also possible but is what White hopes for as after  3.c4  e6  , they could create an attack with  4.Qb3 }
3. c4 { White challenges the center } 3... dxc4
{ You capture the pawn immediately! } 4. Qa4+
{ The most played move by White! } 4... Bd7
{ You block with the bishop, leaving the c6-square open for the knight.   4...c6  would have been an excellent move as it blocks the light-squared bishop but is not in line with the opening strategy always to develop the knight to the natural squares. }
5. Qxc4 Nc6 { You get the knight to the natural square. } 6. Nc3
{ White develops the knight! } 6... h5
{ You want to get rid of the g4-pawn and free the natural square for the knight! }
7. Bd5 { The best reply for White! } 7... Qe7
{ You defend and prepare to castle queenside. } 8. g5
{ White stops the knight from coming to f6 for now! } 8... O-O-O
{ You get your king to safety and rook active. } 9. Nf3
{ White now supports the g5-pawn and keeps restricting your knight! } 9... Nd4
{ It's time to get rid of this knight! Also, you threaten ...Nc2+, so White is forced to capture your knight. }
10. Nxd4 exd4 11. Qxd4
{ The queen captures but will run into a pin on the d-file! } 11... Bc6
{ You start pinning the bishop! } 12. Qc4
{ White should get out of the pin quickly. } 12... Rxd5
{ A beautiful move since after the knight recaptures, you still have another pin on the rook. }
13. Nxd5 Qxg5
{ You get rid of the annoying g5-pawn and attack the pinned knight one more time! }
14. e4 Nf6
{ And finally, the knight comes out to f6 with devastating power! You want to get rid of White's knight in the center. }
15. Nxf6 Qxf6
{ You want to play ...Qf3 where you are close to White's king and harass the rook in the corner. After that, your bishops can join the attack with brutal force.  White can't prevent your queen from going there even with  16.Ke2  because after  16...Qg6  17.d3  Qg4+  White has to drop the king back and allow  18.Ke1  Qf3 }
