[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "15a) English Reti and Sidelines"]
[Black "Hungarian Opening: 1.g3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. g3 { The Hungarian opening. } 1... d5
{ Important since after  1...e5  2.c4  , you are in unfamiliar territory in the English. }
2. Bg2
{ White may play different moves, but they all transpose into lines you have already studied. }
2... e5
{ If White allows you to seize control of the center with your pawns, you should take the opportunity. Your next step is to bring out the knights to their usual squares and ensure the safety of your king by castling. Due to your control of the center, White can't develop their knights to the natural squares yet because you can start attacking them.  Also  2...Nf6  is a very good option, and it will transpose either to variation in the Catalan/ English/Reti openings. }
3. d3 { The most common move, but this likely transposes to the Reti opening. }
3... Nf6 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. O-O Bc5
{ You develop your bishop to the active square as usual. } 6. Nbd2
{ White's most common move is not strong anymore. } 6... e4
{ Since White's knight blocked the d-file, it is powerful to start hunting White's knight immediately.   6...O-O  is also a strong alternative. }
7. dxe4 dxe4 8. Ng5 e3 { Advancing the pawn is a tactic that wins material. }
9. Nde4
{ White would lose the knight after  9.fxe3  when  9...Bxe3+  forks the king and knight. }
9... exf2+
{ You capture the pawn with a check. White is in an unpleasant situation! } 10.
Kh1
{ The best option for White is to sidestep and not run into a pin by capturing the pawn. }
10... Qxd1 11. Rxd1 Nxe4 12. Nxe4 Bb6
{ After all the trades, you are still a pawn up with a better pawn structure. White should be able to win back the f2-pawn eventually, but in that case, you still have a better pawn structure with Black. }
*

