{ Important since after  1...e5  2.c4  , you are in unfamiliar territory in the English. }
2. Bg2
{ White may play different moves, but they all transpose into lines you have already studied. }
2... e5
{ If White allows you to seize control of the center with your pawns, you should take the opportunity. Your next step is to bring out the knights to their usual squares and ensure the safety of your king by castling. Due to your control of the center, White can't develop their knights to the natural squares yet because you can start attacking them.  Also  2...Nf6  is a very good option, and it will transpose either to variation in the Catalan/ English/Reti openings. }
3. d3 { The most common move, but this likely transposes to the Reti opening. }
3... Nf6 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. O-O Bc5
{ You develop your bishop to the active square as usual. } 6. Nxe5
{ White has a common tactic to sacrifice the knight first and then go for the fork after. }
6... Nxe5 7. d4 Bd6
{ Your bishop is stronger than the knight, so you should keep your bishop. } 8.
dxe5 Bxe5 9. c4 c6 { You can block the attack! } 10. cxd5 Nxd5
