1. d3 { The Mieses opening! } 1... d5
{ Responding with ...d5 to all unconventional first moves can provide consistent results.  If you chose  1...e5  instead, White could opt for  2.c4  , transitioning into an English Opening, which you might not be as comfortable with. You aim to continue with the usual plans! }
2. Nf3 Nf6
{ The regular approach is to respond similarly as you would usually do when White plays 1.d4! }
3. g3 c5 4. Bg2 Nc6
{ You develop the other knight and get ready to play ...e5 in one go. } 5. O-O
e5 { You have transposed to the Reti! } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "15a) English Reti and Sidelines"]
[Black "Nimzo-Larsen Attack 1.b3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. b3
{ This is the Nimzo-Larsen attack. Get ready to tackle the sidelines. As a rule of thumb, you can answer the rare moves with ...d5! You can go for your familiar setup against d4-openings. This is a robust option where you get a strong grip on the center and develop the knights quickly. Tackling the sidelines with ...e5 could be tricky because of the other variations learned in this repertoire.  For example,  1.g3  e5  could be answered with  2.c4  when White tricked you in an English opening you didn't study. }
1... d5
{ You place your pawn in the center!   1...e5  is also an alternative; however after  2.Bb2  White will exert pressure on this pawn. }
2. Bb2
{ White controls the center from the flank and prevents you from playing ...e5 }
2... Nf6
{ You develop the knight as usual. You use the concept for when you are playing against a d4-opening.  So you don't opt for  2...Nc6?  where the knight can't exert much pressure on the center when White plays  3.d4 }
3. e3 c5 { Thematic to first move the c-pawn forward before going ...Nc6 } 4.
Nf3 Nc6 { You develop the knight as usual. } 5. Bb5
{ White creates a pin on your knight! You rather want to avoid that White can give you doubled pawns, so you unpin the knight and develop your bishop. }
5... Bd7 6. O-O { White castles! } 6... e6
{ You get ready to play ... Bd6 when you can also castle. You would like to control the e5-square with a queen move and play ...e5 to control the center fully. }
7. d3
{ The variation with the direct  7.Bxc6  Bxc6  almost always transposes back to this variation. }
7... Bd6 { You develop the bishop! } 8. Bxc6 Bxc6 9. Ne5
{ White target your light-squared bishop! } 9... Rc8
{ You support the bishop to avoid getting doubled pawns. } 10. f4
{ The main move and this position could also very well be reached from be bird opening starting with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.f4   White typically has the plan to start attacking your king if you castle! With moves like Rf3-Rh3 and g4-g5! If you know the plan for how to counter this, it won't be dangerous, and you have a good chance to gain an opening advantage. }
10... O-O { You castle! } 11. Nd2
{ The same position could also be reached after @@StartFEN@@2rqk2r/pp3ppp/2bbpn2/2ppN3/8/1P1PP3/PBP2PPP/RN1Q1RK1 w k - 2 10@@EndFEN@@  10.Nd2  O-O  11.f4 }
11... Be8
{ A key move you keep the bishop pair on the board! Also, the bishop is well placed to anticipate a future attack involving Qh5. }
12. Rf3 { When White would continue with the attacking plan } 12... Nd7
{ When White would continue with the attacking plan, you are ready to start trading the knight in the center. }
13. Rg3 { When the rook targets g7, you need to stop White's attack. } 13... f6
{ A great move, both kicking the knight away from the center and blocking the bishop diagonal. }
14. Qg4 { White can threaten both mate with Qxg7 as well as Qxe6! } 14... Qe7
{ You defend everything and have a clearly better position as Black! White needs to move the knight away from the center.  After  15.Nef3  , an excellent way to play, is  15...b5  preparing for ...Nb6 and a break with ...c4, which would activate the rook. }
*

