1. b3
{ This is the Nimzo-Larsen attack. Get ready to tackle the sidelines. As a rule of thumb, you can answer the rare moves with ...d5! You can go for your familiar setup against d4-openings. This is a robust option where you get a strong grip on the center and develop the knights quickly. Tackling the sidelines with ...e5 could be tricky because of the other variations learned in this repertoire.  For example,  1.g3  e5  could be answered with  2.c4  when White tricked you in an English opening you didn't study. }
1... d5
{ You place your pawn in the center!   1...e5  is also an alternative; however after  2.Bb2  White will exert pressure on this pawn. }
2. Bb2
{ White controls the center from the flank and prevents you from playing ...e5 }
2... Nf6
{ You develop the knight as usual. You use the concept for when you are playing against a d4-opening.  So you don't opt for  2...Nc6?  where the knight can't exert much pressure on the center when White plays  3.d4 }
3. e3 c5 { Thematic to first move the c-pawn forward before going ...Nc6 } 4.
Nf3 Nc6 { You develop the knight as usual. } 5. Bb5
{ White creates a pin on your knight! You rather want to avoid that White can give you doubled pawns, so you unpin the knight and develop your bishop. }
5... Bd7 6. O-O { White castles! } 6... e6
{ You get ready to play ... Bd6 when you can also castle. You would like to control the e5-square with a queen move and play ...e5 to control the center fully. }
7. c4
{ The most challenging move White can try! You are loyal to your plan in the course and already captured back after cxd5 with ...Nxd5, and that doesn't change in this variation. }
7... Bd6 { You develop the bishop as usual! } 8. cxd5 Nxd5
{ As always, you capture back with the knight on ...d5! You stay true to the style you learned in the course. Also, you spice up the game as you invite White to capture the pawn on g7. }
9. Bxg7 { White accepts the pawn sacrifice. } 9... Rg8
{ You activate your rook on the open g-file and kick the bishop back. } 10. Bb2
Qe7 { You get ready for a queenside castle! You are ahead in development. } 11.
Nc3 { White gets the knight out! } 11... Nxc3
{ You trade the knight as usual! } 12. Bxc3 O-O-O
{ You castle queenside and finish your development. } 13. g3
{ White can try to safeguard the king with a pawn blockade. } 13... h5
{ You want to go for ... h4 and weaken the White's king. } 14. d4 h4
{ You keep going for the attack!  Now  14...cxd4  would allow White to capture back with the knight  15.Nxd4  and you don't manage to weaken their pawn structure. }
15. dxc5 Bc7 { You keep the bishop ready for the attack! } 16. Qe2 e5
{ You both activate your light-squared bishop and get ready to chase away the defending knight with ...e4! }
17. b4 { White has to support the c5-pawn. } 17... e4
{ You chase away the defending knight! } 18. Bxc6 bxc6
{ You want to take back with the pawn to keep the light-squared bishop in the attack. }
19. Nd4 { The knight moves away! } 19... hxg3
{ It's time to strike and open White's king! } 20. fxg3 Bxg3
{ You sacrifice the bishop!  It's too dangerous for White to capture because after  21.fxg3  Rxg3+  22.Kf2  , you have several ways to win, and the most convincing one is  22...Rg2+  because after  23.Kxg2  Rg8+  White's king is helpless. }
21. Kh1 { The king has to hide in the corner. } 21... Bxh2
{ You capture another pawn and keep capturing the defenders in front of White's king. }
22. Nxc6 { White can sacrifice the knight back to control the h8-square. }
22... Bxc6 23. Qxh2 Rd3
{ You keep the attack going!  White is in an uncomfortable situation but should still be able to survive if they find  24.Rg1  counterattacking on the g-file. You can either trade rooks or play  24...Rgd8  controlling the open d-file. }
*

