{ Same reaction as in the Larsen opening. } 6. Bb2 e6 7. O-O Bd6
{ You develop just like you did against the Larsen opening. Now, you're ready to castle and possess solid control over the center. Once you've castled, your objective is to expand your control in the center and set the stage to play ...e5  White will likely aim to avoid this and may opt to capture your knight, which is currently exerting control over the e5-square. Here's a potential sequence:  8.Bxc6  Bxc6  9.Ne5  Rc8  preventing White from doubling your pawns  10.d3  O-O  11.Nd2  and now  11...Be8!  This preserves your pair of bishops and after  12.Ndf3  , you can play  12...Nd7!  This sets the stage for ...f6 and prepares to seize control of the center with ...e5. }
